\par                                       1891                                  
\par                            THE PICTURE OF DORIAN GRAY                       
\par                                                                             
\par                                  by Oscar Wilde                             
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                               CHAPTER I                                     
\par -                                                                           
\par   The studio was filled with the rich odour of roses, and when the          
\par light summer wind stirred amidst the trees of the garden there came         
\par through the open door the heavy scent of the lilac, or the more             
\par delicate perfume of the pink-flowering thorn.                               
\par   From the corner of the divan of Persian saddle-bags on which he           
\par was lying, smoking, as was his custom, innumerable cigarettes, Lord         
\par Henry Wotton could just catch the gleam of the honey-sweet and              
\par honey-coloured blossoms of a laburnum, whose tremulous branches seemed      
\par hardly able to bear the burden of a beauty so flamelike as theirs; and      
\par now and then the fantastic shadows of birds in flight flitted across        
\par the long tussore-silk curtains that were stretched in front of the          
\par huge window, producing a kind of momentary Japanese effect, and making      
\par him think of those pallid jade-faced painters of Tokio who, through         
\par the medium of an art that is necessarily immobile, seek to convey           
\par the sense of swiftness and motion. The sullen murmur of the bees            
\par shouldering their way through the long unmown grass, or circling            
\par with monotonous insistence round the dusty gilt horns of the                
\par straggling woodbine, seemed to make the stillness more oppressive. The      
\par dim roar of London was like the burdon note of a distant organ.             
\par   In the centre of the room, clamped to an upright easel, stood the         
\par full-length portrait of a young man of extraordinary personal               
\par beauty, and in front of it, some little distance away, was sitting the      
\par artist himself, Basil Hallward, whose sudden disappearance some             
\par years ago caused, at the time, such public excitement, and gave rise        
\par to so many strange conjectures.                                             
\par   As the painter looked at the gracious and comely form he had so           
\par skilfully mirrored in his art, a smile of pleasure passed across his        
\par face, and seemed about to linger there. But he suddenly started up,         
\par and, closing his eyes, placed his fingers upon the lids, as though          
\par he sought to imprison within his brain some curious dream from which        
\par he feared he might awake.                                                   
\par   "It is your best work, Basil, the best thing you have ever done,"         
\par said Lord Henry, languidly. "You must certainly send it next year to        
\par the Grosvenor. The Academy is too large and too vulgar. Whenever I          
\par have gone there, there have either been so many people that I have not      
\par been able to see the pictures, which was dreadful, or so many pictures      
\par that I have not been able to see the people, which was worse. The           
\par Grosvenor is really the only place."                                        
\par   "I don't think I shall send it anywhere," he answered, tossing his        
\par head back in that odd way that used to make his friends laugh at him        
\par at Oxford. "No; I won't send it anywhere."                                  
\par   Lord Henry elevated his eyebrows, and looked at him in amazement          
\par through the thin blue wreaths of smoke that curled up in such fanciful      
\par whorls from his heavy opium-tainted cigarette.                              
\par   "Not send it anywhere? My dear fellow, why? Have you any reason?          
\par What odd chaps you painters are! You do anything in the world to            
\par gain a reputation. As soon as you have one, you seem to want to             
\par throw it away. It is silly of you, for there is only one thing in           
\par the world worse than being talked about, and that is not being              
\par talked about. A portrait like this would set you far above all the          
\par young men in England, and make the old men quite jealous, if old men        
\par are ever capable of any emotion."                                           
\par   "I know you will laugh at me," he replied, "but I really can't            
\par exhibit it. I have put too much of myself into it."                         
\par   Lord Henry stretched himself out on the divan and laughed.                
\par   "Yes, I knew you would; but it is quite true, all the same."              
\par   "Too much of yourself in it! Upon my word, Basil, I didn't know           
\par you were so vain; and I really can't see any resemblance between            
\par you, with your rugged strong face and your coal-black hair, and this        
\par young Adonis, who looks as if he was made out of ivory and                  
\par rose-leaves. Why, my dear Basil, he is a Narcissus, and you- well,          
\par of course you have an intellectual expression, and all that. But            
\par beauty, real beauty, ends where an intellectual expression begins.          
\par Intellect is in itself a mode of exaggeration, and destroys the             
\par harmony of any face. The moment one sits down to think, one becomes         
\par all nose, or all forehead, or something horrid. Look at the successful      
\par men in any of the learned professions. How perfectly hideous they are!      
\par Except, of course, in the church. But then in the church they don't         
\par think. A bishop keeps on saying at the age of eighty what he was            
\par told to say when he was a boy of eighteen, and as a natural                 
\par consequence he always looks absolutely delightful. Your mysterious          
\par young friend, whose name you have never told me, but whose picture          
\par really fascinates me, never thinks. I feel quite sure of that. He is        
\par some brainless, beautiful creature, who should always be here in            
\par winter when we have no flowers to look at, and always here in summer        
\par when we want something to chill our intelligence. Don't flatter             
\par yourself, Basil, you are not in the least like him."                        
\par   "You don't understand me, Harry," answered the artist. "Of course         
\par I am not like him. I know that perfectly well. Indeed, I should be          
\par sorry to look like him. You shrug your shoulders? I am telling you the      
\par truth. There is a fatality about all physical and intellectual              
\par distinction, the sort of fatality that seems to dog through history         
\par the faltering steps of kings. It is better not to be different from         
\par one's fellows. The ugly and the stupid have the best of it in this          
\par world. They can sit at their ease and gape at the play. If they know        
\par nothing of victory, they are at least spared the knowledge of               
\par defeat. They live as we all should live, undisturbed, indifferent, and      
\par without disquiet. They neither bring ruin upon others, nor ever             
\par receive it, from alien hands. Your rank and wealth, Harry; my               
\par brains, such as they are- my art, whatever it may be worth; Dorian          
\par Gray's good looks- we shall all suffer for what the gods have given         
\par us, suffer terribly."                                                       
\par   "Dorian Gray? Is that his name?" asked Lord Henry, walking across         
\par the studio towards Basil Hallward.                                          
\par   "Yes, that is his name. I didn't intend to tell it to you."               
\par   "But why not?"                                                            
\par   "Oh, I can't explain. When I like people immensely I never tell           
\par their names to any one. It is like surrendering a part of them. I have      
\par grown to love secrecy. It seems to be the one thing that can make           
\par modern life mysterious or marvellous to us. The commonest thing is          
\par delightful if one only hides it. When I leave town now I never tell my      
\par people where I am going. If I did, I would lose all my pleasure. It is      
\par a silly habit, I dare say, but somehow it seems to bring a great            
\par deal of romance into one's life. I suppose you think me awfully             
\par foolish about it?"                                                          
\par   "Not at all," answered Lord Henry, "not at all, my dear Basil. You        
\par seem to forget that I am married, and the one charm of marriage is          
\par that it makes a life of deception absolutely necessary for both             
\par parties. I never know where my wife is, and my wife never knows what I      
\par am doing. When we meet- we do meet occasionally, when we dine out           
\par together, or go down to the Duke's- we tell each other the most absurd      
\par stories with the most serious faces. My wife is very good at it-            
\par much better, in fact, than I am. She never gets confused over her           
\par dates, and I always do. But when she does find me out, she makes no         
\par row at all. I sometimes wish she would; but she merely laughs at me."       
\par   "I hate the way you talk about your married life, Harry," said Basil      
\par Hallward, strolling towards the door that led into the garden. "I           
\par believe that you are really a very good husband, but that you are           
\par thoroughly ashamed of your own virtues. You are an extraordinary            
\par fellow. You never say a moral thing, and you never do a wrong thing.        
\par Your cynicism is simply a pose."                                            
\par   "Being natural is simply a pose, and the most irritating pose I           
\par know," cried Lord Henry, laughing; and the two young men went out into      
\par the garden together, and ensconced themselves on a long bamboo seat         
\par that stood in the shade of a tall laurel bush. The sunlight slipped         
\par over the polished leaves. In the grass, white daisies were tremulous.       
\par   After a pause, Lord Henry pulled out his watch. "I am afraid I            
\par must be going, Basil," he murmured, "and before I go, I insist on your      
\par answering a question I put to you some time ago."                           
\par   "What is that?" said the painter, keeping his eyes fixed on the           
\par ground.                                                                     
\par   "You know quite well."                                                    
\par   "I do not, Harry."                                                        
\par   "Well, I will tell you what it is. I want you to explain to me why        
\par you won't exhibit Dorian Gray's picture. I want the real reason."           
\par   "I told you the real reason."                                             
\par   "No, you did not. You said it was because there was too much of           
\par yourself in it. Now, that is childish."                                     
\par   "Harry," said Basil Hallward, looking him straight in the face,           
\par "every portrait that is painted with feeling is a portrait of the           
\par artist, not of the sitter. The sitter is merely the accident, the           
\par occasion. It is not he who is revealed by the painter; it is rather         
\par the painter who, on the coloured canvas, reveals himself. The reason I      
\par will not exhibit this picture is that I am afraid that I have shown in      
\par it the secret of my own soul."                                              
\par   Lord Henry laughed. "And what is that?" he asked.                         
\par   "I will tell you," said Hallward; but an expression of perplexity         
\par came over his face.                                                         
\par   "I am all expectation, Basil," continued his companion, glancing          
\par at him.                                                                     
\par   "Oh, there is really very little to tell, Harry," answered the            
\par painter; "and I am afraid you will hardly understand it. Perhaps you        
\par will hardly believe it."                                                    
\par   Lord Henry smiled, and, leaning down, plucked a pink-petalled             
\par daisy from the grass, and examined it. "I am quite sure I shall             
\par understand it," he replied, gazing intently at the little golden            
\par white-feathered disk, "and as for believing things, I can believe           
\par anything, provided that it is quite incredible."                            
\par   The wind shook some blossoms from the trees, and the heavy                
\par lilac-blooms, with their clustering stars, moved to and fro in the          
\par languid air. A grasshopper began to chirrup by the wall, and like a         
\par blue thread a long thin dragon-fly floated past on its brown gauze          
\par wings. Lord Henry felt as if he could hear Basil Hallward's heart           
\par beating, and wondered what was coming.                                      
\par   "The story is simply this," said the painter after some time. "Two        
\par months ago I went to a crush at Lady Brandon's. You know we poor            
\par artists have to show ourselves in society from time to time, just to        
\par remind the public that we are not savages. With an evening coat and         
\par a white tie, as you told me once, anybody, even a stock-broker, can         
\par gain a reputation for being civilized. Well, after I had been in the        
\par room about ten minutes, talking to huge overdressed dowagers and            
\par tedious Academicians, I suddenly became conscious that some one was         
\par looking at me. I turned halfway round, and saw Dorian Gray for the          
\par first time. When our eyes met, I felt that I was growing pale. A            
\par curious sensation of terror came over me. I knew that I had come            
\par face to face with some one whose mere personality was so fascinating        
\par that, if I allowed it to do so, it would absorb my whole nature, my         
\par whole soul, my very art itself. I did not want any external                 
\par influence in my life. You know yourself, Harry, how independent I am        
\par by nature. I have always been my own master; had at least always            
\par been so, till I met Dorian Gray. Then- but I don't know how to explain      
\par it to you. Something seemed to tell me that I was on the verge of a         
\par terrible crisis in my life. I had a strange feeling that Fate had in        
\par store for me exquisite joys and exquisite sorrows. I grew afraid,           
\par and turned to quit the room. It was not conscience that made me do it:      
\par it was a sort of cowardice. I take no credit to myself for trying to        
\par escape."                                                                    
\par   "Conscience and cowardice are really the same things, Basil.              
\par Conscience is the trade-name of the firm. That is all."                     
\par   "I don't believe that, Harry, and I don't believe you do either.          
\par However, whatever was my motive- and it may have been pride, for I          
\par used to be very proud- I certainly struggled to the door. There, of         
\par course, I stumbled against Lady Brandon. 'You are not going to run          
\par away so soon, Mr. Hallward?' she screamed out. You know her                 
\par curiously shrill voice?"                                                    
\par   "Yes; she is a peacock in everything but beauty," said Lord Henry,        
\par pulling the daisy to bits with his long, nervous fingers.                   
\par   "I could not get rid of her. She brought me up to Royalties, and          
\par people with Stars and Garters, and elderly ladies with gigantic tiaras      
\par and parrot noses. She spoke of me as her dearest friend. I had only         
\par met her once before, but she took it into her head to lionize me. I         
\par believe some picture of mine had made a great success at the time,          
\par at least had been chattered about in the penny newspapers, which is         
\par the nineteenth-century standard of immortality. Suddenly I found            
\par myself face to face with the young man whose personality had so             
\par strangely stirred me. We were quite close, almost touching. Our eyes        
\par met again. It was reckless of me, but I asked Lady Brandon to               
\par introduce me to him. Perhaps it was not so reckless, after all. It was      
\par simply inevitable. We would have spoken to each other without any           
\par introduction. I am sure of that. Dorian told me so afterwards. He,          
\par too, felt that we were destined to know each other."                        
\par   "And how did Lady Brandon describe this wonderful young man?"             
\par asked his companion. "I know she goes in for giving a rapid precis          
\par of all her guests. I remember her bringing me up to a truculent and         
\par red-faced old gentleman covered all over with orders and ribbons,           
\par and hissing into my ear, in a tragic whisper which must have been           
\par perfectly audible to everybody in the room, the most astounding             
\par details. I simply fled. I like to find out people for myself. But Lady      
\par Brandon treats her guests exactly as an auctioneer treats his goods.        
\par She either explains them entirely away, or tells one everything             
\par about them except what one wants to know."                                  
\par   "Poor Lady Brandon! You are hard on her, Harry!" said Hallward,           
\par listlessly.                                                                 
\par   "My dear fellow, she tried to found a salon, and only succeeded in        
\par opening a restaurant. How could I admire her? But tell me, what did         
\par she say about Mr. Dorian Gray?"                                             
\par   "Oh, something like 'Charming boy- poor dear mother and I absolutely      
\par inseparable. Quite forget what he does- afraid he- doesn't do               
\par anything- oh, yes, plays the piano- or is it the violin, dear Mr.           
\par Gray?' Neither of us could help laughing, and we became friends at          
\par once."                                                                      
\par   "Laughter is not at all a bad beginning for a friendship, and it          
\par is far the best ending for one," said the young lord, plucking another      
\par daisy.                                                                      
\par   Hallward shook his head. "You don't understand what friendship is,        
\par Harry," he murmured- "or what enmity is, for that matter. You like          
\par every one; that is to say, you are indifferent to every one."               
\par   "How horribly unjust of you!" cried Lord Henry, tilting his hat           
\par back, and looking up at the little clouds that, like ravelled skeins        
\par of glossy white silk, were drifting across the hollowed turquoise of        
\par the summer sky. "Yes, horribly unjust of you. I make a great                
\par difference between people. I choose my friends for their good looks,        
\par my acquaintances for their good characters, and my enemies for their        
\par good intellects. A man cannot be too careful in the choice of his           
\par enemies. I have not got one who is a fool, they are all men of some         
\par intellectual power, and consequently they all appreciate me. Is that        
\par very vain of me? I think it is rather vain."                                
\par   "I should think it was, Harry. But according to your category I must      
\par be merely an acquaintance."                                                 
\par   "My dear old Basil, you are much more than an acquaintance."              
\par   "And much less than a friend. A sort of brother, I suppose?"              
\par   "Oh, brothers! I don't care for brothers. My elder brother won't          
\par die, and my younger brothers seem never to do anything else."               
\par   "Harry!" exclaimed Hallward, frowning.                                    
\par   "My dear fellow, I am not quite serious. But I can't help                 
\par detesting my relations. I suppose it comes from the fact that none          
\par of us can stand other people having the same faults as ourselves. I         
\par quite sympathize with the rage of the English democracy against what        
\par they call the vices of the upper orders. The masses feel that               
\par drunkenness, stupidity, and immorality should be their own special          
\par property, and that if any one of us makes an ass of himself he is           
\par poaching on their preserves. When poor Southwark got into the               
\par Divorce Court, their indignation was quite magnificent. And yet I           
\par don't suppose that ten per cent of the proletariat live correctly."         
\par   "I don't agree with a single word that you have said, and, what is        
\par more, Harry, I feel sure that you don't either."                            
\par   Lord Henry stroked his pointed brown beard, and tapped the toe of         
\par his patent-leather boot with a tasselled ebony cane. "How English           
\par you are, Basil! That is the second time you have made that                  
\par observation. If one puts forward an idea to a true Englishman-              
\par always a rash thing to do- he never dreams of considering whether           
\par the idea is right or wrong. The only thing he considers of any              
\par importance is whether one believes it oneself. Now, the value of an         
\par idea has nothing whatsoever to do with the sincerity of the man who         
\par expresses it. Indeed, the probabilities are that the more insincere         
\par the man is, the more purely intellectual will the idea be, as in            
\par that case it will not be coloured by either his wants, his desires, or      
\par his prejudices. However, I don't propose to discuss politics,               
\par sociology, or metaphysics with you. I like persons better than              
\par principles, and I like persons with no principles better than anything      
\par else in the world. Tell me more about Mr. Dorian Gray. How often do         
\par you see him?"                                                               
\par   "Every day. I couldn't be happy if I didn't see him every day. He is      
\par absolutely necessary to me."                                                
\par   "How extraordinary! I thought you would never care for anything           
\par but your art."                                                              
\par   "He is all my art to me now," said the painter, gravely. "I               
\par sometimes think, Harry, that there are only two eras of any importance      
\par in the world's history. The first is the appearance of a new medium         
\par for art, and the second is the appearance of a new personality for art      
\par also. What the invention of oil-painting was to the Venetians, the          
\par face of Antinous was to late Greek sculpture, and the face of Dorian        
\par Gray will some day be to me. It is not merely that I paint from him,        
\par draw from him, sketch from him. Of course I have done all that. But he      
\par is much more to me than a model or a sitter. I won't tell you that I        
\par am dissatisfied with what I have done of him or that his beauty is          
\par such that Art cannot express it. There is nothing that Art cannot           
\par express, and I know that the work I have done, since I met Dorian           
\par Gray, is good work, is the best work of my life. But in some curious        
\par way- I wonder will you understand me?- his personality has suggested        
\par to me an entirely new manner in art, an entirely new mode of style.         
\par I see things differently, I think of them differently. I can now            
\par re-create life in a way that was hidden from me before. 'A dream of         
\par form in days of thought:'- who is it who says that? I forget; but it        
\par is what Dorian Gray has been to me. The merely visible presence of          
\par this lad- for he seems to me little more than a lad, though he is           
\par really over twenty- his merely visible presence- ah! I wonder can           
\par you realize all that that means? Unconsciously he defines for me the        
\par lines of a fresh school, a school that is to have in it all the             
\par passion of the romantic spirit, all the perfection of the spirit            
\par that is Greek. The harmony of soul and body- how much that is! We in        
\par our madness have separated the two, and have invented a realism that        
\par is vulgar, an ideality that is void. Harry! if you only knew what           
\par Dorian Gray is to me! You remember that landscape of mine, for which        
\par Agnew offered me such a huge price, but which I would not part with?        
\par It is one of the best things I have ever done. And why is it so?            
\par Because, while I was painting it, Dorian Gray sat beside me. Some           
\par subtle influence passed from him to me, and for the first time in my        
\par life I saw in the plain woodland the wonder I had always looked for,        
\par and always missed."                                                         
\par   "Basil, this is extraordinary! I must see Dorian Gray."                   
\par   Hallward got up from his seat, and walked up and down the garden.         
\par After some time he came back. "Harry," he said, "Dorian Gray is to          
\par me simply a motive in art. You might see nothing in him. I see              
\par everything in him. He is never more present in my work than when no         
\par image of him is there. He is a suggestion, as I have said, of a new         
\par manner. I find him in the curves of certain lines, in the loveliness        
\par and subtleties of certain colours. That is all."                            
\par   "Then why won't you exhibit his portrait?" asked Lord Henry.              
\par   "Because, without intending it, I have put into it some expression        
\par of all this curious artistic idolatry, of which, of course, I have          
\par never cared to speak to him. He knows nothing about it. He shall never      
\par know anything about it. But the world might guess it; and I will not        
\par bare my soul to their shallow, prying eyes. My heart shall never be         
\par put under their microscope. There is too much of myself in the              
\par thing, Harry- too much of myself!"                                          
\par   "Poets are not so scrupulous as you are. They know how useful             
\par passion is for publication. Nowadays a broken heart will run to many        
\par editions."                                                                  
\par   "I hate them for it," cried Hallward. "An artist should create            
\par beautiful things, but should put nothing of his own life into them. We      
\par live in an age when men treat art as if it were meant to be a form          
\par of autobiography. We have lost the abstract sense of beauty. Some           
\par day I will show the world what it is; and for that reason the world         
\par shall never see my portrait of Dorian Gray."                                
\par   "I think you are wrong, Basil, but I won't argue with you. It is          
\par only the intellectually lost who ever argue. Tell me, is Dorian Gray        
\par very fond of you?"                                                          
\par   The painter considered for a few moments. "He likes me," he answered      
\par after a pause; "I know he likes me. Of course I flatter him                 
\par dreadfully. I find a strange pleasure in saying things to him that I        
\par know I shall be sorry for having said. As a rule, he is charming to         
\par me, and we sit in the studio and talk of a thousand things. Now and         
\par then, however, he is horribly thoughtless, and seems to take a real         
\par delight in giving me pain. Then I feel, Harry, that I have given            
\par away my whole soul to some one who treats it as if it were a flower to      
\par put in his coat, a bit of decoration to charm his vanity, an                
\par ornament for a summer's day."                                               
\par   "Days in summer, Basil, are apt to linger," murmured Lord Henry.          
\par "Perhaps you will tire sooner than he will. It is a sad thing to think      
\par of, but there is no doubt that Genius lasts longer than Beauty. That        
\par accounts for the fact that we all take such pains to over-educate           
\par ourselves. In the wild struggle for existence, we want to have              
\par something that endures, and so we fill our minds with rubbish and           
\par facts, in the silly hope of keeping our place. The thoroughly               
\par well-informed man- that is the modern idea. And the mind of the             
\par thoroughly well-informed man is a dreadful thing. It is like a              
\par bric-a-brac shop, all monsters and dust, with everything priced             
\par above its proper value. I think you will tire first, all the same.          
\par Some day you will look at your friend and he will seem to you to be         
\par a little out of drawing, or you won't like his tone of colour, or           
\par something. You will bitterly reproach him in your own heart, and            
\par seriously think that he has behaved very badly to you. The next time        
\par he calls, you will be perfectly cold and indifferent. It will be a          
\par great pity, for it will alter you. What you have told me is quite a         
\par romance, a romance of art one might call it, and the worst of having a      
\par romance of any kind is that it leaves one so unromantic."                   
\par   "Harry, don't talk like that. As long as I live, the personality          
\par of Dorian Gray will dominate me. You can't feel what I feel. You            
\par change too often."                                                          
\par   "Ah, my dear Basil, that is exactly why I can feel it. Those who are      
\par faithful know only the trivial side of love: it is the faithless who        
\par know love's tragedies." And Lord Henry struck a light on a dainty           
\par silver case, and began to smoke a cigarette with a self-conscious           
\par and satisfied air, as if he had summed up the world in a phrase. There      
\par was a rustle of chirruping sparrows in the green lacquer leaves of the      
\par ivy, and the blue cloud-shadows chased themselves across the grass          
\par like swallows. How pleasant it was in the garden! And how delightful        
\par other people's emotions were!- much more delightful than their              
\par ideas, it seemed to him. One's own soul, and the passions of one's          
\par friends- those were the fascinating things in life. He pictured to          
\par himself with silent amusement the tedious luncheon that he had              
\par missed by staying so long with Basil Hallward. Had he gone to his           
\par aunt's, he would have been sure to have met Lord Goodbody there, and        
\par the whole conversation would have been about the feeding of the             
\par poor, and the necessity for model lodging-houses. Each class would          
\par have preached the importance of those virtues, for whose exercise           
\par there was no necessity in their own lives. The rich would have              
\par spoken on the value of thrift, and the idle grown eloquent over the         
\par dignity of labour. It was charming to have escaped all that! As he          
\par thought of his aunt, an idea seemed to strike him. He turned to             
\par Hallward, and said, "My dear fellow, I have just remembered."               
\par   "Remembered what, Harry?"                                                 
\par   "Where I heard the name of Dorian Gray."                                  
\par   "Where was it?" asked Hallward, with a slight frown.                      
\par   "Don't look so angry, Basil. It was at my aunt, Lady Agatha's. She        
\par told me she had discovered a wonderful young man, who was going to          
\par help her in the East End, and that his name was Dorian Gray. I am           
\par bound to state that she never told me he was good-looking. Women            
\par have no appreciation of good looks; at least, good women have not. She      
\par said that he was very earnest, and had a beautiful nature. I at once        
\par pictured to myself a creature with spectacles and lank hair,                
\par horribly freckled, and tramping about on huge feet. I wish I had known      
\par it was your friend."                                                        
\par   "I am very glad you didn't, Harry."                                       
\par   "Why?"                                                                    
\par   "I don't want you to meet him."                                           
\par   "You don't want me to meet him?"                                          
\par   "No."                                                                     
\par   "Mr. Dorian Gray is in the studio, sir," said the butler, coming          
\par into the garden.                                                            
\par   "You must introduce me now," cried Lord Henry, laughing.                  
\par   The painter turned to his servant, who stood blinking in the              
\par sunlight. "Ask Mr. Gray to wait, Parker: I shall be in in a few             
\par moments." The man bowed, and went up the walk.                              
\par   Then he looked at Lord Henry. "Dorian Gray is my dearest friend," he      
\par said. "He has a simple and beautiful nature. Your aunt was quite right      
\par in what she said of him. Don't spoil him. Don't try to influence            
\par him. Your influence would be bad. The world is wide, and has many           
\par marvellous people in it. Don't take away from me the one person who         
\par gives to my art whatever charm it possesses; my life as an artist           
\par depends on him. Mind, Harry, I trust you." He spoke very slowly, and        
\par the words seemed wrung out of him almost against his will.                  
\par   "What nonsense you talk!" said Lord Henry, smiling, and, taking           
\par Hallward by the arm, he almost led him into the house.                      
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                               CHAPTER II                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   As they entered they saw Dorian Gray. He was seated at the piano,         
\par with his back to them, turning over the pages of a volume of                
\par Schumann's "Forest Scenes." "You must lend me these, Basil," he cried.      
\par "I want to learn them. They are perfectly charming."                        
\par   "That depends entirely on how you sit to-day, Dorian."                    
\par   "Oh, I am tired of sitting, and I don't want a life-sized portrait        
\par of myself," answered the lad, swinging round on the music-stool, in         
\par a wilful, petulant manner. When he caught sight of Lord Henry, a faint      
\par blush coloured his cheeks for a moment, and he started up. "I beg your      
\par pardon, Basil, but I didn't know you had any one with you."                 
\par   "This is Lord Henry Wotton, Dorian, an old Oxford friend of mine.         
\par I have just been telling him what a capital sitter you were, and now        
\par you have spoiled everything."                                               
\par   "You have not spoiled my pleasure in meeting you, Mr. Gray," said         
\par Lord Henry, stepping forward and extending his hand. "My aunt has           
\par often spoken to me about you. You are one of her favourites, and, I am      
\par afraid, one of her victims, also."                                          
\par   "I am in Lady Agatha's black books at present," answered Dorian,          
\par with a funny look of penitence. "I promised to go to a club in              
\par Whitechapel with her last Tuesday, and I really forgot all about it.        
\par We were to have played a duet together- three duets, I believe. I           
\par don't know what she will say to me. I am far too frightened to call."       
\par   "Oh, I will make your peace with my aunt. She is quite devoted to         
\par you. And I don't think it really matters about your not being there.        
\par The audience probably thought it was a duet. When Aunt Agatha sits          
\par down to the piano she makes quite enough noise for two people."             
\par   "That is very horrid to her, and not very nice to me," answered           
\par Dorian, laughing.                                                           
\par   Lord Henry looked at him. Yes, he was certainly wonderfully               
\par handsome, with his finely-curved scarlet lips, his frank blue eyes,         
\par his crisp gold hair. There was something in his face that made one          
\par trust him at once. All the candour of youth was there, as well as           
\par all youth's passionate purity. One felt that he had kept himself            
\par unspotted from the world. No wonder Basil Hallward worshipped him.          
\par   "You are too charming to go in for philanthropy, Mr. Gray- far too        
\par charming." And Lord Henry flung himself down on the divan, and              
\par opened his cigarette-case.                                                  
\par   The painter had been busy mixing his colours and getting his brushes      
\par ready. He was looking worried, and when he heard Lord Henry's last          
\par remark he glanced at him, hesitated for a moment, and then said,            
\par "Harry, I want to finish this picture to-day. Would you think it            
\par awfully rude of me if I asked you to go away?"                              
\par   Lord Henry smiled, and looked at Dorian Gray. "Am I to go, Mr.            
\par Gray?" he asked.                                                            
\par   "Oh, please don't, Lord Henry. I see that Basil is in one of his          
\par sulky moods; and I can't bear him when he sulks. Besides, I want you        
\par to tell me why I should not go in for philanthropy."                        
\par   "I don't know that I shall tell you that, Mr. Gray. It is so tedious      
\par a subject that one would have to talk seriously about it. But I             
\par certainly shall not run away, now that you have asked me to stop.           
\par You don't really mind, Basil, do you? You have often told me that           
\par you liked your sitters to have some one to chat to."                        
\par   Hallward bit his lip. "If Dorian wishes it, of course you must stay.      
\par Dorian's whims are laws to everybody, except himself."                      
\par   Lord Henry took up his hat and gloves. "You are very pressing,            
\par Basil, but I am afraid I must go. I have promised to meet a man at the      
\par Orleans. Good-bye, Mr. Gray. Come and see me some afternoon in              
\par Curzon Street. I am nearly always at home at five o'clock. Write to me      
\par when you are coming. I should be sorry to miss you."                        
\par   "Basil," cried Dorian Gray, "if Lord Henry Wotton goes I shall go         
\par too. You never open your lips while you are painting, and it is             
\par horribly dull standing on a platform and trying to look pleasant.           
\par Ask him to stay. I insist upon it."                                         
\par   "Stay, Harry, to oblige Dorian, and to oblige me," said Hallward,         
\par gazing intently at his picture. "It is quite true, I never talk when I      
\par am working, and never listen either, and it must be dreadfully tedious      
\par for my unfortunate sitters. I beg you to stay."                             
\par   "But what about my man at the Orleans?"                                   
\par   The painter laughed. "I don't think there will be any difficulty          
\par about that. Sit down again, Harry. And now, Dorian, get up on the           
\par platform, and don't move about too much, or pay any attention to            
\par what Lord Henry says. He has a very bad influence over all his              
\par friends, with the single exception of myself."                              
\par   Dorian Gray stepped up on the dais, with the air of a young Greek         
\par martyr, and made a little moue of discontent to Lord Henry, to whom he      
\par had rather taken a fancy. He was so unlike Basil. They made a               
\par delightful contrast. And he had such a beautiful voice. After a few         
\par moments he said to him, "Have you really a very bad influence, Lord         
\par Henry? As bad as Basil says?"                                               
\par   "There is no such thing as a good influence, Mr. Gray. All influence      
\par is immoral- immoral from the scientific point of view."                     
\par   "Why?"                                                                    
\par   "Because to influence a person is to give him one's own soul. He          
\par does not think his natural thoughts, or burn with his natural               
\par passions. His virtues are not real to him. His sins, if there are such      
\par things as sins, are borrowed. He becomes an echo of some one else's         
\par music, an actor of a part that has not been written for him. The aim        
\par of life is self-development. To realize one's nature perfectly- that        
\par is what each of us is here for. People are afraid of themselves,            
\par nowadays. They have forgotten the highest of all duties, the duty that      
\par one owes to one's self. Of course they are charitable. They feed the        
\par hungry, and clothe the beggar. But their own souls starve, and are          
\par naked. Courage has gone out of our race. Perhaps we never really had        
\par it. The terror of society, which is the basis of morals, the terror of      
\par God, which is the secret of religion- these are the two things that         
\par govern us. And yet--"                                                       
\par   "Just turn your head a little more to the right, Dorian, like a good      
\par boy," said the painter, deep in his work, and conscious only that a         
\par look had come into the lad's face that he had never seen there before.      
\par   "And yet," continued Lord Henry, in his low, musical voice, and with      
\par that graceful wave of the hand that was always so characteristic of         
\par him, and that he had even in his Eton days, "I believe that if one man      
\par were to live out his life fully and completely, were to give form to        
\par every feeling, expression to every thought, reality to every dream-         
\par I believe that the world would gain such a fresh impulse of joy that        
\par we would forget all the maladies of mediaevalism, and return to the         
\par Hellenic ideal- to something finer, richer, than the Hellenic ideal,        
\par it may be. But the bravest man amongst us is afraid of himself. The         
\par mutilation of the savage has its tragic survival in the self-denial         
\par that mars our lives. We are punished for our refusals. Every impulse        
\par that we strive to strangle broods in the mind, and poisons us. The          
\par body sins once, and has done with its sin, for action is a mode of          
\par purification. Nothing remains then but the recollection of a pleasure,      
\par or the luxury of a regret. The only way to get rid of a temptation          
\par is to yield to it. Resist it, and your soul grows sick with longing         
\par for the things it has forbidden to itself, with desire for what its         
\par monstrous laws have made monstrous and unlawful. It has been said that      
\par the great events of the world take place in the brain. It is in the         
\par brain, and the brain only, that the great sins of the world take place      
\par also. You, Mr. Gray, you yourself, with your rose-red youth and your        
\par rose-white boyhood, you have had passions that have made you afraid,        
\par thoughts that have filled you with terror, day-dreams and sleeping          
\par dreams whose mere memory might stain your cheek with shame-"                
\par   "Stop!" faltered Dorian Gray, "stop! you bewilder me. I don't know        
\par what to say. There is some answer to you, but I cannot find it.             
\par Don't speak. Let me think. Or, rather, let me try not to think."            
\par   For nearly ten minutes he stood there, motionless, with parted lips,      
\par and eyes strangely bright. He was dimly conscious that entirely             
\par fresh influences were at work within him. Yet they seemed to him to         
\par have come really from himself. The few words that Basil's friend had        
\par said to him- words spoken by chance, no doubt, and with wilful paradox      
\par in them- had touched some secret chord that had never been touched          
\par before, but that he felt was now vibrating and throbbing to curious         
\par pulses.                                                                     
\par   Music had stirred him like that. Music had troubled him many              
\par times. But music was not articulate. It was not a new world, but            
\par rather another chaos, that it created in us. Words! Mere words! How         
\par terrible they were! How clear, and vivid, and cruel. One could not          
\par escape from them. And yet what a subtle magic there was in them.            
\par They seemed to be able to give a plastic form to formless things,           
\par and to have a music of their own as sweet as that of viol or of             
\par lute. Mere words! Was there anything so real as words?                      
\par   Yes, there had been things in his boyhood that he had not                 
\par understood. He understood them now. Life suddenly had become                
\par fiery-coloured to him. It seemed to him that he had been walking in         
\par fire. Why had he not known it?                                              
\par   With his subtle smile, Lord Henry watched him. He knew the precise        
\par psychological moment when to say nothing. He felt intensely                 
\par interested. He was amazed at the sudden impression that his words           
\par had produced, and, remembering a book that he had read when he was          
\par sixteen, a book which had revealed to him much that he had not known        
\par before, he wondered whether Dorian Gray was passing through a               
\par similar experience. He had merely shot an arrow into the air. Had it        
\par hit the mark? How fascinating the lad was!                                  
\par   Hallward painted away with that marvellous bold touch of his, that        
\par had the true refinement and perfect delicacy that in art, at any rate,      
\par comes only from strength. He was unconscious of the silence.                
\par   "Basil, I am tired of standing," cried Dorian Gray, suddenly. "I          
\par must go out and sit in the garden. The air is stifling here."               
\par   "My dear fellow, I am so sorry. When I am painting, I can't think of      
\par anything else. But you never sat better. You were perfectly still. And      
\par I have caught the effect I wanted- the half-parted lips and the bright      
\par look in the eyes. I don't know what Harry has been saying to you,           
\par but he has certainly made you have the most wonderful expression. I         
\par suppose he has been paying you compliments. You mustn't believe a word      
\par that he says."                                                              
\par   "He has certainly not been paying me compliments. Perhaps that is         
\par the reason that I don't believe anything he has told me."                   
\par   "You know you believe it all," said Lord Henry, looking at him            
\par with his dreamy, languorous eyes. "I will go out to the garden with         
\par you. It is horribly hot in the studio. Basil, let us have something         
\par iced to drink, something with strawberries in it."                          
\par   "Certainly, Harry. Just touch the bell, and when Parker comes I will      
\par tell him what you want. I have got to work up this background, so I         
\par will join you later on. Don't keep Dorian too long. I have never            
\par been in better form for painting than I am to-day. This is going to be      
\par my masterpiece. It is my masterpiece as it stands."                         
\par   Lord Henry went out to the garden, and found Dorian Gray burying his      
\par face in the great cool lilac-blossoms, feverishly drinking in their         
\par perfume as if it had been wine. He came close to him, and put his hand      
\par upon his shoulder. "You are quite right to do that," he murmured.           
\par "Nothing can cure the soul but the senses, just as nothing can cure         
\par the senses but the soul."                                                   
\par   The lad started and drew back. He was bare-headed, and the leaves         
\par had tossed his rebellious curls and tangled all their gilded                
\par threads. There was a look of fear in his eyes, such as people have          
\par when they are suddenly awakened. His finely-chiselled nostrils              
\par quivered, and some hidden nerve shook the scarlet of his lips and left      
\par them trembling.                                                             
\par   "Yes," continued Lord Henry, "that is one of the great secrets of         
\par life- to cure the soul by means of the senses, and the senses by means      
\par of the soul. You are a wonderful creation. You know more than you           
\par think you know, just as you know less than you want to know."               
\par   Dorian Gray frowned and turned his head away. He could not help           
\par liking the tall, graceful young man who was standing by him. His            
\par romantic olive-coloured face and worn expression interested him. There      
\par was something in his low, languid voice that was absolutely                 
\par fascinating. His cool, white, flower-like hands, even, had a curious        
\par charm. They moved, as he spoke, like music, and seemed to have a            
\par language of their own. But he felt afraid of him, and ashamed of being      
\par afraid. Why had it been left for a stranger to reveal him to                
\par himself? He had known Basil Hallward for months, but the friendship         
\par between them had never altered him. Suddenly there had come some one        
\par across his life who seemed to have disclosed to him life's mystery.         
\par And, yet, what was there to be afraid of? He was not a schoolboy or         
\par a girl. It was absurd to be frightened.                                     
\par   "Let us go and sit in the shade," said Lord Henry. "Parker has            
\par brought out the drinks, and if you stay any longer in this glare you        
\par will be quite spoiled, and Basil will never paint you again. You            
\par really must not allow yourself to become sunburnt. It would be              
\par unbecoming."                                                                
\par   "What can it matter?" cried Dorian Gray, laughing, as he sat down on      
\par the seat at the end of the garden.                                          
\par   "It should matter everything to you, Mr. Gray."                           
\par   "Why?"                                                                    
\par   "Because you have the most marvellous youth, and youth is the one         
\par thing worth having."                                                        
\par   "I don't feel that, Lord Henry."                                          
\par   "No, you don't feel it now. Some day, when you are old and                
\par wrinkled and ugly, when thought has seared your forehead with its           
\par lines, and passion branded your lips with its hideous fires, you            
\par will feel it, you will feel it terribly. Now, wherever you go, you          
\par charm the world. Will it always be so?... You have a wonderfully            
\par beautiful face, Mr. Gray. Don't frown. You have. And Beauty is a            
\par form of Genius- is higher, indeed, than Genius, as it needs no              
\par explanation. It is of the great facts of the world, like sunlight,          
\par or spring-time, or the reflection in dark waters of that silver             
\par shell we call the moon. It cannot be questioned. It has its divine          
\par right of sovereignty. It makes princes of those who have it. You            
\par smile? Ah! when you have lost it you won't smile.... People say             
\par sometimes that Beauty is only superficial. That may be so. But at           
\par least it is not so superficial as Thought is. To me, Beauty is the          
\par wonder of wonders. It is only shallow people who do not judge by            
\par appearances. The true mystery of the world is the visible, not the          
\par invisible.... Yes, Mr. Gray, the gods have been good to you. But            
\par what the gods give they quickly take away. You have only a few years        
\par in which to live really, perfectly, and fully. When your youth goes,        
\par your beauty will go with it, and then you will suddenly discover            
\par that there are no triumphs left for you, or have to content yourself        
\par with those mean triumphs that the memory of your past will make more        
\par bitter than defeats. Every month as it wanes brings you nearer to           
\par something dreadful. Time is jealous of you, and wars against your           
\par lilies and your roses. You will become sallow, and hollow-cheeked, and      
\par dull-eyed. You will suffer horribly.... Ah! realize your youth while        
\par you have it. Don't squander the gold of your days, listening to the         
\par tedious, trying to improve the hopeless failure, or giving away your        
\par life to the ignorant, the common, and the vulgar. These are the sickly      
\par aims, the false ideals, of our age. Live! Live the wonderful life that      
\par is in you! Let nothing be lost upon you. Be always searching for new        
\par sensations. Be afraid of nothing.... A new Hedonism- that is what           
\par our century wants. You might be its visible symbol. With your               
\par personality there is nothing you could not do. The world belongs to         
\par you for a season.... The moment I met you I saw that you were quite         
\par unconscious of what you really are, of what you really might be. There      
\par was so much in you that charmed me that I felt I must tell you              
\par something about yourself. I thought how tragic it would be if you were      
\par wasted. For there is such a little time that your youth will last-          
\par such a little time. The common hill-flowers wither, but they blossom        
\par again. The laburnum will be as yellow next June as it is now. In a          
\par month there will be purple stars on the clematis, and year after            
\par year the green night of its leaves will hold its purple stars. But          
\par we never get back our youth. The pulse of joy that beats in us at           
\par twenty, becomes sluggish. Our limbs fail, our senses rot. We                
\par degenerate into hideous puppets, haunted by the memory of the passions      
\par of which we were too much afraid, and the exquisite temptations that        
\par we had not the courage to yield to. Youth! Youth! There is                  
\par absolutely nothing in the world but youth!"                                 
\par   Dorian Gray listened, open-eyed and wondering. The spray of lilac         
\par fell from his hand upon the gravel. A furry bee came and buzzed             
\par round it for a moment. Then it began to scramble all over the oval          
\par stellated globe of its tiny blossoms. He watched it with that               
\par strange interest in trivial things that we try to develop when              
\par things of high import make us afraid, or when we are stirred by some        
\par new emotion for which we cannot find expression, or when some               
\par thought that terrifies us lays sudden siege to the brain and calls          
\par on us to yield. After a time the bee flew away. He saw it creeping          
\par into the stained trumpet of a Tyrian convolvulus. The flower seemed to      
\par quiver, and then swayed gently to and fro.                                  
\par   Suddenly the painter appeared at the door of the studio, and made         
\par staccato signs for them to come in. They turned to each other, and          
\par smiled.                                                                     
\par   "I am waiting," he cried. "Do come in. The light is quite perfect,        
\par and you can bring your drinks."                                             
\par   They rose up, and sauntered down the walk together. Two                   
\par green-and-white butterflies fluttered past them, and in the                 
\par pear-tree at the corner of the garden a thrush began to sing.               
\par   "You are glad you have met me, Mr. Gray," said Lord Henry, looking        
\par at him.                                                                     
\par   "Yes, I am glad now. I wonder shall I always be glad?"                    
\par   "Always! that is a dreadful word. It makes me shudder when I hear         
\par it. Women are so fond of using it. They spoil every romance by              
\par trying to make it last forever. It is a meaningless word, too. The          
\par only difference between a caprice and a life-long passion is that           
\par the caprice lasts a little longer."                                         
\par   As they entered the studio, Dorian Gray put his hand upon Lord            
\par Henry's arm. "In that case, let our friendship be a caprice," he            
\par murmured, flushing at his own boldness, then stepped up on the              
\par platform and resumed his pose.                                              
\par   Lord Henry flung himself into a large wicker arm-chair and watched        
\par him. The sweep and dash of the brush on the canvas made the only sound      
\par that broke the stillness, except when, now and then, Hallward               
\par stepped back to look at his work from a distance. In the slanting           
\par beams that streamed through the open doorway the dust danced and was        
\par golden. The heavy scent of the roses seemed to brood over everything.       
\par   After about a quarter of an hour Hallward stopped painting, looked        
\par for a long time at Dorian Gray, and then for a long time at the             
\par picture, biting the end of one of his huge brushes, and frowning.           
\par "It is quite finished," he cried at last, and stooping down he wrote        
\par his name in long vermilion letters on the left-hand corner of the           
\par canvas.                                                                     
\par   Lord Henry came over and examined the picture. It was certainly a         
\par wonderful work of art, and a wonderful likeness as well.                    
\par   "My dear fellow, I congratulate you most warmly," he said. "It is         
\par the finest portrait of modern times. Mr. Gray, come over and look at        
\par yourself."                                                                  
\par   The lad started, as if awakened from some dream. "Is it really            
\par finished?" he murmured, stepping down from the platform.                    
\par   "Quite  finished," said the painter. "And you have sat splendidly         
\par to-day. I am awfully obliged to you."                                       
\par   "That is entirely due to me," broke in Lord Henry. "Isn't it, Mr.         
\par Gray?"                                                                      
\par   Dorian made no answer, but passed listlessly in front of his picture      
\par and turned towards it. When he saw it he drew back, and his cheeks          
\par flushed for a moment with pleasure. A look of joy came into his             
\par eyes, as if he had recognized himself for the first time. He stood          
\par there motionless and in wonder, dimly conscious that Hallward was           
\par speaking to him, but not catching the meaning of his words. The             
\par sense of his own beauty came on him like a revelation. He had never         
\par felt it before. Basil Hallward's compliments had seemed to him to be        
\par merely the charming exaggerations of friendship. He had listened to         
\par them, laughed at them, forgotten them. They had not influenced his          
\par nature. Then had come Lord Henry Wotton with his strange panegyric          
\par on youth, his terrible warning of its brevity. That had stirred him at      
\par the time, and now, as he stood gazing at the shadow of his own              
\par loveliness, the full reality of the description flashed across him.         
\par Yes, there would be a day when his face would be wrinkled and wizened,      
\par his eyes dim and colourless, the grace of his figure broken and             
\par deformed. The scarlet would pass away from his lips, and the gold           
\par steal from his hair. The life that was to make his soul would mar           
\par his body. He would become dreadful, hideous, and uncouth.                   
\par   As he thought of it, a sharp pang of pain struck through him like         
\par a knife, and made each delicate fibre of his nature quiver. His eyes        
\par deepened into amethyst, and across them came a mist of tears. He            
\par felt as if a hand of ice had been laid upon his heart.                      
\par   "Don't you like it?" cried Hallward at last, stung a little by the        
\par lad's silence, not understanding what it meant.                             
\par   "Of course he likes it," said Lord Henry. "Who wouldn't like it?          
\par It is one of the greatest things in modern art. I will give you             
\par anything you like to ask for it. I must have it."                           
\par   "It is not my property, Harry."                                           
\par   "Whose property is it?"                                                   
\par   "Dorian's, of course," answered the painter.                              
\par   "He is a very lucky fellow."                                              
\par   "How sad it is!" murmured Dorian Gray, with his eyes still fixed          
\par upon his own portrait. "How sad it is! I shall grow old, and horrible,      
\par and dreadful. But this picture will remain always young. It will never      
\par be older than this particular day of June.... If it were only the           
\par other way! If it were I who was to be always young, and the picture         
\par that was to grow old! For that- for that- I would give everything!          
\par Yes, there is nothing in the whole world I would not give! I would          
\par give my soul for that!"                                                     
\par   "You would hardly care for such an arrangement, Basil," cried Lord        
\par Henry, laughing. "It would be rather hard lines on your work."              
\par   "I should object very strongly, Harry," said Hallward.                    
\par   Dorian Gray turned and looked at him. "I believe you would, Basil.        
\par You like your art better than your friends. I am no more to you than a      
\par green bronze figure. Hardly as much, I dare say."                           
\par   The painter stared in amazement. It was so unlike Dorian to speak         
\par like that. What had happened? He seemed quite angry. His face was           
\par flushed and his cheeks burning.                                             
\par   "Yes," he continued, "I am less to you than your ivory Hermes or          
\par your silver Faun. You will like them always. How long will you like         
\par me? Till I have my first wrinkle, I suppose. I know, now, that when         
\par one loses one's good looks, whatever they may be, one loses                 
\par everything. Your picture has taught me that. Lord Henry Wotton is           
\par perfectly, right. Youth is the only thing worth having. When I find         
\par that I am growing old, I shall kill myself."                                
\par   Hallward turned pale, and caught his hand. "Dorian! Dorian!" he           
\par cried, "don't talk like that. I have never had such a friend as you,        
\par and I shall never have such another. You are not jealous of material        
\par things, are you?- you who are finer than any of them!"                      
\par   "I am jealous of everything whose beauty does not die. I am               
\par jealous of the portrait you have painted of me. Why should it keep          
\par what I must lose? Every moment that passes takes something from me,         
\par and gives something to it. Oh, if it were only the other way! If the        
\par picture could change. and I could be always what I am now! Why did you      
\par paint it? It will mock me some day- mock me horribly!" The hot tears        
\par welled into his eyes; he tore his hand away, and, flinging himself          
\par on the divan, he buried his face in the cushions, as though he was          
\par praying.                                                                    
\par   "This is your doing, Harry," said the painter, bitterly.                  
\par   Lord Henry shrugged his shoulders. "It is the real Dorian Gray- that      
\par is all."                                                                    
\par   "It is not."                                                              
\par   "If it is not, what have I to do with it?"                                
\par   "You should have gone away when I asked you," he muttered.                
\par   "I stayed when you asked me," was Lord Henry's answer.                    
\par   "Harry, I can't quarrel with my two best friends at once, but             
\par between you both you have made me hate the finest piece of work I have      
\par ever done, and I will destroy it. What is it but canvas and colour?         
\par I will not let it come across our three lives and mar them."                
\par   Dorian Gray lifted his golden head from the pillow, and with              
\par pallid face and tear-stained eyes looked at him, as he walked over          
\par to the deal painting-table that was set beneath the high curtained          
\par window. What was he doing there? His fingers were straying about among      
\par the litter of tin tubes and dry brushes, seeking for something. Yes,        
\par it was for the long palette-knife, with its thin blade of lithe steel.      
\par He had found it at last. He was going to rip up the canvas.                 
\par   With a stifled sob the lad leaped from the couch, and, rushing            
\par over to Hallward, tore the knife out of his hand, and flung it to           
\par the end of the studio. "Don't, Basil, don't!" he cried. "It would be        
\par murder!"                                                                    
\par   "I am glad you appreciate my work at last, Dorian," said the              
\par painter, coldly, when he had recovered from his surprise. "I never          
\par thought you would."                                                         
\par   "Appreciate it? I am in love with it, Basil. It is part of myself. I      
\par feel that."                                                                 
\par   "Well, as soon as you are dry, you shall be varnished, and framed,        
\par and sent home. Then you can do what you like with yourself." And he         
\par walked across the room and rang the bell for tea. "You will have            
\par tea, of course, Dorian? And so will you, Harry? Or do you object to         
\par such simple pleasures?"                                                     
\par   "I adore simple pleasures," said Lord Henry. "They are the last           
\par refuge of the complex. But I don't like scenes, except on the stage.        
\par What absurd fellows you are, both of you! I wonder who it was               
\par defined man as a rational animal. It was the most premature definition      
\par ever given. Man is many things, but he is not rational. I am glad he        
\par is not, after all: though I wish you chaps would not squabble over the      
\par picture. You had much better let me have it, Basil. This silly boy          
\par doesn't really want it, and I really do."                                   
\par   "If you let any one have it but me, Basil, I shall never forgive          
\par you!" cried Dorian Gray; "and I don't allow people to call me a             
\par silly boy."                                                                 
\par   "You know the picture is yours, Dorian. I gave it to you before it        
\par existed."                                                                   
\par   "And you know you have been a little silly, Mr. Gray, and that you        
\par don't really object to being reminded that you are extremely young."        
\par   "I should have objected very strongly this morning, Lord Henry."          
\par   "Ah! this morning! You have lived since then."                            
\par   There came a knock at the door, and the butler entered with a             
\par laden tea-tray, and set it down upon a small Japanese table. There was      
\par a rattle of cups and saucers and the hissing of a fluted Georgian urn.      
\par Two globe-shaped china dishes were brought in by a page. Dorian Gray        
\par went over and poured out the tea. The two men sauntered languidly to        
\par the table, and examined what was under the covers.                          
\par   "Let us go to the theatre to-night," said Lord Henry. "There is sure      
\par to be something on, somewhere. I have promised to dine at White's, but      
\par it is only with an old friend, so I can send him a wire to say that         
\par I am ill, or that I am prevented from coming in consequence of a            
\par subsequent engagement. I think that would be a rather nice excuse:          
\par it would have all the surprise of candour."                                 
\par   "It is such a bore putting on one's dress-clothes," muttered              
\par Hallward. "And, when one has them on, they are so horrid."                  
\par   "Yes," answered Lord Henry, dreamily, "the costume of the nineteenth      
\par century is detestable. It is so sombre, so depressing. Sin is the only      
\par real colour-element left in modern life."                                   
\par   "You really must not say things like that before Dorian, Harry."          
\par   "Before which Dorian? The one who is pouring out tea for us, or           
\par the one in the picture?"                                                    
\par   "Before either."                                                          
\par   "I should like to come to the theatre with you, Lord Henry," said         
\par the lad.                                                                    
\par   "Then you shall come; and you will come too, Basil, won't you?"           
\par   "I can't really. I would sooner not. I have a lot of work to do."         
\par   "Well, then, you and I will go, Mr. Gray."                                
\par   "I should like that awfully."                                             
\par   The painter bit his lip and walked over, cup in hand, to the              
\par picture. "I shall stay with the real Dorian," he said, sadly.               
\par   "Is it the real Dorian?" cried the original of the portrait,              
\par strolling across to him. "Am I really like that?"                           
\par   "Yes; you are just like that."                                            
\par   "How wonderful, Basil!"                                                   
\par   "At least you are like it in appearance. But it will never alter,"        
\par sighed Hallward. "That is something."                                       
\par   "What a fuss people make about fidelity!" exclaimed Lord Henry.           
\par "Why, even in love it is purely a question of physiology. It has            
\par nothing to do with our own will. Young men want to be faithful, and         
\par are not; old men want to be faithless, and cannot: that is all one can      
\par say."                                                                       
\par   "Don't go to the theatre to-night, Dorian," said Hallward. "Stop and      
\par dine with me."                                                              
\par   "I can't, Basil."                                                         
\par   "Why?"                                                                    
\par   "Because I have promised Lord Henry Wotton to go with him."               
\par   "He won't like you any better for keeping your promises. He always        
\par breaks his own. I beg you not to go."                                       
\par   Dorian Gray laughed and shook his head.                                   
\par   "I entreat you."                                                          
\par   The lad hesitated, and looked over at Lord Henry, who was watching        
\par them from the tea-table with an amused smile.                               
\par   "I must go, Basil," he answered.                                          
\par   "Very well," said Hallward; and he went over and laid down his cup        
\par on the tray. "It is rather late, and, as you have to dress, you had         
\par better lose no time. Good-bye, Harry. Good-bye, Dorian. Come and see        
\par me soon. Come to-morrow."                                                   
\par   "Certainly."                                                              
\par   "You won't forget?"                                                       
\par   "No, of course not," cried Dorian.                                        
\par   "And... Harry!"                                                           
\par   "Yes, Basil?"                                                             
\par   "Remember what I asked you, when we were in the garden this               
\par morning?"                                                                   
\par   "I have forgotten it."                                                    
\par   "I trust you."                                                            
\par   "I wish I could trust myself," said Lord Henry, laughing. "Come, Mr.      
\par Gray, my hansom is outside, and I can drop you at your own place.           
\par Good-bye, Basil. It has been a most interesting afternoon."                 
\par   As the door closed behind them, the painter flung himself down on         
\par a sofa, and a look of pain came into his face.                              
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                              CHAPTER III                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   At half-past twelve next day Lord Henry Wotton strolled from              
\par Curzon Street over to the Albany to call on his uncle, Lord Fermor,         
\par a genial if somewhat rough-mannered old bachelor, whom the outside          
\par world called selfish because it derived no particular benefit from          
\par him, but who was considered generous by Society as he fed the people        
\par who amused him. His father had been our ambassador at Madrid when           
\par Isabella was young, and Prim unthought of, but had retired from the         
\par Diplomatic Service in a capricious moment of annoyance on not being         
\par offered the Embassy at Paris, a post to which he considered that he         
\par was fully entitled by reason of his birth, his indolence, the good          
\par English of his despatches, and his inordinate passion for pleasure.         
\par The son, who had been his father's secretary, had resigned along            
\par with his chief, somewhat foolishly as was thought at the time, and          
\par on succeeding some months later to the title, had set himself to the        
\par serious study of the great aristocratic art of doing absolutely             
\par nothing. He had two large town houses, but preferred to live in             
\par chambers as it was less trouble, and took most of his meals at his          
\par club. He paid some attention to the management of his collieries in         
\par the Midland counties, excusing himself for this taint of industry on        
\par the ground that the one advantage of having coal was that it enabled a      
\par gentleman to afford the decency of burning wood on his own hearth.          
\par In politics he was a Tory, except when the Tories were in office,           
\par during which period he roundly abused them for being a pack of              
\par Radicals. He was a hero to his valet, who bullied him, and a terror to      
\par most of his relations, whom he bullied in turn. Only England could          
\par have produced him, and he always said that the country was going to         
\par the dogs. His principles were out of date, but there was a good deal        
\par to be said for his prejudices.                                              
\par   When Lord Henry entered the room, he found his uncle sitting in a         
\par rough shooting coat, smoking a cheroot and grumbling over The Times.        
\par "Well, Harry," said the old gentleman, "what brings you out so              
\par early? I thought you dandies never got up until two, and were not           
\par visible until five."                                                        
\par   "Pure family affection, I assure you, Uncle George. I want to get         
\par something out of you."                                                      
\par   "Money, I suppose," said Lord Fermor, making a wry face. "Well,           
\par sit down and tell me all about it. Young people, nowadays, imagine          
\par that money is everything."                                                  
\par   "Yes," murmured Lord Henry, settling his buttonhole in his coat;          
\par "and when they grow older they know it. But I don't want money. It          
\par is only people who pay their bills who want that, Uncle George, and         
\par I never pay mine. Credit is the capital of a younger son, and one           
\par lives charmingly upon it. Besides, I always deal with Dartmoor's            
\par tradesmen, and consequently they never bother me. What I want is            
\par information; not useful information, of course; useless information."       
\par   "Well, I can tell you anything that is in an English Blue-book,           
\par Harry, although those fellows nowadays write a lot of nonsense. When I      
\par was in the Diplomatic, things were much better. But I hear they let         
\par them in now by examination. What can you expect? Examinations, sir,         
\par are pure humbug from beginning to end. If a man is a gentleman, he          
\par knows quite enough, and if he is not a gentleman, whatever he knows is      
\par bad for him."                                                               
\par   "Mr. Dorian Gray does not belong to Blue-books, Uncle George,"            
\par said Lord Henry, languidly.                                                 
\par   "Mr. Dorian Gray? Who is he?" asked Lord Fermor, knitting his             
\par bushy white eyebrows.                                                       
\par   "That is what I have come to learn, Uncle George. Or rather, I            
\par know who, he is. He is the last Lord Kelso's grandson. His mother           
\par was a Devereux, Lady Margaret Devereux. I want you to tell me about         
\par his mother. What was she like? Whom did she marry? You have known           
\par nearly everybody in your time, so you might have known her. I am            
\par very much interested in Mr. Gray at present. I have only just met           
\par him."                                                                       
\par   "Kelso's grandson!" echoed the old gentleman. "Kelso's                    
\par grandson!... Of course.... I knew his mother intimately. I believe I        
\par was at her christening. She was an extraordinarily beautiful girl,          
\par Margaret Devereux, and made all the men frantic by running away with a      
\par penniless young fellow, a mere nobody, sir, a subaltern in a foot           
\par regiment, or something of that kind. Certainly. I remember the whole        
\par thing as if it happened yesterday. The poor chap was killed in a            
\par duel at Spa a few months after the marriage. There was an ugly story        
\par about it. They said Kelso got some rascally adventurer, some Belgian        
\par brute, to insult his son-in-law in public, paid him, sir, to do it,         
\par paid him, and that the fellow spitted his man as if he had been a           
\par pigeon. The thing was hushed up, but, egad, Kelso ate his chop alone        
\par at the club for some time afterwards. He brought his daughter back          
\par with him, I was told, and she never spoke to him again. Oh, yes; it         
\par was a bad business. The girl died too, died within a year. So she left      
\par a son, did she? I had forgotten that. What sort of a boy is he? If          
\par he is like his mother he must be a good-looking chap."                      
\par   "He is very good-looking," assented Lord Henry.                           
\par   "I hope he will fall into proper hands," continued the old man.           
\par "He should have a pot of money waiting for him if Kelso did the             
\par right thing by him. His mother had money too. All the Selby property        
\par came to her, through her grandfather. Her grandfather hated Kelso,          
\par thought him a mean dog. He was, too. Came to Madrid once when I was         
\par there. Egad, I was ashamed of him. The Queen used to ask me about           
\par the English noble who was always quarrelling with the cabmen about          
\par their fares. They made quite a story of it. I didn't dare show my face      
\par at Court for a month. I hope he treated his grandson better than he         
\par did the jarvies."                                                           
\par   "I don't know," answered Lord Henry. "I fancy that the boy will be        
\par well off. He is not of age yet. He has Selby, I know. He told me so.        
\par And... his mother was very beautiful?"                                      
\par   "Margaret Devereux was one of the loveliest creatures I ever saw,         
\par Harry. What on earth induced her to behave as she did, I never could        
\par understand. She could have married anybody she chose. Carlington was        
\par mad after her. She was romantic though. All the women of that family        
\par were. The men were a poor lot, but, egad! the women were wonderful.         
\par Carlington went on his knees to her. Told me so himself. She laughed        
\par at him, and there wasn't a girl in London at the time who wasn't after      
\par him. And by the way, Harry, talking about silly marriages, what is          
\par this humbug your father tells me about Dartmoor wanting to marry an         
\par American? Ain't English girls good enough for him?"                         
\par   "It is rather fashionable to marry Americans just now, Uncle              
\par George."                                                                    
\par   "I'll back English women against the world, Harry," said Lord             
\par Fermor, striking the table with his fist.                                   
\par   "The betting is on the Americans."                                        
\par   "They don't last, I am told," muttered his uncle.                         
\par   "A long engagement exhausts them, but they are capital at a               
\par steeplechase. They take things flying. I don't think Dartmoor has a         
\par chance."                                                                    
\par   "Who are her people?" grumbled the old gentleman. "Has she got any?"      
\par   Lord Henry shook his head. "American girls are as clever at               
\par concealing their parents, as English women are at concealing their          
\par past," he said, rising to go.                                               
\par   "They are pork-packers, I suppose?"                                       
\par   "I hope so, Uncle George, for Dartmoor's sake. I am told that             
\par pork-packing is the most lucrative profession in America, after             
\par politics."                                                                  
\par   "Is she pretty?"                                                          
\par   "She behaves as if she was beautiful. Most American women do. It          
\par is the secret of their charm."                                              
\par   "Why can't these American women stay in their own country? They           
\par are always telling us that it is the Paradise for women."                   
\par   "It is. That is the reason why, like Eve, they are so excessively         
\par anxious to get out of it," said Lord Henry. "Good-bye, Uncle George. I      
\par shall be late for lunch, if I stop any longer. Thanks for giving me         
\par the information I wanted. I always like to know everything about my         
\par new friends, and nothing about my old ones."                                
\par   "Where are you lunching, Harry?"                                          
\par   "At Aunt Agatha's. I have asked myself and Mr. Gray. He is her            
\par latest protege."                                                            
\par   "Humph! Tell your Aunt Agatha, Harry, not to bother me with any more      
\par of her charity appeals. I am sick of them. Why, the good woman              
\par thinks that I have nothing to do but write cheques for her silly            
\par fads."                                                                      
\par   "All right, Uncle George, I'll tell her, but it won't have any            
\par effect. Philanthropic people lose all sense of humanity. It is their        
\par distinguishing characteristic."                                             
\par   The old gentleman growled approvingly, and rang the bell for his          
\par servant. Lord Henry passed up the low arcade into Burlington Street,        
\par and turned his steps in the direction of Berkeley Square.                   
\par   So that was the story of Dorian Gray's parentage. Crudely as it           
\par had been told to him, it had yet stirred him by its suggestion of a         
\par strange, almost modern romance. A beautiful woman risking everything        
\par for a mad passion. A few wild weeks of happiness cut short by a             
\par hideous, treacherous crime. Months of voiceless agony, and then a           
\par child born in pain. The mother snatched away by death, the boy left to      
\par solitude and the tyranny of an old and loveless man. Yes; it was an         
\par interesting background. It posed the lad, made him more perfect as          
\par it were. Behind every exquisite thing that existed, there was               
\par something tragic. Worlds had to be in travail, that the meanest flower      
\par might blow.... And how charming he had been at dinner the night             
\par before, as with startled eyes and lips parted in frightened pleasure        
\par he had sat opposite to him at the club, the red candleshades                
\par staining to a richer rose the wakening wonder of his face. Talking          
\par to him was like playing upon an exquisite violin. He answered to every      
\par touch and thrill of the bow.... There was something terribly                
\par enthralling in the exercise of influence. No other activity was like        
\par it. To project one's soul into some gracious form, and let it tarry         
\par there for a moment; to hear one's own intellectual views echoed back        
\par to one with all the added music of passion and youth; to convey             
\par one's temperament into another as though it were a subtle fluid or a        
\par strange perfume: there was a real joy in that- perhaps the most             
\par satisfying joy left to us in an age so limited and vulgar as our            
\par own, an age grossly carnal in its pleasures, and grossly common in its      
\par aims.... He was a marvellous type, too, this lad, whom by so curious a      
\par chance he had met in Basil's studio, or could be fashioned into a           
\par marvellous type, at any rate. Grace was his, and the white purity of        
\par boyhood, and beauty such as old Greek marbles have kept for us.             
\par There was nothing that one could not do with him. He could be made a        
\par Titan or a toy. What a pity it was that such beauty was destined to         
\par fade!... And Basil? From a psychological point of view, how                 
\par interesting he was! The new manner in art, the fresh mode of looking        
\par at life, suggested so strangely by the merely visible presence of           
\par one who was unconscious of it all; the silent spirit that dwelt in dim      
\par woodland, and walked unseen in open field, suddenly showing herself,        
\par Dryad-like and not afraid, because in his soul who sought for her           
\par there had been awakened that wonderful vision to which alone are            
\par wonderful things revealed; the mere shapes and patterns of things           
\par becoming, as it were, refined, and gaining a kind of symbolical value,      
\par as though they were themselves patterns of some other and more perfect      
\par form whose shadow they made real: how strange it all was! He                
\par remembered something like it in history. Was it not Plato, that artist      
\par in thought, who had first analyzed it? Was it not Buonarotti who had        
\par carved it in the coloured marbles of a sonnet-sequence? But in our own      
\par country it was strange.... Yes; he would try to be to Dorian Gray           
\par what, without knowing it, the lad was to the painter who had fashioned      
\par the wonderful portrait. He would seek to dominate him- had already,         
\par indeed, half done so. He would make that wonderful spirit his own.          
\par There was something fascinating in this son of Love and Death.              
\par   Suddenly he stopped, and glanced up at the houses. He found that          
\par he had passed his aunt's some distance, and smiling to himself, turned      
\par back. When he entered the somewhat sombre hall the butler told him          
\par that they had gone in to lunch. He gave one of the footmen his hat and      
\par stick and passed into the dining-room.                                      
\par   "Late as usual, Harry," cried his aunt, shaking her head at him.          
\par   He invented a facile excuse, and having taken the vacant seat next        
\par to her, looked round to see who was there. Dorian bowed to him shyly        
\par from the end of the table, a flush of pleasure stealing into his            
\par cheek. Opposite was the Duchess of Harley, a lady of admirable              
\par good-nature and good temper, much liked by every one who knew her, and      
\par of those ample architectural proportions that in women who are not          
\par Duchesses are described by contemporary historians as stoutness.            
\par Next to her sat, on her right, Sir Thomas Burdon, a Radical member          
\par of Parliament, who followed his leader in public life and in private        
\par life followed the best cooks, dining with the Tories, and thinking          
\par with the Liberals, in accordance with a wise and well-known rule.           
\par The post on her left was occupied by Mr. Erskine of Treadley, an old        
\par gentleman of considerable charm and culture, who had fallen,                
\par however, into bad habits of silence, having, as he explained once to        
\par Lady Agatha, said everything that he had to say before he was               
\par thirty. His own neighbour was Mrs. Vandeleur, one of his aunt's oldest      
\par friends, a perfect saint amongst women, but so dreadfully dowdy that        
\par she reminded one of a badly bound hymn book. Fortunately for him she        
\par had on the other side Lord Faudel, a most intelligent middle-aged           
\par mediocrity, as bad as a Ministerial statement in the House of Commons,      
\par with whom she was conversing in that intensely earnest manner which is      
\par the one unpardonable error, as he remarked once himself, that all           
\par really good people fall into, and from which none of them ever quite        
\par escape.                                                                     
\par   "We are talking about poor Dartmoor, Lord Henry," cried the Duchess,      
\par nodding pleasantly to him across the table. "Do you think he will           
\par really marry this fascinating young person?"                                
\par   "I believe she has made up her mind to propose to him, Duchess."          
\par   "How dreadful!" exclaimed Lady Agatha. "Really, some one should           
\par interfere."                                                                 
\par   "I am told, on excellent authority, that her father keeps an              
\par American dry-goods store," said Sir Thomas Burdon, looking                  
\par supercilious.                                                               
\par   "My uncle has already suggested pork-packing, Sir Thomas."                
\par   "Dry-goods! What are American dry-goods?" asked the Duchess, raising      
\par her large hands in wonder, and accentuating the verb.                       
\par   "American novels," answered Lord Henry, helping himself to some           
\par quail.                                                                      
\par   The Duchess looked puzzled.                                               
\par   "Don't mind him, my dear," whispered Lady Agatha. "He never means         
\par anything that he says."                                                     
\par   "When America was discovered," said the Radical member, and he began      
\par to give some wearisome facts. Like all people who try to exhaust a          
\par subject, he exhausted his listeners. The Duchess sighed, and exercised      
\par her privilege of interruption. "I wish to goodness it never had been        
\par discovered at all!" she exclaimed. "Really, our girls have no chance        
\par nowadays. It is most unfair."                                               
\par   "Perhaps, after all, America never has been discovered," said Mr.         
\par Erskine; "I myself would say that it had merely been detected."             
\par   "Oh! but I have seen specimens of the inhabitants," answered the          
\par Duchess, vaguely. "I must confess that most of them are extremely           
\par pretty. And they dress well, too. They get all their dresses in Paris.      
\par I wish I could afford to do the same."                                      
\par   "They say that when good Americans die they go to Paris," chuckled        
\par Sir Thomas, who had a large wardrobe of Humour's cast-off clothes.          
\par   "Really! And where do bad Americans go when they die?" inquired           
\par the Duchess.                                                                
\par   "They go to America," murmured Lord Henry.                                
\par   Sir Thomas frowned. "I am afraid that your nephew is prejudiced           
\par against that great country," he said to Lady Agatha. "I have travelled      
\par all over it, in cars provided by the directors, who, in such                
\par matters, are extremely civil. I assure you that it is an education          
\par to visit it."                                                               
\par   "But must we really see Chicago in order to be educated?" asked           
\par Mr. Erskine, plaintively. "I don't feel up to the journey."                 
\par   Sir Thomas waved his hand. "Mr. Erskine of Treadley has the world on      
\par his shelves. We practical men like to see things, not to read about         
\par them. The Americans are an extremely interesting people. They are           
\par absolutely reasonable. I think that is their distinguishing                 
\par characteristic. Yes, Mr. Erskine, an absolutely reasonable people. I        
\par assure you there is no nonsense about the Americans."                       
\par   "How dreadful!" cried Lord Henry. "I can stand brute force, but           
\par brute reason is quite unbearable. There is something unfair about           
\par its use. It is hitting below the intellect."                                
\par   "I do not understand you," said Sir Thomas, growing rather red.           
\par   "I do, Lord Henry," murmured Mr. Erskine, with a smile.                   
\par   "Paradoxes are all very well in their way..." rejoined the Baronet.       
\par   "Was that a paradox?" asked Mr. Erskine. "I did not think so.             
\par Perhaps it was. Well, the way of paradoxes is the way of truth. To          
\par test Reality we must see it on the tight-rope. When the Verities            
\par become acrobats we can judge them."                                         
\par   "Dear me!" said Lady Agatha, "how you men argue! I am sure I never        
\par can make out what you are talking about. Oh! Harry, I am quite vexed        
\par with you. Why do you try to persuade our nice Mr. Dorian Gray to            
\par give up the East End? I assure you he would be quite invaluable.            
\par They would love his playing."                                               
\par   "I want him to play to me," cried Lord Henry, smiling, and he looked      
\par down the table and caught a bright answering glance.                        
\par   "But they are so unhappy in Whitechapel," continued Lady Agatha.          
\par   "I can sympathize with everything, except suffering," said Lord           
\par Henry, shrugging his shoulders. "I cannot sympathize with that. It          
\par is too ugly, too horrible, too distressing. There is something              
\par terribly morbid in the modern sympathy with pain. One should                
\par sympathize with the colour, the beauty, the joy of life. The less said      
\par about life's sores the better."                                             
\par   "Still, the East End is a very important problem," remarked Sir           
\par Thomas, with a grave shake of the head.                                     
\par   "Quite so," answered the young lord. "It is the problem of                
\par slavery, and we try to solve it by amusing the slaves."                     
\par   The politician looked at him keenly. "What change do you propose,         
\par then?" he asked.                                                            
\par   Lord Henry laughed. "I don't desire to change anything in England         
\par except the weather," he answered. "I am quite content with philosophic      
\par contemplation. But, as the nineteenth century has gone bankrupt             
\par through an over-expenditure of sympathy, I would suggest that we            
\par should appeal to Science to put us straight. The advantage of the           
\par emotions is that they lead us astray, and the advantage of Science          
\par is that it is not emotional."                                               
\par   "But we have such grave responsibilities," ventured Mrs.                  
\par Vandeleur, timidly.                                                         
\par   "Terribly grave," echoed Lady Agatha.                                     
\par   Lord Henry looked over at Mr. Erskine. "Humanity takes itself too         
\par seriously. It is the world's original sin. If the caveman had known         
\par how to laugh; History would have been different."                           
\par   "You are really very comforting," warbled the Duchess. "I have            
\par always felt rather guilty when I came to see your dear aunt, for I          
\par take no interest at all in the East End. For the future I shall be          
\par able to look her in the face without a blush."                              
\par   "A blush is very becoming, Duchess," remarked Lord Henry.                 
\par   "Only when one is young," she answered. "When an old woman like           
\par myself blushes, it is a very bad sign. Ah! Lord Henry, I wish you           
\par would tell me how to become young again."                                   
\par   He thought for a moment. "Can you remember any great error that           
\par you committed in your early days, Duchess?" he asked, looking at her        
\par across the table.                                                           
\par   "A great many, I fear," she cried.                                        
\par   "Then commit them over again," he said, gravely. "To get back             
\par one's youth, one has merely to repeat one's follies."                       
\par   "A delightful theory!" she exclaimed. "I must put it into practice."      
\par   "A dangerous theory," came from Sir Thomas's tight lips. Lady Agatha      
\par shook her head, but could not help being amused. Mr. Erskine listened.      
\par   "Yes," he continued, "that is one of the great secrets of life.           
\par Nowadays most people die of a sort of creeping common sense, and            
\par discover when it is too late that the only things one never regrets         
\par are one's mistakes."                                                        
\par   A laugh ran round the room.                                               
\par   He played with the idea, and grew wilful; tossed it into the air and      
\par transformed it; let it escape and recaptured it; made it iridescent         
\par with fancy, and winged it with paradox. The praise of folly, as he          
\par went on, soared into a philosophy, and Philosophy herself became            
\par young, and catching the mad music of Pleasure, wearing, one might           
\par fancy, her wine-stained robe and wreath of ivy, danced like a               
\par Bacchante over the hills of life, and mocked the slow Silenus for           
\par being sober. Facts fled before her like frightened forest things.           
\par Her white feet trod the huge press at which wise Omar sits, till the        
\par seething grape-juice rose round her bare limbs in waves of purple           
\par bubbles, or crawled in red foam over the vat's black, dripping,             
\par sloping sides. It was an extraordinary improvisation. He felt that the      
\par eyes of Dorian Gray were fixed on him, and the consciousness that           
\par amongst his audience there was one whose temperament he wished to           
\par fascinate, seemed to give his wit keenness, and to lend colour to           
\par his imagination. He was brilliant, fantastic, irresponsible. He             
\par charmed his listeners out of themselves, and they followed his pipe         
\par laughing. Dorian Gray never took his gaze off him, but sat like one         
\par under a spell, smiles chasing each other over his lips, and wonder          
\par growing grave in his darkening eyes.                                        
\par   At last, liveried in the costume of the age, Reality entered the          
\par room in the shape of a servant to tell the Duchess that her carriage        
\par was waiting. She wrung her hands in mock despair. "How annoying!"           
\par she cried. "I must go. I have to call for my husband at the club, to        
\par take him to some absurd meeting at Willis's Rooms, where he is going        
\par to be in the chair. If I am late he is sure to be furious, and I            
\par couldn't have a scene in this bonnet. It is far too fragile. A harsh        
\par word would ruin it. No, I must go, dear Agatha. Good-bye, Lord              
\par Henry, you are quite delightful, and dreadfully demoralizing. I am          
\par sure I don't know what to say about your views. You must come and dine      
\par with us some night. Tuesday,? Are you disengaged Tuesday?"                  
\par   "For you I would throw over anybody, Duchess," said Lord Henry, with      
\par a bow.                                                                      
\par   "Ah! that is very nice, and very wrong of you," she cried; "so            
\par mind you come;" and she swept out of the room, followed by Lady Agatha      
\par and the other ladies.                                                       
\par   When Lord Henry had sat down again, Mr. Erskine moved round, and          
\par taking a chair close to him, placed his hand upon his arm.                  
\par   "You talk books away," he said; "why don't you write one?"                
\par   "I am too fond of reading books to care to write them, Mr.                
\par Erskine. I should like to write a novel certainly, a novel that             
\par would be as lovely as a Persian carpet and as unreal. But there is          
\par no literary public in England for anything except newspapers, primers,      
\par and encyclopaedies. Of all people in the world the English have the         
\par least sense of the beauty of literature."                                   
\par   "I fear you are right," answered Mr. Erskine. "I myself used to have      
\par literary ambitions, but I gave them up long ago. And now, my dear           
\par young friend, if you will allow me to call you so, may I ask if you         
\par really meant all that you said to us at lunch?"                             
\par   "I quite forget what I said," smiled Lord Henry. "Was it all very         
\par bad?"                                                                       
\par   "Very bad indeed. In fact I consider you extremely dangerous, and if      
\par anything happens to our good Duchess we shall all look on you as being      
\par primarily responsible. But I should like to talk to you about life.         
\par The generation into which I was born was tedious. Some day, when you        
\par are tired of London, come down to Treadley, and expound to me your          
\par philosophy of pleasure over some admirable Burgundy I am fortunate          
\par enough to possess."                                                         
\par   "I shall be charmed. A visit to Treadley would be a great privilege.      
\par It has a perfect host, and a perfect library."                              
\par   "You will complete it," answered the old gentleman, with a courteous      
\par bow. "And now I must bid good-bye to your excellent aunt. I am due          
\par at the Athenaeum. It is the hour when we sleep there."                      
\par   "All of you, Mr. Erskine?"                                                
\par   "Forty of us, in forty arm-chairs. We are practising for an               
\par English Academy of Letters."                                                
\par   Lord Henry laughed, and rose. "I am going to the Park," he cried.         
\par    As he was passing out of the door Dorian Gray touched him on the         
\par arm. "Let me come with you," he murmured.                                   
\par   "But I thought you had promised Basil Hallward to go and see him,"        
\par answered Lord Henry.                                                        
\par   "I would sooner come with you; yes, I feel I must come with you.          
\par Do let me. And you will promise to talk to me all the time? No one          
\par talks so wonderfully as you do."                                            
\par    "Ah! I have talked quite enough for to-day," said Lord Henry,            
\par smiling. "All I want now is to look at life. You may come and look          
\par at it with me, if you care to."                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                               CHAPTER IV                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   One afternoon, a month later, Dorian Gray was reclining in a              
\par luxurious arm-chair, in the little library of Lord Henry's house in         
\par Mayfair. It was, in its way, a very charming room, with its high            
\par panelled wainscoting of olive-stained oak, its cream-coloured frieze        
\par and ceiling of raised plaster-work, and its brick-dust felt carpet          
\par strewn with silk long-fringed Persian rugs. On a tiny satinwood             
\par table stood a statuette by Clodion, and beside it lay a copy of "Les        
\par Cent Nouvelles," bound for Margaret of Valois by Clovis Eve, and            
\par powdered with the gilt daisies that Queen had selected for her device.      
\par Some large blue china jars and parrot-tulips were ranged on the             
\par mantelshelf, and through the small leaded panes of the window streamed      
\par the apricot-coloured light of a summer day in London.                       
\par   Lord Henry had not yet come in. He was always late on principle, his      
\par principle being that punctuality is the thief of time. So the lad           
\par was looking rather sulky, as with listless fingers he turned over           
\par the pages of an elaborately-illustrated edition of "Manon Lescaut"          
\par that he had found in one of the bookcases. The formal monotonous            
\par ticking of the Louis Quatorze clock annoyed him. Once or twice he           
\par thought of going away.                                                      
\par   At last he heard a step outside, and the door opened. "How late           
\par you are, Harry!" he murmured.                                               
\par   "I am afraid it is not Harry, Mr. Gray," answered a shrill voice.         
\par   He glanced quickly round, and rose to his feet. "I beg your               
\par pardon. I thought--"                                                        
\par   "You thought it was my husband. It is only his wife. You must let me      
\par introduce myself. I know you quite well by your photographs. I think        
\par my husband has got seventeen of them."                                      
\par   "Not seventeen, Lady Henry?"                                              
\par   "Well, eighteen, then. And I saw you with him the other night at the      
\par Opera." She laughed nervously as she spoke, and watched him with her        
\par vague forget-me-not eyes. She was a curious woman, whose dresses            
\par always looked as if they had been designed in a rage and put on in a        
\par tempest. She was usually in love with somebody, and, as her passion         
\par was never returned, she had kept all her illusions. She tried to            
\par look picturesque, but only succeeded in being untidy. Her name was          
\par Victoria, and she had a perfect mania for going to church.                  
\par   "That was at 'Lohengrin,' Lady Henry, I think?"                           
\par   "Yes; it was at dear 'Lohengrin.' I like Wagner's music better            
\par than anybody's. It is so loud that one can talk the whole time without      
\par other people hearing what one says. That is a great advantage: don't        
\par you think so, Mr. Gray?"                                                    
\par   The same nervous staccato laugh broke from her thin lips, and her         
\par fingers began to play with a long tortoise-shell paper-knife.               
\par   Dorian smiled, and shook his head: "I am afraid I don't think so,         
\par Lady Henry. I never talk during music- at least, during good music. If      
\par one hears bad music, it is one's duty to drown it in conversation."         
\par   "Ah! that is one of Harry's views, isn't it, Mr. Gray? I always hear      
\par Harry's views from his friends. It is the only way I get to know of         
\par them. But you must not think I don't like good music. I adore it,           
\par but I am afraid of it. It makes me too romantic. I have simply              
\par worshipped pianists- two at a time, sometimes, Harry tells me. I don't      
\par know what it is about them. Perhaps it is that they are foreigners.         
\par They all are, ain't they? Even those that are born in England become        
\par foreigners after a time, don't they? It is so clever of them, and such      
\par a compliment to art. Makes it quite cosmopolitan, doesn't it? You have      
\par never been to any of my parties, have you, Mr. Gray? You must come.         
\par I can't afford orchids, but I spare no expense in foreigners. They          
\par make one's rooms look so picturesque. But here is Harry!- Harry, I          
\par came in to look for you, to ask you something- I forget what it was-        
\par and I found Mr. Gray here. We have had such a pleasant chat about           
\par music. We have quite the same ideas. No; I think our ideas are quite        
\par different. But he has been most pleasant. I am so glad I've seen him."      
\par   "I am charmed, my love, quite charmed," said Lord Henry, elevating        
\par his dark crescent-shaped eyebrows and looking at them both with an          
\par amused smile. "So sorry I am late, Dorian. I went to look after a           
\par piece of old brocade in Wardour Street, and had to bargain for hours        
\par for it. Nowadays people know the price of everything, and the value of      
\par nothing."                                                                   
\par   "I am afraid I must be going," exclaimed Lady Henry, breaking an          
\par awkward silence with her silly sudden laugh. "I have promised to drive      
\par with the Duchess. Good-bye, Mr. Gray. Good-bye, Harry. You are              
\par dining out, I suppose? So am I. Perhaps I shall see you at Lady             
\par Thornbury's."                                                               
\par   "I dare say, my dear," said Lord Henry, shutting the door behind          
\par her, as, looking like a bird of paradise that had been out all night        
\par in the rain, she flitted out of the room, leaving a faint odour of          
\par frangi-pani. Then he lit a cigarette, and flung himself down on the         
\par sofa.                                                                       
\par   "Never marry a woman with straw-coloured hair, Dorian," he said,          
\par after a few puffs.                                                          
\par   "Why, Harry?"                                                             
\par   "Because they are so sentimental."                                        
\par   "But I like sentimental people."                                          
\par   "Never marry at all, Dorian. Men marry because they are tired; women      
\par because they are curious: both are disappointed."                           
\par   "I don't think I am likely to marry, Harry. I am too much in love.        
\par That is one of your aphorisms. I am putting it into practice, as I          
\par do everything that you say."                                                
\par   "Who are you in love with?" asked Lord Henry, after a pause.              
\par   "With an actress," said Dorian Gray, blushing.                            
\par   Lord Henry shrugged his shoulders. "That is a rather commonplace          
\par debut."                                                                     
\par   "You would not say so if you saw her, Harry."                             
\par   "Who is she?"                                                             
\par   "Her name is Sibyl Vane."                                                 
\par   "Never heard of her."                                                     
\par   "No one has. People will some day, however. She is a genius."             
\par   "My dear boy, no woman is a genius. Women are a decorative sex. They      
\par never have anything to say, but they say it charmingly. Women               
\par represent the triumph of matter over mind, just as men represent the        
\par triumph of mind over morals."                                               
\par   "Harry, how can you?"                                                     
\par   "My dear Dorian, it is quite true. I am analyzing women at                
\par present, so I ought to know. The subject is not so abstruse as I            
\par thought it was. I find that, ultimately, there are only two kinds of        
\par women, the plain and the coloured. The plain women are very useful. If      
\par you want to gain a reputation for respectability, you have merely to        
\par take them down to supper. The other women are very charming. They           
\par commit one mistake, however. They paint in order to try and look            
\par young. Our grandmothers painted in order to try and talk                    
\par brilliantly. Rouge and esprit used to go together. That is all over         
\par now. As long as a woman can look ten years younger than her own             
\par daughter, she is perfectly satisfied. As for conversation, there are        
\par only five women in London worth talking to and two of these can't be        
\par admitted into decent society. However, tell me about your genius.           
\par How long have you known her?"                                               
\par   "Ah! Harry, your views terrify me."                                       
\par   "Never mind that. How long have you known her?"                           
\par   "About three weeks."                                                      
\par   "And where did you come across her?"                                      
\par   "I will tell you, Harry; but you mustn't be unsympathetic about           
\par it. After all, it never would have happened if I had not met you.           
\par You filled me with a wild desire to know everything about life. For         
\par days after I met you, something seemed to throb in my veins. As I           
\par lounged in the Park, or strolled down Piccadilly, I used to look at         
\par every one who passed me, and wonder, with a mad curiosity, what sort        
\par of lives they led. Some of them fascinated me. Others filled me with        
\par terror. There was an exquisite poison in the air. I had a passion           
\par for sensations.... Well, one evening about seven o'clock, I determined      
\par to go out in search of some adventure. I felt that this grey,               
\par monstrous London of ours, with its myriads of people, its sordid            
\par sinners, and its splendid sins, as you once phrased it, must have           
\par something in store for me. I fancied a thousand things. The mere            
\par danger gave me a sense of delight. I remembered what you had said to        
\par me on that wonderful evening when we first dined together, about the        
\par search for beauty being the real secret of life. I don't know what I        
\par expected, but I went out and wandered eastward, soon losing my way          
\par in a labyrinth of grimy streets and black, grassless squares. About         
\par half-past eight I passed by an absurd little theatre, with great            
\par flaring gas-jets and gaudy playbills. A hideous Jew, in the most            
\par amazing waistcoat I ever beheld in my life, was standing at the             
\par entrance, smoking a vile cigar. He had greasy ringlets, and an              
\par enormous diamond blazed in the centre of a soiled shirt. 'Have a            
\par box, My Lord?' he said, when he saw me, and he took off his hat with        
\par an air of gorgeous servility. There was something about him, Harry,         
\par that amused me. He was such a monster. You will laugh at me, I know,        
\par but I really went in and paid a whole guinea for the stage-box. To the      
\par present day I can't make out why I did so; and yet if I hadn't- my          
\par dear Harry, if I hadn't, I should have missed the greatest romance          
\par of my life. I see you are laughing. It is horrid of you!"                   
\par   "I am not laughing, Dorian; at least I am not laughing at you. But        
\par you should not say the greatest romance of your life. You should say        
\par the first romance of your life. You will always be loved, and you will      
\par always be in love with love. A grande passion is the privilege of           
\par people who have nothing to do. That is the one use of the idle classes      
\par of a country. Don't be afraid. There are exquisite things in store for      
\par you. This is merely the beginning."                                         
\par   "Do you think my nature so shallow?" cried Dorian Gray, angrily.          
\par   "No; I think your nature so deep."                                        
\par   "How do you mean?"                                                        
\par   "My dear boy, the people who love only once in their lives are            
\par really the shallow people. What they call their loyalty, and their          
\par fidelity, I call either the lethargy of custom or their lack of             
\par imagination. Faithfulness is to the emotional life what consistency is      
\par to the life of the intellect- simply a confession of failure.               
\par Faithfulness! I must analyze it some day. The passion for property          
\par is in it. There are many things that we would throw away if we were         
\par not afraid that others might pick them up. But I don't want to              
\par interrupt you. Go on with your story."                                      
\par   "Well, I found myself seated in a horrid little private box, with         
\par a vulgar drop-scene staring me in the face. I looked out from behind        
\par the curtain, and surveyed the house. It was a tawdry affair, all            
\par Cupids and cornucopias, like a third-rate wedding-cake. The gallery         
\par and pit were fairly full, but the two rows of dingy stalls were             
\par quite empty, and there was hardly a person in what I suppose they           
\par called the dress-circle. Women went about with oranges and                  
\par ginger-beer, and there was a terrible consumption of nuts going on."        
\par   "It must have been just like the palmy days of the British Drama."        
\par   "Just like, I should fancy, and very depressing. I began to wonder        
\par what on earth I should do, when I caught sight of the play-bill.            
\par What do you think the play was, Harry?"                                     
\par   "I should think 'The Idiot Boy, or Dumb but Innocent.' Our fathers        
\par used to like that sort of piece, I believe. The longer I live, Dorian,      
\par the more keenly I feel that whatever was good enough for our fathers        
\par is not good enough for us. In art, as in politics, les grandperes           
\par ont toujours tort."                                                         
\par   "This play was good enough for us, Harry. It was 'Romeo and Juliet.'      
\par I must admit I was rather annoyed at the idea of seeing Shakespeare         
\par done in such a wretched hole of a place. Still, I felt interested,          
\par in a sort of way. At any rate, I determined to wait for the first act.      
\par There was a dreadful orchestra, presided over by a young Hebrew who         
\par sat at a cracked piano, that nearly drove me away, but at last the          
\par drop-scene was drawn up, and the play began. Romeo was a stout elderly      
\par gentleman, with corked eyebrows, a husky tragedy voice, and a figure        
\par like a beer-barrel. Mercutio was almost as bad. He was played by the        
\par low-comedian, who had introduced gags of his own and was on most            
\par friendly terms with the pit. They were both as grotesque as the             
\par scenery, and that looked as if it had come out of a country-booth. But      
\par Juliet! Harry, imagine a girl, hardly seventeen years of age, with a        
\par little flower-like face, a small Greek head with plaited coils of           
\par dark-brown hair, eyes that were violet wells of passion, lips that          
\par were like the petals of a rose. She was the loveliest thing I had ever      
\par seen in my life. You said to me once that pathos left you unmoved, but      
\par that beauty, mere beauty, could fill your eyes with tears. I tell you,      
\par Harry, I could hardly see this girl for the mist of tears that came         
\par across me. And her voice- I never heard such a voice. It was very           
\par low at first, with deep mellow notes, that seemed to fall singly            
\par upon one's ear. Then it became a little louder, and sounded like a          
\par flute or a distant haut-bois. In the garden-scene it had all the            
\par tremulous ecstasy that one hears just before dawn when nightingales         
\par are singing. There was moments, later on, when it had the wild passion      
\par of violins. You know how a voice can stir one. Your voice and the           
\par voice of Sibyl Vane are two things that I shall never forget. When I        
\par close my eyes, I hear them, and each of them says something different.      
\par I don't know which to follow. Why should I not love her? Harry, I do        
\par love her. She is everything to me in life. Night after night I go to        
\par see her play. One evening she is Rosalind, and the next evening- she        
\par is Imogen. I have seen her die in the gloom of an Italian tomb,             
\par sucking the poison from her lover's lips. I have watched her wandering      
\par through the forest of Arden, disguised as a pretty boy in hose and          
\par doublet and dainty cap. She has been mad, and has come into the             
\par presence of a guilty king, and given him rue to wear, and bitter herbs      
\par to taste of. She has been innocent, and the black hands of jealousy         
\par have crushed her reed-like throat. I have seen her in every age and in      
\par every costume. Ordinary women never appeal to one's imagination.            
\par They are limited to their century. No glamour ever transfigures             
\par them. One knows their minds as easily as one knows their bonnets.           
\par One can always find them. There is no mystery in any of them: they          
\par ride in the Park in the morning, and chatter at tea-parties in the          
\par afternoon. They have their stereotyped smile, and their fashionable         
\par manner. They are quite obvious. But an actress! How different an            
\par actress is! Harry! why didn't you tell me that the only thing worth         
\par loving is an actress?"                                                      
\par   "Because I have loved so many of them, Dorian."                           
\par   "Oh, yes, horrid people with dyed hair and painted faces."                
\par   "Don't run down dyed hair and painted faces. There is an                  
\par extraordinary charm in them, sometimes," said Lord Henry.                   
\par   "I wish now I had not told you about Sibyl Vane."                         
\par   "You could not have helped telling me, Dorian. All through your life      
\par you will tell me everything you do."                                        
\par   "Yes, Harry, I believe that is true, I cannot help telling you            
\par things. You have a curious influence over me. If I ever did a crime, I      
\par would come and confess it to you. You would understand me."                 
\par   "People like you- the wilful sunbeams of life- don't commit               
\par crimes, Dorian. But I am much obliged for the compliment, all the           
\par same. And now tell me- reach me the matches, like a good boy: thanks:-      
\par what are your actual relations with Sibyl Vane?"                            
\par   Dorian Gray leaped to his feet, with flushed cheeks and burning           
\par eyes. "Harry! Sibyl Vane is sacred!"                                        
\par   "It is only the sacred things that are worth touching, Dorian," said      
\par Lord Henry, with a strange touch of pathos in his voice. "But why           
\par should you be annoyed? I suppose she will belong to you some day. When      
\par one is in love, one always begins by deceiving one's self, and one          
\par always ends by deceiving others. That is what the world calls a             
\par romance. You know her, at any rate, I suppose?"                             
\par   "Of course I know her. On the first night I was at the theatre,           
\par the horrid old Jew came round to the box after the performance was          
\par over, and offered to take me behind the scenes and introduce me to          
\par her. I was furious with him, and told him that Juliet had been dead         
\par for hundreds of years, and that her body was lying in a marble tomb in      
\par Verona. I think, from his blank look of amazement, that he was under        
\par the impression that I had taken too much champagne, or something."          
\par   "I am not surprised."                                                     
\par   "Then he asked me if I wrote for any of the newspapers. I told him I      
\par never even read them. He seemed terribly disappointed at that, and          
\par confided to me that all the dramatic critics were in a conspiracy           
\par against him, and that they were every one of them to be bought."            
\par   "I should not wonder if he was quite right there. But, on the             
\par other hand, judging from their appearance, most of them cannot be at        
\par all expensive."                                                             
\par   "Well, he seemed to think they were beyond his means," laughed            
\par Dorian. "By this time, however, the lights were being put out in the        
\par theatre, and I had to go. He wanted me to try some cigars that he           
\par strongly recommended. I declined. The next night, of course, I arrived      
\par at the place again. When he saw me he made a low bow, and assured me        
\par that I was a munificent patron of art. He was a most offensive              
\par brute, though he had an extraordinary passion for Shakespeare. He told      
\par me once, with an air of pride, that his five bankruptcies were              
\par entirely due to 'The Bard,' as he insisted on calling him. He seemed        
\par to think it a distinction."                                                 
\par   "It was a distinction, my dear Dorian- a great distinction. Most          
\par people become bankrupt through having invested too heavily in the           
\par prose of life. To have ruined one's self over poetry is an honour. But      
\par when did you first speak to Miss Sibyl Vane?"                               
\par   "The third night. She had been playing Rosalind. I could not help         
\par going round. I had thrown her some flowers, and she had looked at           
\par me; at least I fancied that she had. The old Jew was persistent. He         
\par seemed determined to take me behind, so I consented. It was curious my      
\par not wanting to know her, wasn't it?"                                        
\par   "No; I don't think so."                                                   
\par   "My dear Harry, why?"                                                     
\par   "I will tell you some other time. Now I want to know about the            
\par girl."                                                                      
\par   "Sibyl? Oh, she was so shy, and so gentle. There is something of a        
\par child about her. Her eyes opened wide in exquisite wonder when I            
\par told her what I thought of her performance, and she seemed quite            
\par unconscious of her power. I think we were both rather nervous. The old      
\par Jew stood grinning at the doorway of the dusty greenroom, making            
\par elaborate speeches about us both, while we stood looking at each other      
\par like children. He would insist on calling me 'My Lord,' so I had to         
\par assure Sibyl that I was not anything of the kind. She said quite            
\par simply to me, 'You look more like a prince. I must call you Prince          
\par Charming.'"                                                                 
\par   "Upon my word, Dorian, Miss Sibyl knows how to pay compliments."          
\par   "You don't understand her, Harry. She regarded me merely as a person      
\par in a play. She knows nothing of life. She lives with her mother, a          
\par faded tired woman who played Lady Capulet in a sort of magenta              
\par dressing-wrapper on the first night, and looks as if she had seen           
\par better days."                                                               
\par   "I know that look. It depresses me," murmured Lord Henry,                 
\par examining his rings.                                                        
\par   "The Jew wanted to tell me her history, but I said it did not             
\par interest me."                                                               
\par   "You were quite right. There is always something infinitely mean          
\par about other people's tragedies."                                            
\par   "Sibyl is the only thing I care about. What is it to me where she         
\par came from? From her little head to her little feet, she is                  
\par absolutely and entirely divine. Every night of my life I go to see her      
\par act, and every night she is more marvellous."                               
\par   "That is the reason, I suppose, that you never dine with me now. I        
\par thought you must have some curious romance on hand. You have; but it        
\par is not quite what I expected."                                              
\par   "My dear Harry, we either lunch or sup together every day, and I          
\par have been to the Opera with you several times," said Dorian, opening        
\par his blue eyes in wonder.                                                    
\par   "You always come dreadfully late."                                        
\par   "Well, I can't help going to see Sibyl play," he cried, "even if          
\par it is only for a single act. I get hungry for her presence; and when I      
\par think of the wonderful soul that is hidden away in that little ivory        
\par body, I am filled with awe."                                                
\par   "You can dine with me to-night, Dorian, can't you?"                       
\par   He shook his head. "To-night she is Imogen," he answered, "and            
\par to-morrow night she will be Juliet."                                        
\par   "When is she Sibyl Vane?"                                                 
\par   "Never."                                                                  
\par   "I congratulate you."                                                     
\par   "How horrid you are! She is all the great heroines of the world in        
\par one. She is more than an individual. You laugh, but I tell you she has      
\par genius. I love her, and I must make her love me. You, who know all the      
\par secrets of life, tell me how to charm Sibyl Vane to love me! I want to      
\par make Romeo jealous. I want the dead lovers of the world to hear our         
\par laughter, and grow sad. I want a breath of our passion to stir their        
\par dust into consciousness, to wake their ashes into pain. My God, Harry,      
\par how I worship her!" He was walking up and down the room as he spoke.        
\par Hectic spots of red burned on his cheeks. He was terribly excited.          
\par   Lord Henry watched him with a subtle sense of pleasure. How               
\par different he was now from the shy, frightened boy he had met in             
\par Basil Hallward's studio! His nature had developed like a flower, had        
\par borne blossoms of scarlet flame. Out of its secret hiding-place had         
\par crept his Soul, and Desire had come to meet it on the way.                  
\par   "And what do you propose to do?" said Lord Henry, at last.                
\par   "I want you and Basil to come with me some night and see her act.         
\par I have not the slightest fear of the result. You are certain to             
\par acknowledge her genius. Then we must get her out of the Jew's hands.        
\par She is bound to him for three years- at least for two years and             
\par eight months- from the present time. I shall have to pay him                
\par something, of course. When all that is settled, I shall take a West         
\par End theatre and bring her out properly. She will make the world as mad      
\par as she has made me."                                                        
\par   "That would be impossible, my dear boy."                                  
\par   "Yes, she will. She has not merely art, consummate art-instinct,          
\par in her but she has personality also; and you have often told me that        
\par it is personalities, not principles, that move the age."                    
\par   "Well, what night shall we go?"                                           
\par   "Let me see. To-day is Tuesday. Let us fix to-morrow. She plays           
\par Juliet to-morrow."                                                          
\par   "All right. The Bristol at eight o'clock; and I will get Basil."          
\par   "Not eight, Harry, please. Half-past six. We must be there before         
\par the curtain rises. You must see her in the first act, where she             
\par meets Romeo."                                                               
\par   "Half-past six! What an hour! It will be like having a meat-tea,          
\par or reading an English novel. It must be seven. No gentleman dines           
\par before seven. Shall you see Basil between this and then? Or shall I         
\par write to him?"                                                              
\par   "Dear Basil! I have not laid eyes on him for a week. It is rather         
\par horrid of me, as he has sent me my portrait in the most wonderful           
\par frame, specially designed by himself, and, though I am a little             
\par jealous of the picture for being a whole month younger than I am, I         
\par must admit that I delight in it. Perhaps you had better write to            
\par him. I don't want to see him alone. He says things that annoy me. He        
\par gives me good advice."                                                      
\par   Lord Henry smiled. "People are very fond of giving away what they         
\par need most themselves. It is what I call the depth of generosity."           
\par   "Oh, Basil is the best of fellows, but he seems to me to be just a        
\par bit of a Philistine. Since I have known you, Harry, I have                  
\par discovered that."                                                           
\par   "Basil, my dear boy, puts everything that is charming in him into         
\par his work. The consequence is that he has nothing left for life but his      
\par prejudices, his principles, and his common sense. The only artists I        
\par have ever known, who are personally delightful, are bad artists.            
\par Good artists exist simply in what they make, and consequently are           
\par perfectly uninteresting in what they are. A great poet, a really great      
\par poet, is the most unpoetical of all creatures. But inferior poets           
\par are absolutely fascinating. The worse their rhymes are, the more            
\par picturesque they look. The mere fact of having published a book of          
\par second-rate sonnets makes a man quite irresistible. He lives the            
\par poetry that he cannot write. The others write the poetry that they          
\par dare not realize."                                                          
\par   "I wonder is that really so, Harry?" said Dorian Gray, putting            
\par some perfume on his handkerchief out of a large gold-topped bottle          
\par that stood on the table. "It must be, if you say it. And now I'm            
\par off. Imogen is waiting for me. Don't forget about to-morrow.                
\par Good-bye."                                                                  
\par   As he left the room Lord Henry's heavy eyelids drooped, and he began      
\par to think. Certainly few people had ever interested him so much as           
\par Dorian Gray, and yet the lad's mad adoration of some one else caused        
\par him not the slightest pang of annoyance or jealousy. He was pleased by      
\par it. It made him a more interesting study. He had always been                
\par enthralled by the methods of natural science, but the ordinary subject      
\par matter of that science had seemed to him trivial and of no import. And      
\par so he had begun by vivisecting himself, as he had ended by vivisecting      
\par others. Human life- that appeared to him the one thing worth                
\par investigating. Compared to it there was nothing else of any value.          
\par It was true that as one watched life in its curious crucible of pain        
\par and pleasure, one could not wear over one's face a mask of glass,           
\par nor keep the sulphurous fumes from troubling the brain and making           
\par the imagination turbid with monstrous fancies and misshapen dreams.         
\par There were poisons so subtle that to know their properties one had          
\par to sicken of them. There were maladies so strange that one had to pass      
\par through them if one sought to understand their nature. And, yet,            
\par what a great reward one received! How wonderful the whole world became      
\par to one! To note the curious hard logic of passion, and the emotional        
\par coloured life of the intellect- to observe where they met, and where        
\par they separated, at what point they were in unison, and at what point        
\par they were at discord- there was a delight in that. What matter what         
\par the cost was? One could never pay too high a price for any sensation.       
\par   He was conscious- and the thought brought a gleam of pleasure into        
\par his brown agate eyes- that it was through certain words of his,             
\par musical words said with musical utterance, that Dorian Gray's soul had      
\par turned to this white girl and bowed in worship before her. To a             
\par large extent the lad was his own creation. He had made him                  
\par premature. That was something. Ordinary people waited till life             
\par disclosed to them its secrets, but to the few, to the elect, the            
\par mysteries of life were revealed before the veil was drawn away.             
\par Sometimes this was the effect of art, and chiefly of the art of             
\par literature, which dealt immediately with the passions and the               
\par intellect. But now and then a complex personality took the place and        
\par assumed the office of art, was indeed, in its way, a real work of art,      
\par Life having its elaborate masterpieces, just as poetry has, or              
\par sculpture, or painting.                                                     
\par   Yes, the lad was premature. He was gathering his harvest while it         
\par was yet spring. The pulse and passion of youth were in him, but he was      
\par becoming self-conscious. It was delightful to watch him. With his           
\par beautiful face, and his beautiful soul, he was a thing to wonder at.        
\par It was no matter how it all ended, or was destined to end. He was like      
\par one of those gracious figures in a pageant or a play, whose joys            
\par seem to be remote from one, but whose sorrows stir one's sense of           
\par beauty, and whose wounds are like red roses.                                
\par   Soul and body, body and soul- how mysterious they were! There was         
\par animalism in the soul, and the body had its moments of spirituality.        
\par The senses could refine, and the intellect could degrade. Who could         
\par say where the fleshly impulse ceased, or the psychical impulse              
\par began? How shallow were the arbitrary definitions of ordinary               
\par psychologists! And yet how difficult to decide between the claims of        
\par the various schools! Was the soul a shadow seated in the house of sin?      
\par Or was the body really in the soul, as Giordano Bruno thought? The          
\par separation of spirit from matter was a mystery, and the union of            
\par spirit with matter was a mystery also.                                      
\par    He began to wonder whether we could ever make psychology so              
\par absolute a science that each little spring of life would be revealed        
\par to us. As it was, we always misunderstood ourselves, and rarely             
\par understood others. Experience was of no ethical value. It was merely        
\par the name men gave to their mistakes. Moralists had, as a rule,              
\par regarded it as a mode of warning, had claimed for it a certain ethical      
\par efficacy in the formation of character, had praised it as something         
\par that taught us what to follow and showed us what to avoid. But there        
\par was no motive power in experience. It was as little of an active cause      
\par as conscience itself. All that it really demonstrated was that our          
\par future would be the same as our past, and that the sin we had done          
\par once, and with loathing, we would do many times, and with joy.              
\par   It was clear to him that the experimental method was the only method      
\par by which one could arrive at any scientific analysis of the                 
\par passions; and certainly Dorian Gray was a subject made to his hand,         
\par and seemed to promise rich and fruitful results. His sudden mad love        
\par for Sibyl Vane was a psychological phenomenon of no small interest.         
\par There was no doubt that curiosity had much to do with it, curiosity         
\par and the desire for new experiences; yet it was not a simple but rather      
\par a very complex passion. What there was in it of the purely sensuous         
\par instinct of boyhood had been transformed by the workings of the             
\par imagination, changed into something that seemed to the lad himself          
\par to be remote from sense, and was for that very reason all the more          
\par dangerous. It was the passions about whose origin we deceived               
\par ourselves that tyrannized most strongly over us. Our weakest motives        
\par were those of whose nature we were conscious. It often happened that        
\par when we thought we were experimenting on others we were really              
\par experimenting on ourselves.                                                 
\par   While Lord Henry sat dreaming on these things, a knock came to the        
\par door, and his valet entered, and reminded him it was time to dress for      
\par dinner. He got up and looked out into the street. The sunset had            
\par smitten into scarlet gold the upper windows of the houses opposite.         
\par The panes glowed like plates of heated metal. The sky above was like a      
\par faded rose. He thought of his friend's young fiery-coloured life,           
\par and wondered how it was all going to end.                                   
\par   When he arrived home, about half-past twelve o'clock, he saw a            
\par telegram lying on the hall table. He opened it, and found it was            
\par from Dorian Gray. It was to tell him that he was engaged to be married      
\par to Sibyl Vane.                                                              
