\par                               CHAPTER V                                     
\par -                                                                           
\par   "Mother, mother, I am so happy!" whispered the girl, burying her          
\par face in the lap of the faded, tired-looking woman who, with back            
\par turned to the shrill intrusive light, was sitting in the one arm-chair      
\par that their dingy sitting-room contained. "I am so happy!" she               
\par repeated, "and you must be happy too!"                                      
\par   Mrs. Vane winced, and put her thin bismuth-whitened hands on her          
\par daughter's head. "Happy!" she echoed, "I am only happy, Sibyl, when         
\par I see you act. You must not think of anything but your acting. Mr.          
\par Isaacs has been very good to us, and we owe him money."                     
\par   The girl looked up and pouted. "Money, mother?" she cried. "What          
\par does money matter? Love is more than money."                                
\par   "Mr. Isaacs has advanced us fifty pounds to pay off our debts, and        
\par to get a proper outfit for James. You must not forget that, Sibyl.          
\par Fifty pounds is a very large sum. Mr. Isaacs has been most                  
\par considerate."                                                               
\par   "He is not a gentleman, mother, and I hate the way he talks to            
\par me," said the girl, rising to her feet, and going over to the window.       
\par   "I don't know how we could manage without him," answered the elder        
\par woman, querulously.                                                         
\par   Sibyl Vane tossed her head and laughed. "We don't want him any more,      
\par mother. Prince Charming rules life for us now." Then she paused. A          
\par rose shook in her blood, and shadowed her cheeks. Quick breaths parted      
\par the petals of her lips. They trembled. Some southern wind of passion        
\par swept over her, and stirred the dainty folds of her dress. "I love          
\par him," she said, simply,.                                                    
\par   "Foolish child! foolish child!" was the parrot-phrase flung in            
\par answer. The waving of crooked, false-jewelled fingers gave                  
\par grotesqueness to the words.                                                 
\par   The girl laughed again. The joy of a caged bird was in her voice.         
\par Her eyes caught the melody and echoed it in radiance: then closed           
\par for a moment, as though to hide their secret. When they opened, the         
\par mist of a dream had passed across them.                                     
\par   Thin-lipped wisdom spoke at her from the worn chair, hinted at            
\par prudence, quoted from that book of cowardice whose author apes the          
\par name of common sense. She did not listen. She was free in her prison        
\par of passion. Her prince, Prince Charming, was with her. She had              
\par called on Memory to remake him. She had sent her soul to search for         
\par him, and it had brought him back. His kiss burned again upon her            
\par mouth. Her eyelids were warm with his breath.                               
\par   Then Wisdom altered its method and spoke of espial and discovery.         
\par This young man might be rich. If so, marriage should be thought of.         
\par Against the shell of her ear broke the waves of worldly cunning. The        
\par arrows of craft shot by her. She saw the thin lips moving, and smiled.      
\par   Suddenly she felt the need to speak. The wordy silence troubled her.      
\par "Mother, mother," she cried, "why does he love me so much? I know           
\par why I love him. I love him because he is like what Love himself should      
\par be. But what does he see in me? I am not worthy of him. And yet-            
\par why, I cannot tell- though I feel so much beneath him, I don't feel         
\par humble. I feel proud, terribly proud. Mother, did you love my father        
\par as I love Prince Charming?"                                                 
\par   The elder woman grew pale beneath the coarse powder that daubed           
\par her cheeks, and her dry lips twitched with a spasm of pain. Sibyl           
\par rushed to her, flung her arms round her neck, and kissed her. "Forgive      
\par me, mother. I know it pains you to talk about our father. But it            
\par only pains you because you loved him so much. Don't look so sad. I          
\par am as happy to-day as you were twenty years ago. Ah! let me be happy        
\par forever!"                                                                   
\par   "My child, you are far too young to think of falling in love.             
\par Besides, what do you know of this young man. You don't even know his        
\par name. The whole thing is most inconvenient, and really, when James          
\par is going away to Australia, and I have so much to think of, I must say      
\par that you should have shown more consideration. However, as I said           
\par before, if he is rich..."                                                   
\par   "Ah! mother, mother, let me be happy!"                                    
\par   Mrs. Vane glanced at her, and with one of those false theatrical          
\par gestures that so often become a mode of second nature to a                  
\par stage-player, clasped her in her arms. At this moment the door opened,      
\par and a young lad with rough brown hair came into the room. He was            
\par thick-set of figure, and his hands and feet were large, and somewhat        
\par clumsy in movement. He was not so finely bred as his sister. One would      
\par hardly have guessed the close relationship that existed between             
\par them. Mrs. Vane fixed her eyes on him, and intensified her smile.           
\par She mentally elevated her son to the dignity of an audience. She            
\par felt sure that the tableau was interesting.                                 
\par   "You might keep some of your kisses for me, Sibyl, I think," said         
\par the lad, with a good-natured grumble.                                       
\par   "Ah! but you don't like being kissed, Jim," she cried. "You are a         
\par dreadful old bear." And she ran across the room and hugged him.             
\par   James Vane looked into his sister's face with tenderness. "I want         
\par you to come out with me for a walk, Sibyl. I don't suppose I shall          
\par ever see this horrid London again. I am sure I don't want to."              
\par   "My son, don't say such dreadful things," murmured Mrs. Vane, taking      
\par up a tawdry theatrical dress, with a sigh, and beginning to patch           
\par it. She felt a little disappointed that he had not joined the group.        
\par It would have increased the theatrical picturesqueness of the               
\par situation.                                                                  
\par   "Why not, mother? I mean it."                                             
\par   "You pain me, my son. I trust you will return from Australia in a         
\par position of affluence. I believe there is no society of any kind in         
\par the Colonies, nothing that I would call society; so when you have made      
\par your fortune you must come back and assert yourself in London."             
\par   "Society!" muttered the lad. "I don't want to know anything about         
\par that. I should like to make some money to take you and Sibyl off the        
\par stage. I hate it."                                                          
\par   "Oh, Jim!" said Sibyl, laughing, "how unkind of you! But are you          
\par really going for a walk with me? That will be nice! I was afraid you        
\par were going to say good-bye to some of your friends- to Tom Hardy,           
\par who gave you that hideous pipe, or Ned Langton, who makes fun of you        
\par for smoking it. It is very sweet of you to let me have your last            
\par afternoon. Where shall we go? Let us go to the Park."                       
\par   "I am too shabby," he answered, frowning. "Only swell people go to        
\par the Park."                                                                  
\par   "Nonsense, Jim," she whispered, stroking the sleeve of his coat.          
\par   He hesitated for a moment. "Very well," he said at last, "but             
\par don't be to long dressing." She danced out of the door. One could hear      
\par her singing as she ran upstairs. Her little feet pattered overhead.         
\par   He walked up and down the room two or three times. Then he turned to      
\par the still figure in the chair. "Mother, are my things ready?" he            
\par asked.                                                                      
\par   "Quite ready, James," she answered, keeping her eyes on her work.         
\par For some months past she had felt ill at ease when she was alone            
\par with this rough, stern son of hers. Her shallow secret nature was           
\par troubled when their eyes met. She used to wonder if he suspected            
\par anything. The silence, for he made no other observation, became             
\par intolerable to her. She began to complain. Women defend themselves          
\par by attacking, just as they attack by sudden and strange surrenders. "I      
\par hope you will be contented, James, with your sea-faring life," she          
\par said. "You must remember that it is your own choice. You might have         
\par entered a solicitor's office. Solicitors are a very respectable class,      
\par and in the country often dine with the best families."                      
\par   "I hate offices, and I hate clerks," he replied. "But you are             
\par quite right. I have chosen my own life. All I say is, watch over            
\par Sibyl. Don't let her come to any harm. Mother, you must watch over          
\par her."                                                                       
\par   "James, you really talk very strangely. Of course I watch over            
\par Sibyl."                                                                     
\par   "I hear a gentleman comes every night to the theatre, and goes            
\par behind to talk to her. Is that right? What about that?"                     
\par   "You are speaking about things you don't understand, James. In the        
\par profession we are accustomed to receive a great deal of most                
\par gratifying attention. I myself used to receive many bouquets at one         
\par time. That was when acting was really understood. As for Sibyl, I do        
\par not know at present whether her attachment is serious or not. But           
\par there is no doubt that the young man in question is a perfect               
\par gentleman. He is always most polite to me. Besides, he has the              
\par appearance of being rich, and the flowers he sends are lovely."             
\par   "You don't know his name, though," said the lad, harshly.                 
\par   "No," answered his mother, with a placid expression in her face. "He      
\par has not yet revealed his real name. I think it is quite romantic of         
\par him. He is probably a member of the aristocracy."                           
\par   James Vane bit his lip. "Watch over Sibyl, mother," he cried, "watch      
\par over her."                                                                  
\par   "My son, you distress me very much. Sibyl is always under my special      
\par care. Of course, if this gentleman is wealthy, there is no reason           
\par why she could not contract an alliance with him. I trust he is one          
\par of the aristocracy. He has all the appearance of it, I must say. It         
\par might be a most brilliant marriage for Sibyl. They would make a             
\par charming couple. His good looks are really quite remarkable; everybody      
\par notices them."                                                              
\par   The lad muttered something to himself, and drummed on the windowpane      
\par with his coarse fingers. He had just turned round to say something,         
\par when the door opened, and Sibyl ran in.                                     
\par   "How serious you both are!" she cried. "What is the matter?"              
\par   "Nothing," he answered. "I suppose one must be serious sometimes.         
\par Good-bye, mother. I will have my dinner at five o'clock. Everything is      
\par packed, except my shirts, so you need not trouble."                         
\par   "Good-bye, my son," she answered, with a bow of strained                  
\par stateliness.                                                                
\par   She was extremely annoyed at the tone he had adopted with her, and        
\par there was something in his look that had made her feel afraid.              
\par   "Kiss me, mother," said the girl. Her flower-like lips touched the        
\par withered cheek, and warmed its frost.                                       
\par   "My child! my child!" cried Mrs. Vane, looking up to the ceiling          
\par in search of an imaginary gallery.                                          
\par   "Come, Sibyl," said her brother, impatiently. He hated his                
\par mother's affectations.                                                      
\par   They went out into the flickering wind-blown sunlight, and                
\par strolled down the dreary Euston Road. The passers-by glanced in wonder      
\par at the sullen, heavy youth, who, in coarse, ill-fitting clothes, was        
\par in the company of such a graceful, refined-looking girl. He was like a      
\par common gardener walking with a rose.                                        
\par   Jim frowned from time to time when he caught the inquisitive              
\par glance of some stranger. He had that dislike of being stared at             
\par which comes on geniuses late in life, and never leaves the                  
\par commonplace. Sibyl, however, was quite unconscious of the effect she        
\par was producing. Her love was trembling in laughter on her lips. She was      
\par thinking of Prince Charming, and, that she might think of him all           
\par the more, she did not talk of him, but prattled on about the ship in        
\par which Jim was going to sail, about the gold he was certain to find,         
\par about the wonderful heiress whose life he was to save from the wicked,      
\par red-shirted bushrangers. For he was not to remain a sailor, or a            
\par super-cargo, or whatever he was going to be. Oh, no! A sailor's             
\par existence was dreadful. Fancy being cooped up in a horrid ship, with        
\par the hoarse, hump-backed waves trying to get in, and a black wind            
\par blowing the masts down, and tearing the sails into long screaming           
\par ribands! He was to leave the vessel at Melbourne, bid a polite              
\par good-bye to the captain, and go off at once to the gold-fields. Before      
\par a week was over he was to come across a large nugget of pure gold, the      
\par largest nugget that had ever been discovered, and bring it down to the      
\par coast in a waggon guarded by six mounted policemen. The bushrangers         
\par were to attack them three times, and be defeated with immense               
\par slaughter. Or, no. He was not to go to the gold-fields at all. They         
\par were horrid places, where men got intoxicated, and shot each other          
\par in bar-rooms, and used bad language. He was to be a nice sheep-farmer,      
\par and one evening, as he was riding home, he was to see the beautiful         
\par heiress being carried off by a robber on a black horse, and give            
\par chase, and rescue her. Of course she would fall in love with him,           
\par and he with her, and they would get married, and come home, and live        
\par in an immense house in London. Yes, there were delightful things in         
\par store for him. But he must be very good, and not lose his temper, or        
\par spend his money foolishly. She was only a year older than he was,           
\par but she knew so much more of life. He must be sure, also, to write          
\par to her by every mail, and to say his prayers each night before he went      
\par to sleep. God was very good, and would watch over him. She would            
\par pray for him too, and in a few years he would come back quite rich and      
\par happy.                                                                      
\par   The lad listened sulkily to her, and made no answer. He was               
\par heart-sick at leaving home.                                                 
\par   Yet it was not this alone that made him gloomy and morose.                
\par Inexperienced though he was, he had still a strong sense of the danger      
\par of Sibyl's position. This young dandy who was making love to her could      
\par mean her no good. He was a gentleman, and he hated him for that, hated      
\par him through some curious race-instinct for which he could not account,      
\par and which for that reason was all the more dominant within him. He was      
\par conscious also of the shallowness and vanity of his mother's nature,        
\par and in that saw infinite peril for Sibyl and Sibyl's happiness.             
\par Children begin by loving their parents; as they grow older they             
\par judge them; sometimes they forgive them.                                    
\par   His mother! He had something on his mind to ask her, something            
\par that he had brooded on for many months of silence. A chance phrase          
\par that he had heard at the theatre, a whispered sneer that had reached        
\par his ears one night as he waited at the stage-door, had set loose a          
\par train of horrible thoughts. He remembered it as if it had been the          
\par lash of a hunting-crop across his face. His brows knit together into a      
\par wedge-like furrow, and with a twitch of pain he bit his under-lip.          
\par   "You are not listening to a word I am saying, Jim," cried Sibyl,          
\par "and I am making the most delightful plans for your future. Do say          
\par something."                                                                 
\par   "What do you want me to say?"                                             
\par   "Oh! that you will be a good boy, and not forget us," she                 
\par answered, smiling at him.                                                   
\par   He shrugged his shoulders. "You are more likely to forget me, than I      
\par am to forget you, Sibyl."                                                   
\par   She flushed. "What do you mean, Jim?" she asked.                          
\par   "You have a new friend, I hear. Who is he? Why have you not told          
\par me about him? He means you no good."                                        
\par   "Stop, Jim!" she exclaimed. "You must not say anything against            
\par him. I love him."                                                           
\par   "Why, you don't even know his name," answered the lad. "Who is he? I      
\par have a right to know."                                                      
\par   "He is called Prince Charming. Don't you like the name? Oh! you           
\par silly boy,! you should never forget it. If you only saw him, you would      
\par think him the most wonderful person in the world. Some day you will         
\par meet him: when you come back from Australia. You will like him so           
\par much. Everybody likes him, and I... love him. I wish you could come to      
\par the theatre to-night. He is going to be there, and I am to play             
\par Juliet. Oh! how I shall play it! Fancy, Jim, to be in love and play         
\par Juliet! To have him sitting there! To play for his delight! I am            
\par afraid I may frighten the company, frighten or enthrall them. To be in      
\par love is to surpass one's self. Poor dreadful Mr. Isaacs will be             
\par shouting 'genius' to his loafers at the bar. He has preached me as a        
\par dogma; to-night he will announce me as a revelation. I feel it. And it      
\par is all his, his only, Prince Charming, my wonderful lover, my god of        
\par graces. But I am poor beside him. Poor? What does that matter? When         
\par poverty creeps in at the door, love flies in through the window. Our        
\par proverbs want re-writing. They were made in winter, and it is summer        
\par now; spring-time for me, I think, a very dance of blossoms in blue          
\par skies."                                                                     
\par   "He is a gentleman," said the lad, sullenly.                              
\par   "A Prince!" she cried, musically. "What more do you want?"                
\par   "He wants to enslave you."                                                
\par   "I shudder at the thought of being free."                                 
\par   "I want you to beware of him."                                            
\par   "To see him is to worship him, to know him is to trust him."              
\par   "Sibyl, you are mad about him."                                           
\par   She laughed, and took his arm. "You dear old Jim, you talk as if you      
\par were a hundred. Some day you will be in love yourself. Then you will        
\par know what it is. Don't look so sulky. Surely you should be glad to          
\par think that, though you are going away, you leave me happier than I          
\par have ever been before. Life has been hard for us both, terribly hard        
\par and difficult. But it will be different now. You are going to a new         
\par world, and I have found one. Here are two chairs; let us sit down           
\par and see the smart people go by."                                            
\par   They took their seats amidst a crowd if watchers. The tulip-beds          
\par across the road flamed like throbbing rings of fire. A white dust,          
\par tremulous cloud of orris-root it seemed, hung in the panting air.           
\par The brightly-coloured parasols danced and dipped like monstrous             
\par butterflies.                                                                
\par   She made her brother talk of himself, his hopes, his prospects. He        
\par spoke slowly and with effort. They passed words to each other as            
\par players at a game pass counters. Sibyl felt pressed. She could not          
\par communicate her joy. A faint smile curving that sullen mouth was all        
\par the echo she could win. After some time she became silent. Suddenly         
\par she caught a glimpse of golden hair and laughing lips, and in an            
\par open carriage with two ladies Dorian Gray drove past.                       
\par   She started to her feet. "There he is!" she cried.                        
\par   "Who?" said Jim Vane.                                                     
\par   "Prince Charming," she answered, looking after the victoria.              
\par   He jumped up, and seized her roughly by the arm. "Show him to me.         
\par Which is he? Point him out. I must see him!" he exclaimed; but at that      
\par moment the Duke of Berwick's four-in-hand came between, and when it         
\par had left the space clear, the carriage had swept out of the Park.           
\par   "He is gone," murmured Sibyl, sadly. "I wish you had seen him."           
\par   "I wish I had, for as sure as there is a God in heaven, if he ever        
\par does you any wrong, I shall kill him."                                      
\par   She looked at him in horror. He repeated his words. They cut the air      
\par like a dagger. The people round began to gape. A lady standing close        
\par to her tittered.                                                            
\par   "Come away, Jim; come away," she whispered. He followed her doggedly      
\par as she passed through the crowd. He felt glad at what he had said.          
\par   When they reached the Achilles Statue she turned round. There was         
\par pity in her eyes that became laughter on her lips. She shook her            
\par head at him. "You are foolish, Jim, utterly foolish; a bad-tempered         
\par boy, that is all. How can you say such horrible things? You don't know      
\par what you are talking about. You are simply jealous and unkind. Ah! I        
\par wish you would fall in love. Love makes people good, and what you said      
\par was wicked."                                                                
\par   "I am sixteen," he answered, "and I know what I am about. Mother          
\par is no help to you. She doesn't understand how to look after you. I          
\par wish now that I was not going to Australia at all. I have a great mind      
\par to chuck the whole thing up. I would, if my articles hadn't been            
\par signed."                                                                    
\par   "Oh, don't be so serious, Jim. You are like one of the heroes of          
\par those silly melodramas mother used to be so fond of acting in. I am         
\par not going to quarrel with you. I have seen him, and oh! to see him          
\par is perfect happiness. We won't quarrel. I know you would never harm         
\par any one I love, would you?"                                                 
\par   "Not as long as you love him, I suppose," was the sullen answer.          
\par   "I shall love him for ever!" she cried.                                   
\par   "And he?"                                                                 
\par   "For ever, too!"                                                          
\par   "He had better."                                                          
\par   She shrank from him. Then she laughed and put her hand on his arm.        
\par He was merely a boy.                                                        
\par   At the Marble Arch they hailed an omnibus, which left them close          
\par to their shabby home in the Euston Road. It was after five o'clock,         
\par and Sibyl had to lie down for a couple of hours before acting. Jim          
\par insisted that she should do so. He said that he would sooner part with      
\par her when their mother was not present. She would be sure to make a          
\par scene, and he detested scenes of every kind.                                
\par   In Sibyl's own room they parted. There was jealousy in the lad's          
\par heart, and a fierce, murderous hatred of the stranger who, as it            
\par seemed to him, had come between them. Yet, when her arms were flung         
\par around his neck, and her fingers strayed through his hair, he               
\par softened, and kissed her with real affection. There were tears in           
\par his eyes as he went downstairs.                                             
\par   His mother was waiting for him below. She grumbled at his                 
\par unpunctuality, as he entered. He made no answer, but sat down to his        
\par meagre meal. The flies buzzed round the table, and crawled over the         
\par stained cloth. Through the rumble of omnibuses, and the clatter of          
\par street-cabs, he could hear the droning voice devouring each minute          
\par that was left to him.                                                       
\par   After some time, he thrust away his plate, and put his head in his        
\par hands. He felt that he had a right to know. It should have been told        
\par to him before, if it was as he suspected. Leaden with fear, his mother      
\par watched him. Words dropped mechanically from her lips. A tattered lace      
\par handkerchief twitched in her fingers. When the clock struck six, he         
\par got up, and went to the door. When he turned back, and looked at            
\par her. Their eyes met. In hers he saw a wild appeal for mercy. It             
\par enraged him.                                                                
\par   "Mother, I have something to ask you," he said. Her eyes wandered         
\par vaguely about the room. She made no answer. "Tell me the truth. I have      
\par a right to know. Were you married to my father?"                            
\par   She heaved a deep sigh. It was a sigh of relief. The terrible             
\par moment, the moment that night and day, for weeks and months, she had        
\par dreaded, had come at last, and yet she felt no terror. Indeed in            
\par some measure it was a disappointment to her. The vulgar directness          
\par of the question called for a direct answer. The situation had not been      
\par gradually led up to. It was crude. It reminded her of a bad rehearsal.      
\par   "No," she answered, wondering at the harsh simplicity of life.            
\par   "My father was a scoundrel then!" cried the lad, clenching his            
\par fists.                                                                      
\par   She shook her head. "I knew he was not free. We loved each other          
\par very much. If he had lived, he would have made provision for us. Don't      
\par speak against him, my son. He was your father, and a gentleman. Indeed      
\par he was highly connected."                                                   
\par   An oath broke from his lips. "I don't care for myself," he                
\par exclaimed, "but don't let Sibyl... It is a gentleman, isn't it, who is      
\par in love with her, or says he is? Highly connected, too, I suppose."         
\par   For a moment a hideous sense of humiliation came over the woman. Her      
\par head drooped. She wiped her eyes with shaking hands. "Sibyl has a           
\par mother," she murmured; "I had none."                                        
\par   The lad was touched. He went towards her, and stooping down he            
\par kissed her. "I am sorry if I have pained you by asking about my             
\par father," he said, "but I could not help it. I must go now. Good-bye.        
\par Don't forget that you will have only one child now to look after,           
\par and believe me that if this man wrongs my sister, I will find out           
\par who he is, track him down, and kill him like a dog. I swear it."            
\par   The exaggerated folly of the threat, the passionate gesture that          
\par accompanied it, the mad melodramatic words, made life seem more             
\par vivid to her. She was familiar with the atmosphere. She breathed            
\par more freely, and for the first time in many months she really               
\par admired her son. She would have liked to have continued the scene on        
\par the same emotional scale, but he cut her short. Trunks had to be            
\par carried down, and mufflers looked for. The lodging-house drudge             
\par bustled in and out. There was the bargaining with the cab-man. The          
\par moment was lost in vulgar details. It was with a renewed feeling of         
\par disappointment that she waved the tattered lace handkerchief from           
\par the window, as her son drove away. She was conscious that a great           
\par opportunity had been wasted. She consoled herself by telling Sibyl how      
\par desolate she felt her life would be, now that she had only one child        
\par to look after. She remembered the phrase. It had pleased her. Of the        
\par threat she said nothing. It was vividly and dramatically expressed.         
\par She felt that they would all laugh at it some day.                          
