\par                               CHAPTER VI                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   "I suppose you have heard the news, Basil?" said Lord Henry that          
\par evening, as Hallward was shown into a little private room at the            
\par Bristol where dinner had been laid for three.                               
\par   "No, Harry," answered the artist, giving his hat and coat to the          
\par bowing waiter. "What is it? Nothing about politics, I hope? They don't      
\par interest me. There is hardly a single person in the House of Commons        
\par worth painting; though many of them would be the better for a little        
\par whitewashing."                                                              
\par   "Dorian Gray is engaged to be married," said Lord Henry, watching         
\par him as he spoke.                                                            
\par   Hallward started, and then frowned. "Dorian engaged to be                 
\par married!" he cried. "Impossible!"                                           
\par   "It is perfectly true."                                                   
\par   "To whom?"                                                                
\par   "To some little actress or other."                                        
\par   "I can't believe it. Dorian is far too sensible."                         
\par   "Dorian is far too wise not to do foolish things now and then, my         
\par dear Basil."                                                                
\par   "Marriage is hardly a thing that one can do now and then, Harry."         
\par   "Except in America," rejoined Lord Henry, languidly. "But I didn't        
\par say he was married. I said he was engaged to be married. There is a         
\par great difference. I have a distinct remembrance of being married,           
\par but I have no recollection at all of being engaged. I am inclined to        
\par think that I never was engaged."                                            
\par   "But think of Dorian's birth, and position, and wealth. It would          
\par be absurd for him to marry so much beneath him."                            
\par   "If you want to make him marry this girl tell him that, Basil. He is      
\par sure to do it, then. Whenever a man does a thoroughly stupid thing, it      
\par is always from the noblest motives."                                        
\par   "I hope the girl is good, Harry. I don't want to see Dorian tied          
\par to some vile creature, who might degrade his nature and ruin his            
\par intellect."                                                                 
\par   "Oh, she is better than good- she is beautiful," murmured Lord            
\par Henry, sipping a glass of vermouth and orange-bitters. "Dorian says         
\par she is beautiful; and he is not often wrong about things of that kind.      
\par Your portrait of him has quickened his appreciation of the personal         
\par appearance of other people. It has had that excellent effect,               
\par amongst others. We are to see her to-night, if that boy doesn't forget      
\par his appointment."                                                           
\par   "Are you serious?"                                                        
\par   "Quite serious, Basil. I should be miserable if I thought I should        
\par ever be more serious than I am at the present moment."                      
\par   "But do you approve of it, Harry?" asked the painter, walking up and      
\par down the room, and biting his lip. "You can't approve of it, possibly.      
\par It is some silly infatuation."                                              
\par   "I never approve, or disapprove, of anything now. It is an absurd         
\par attitude to take towards life. We are not sent into the world to air        
\par our moral prejudices. I never take any notice of what common people         
\par say, and I never interfere with what charming people do. If a               
\par personality fascinates me, whatever mode of expression that                 
\par personality selects is absolutely delightful to me. Dorian Gray             
\par falls in love with a beautiful girl who acts Juliet, and proposes to        
\par marry her. Why not? If he wedded Messalina he would be none the less        
\par interesting. You know I am not a champion of marriage. The real             
\par drawback to marriage is that it makes one unselfish. And unselfish          
\par people are colourless. They lack individuality. Still, there are            
\par certain temperaments that marriage makes more complex. They retain          
\par their egotism, and add to it many other egos. They are forced to            
\par have more than one life. They become highly organized, and to be            
\par highly organized is, I should fancy, the object of man's existence.         
\par Besides, every experience is of value, and, whatever one may say            
\par against marriage, it is certainly an experience. I hope that Dorian         
\par Gray will make this girl his wife, passionately adore her for six           
\par months, and then suddenly become fascinated by some one else. He would      
\par be a wonderful study."                                                      
\par   "You don't mean a single word of all that, Harry; you know you            
\par don't. If Dorian Gray's life were spoiled, no one would be sorrier          
\par than yourself. You are much better than you pretend to be."                 
\par   Lord Henry laughed. "The reason we all like to think so well of           
\par others is that we are all afraid for ourselves. The basis of                
\par optimism is sheer terror. We think that we are generous because we          
\par credit our neighbour with the possession of those virtues that are          
\par likely to be a benefit to us. We praise the banker that we may              
\par overdraw our account, and find good qualities in the highwayman in the      
\par hope that he may spare our pockets. I mean everything that I have           
\par said. I have the greatest contempt for optimism. As for a spoiled           
\par life, no life is spoiled but one whose growth is arrested. If you want      
\par to mar a nature, you have merely to reform it. As for marriage, of          
\par course that would be silly, but there are other and more interesting        
\par bonds between men and women. I will certainly encourage them. They          
\par have the charm of being fashionable. But here is Dorian himself. He         
\par will tell you more than I can."                                             
\par   "My dear Harry, my dear Basil, you must both congratulate me!"            
\par said the lad, throwing off his evening cape with its satin-lined            
\par wings, and shaking each of his friends by the hand in turn. "I have         
\par never been so happy. Of course it is sudden: all really delightful          
\par things are. And yet it seems to me to be the one thing I have been          
\par looking for all my life." He was flushed with excitement and pleasure,      
\par and looked extraordinarily handsome.                                        
\par   "I hope you will always be very happy, Dorian," said Hallward,            
\par "but I don't quite forgive you for not having let me know of your           
\par engagement. You let Harry know."                                            
\par   "And I don't forgive you for being late for dinner," broke in Lord        
\par Henry, putting his hand on the lad's shoulder, and smiling as he            
\par spoke. "Come, let us sit down and try what the new chef here is             
\par like, and then you will tell us how it all came about."                     
\par   "There is really not much to tell," cried Dorian, as they took their      
\par seats at the small round table. "What happened was simply this.             
\par After I left you yesterday evening, Harry, I dressed, had some              
\par dinner at that little Italian restaurant in Rupert Street, you              
\par introduced me to, and went down at eight o'clock to the theatre. Sibyl      
\par was playing Rosalind. Of course the scenery was dreadful, and the           
\par Orlando absurd. But Sibyl! You should have seen her! When she came          
\par on in her boy's clothes she was perfectly wonderful. She wore a             
\par moss-coloured velvet jerkin with cinnamon sleeves, slim brown               
\par cross-gartered hose, a dainty little green cap with a hawk's feather        
\par caught in a jewel, and a hooded cloak lined with dull red. She had          
\par never seemed to me more exquisite. She had all the delicate grace of        
\par that Tanagra figurine that you have in your studio, Basil. Her hair         
\par clustered round her face like dark leaves round a pale rose. As for         
\par her acting- well, you shall see her to-night. She is simply a born          
\par artist. I sat in the dingy box absolutely enthralled. I forgot that         
\par I was in London and in the nineteenth century. I was away with my love      
\par in a forest that no man had ever seen. After the performance was            
\par over I went behind, and spoke to her. As we were sitting together,          
\par suddenly there came into her eyes a look that I had never seen there        
\par before. My lips moved toward hers. We kissed each other. I can't            
\par describe to you what I felt at that moment. It seemed to me that all        
\par my life had been narrowed to one perfect point of rose-coloured joy.        
\par She trembled all over, and shook like a white narcissus. Then she           
\par flung herself on her knees and kissed my hands. I feel that I should        
\par not tell you all this, but I can't help it. Of course our engagement        
\par is a dead secret. She has not even told her own mother. I don't know        
\par what my guardian will say. Lord Radley is sure to be furious. I             
\par don't care. I shall be of age in less than a year, and then I can do        
\par what I like. I have been right, Basil, haven't I, to take my love           
\par out of poetry, and to find my wife in Shakespeare's plays? Lips that        
\par Shakespeare taught to speak have whispered their secret in my ear. I        
\par have had the arms of Rosalind around me, and kissed Juliet on the           
\par mouth."                                                                     
\par   "Yes, Dorian, I suppose you were right," said Hallward, slowly.           
\par   "Have you seen her to-day?" asked Lord Henry.                             
\par   Dorian Gray shook his head. "I left her in the forest of Arden, I         
\par shall find her in an orchard in Verona."                                    
\par   Lord Henry sipped his champagne in a meditative manner. "At what          
\par particular point did you mention the word marriage, Dorian? And what        
\par did she say in answer? Perhaps you forgot all about it."                    
\par   "My dear Harry, I did not treat it as a business transaction, and         
\par I did not make any formal proposal. I told her that I loved her, and        
\par she said she was not worthy to be my wife. Not worthy! Why, the             
\par whole world is nothing to me compared with her."                            
\par   "Women are wonderfully practical," murmured Lord Henry, "much more        
\par practical than we are. In situations of that kind we often forget to        
\par say anything about marriage, and they always remind us."                    
\par   Hallward laid his hand upon his arm. "Don't, Harry. You have annoyed      
\par Dorian. He is not like other men. He would never bring misery upon any      
\par one, His nature is too fine for that."                                      
\par   Lord Henry looked across the table. "Dorian is never annoyed with         
\par me," he answered. "I asked the question for the best reason                 
\par possible, for the only reason, indeed, that excuses one for asking any      
\par question- simply curiosity. I have a theory that it is always the           
\par women who propose to us, and not we who propose to the women.               
\par Except, of course, in the middle-class life. But then the middle            
\par classes are not modern."                                                    
\par   Dorian Gray laughed, and tossed his head. "You are quite                  
\par incorrigible, Harry; but I don't mind. It is impossible to be angry         
\par with you. When you see Sibyl Vane you will feel that the man who could      
\par wrong her would be a beast, a beast without a heart. I cannot               
\par understand how any one can wish to shame the thing he loves. I love         
\par Sibyl Vane. I want to place her on a pedestal of gold, and to see           
\par the world worship the woman who is mine. What is marriage? An               
\par irrevocable vow. You mock at it for that. Ah! don't mock. It is an          
\par irrevocable vow that I want to take. Her trust makes me faithful,           
\par her belief makes me good. When I am with her, I regret all that you         
\par have taught me. I become different from what you have known me to           
\par be. I am changed, and the mere touch of Sibyl Vane's hand makes me          
\par forget you and all your wrong, fascinating, poisonous, delightful           
\par theories."                                                                  
\par   "And those are...?" asked Lord Henry, helping himself to some salad.      
\par   "Oh, your theories about life, your theories about love, your             
\par theories about pleasure. All your theories, in fact, Harry."                
\par   "Pleasure is the only thing worth having a theory about," he              
\par answered, in his slow, melodious voice. "But I am afraid I cannot           
\par claim my theory as my own. It belongs to Nature, not to me. Pleasure        
\par is Nature's test, her sign of approval. When we are happy we are            
\par always good, but when we are good we are not always happy."                 
\par   "Ah! but what do you mean by good?" cried Basil Hallward.                 
\par   "Yes," echoed Dorian, leaning back in his chair, and looking at Lord      
\par Henry over the heavy clusters of purple-lipped irises that stood in         
\par the centre of the table, "what do you mean by good, Harry?"                 
\par   "To be good is to be in harmony with one's self," he replied,             
\par touching the thin stem of his glass with his pale, fine-pointed             
\par fingers. "Discord is to be forced to be in harmony with others.             
\par One's own life- that is the important thing. As for the lives of one's      
\par neighbors, if one wishes to be a prig or a Puritan, one can flaunt          
\par one's moral views about them, but they are not one's concern. Besides,      
\par Individualism has really the higher aim. Modern morality consists in        
\par accepting the standard of one's age. I consider that for any man of         
\par culture to accept the standard of his age is a form of the grossest         
\par immorality."                                                                
\par   "But, surely, if one lives merely for one's self, Harry, one pays         
\par a terrible price for doing so?" suggested the painter.                      
\par   "Yes, we are overcharged for everything nowadays. I should fancy          
\par that the real tragedy of the poor is that they can afford nothing           
\par but self-denial. Beautiful sins, like beautiful things, are the             
\par privilege of the rich."                                                     
\par   "One has to pay in other ways but money."                                 
\par   "What sort of ways, Basil?"                                               
\par   "Oh! I should fancy in remorse, in suffering, in... well, in the          
\par consciousness of degradation."                                              
\par   Lord Henry shrugged his shoulders. "My dear fellow, mediaeval art is      
\par charming, but mediaeval emotions are out of date. One can use them          
\par in fiction, of course. But then the only things that one can use in         
\par fiction are the things that one has ceased to use in fact. Believe me,      
\par no civilized man ever regrets a pleasure, and no uncivilized man            
\par ever knows what a pleasure is."                                             
\par   "I know what pleasure is," cried Dorian Gray. "It is to adore some        
\par one."                                                                       
\par   "That is certainly better than being adored," he answered, toying         
\par with some fruits. "Being adored is a nuisance. Women treat us just          
\par as Humanity treats its gods. They worship us, and are always bothering      
\par us to do something for them."                                               
\par   "I should have said that whatever they ask for they had first             
\par given to us," murmured the lad, gravely. "They create Love in our           
\par natures. They have a right to demand it back."                              
\par   "That is quite true, Dorian," cried Hallward.                             
\par   "Nothing is ever quite true," said Lord Henry.                            
\par   "This is," interrupted Dorian. "You must admit, Harry, that women         
\par give to men the very gold of their lives."                                  
\par   "Possibly," he sighed, "but they invariably want it back in such          
\par very small change. That is the worry. Women, as some witty Frenchman        
\par once put it, inspire us with the desire to do masterpieces, and always      
\par prevent us from carrying them out."                                         
\par   "Harry, you are dreadful! I don't know why I like you so much."           
\par   "You will always like me, Dorian," he replied. "Will you have some        
\par coffee, you fellows? Waiter, bring coffee, and fine-champagne, and          
\par some cigarettes. No; don't mind the cigarettes; I have some. Basil,         
\par I can't allow you to smoke cigars. You must have a cigarette. A             
\par cigarette is the perfect type of a perfect pleasure. It is                  
\par exquisite, and it leaves one unsatisfied. What more can one want? Yes,      
\par Dorian, you will always be fond of me. I represent to you all the sins      
\par you have never had the courage to commit."                                  
\par   "What nonsense you talk, Harry!" cried the lad, taking a light            
\par from a fire-breathing silver dragon that the waiter had placed on           
\par the table. "Let us go down to the theatre. When Sibyl comes on the          
\par stage you will have a new ideal of life. She will represent                 
\par something to you that you have never known."                                
\par   "I have known everything," said Lord Henry, with a tired look in his      
\par eyes, "but I am always ready for a new emotion. I am afraid,                
\par however, that, for me  at any rate, there is no such thing. Still,          
\par your wonderful girl may thrill me. I love acting. It is so much more        
\par real than life. Let us go. Dorian, you will come with me. I am so           
\par sorry, Basil, but there is only room for two in the brougham, You must      
\par follow us in a hansom."                                                     
\par   They got up and put on their coats, sipping their coffee standing.        
\par The painter was silent and preoccupied. There was a gloom over him. He      
\par could not bear this marriage, and yet it seemed to him to be better         
\par than many other things that might have happened. After a few                
\par minutes, they all passed downstairs. He drove off by himself, as had        
\par been arranged, and watched the flashing lights of the little                
\par brougham in front of him. A strange sense of loss came over him. He         
\par felt that Dorian Gray would never again be to him all that he had been      
\par in the past. Life had come between them.... His eyes darkened, and the      
\par crowded, flaring streets became blurred to his eyes. When the cab drew      
\par up at the theatre, it seemed to him that he had grown years older.          
