\par                              CHAPTER VII                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   For some reason or other, the house was crowded that night, and           
\par the fat Jew manager who met them at the door was beaming from ear to        
\par ear with an oily, tremulous smile. He escorted them to their box            
\par with sort of pompous humility, waving his fat jewelled hands, and           
\par talking at the top of his voice. Dorian Gray loathed him more than          
\par ever. He felt as if he had come to look for Miranda and had been met        
\par by Caliban. Lord Henry, upon the other hand, rather liked him. At           
\par least he declared he did, and insisted on shaking him by the hand, and      
\par assuring him that he was proud to meet a man who had discovered a real      
\par genius and gone bankrupt over a poet. Hallward amused himself with          
\par watching the faces in the pit. The heat was terribly oppressive, and        
\par the huge sunlight flamed like a monstrous dahlia with petals of yellow      
\par fire. The youths in the gallery had taken off their coats and               
\par waistcoats and hung them over the side. They talked to each other           
\par across the theatre, and shared their oranges with the tawdry girls who      
\par sat beside them. Some women were laughing in the pit. Their voices          
\par were horribly shrill and discordant. The sound of the popping of corks      
\par came from the bar.                                                          
\par   "What a place to find one's divinity in!" said Lord Henry.                
\par   "Yes!" answered Dorian Gray. "It was here I found her, and she is         
\par divine beyond all living things. When she acts you will forget              
\par everything. These common, rough people, with their coarse faces and         
\par brutal gestures, become quite different when she is on the stage. They      
\par sit silently and watch her. They weep and laugh as she wills them to        
\par do. She makes them as responsive as a violin. She spiritualizes             
\par them, and one feels that they are of the same flesh and blood as one's      
\par self."                                                                      
\par   "The same flesh and blood as one's self! Oh, I hope not!"                 
\par exclaimed Lord Henry, who was scanning the occupants of the gallery         
\par through his opera-glass.                                                    
\par   "Don't pay an attention to him, Dorian," said the painter. "I             
\par understand what you mean, and I believe in this girl. Any one you love      
\par must be marvellous, and any girl that has the effect you describe must      
\par be fine and noble. To spiritualize one's age- that is something             
\par worth doing. If this girl can give a soul to those who have lived           
\par without one, if she can create the sense of beauty in people whose          
\par lives have been sordid and ugly, if she can strip them of their             
\par selfishness and lend them tears for sorrows that are not their own,         
\par she is worthy of all your adoration, worthy of the adoration of the         
\par world. This marriage is quite right. I did not think so at first,           
\par but I admit it now. The gods made Sibyl Vane for you. Without her           
\par you would have been incomplete."                                            
\par   "Thanks, Basil," answered Dorian Gray, pressing his hand. "I knew         
\par that you would understand me. Harry is so cynical, he terrifies me.         
\par But here is the orchestra. It is quite dreadful, but it only lasts for      
\par about five minutes. Then the curtain rises, and you will see the            
\par girl to whom I am going to give all my life, to whom I have given           
\par everything that is good in me."                                             
\par   A quarter of an hour afterwards, amidst an extraordinary turmoil          
\par of applause, Sibyl Vane stepped on the stage. Yes, she was                  
\par certainly, lovely to look at- one of the loveliest creatures, Lord          
\par Henry thought, that he had ever seen. There was something of the            
\par fawn in her shy grace and startled eyes. A faint blush, like the            
\par shadow of a rose in a mirror of silver, came to her cheeks as she           
\par glanced at the crowded, enthusiastic house. She stepped back a few          
\par paces, and her lips seemed to tremble. Basil Hallward leaped to his         
\par feet and began to applaud. Motionless, and as one in a dream, sat           
\par Dorian Gray, gazing at her. Lord Henry peered through his glasses,          
\par murmuring, "Charming! charming!"                                            
\par   The scene was the hall of Capulet's house, and Romeo in his               
\par pilgrim's dress had entered with Mercutio and his other friends. The        
\par band, such as it was, struck up a few bars of music, and the dance          
\par began. Through the crowd of ungainly, shabbily-dressed actors, Sibyl        
\par Vane moved like a creature from a finer world. Her body swayed,             
\par while she danced, as a plant sways in the water. The curves of her          
\par throat were the curves of the white lily. Her hands seemed to be            
\par made of cool ivory.                                                         
\par   Yet she was curiously listless. She showed no sign of love when           
\par her eyes rested on Romeo. The few words she had to speak-                   
\par -                                                                           
\par           Good pilgrim, you do wrong your hand too much,                    
\par             Which mannerly devotion shows in this'                          
\par           For saints have hands that pilgrims' hands do touch,              
\par             And palm to palm is holy palmers' kiss-                         
\par -                                                                           
\par with the brief dialogue that follows, were spoken in a thoroughly           
\par artificial manner. The voice was exquisite, but from the point of view      
\par of tone it was absolutely false. It was wrong in colour. It took            
\par away all life from the verse. It made the passion unreal.                   
\par   Dorian Gray grew pale as he watched her. He was puzzled and anxious.      
\par Neither of his friends dared to say anything to him. She seemed to          
\par them to be absolutely incompetent. They were horribly disappointed.         
\par   Yet they felt that the true test of any Juliet is the balcony             
\par scene of the second act. They waited for that. If she failed there,         
\par there was nothing in her.                                                   
\par   She looked charming as she came out in the moonlight. That could not      
\par be denied. But the staginess of her acting was unbearable, and grew         
\par worse as she went on. Her gestures became absurdly artificial. She          
\par overemphasized everything that she had to say. The beautiful passage-       
\par -                                                                           
\par          Thou knowest the mask of night is on my face,                      
\par          Else would a maiden blush bepaint my cheek                         
\par          For that which thou hast heard me speak to-night-                  
\par -                                                                           
\par was declaimed with the painful precision of a school-girl who has been      
\par taught to recite by some second-rate professor of elocution. When           
\par she leaned over the balcony and came to those wonderful lines-              
\par -                                                                           
\par                       Although I joy in thee,                               
\par          I have no joy of this contract to-night;                           
\par          It is too rash, too unadvised, too sudden;                         
\par          Too like the lightning, which doth cease to be                     
\par          Ere one can say, "It lightens." Sweet, good-night!                 
\par          This bud of love by summer's ripening breath                       
\par          May prove a beauteous flower when next we meet-                    
\par -                                                                           
\par she spoke the words as though they conveyed no meaning to her. It           
\par was not nervousness. Indeed, so far from being nervous, she was             
\par absolutely self-contained. It was simply bad art. She was a complete        
\par failure.                                                                    
\par   Even the common, uneducated audience of the pit and gallery lost          
\par their interest in the play. They got restless, and began to talk            
\par loudly and to whistle. The Jew manager, who was standing, at the            
\par back of the dress-circle, stamped and swore with rage. The only person      
\par unmoved was the girl herself.                                               
\par   When the second act was over there came a storm of hisses, and            
\par Lord Henry got up from his chair and put on His coat. "She is quite         
\par beautiful, Dorian," he said, "but she can't act. Let us go."                
\par   "I am going to see the play through," answered the lad, in a hard,        
\par bitter voice. "I am awfully sorry that I have made you waste an             
\par evening, Harry. I apologize to you both."                                   
\par   "My dear Dorian, I should think Miss Vane was ill," interrupted           
\par Hallward. "We will come some other night."                                  
\par   "I wish she were ill," he rejoined. "But she seems to me to be            
\par simply callous and cold. She has entirely altered. Last night she           
\par was a great artist. This evening she is merely a conmmon-place,             
\par mediocre actress."                                                          
\par   "Don't talk like that about any one you love, Dorian. Love is a more      
\par wonderful thing than Art."                                                  
\par   "They are both simply forms of imitation," remarked Lord Henry. "But      
\par do let us go. Dorian, you must not stay here any longer. It is not          
\par good for one's morals to see bad acting. Besides, I don't suppose           
\par you will want your wife to act. So what does it matter if she plays         
\par Juliet like a wooden doll? She is very lovely, and if she knows as          
\par little about life as she does about acting, she will be a delightful        
\par experience. There are only two kinds of people who are really               
\par fascinating- people who know absolutely everything, and people who          
\par know absolutely nothing. Good heavens, my dear boy, don't look so           
\par tragic! The secret of remaining young is never to have an emotion that      
\par is unbecoming. Come to the club with Basil and myself. We will smoke        
\par cigarettes and drink to the beauty of Sibyl Vane. She is beautiful.         
\par What more can you want?"                                                    
\par   "Go away, Harry," cried the lad. "I want to be alone. Basil, you          
\par must go. Ah! can't you see that my heart is breaking?" The hot tears        
\par came to his eyes. His lips trembled, and rushing to the back of the         
\par box, he leaned up against the wall, hiding his face in his hands.           
\par   "Let us go, Basil," said Lord Henry, with a strange tenderness in         
\par his voice; and the two young men passed out together.                       
\par   A few moments afterwards the footlights flared up, and the curtain        
\par rose on the third act. Dorian Gray went back to his seat. He looked         
\par pale, and proud, and indifferent. The play ragged on, and seemed            
\par interminable. Half of the audience went out, tramping in heavy              
\par boots, and laughing. The whole thing was a fiasco. The last act was         
\par played to almost empty benches. The curtain went down on a titter, and      
\par some groans.                                                                
\par   As soon as it was over, Dorian Gray rushed behind the scenes into         
\par the greenroom. The girl was standing there alone, with a look of            
\par triumph on her face. Her eyes lit with an exquisite fire. There was         
\par a radiance about her. Her parted lips were smiling over some secret of      
\par their own.                                                                  
\par   When he entered, she looked at him and an expression of infinite joy      
\par came over her. "How badly I acted to-night, Dorian!" she cried.             
\par   "Horribly!" he answered, gazing at her in amazement, "horribly! It        
\par was dreadful. Are you ill? You have no idea what it was. You have no        
\par idea what I suffered."                                                      
\par   The girl smiled. "Dorian," she answered, lingering over his name          
\par with long-drawn music in her voice, as though it were sweeter than          
\par honey to the red petals of her mouth- "Dorian, you should have              
\par understood. But you understand now, don't you?"                             
\par   "Understand what?" he asked angrily.                                      
\par   "Why I was so bad to-night. Why I shall always be bad. Why I shall        
\par never act well again."                                                      
\par   He shrugged his shoulders. "You are ill, I suppose. When you are ill      
\par you shouldn't act. You make yourself ridiculous. My friends were            
\par bored. I was bored."                                                        
\par   She seemed not to listen to him. She was transfigured with joy. An        
\par ecstasy of happiness dominated her.                                         
\par   "Dorian, Dorian," she cried, "before I knew you, acting was the           
\par one reality of my life. It was only in the theatre that I lived. I          
\par thought that it was all true. I was Rosalind one night, and Portia the      
\par other. The joy of Beatrice was my joy, and the sorrows of Cordelia          
\par were mine also. I believed in everything. The common people who             
\par acted with me seemed to me to be godlike. The painted scenes were my        
\par world. I knew nothing but shadows, and I thought them real. You             
\par came- oh, my beautiful love!- and you freed my soul from prison. You        
\par taught me what reality really is. To-night, for the first time in my        
\par life, I saw through the hollowness, the sham, the silliness of the          
\par empty pageant in which I had always played. To-night, for the first         
\par time, I became conscious that the Romeo was hideous, and old, and           
\par painted, and that the moonlight in the orchard was false, that the          
\par scenery was vulgar, and that the words I had to speak were unreal,          
\par were not my words, were not what I wanted to say. You had brought me        
\par something higher, something of which all art is but a reflection.           
\par You had made me understand what love really is. My love! my love!           
\par Prince Charming! Prince of life! I have grown sick of shadows. You are      
\par more to me than all art can ever be. What have I to do with the             
\par puppets of a play? When I came on to-night, I could not understand how      
\par it was that everything had gone from me. I thought that I was going to      
\par be wonderful. I found that I could do nothing. Suddenly it dawned on        
\par my soul what it all meant. The knowledge was exquisite to me. I             
\par heard them hissing, and I smiled. What could they know of love such as      
\par ours? Take me away, Dorian- take me away with you, where we can be          
\par quite alone. I hate the stage. I might mimic a passion that I do not        
\par feel, but I cannot mimic one that burns me like fire. Oh, Dorian,           
\par Dorian, you understand now what it signifies? Even if I could do it,        
\par it would be profanation for me to play at being in love. You have made      
\par me see that."                                                               
\par   He flung himself down on the sofa, and turned away his face. "You         
\par have killed my love," he muttered.                                          
\par   She looked at him in wonder, and laughed. He made no answer. She          
\par came across to him, and with her little fingers stroked his hair.           
\par She knelt down and pressed his hands to her lips. He drew them away,        
\par and a shudder ran through him.                                              
\par   Then he leaped up, and went to the door. "Yes," he cried, "you            
\par have killed my love. You used to stir my imagination. Now you don't         
\par even stir my curiosity. You simply produce no effect. I loved you           
\par because you were marvellous, because you had genius and intellect,          
\par because you realized the dreams of great poets and gave shape and           
\par substance to the shadows of art. You have thrown it all away. You           
\par are shallow and stupid. My God! how mad I was to love you! What a fool      
\par I have been! You are nothing to me now. I will never see you again.         
\par I will never think of you. I will never mention your name. You don't        
\par know what you were to me, once. Why, once... Oh, I can't bear to think      
\par of it! I wish I had never laid eyes upon you! You have spoiled the          
\par romance of my life. How little you can know of love, if you say it          
\par mars your art! Without your art you are nothing. I would have made you      
\par famous, splendid, magnificent. The world would have worshipped you,         
\par and you would have borne my name. What are you now? A third-rate            
\par actress with a pretty face."                                                
\par   The girl grew white, and trembled. She clenched her hands                 
\par together, and her voice seemed to catch in her throat. "You are not         
\par serious, Dorian?" she murmured. "You are acting."                           
\par   "Acting! I leave that to you. You do it so well," he answered,            
\par bitterly.                                                                   
\par   She rose from her knees, and, with a piteous expression of pain in        
\par her face, came across the room to him. She put her hand upon his            
\par arm, and looked into his eyes. He thrust her back. "Don't touch me!"        
\par he cried.                                                                   
\par   A low moan broke from her, and she flung herself at his feet, and         
\par lay there like a trampled flower. "Dorian, Dorian, don't leave me!"         
\par she whispered. "I am so sorry I didn't act well. I was thinking of you      
\par all the time. But I will try- indeed, I will try. It came so                
\par suddenly across me, my love for you. I think I should never have known      
\par it if you had not kissed me- if we had not kissed each other. Kiss          
\par me again, my love. Don't go away from me. I couldn't bear it. Oh!           
\par don't go away from me. My brother... No; never mind. He didn't mean         
\par it. He was in jest... But you, oh! can't you forgive me for                 
\par to-night? I will work so hard, and try to improve. Don't be cruel to        
\par me because I love you better than anything in the world. After all, it      
\par is only once that I have not pleased you. But you are quite right,          
\par Dorian. I should have shown myself more of an artist. It was foolish        
\par of me; and yet I couldn't help it. Oh, don't leave me, don't leave          
\par me." A fit of passionate sobbing choked her. She crouched on the floor      
\par like a wounded thing, and Dorian Gray, with his beautiful eyes, looked      
\par down at her, and his chiselled lips curled in exquisite disdain. There      
\par is always something ridiculous about the emotions of people whom one        
\par has ceased to love. Sibyl Vane seemed to him to be absurdly                 
\par melodromatic. Her tears and sobs annoyed him.                               
\par   "I am going," he said at last, in his calm, clear voice. "I don't         
\par wish to be unkind, but I can't see you again. You have disappointed         
\par me."                                                                        
\par   She wept silently, and made no answer, but crept nearer. Her              
\par little hands stretched blindly out, and appeared to be seeking for          
\par him. He turned on his heel, and left the room. In a few moments he was      
\par out of the theatre.                                                         
\par   Where he went to he hardly knew. He remembered wandering through          
\par dimly-lit streets, past gaunt black-shadowed archways and evil-looking      
\par houses. Women with hoarse voices and harsh laughter had called after        
\par him. Drunkards had reeled by cursing, and chattering to themselves          
\par like monstrous apes. He had seen grotesque children huddled upon            
\par doorsteps, and heard shrieks and oaths from gloomy courts.                  
\par   As the dawn was just breaking he found himself close to Covent            
\par Garden. The darkness lifted, and, flushed with faint fires, the sky         
\par hollowed itself into a perfect pearl. Huge carts filled with nodding        
\par lilies rumbled slowly down the polished empty street. The air was           
\par heavy with the perfume of the flowers, and their beauty seemed to           
\par bring him an anodyne for His pain. He followed into the market, and         
\par watched the men unloading their waggons. A white-smocked carter             
\par offered him some cherries. He thanked him, wondered why he refused          
\par to accept any money for them, and began to eat them listlessly. They        
\par had been plucked at midnight, and the coldness of the moon had entered      
\par into them. A long line of boys carrying crates of striped tulips,           
\par and of yellow and red roses, defiled in front of him, threading             
\par their way through the huge jade-green piles of vegetables. Under the        
\par portico, with its grey sun-bleached pillars, loitered a troop of            
\par draggled bareheaded girls, waiting for the auction to be over.              
\par Others crowded round the swinging doors of the coffee-house in the          
\par piazza. The heavy cart-horses slipped and stamped upon the rough            
\par stones, shaking their bells and trappings. Some of the drivers were         
\par lying asleep on a pile of sacks. Iris-necked, and pink-footed, the          
\par pigeons ran about picking up seeds.                                         
\par   After a little while, he hailed a hansom, and drove home. For a           
\par few moments he loitered upon the doorstep, looking round at the silent      
\par Square with its blank close-shuttered windows, and its staring blinds.      
\par The sky was pure opal now, and the roofs of the houses glistened            
\par like silver against it. From some chimney opposite a thin wreath of         
\par smoke was rising. It curled, a violet riband, through the                   
\par nacre-coloured air.                                                         
\par   In the huge gilt Venetian lantern, spoil of some Doge's barge,            
\par that hung from the ceiling of the great oak-panelled hall of entrance,      
\par lights were still burning from three flickering jets: thin blue petals      
\par of flame they seemed, trimmed with white fire. He turned them out,          
\par and, having thrown his hat and cape on the table, passed through the        
\par library towards the door of his bedroom, a large octagonal chamber          
\par on the ground floor that, in his new-born feeling for luxury, he had        
\par just had decorated for himself, and hung with some curious Renaissance      
\par tapestries that had been discovered stored in a disused attic at Selby      
\par Royal. As he was turning the handle of the door, his eye fell upon the      
\par portrait Basil Hallward had painted of him. He started back as if in        
\par surprise. Then he went on into his own room, looking somewhat puzzled.      
\par After he had taken the buttonhole out of his coat, he seemed to             
\par hesitate. Finally he came back, went over to the picture, and examined      
\par it. In the dim arrested light that struggled through the                    
\par cream-coloured silk blinds, the face appeared to him to be a little         
\par changed. The expression looked different. One would have said that          
\par there was a touch of cruelty in the mouth. It was certainly strange.        
\par   He turned round, and, walking to the window, drew up the blind.           
\par The bright dawn flooded the room, and swept the fantastic shadows into      
\par dusky corners, where they lay shuddering. But the strange expression        
\par that he had noticed in the face of the portrait seemed to linger            
\par there, to be more intensified even. The quivering, ardent sunlight          
\par showed him the lines of cruelty round the mouth as clearly as if he         
\par been looking into a mirror after he had done some dreadful thing.           
\par   He winced, and taking up from the table an oval glass framed in           
\par ivory Cupids, one of Lord Henry's many presents to him, glanced             
\par hurriedly into its polished depths. No line like that warped his red        
\par lips. What did it mean?                                                     
\par   He rubbed his eyes, and came close to the picture, and examined it        
\par again. There were no signs of any change when he looked into the            
\par actual painting, and yet there was no doubt that the whole                  
\par expression had altered. It was not a mere fancy of his own. The             
\par thing was horribly apparent.                                                
\par   He threw himself into a chair, and began to think. Suddenly there         
\par flashed across his mind what he had said in Basil Hallward's studio         
\par the day the picture had been finished. Yes, he remembered it                
\par perfectly. He had uttered a mad wish that he himself might remain           
\par young, and the portrait grow old; that his own beauty might be              
\par untarnished, and the face on the canvas bear the burden of his              
\par passions and his sins; that the painted image might be seared with the      
\par lines of suffering and thought, and that he might keep all the              
\par delicate bloom and loveliness of his then just conscious boyhood.           
\par Surely his wish had not been fulfilled? Such things were impossible.        
\par It seemed monstrous even to think of them. And, yet, there was the          
\par picture before him, with the touch of cruelty in the mouth.                 
\par   Cruelty! Had he been cruel? It was the girl's fault, not his. He had      
\par dreamed of her as a great artist, had given his love to her because he      
\par had thought her great. Then she had disappointed him. She had been          
\par shallow and unworthy. And, yet, a feeling of infinite regret came over      
\par him, as he thought of her lying at his feet sobbing like a little           
\par child. He remembered with what callousness he had watched her. Why had      
\par he been made like that? Why had such a soul been given to him? But          
\par he had suffered also. During the three terrible hours that the play         
\par had lasted, he had lived centuries of pain, aeon upon aeon of torture.      
\par His life was well worth hers. She had marred him for a moment, if he        
\par had wounded her for an age. Besides, women were better suited to            
\par bear sorrow than men. They lived on their emotions. They only               
\par thought of their emotions. When they took lovers, it was merely to          
\par have some one with whom they could have scenes. Lord Henry had told         
\par him that, and Lord Henry knew what women were. Why should he trouble        
\par about Sibyl Vane? She was nothing to him now.                               
\par   But the picture? What was he to say of that? It held the secret of        
\par his life, and told his story. It had taught him to love his own             
\par beauty. Would it teach him to loathe his own soul? Would he ever            
\par look at it again?                                                           
\par   No; it was merely an illusion wrought on the troubled senses. The         
\par horrible night that he had passed had left phantoms behind it.              
\par Suddenly there had fallen upon his brain that tiny scarlet speck            
\par that makes men mad. The picture had not changed. It was folly to think      
\par so.                                                                         
\par   Yet it was watching him, with its beautiful marred face and its           
\par cruel smile. Its bright hair gleamed in the early sunlight. Its blue        
\par eyes met his own. A sense of infinite pity, not for himself, but for        
\par the painted image of himself, came over him. It had altered already,        
\par and would alter more. Its gold would wither into grey. Its red and          
\par white roses would die. For every sin that he committed, a stain             
\par would fleck and wreck its fairness. But he would not sin. The picture,      
\par changed or unchanged, would be to him the visible emblem of                 
\par conscience. He would resist temptation. He would not see Lord Henry         
\par any more- would not, at any rate, listen to those subtle poisonous          
\par theories that in Basil Hallward's garden had first stirred within           
\par him the passion for impossible things. He would go back to Sibyl Vane,      
\par make her amends, marry her, try to love her again. Yes, it was his          
\par duty to do so. She must have suffered more than he had. Poor child! He      
\par had been selfish and cruel to her. The fascination that she had             
\par exercised over him would return. They would be happy together. His          
\par life with her would be beautiful and pure.                                  
\par   He got up from his chair, and drew a large screen right in front          
\par of the portrait, shuddering as he glanced at it. "How horrible!" he         
\par murmured to himself, and he walked across to the window and opened it.      
\par When he stepped out on to the grass, he drew a deep breath. The             
\par fresh morning air seemed to drive away all his sombre passions. He          
\par thought only of Sibyl. A faint echo of his love came back to him. He        
\par repeated her name over and over again. The birds that were singing          
\par in the dew-drenched garden seemed to be telling the flowers about her.      
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                              CHAPTER VIII                                   
\par -                                                                           
\par   It was long past noon when he awoke. His valet had crept several          
\par times on tiptoe into the room to see if he was stirring, and had            
\par wondered what made his young master sleep so late. Finally his bell         
\par sounded, and Victor came in softly with a cup of tea, and a pile of         
\par letters, on a small tray of old Sevres china, and drew back the             
\par olive-satin curtains, with, their shimmering blue lining, that hung in      
\par front of the three tall windows.                                            
\par   "Monsieur has slept well this morning," he said, smiling.                 
\par   "What o'clock is it, Victor?" asked Dorian Gray, drowsily.                
\par   "One hour and a quarter, Monsieur."                                       
\par   How late it was! He sat up, and, having sipped some tea, turned over      
\par his letters. One of them was from Lord Henry, and had been brought          
\par by hand this morning. He hesitated for a moment, and then put it            
\par aside. The others he opened listlessly. They contained the usual            
\par collection of cards, invitations to dinner, tickets for private views,      
\par programmes of charity concerts, and the like, that are showered on          
\par fashionable young men every morning during the season. There was a          
\par rather heavy bill, for a chased silver Louis-Quinze toilet-set, that        
\par he had not yet had the courage to send on to his guardians, who were        
\par extremely old-fashioned people and did not realize that we live in          
\par an age when unnecessary things are our only necessities; and there          
\par were several very courteously worded communications from Jermyn Street      
\par money-lenders offering to advance any sum of money at a moment's            
\par notice and at the most reasonable rates of interest.                        
\par   After about ten minutes he got up, and, throwing on an elaborate          
\par dressing-gown of silk-embroidered cashmere wool, passed into the            
\par onyx-paved bathroom. The cool water refreshed him after his long            
\par sleep. He seemed to have forgotten all that he had gone through. A dim      
\par sense of having taken part in some strange tragedy came to him once or      
\par twice, but there was the unreality of a dream about it.                     
\par   As soon as he was dressed, he went into the library and sat down          
\par to a light French breakfast, that had been laid out for him on a small      
\par round table close to the open window. It was an exquisite day. The          
\par warm air seemed laden with spices. A bee flew in, and buzzed round the      
\par blue-dragon bowl that, filled with sulphur-yellow roses, stood              
\par before him. He felt perfectly happy.                                        
\par   Suddenly his eye fell on the screen that he had placed in front of        
\par the portrait, and he started.                                               
\par   "Too cold for Monsieur?" asked his valet, putting an omelette on the      
\par table. "I shut the window?"                                                 
\par   Dorian shook his head. "I am not cold," he murmured.                      
\par   Was it all true? Had the portrait really changed? Or had it been          
\par simply his own imagination that had made him see a look of evil             
\par where there had been a look of joy? Surely a painted canvas could           
\par not alter? The thing was absurd. It would serve as a tale to tell           
\par Basil some day. It would make him smile.                                    
\par   And, yet, how vivid was his recollection of the whole thing! First        
\par in the dim twilight, and then in the bright dawn, he had seen the           
\par touch of cruelty round the warped lips. He almost dreaded his valet         
\par leaving the room. He knew that when he was alone he would have to           
\par examine the portrait. He was afraid of certainty. When the coffee           
\par and cigarettes had been brought and the man turned to go, he felt a         
\par wild desire to tell him to remain. As the door was closing behind           
\par him he called him back. The man stood waiting for his orders. Dorian        
\par looked at him for a moment. "I am not at home to any one, Victor,"          
\par he said, with a sigh. The man bowed and retired.                            
\par   Then he rose from the table, lit a cigarette and flung himself            
\par down on a luxuriously-cushioned couch that stood facing the screen.         
\par The screen was an old one, of gilt Spanish leather, stamped and             
\par wrought with a rather florid Louis-Quatorze pattern. He scanned it          
\par curiously, wondering if ever before it had concealed the secret of a        
\par man's life.                                                                 
\par   Should he move it aside, after all? Why not let it stay there?            
\par What was the use of knowing? If the thing was true, it was terrible.        
\par If it was not true, why trouble about it? But what if, by some fate or      
\par deadlier chance, eyes other than his spied behind, and saw the              
\par horrible change? What should he do if Basil Hallward came and asked to      
\par look at his own picture? Basil would be sure to do that. No; the thing      
\par had to be examined, and at once. Anything would be better than this         
\par dreadful state of doubt.                                                    
\par   He got up, and locked both doors. At least he would be alone when he      
\par looked upon the mask of his shame. Then he drew the screen aside,           
\par and saw himself face to face. It was perfectly true. The portrait           
\par had altered.                                                                
\par   As he often remembered afterwards, and always with no small               
\par wonder, he found himself at first gazing at the portrait with a             
\par feeling of almost scientific interest. That such a change should            
\par have taken place was incredible to him. And yet it was a fact. Was          
\par there some subtle affinity between the chemical atoms, that shaped          
\par themselves into form and colour on the canvas, and the soul that was        
\par within him? Could it be that what that soul thought, they realized?-        
\par that what it dreamed, they made true? Or was there some other, more         
\par terrible reason? He shuddered, and felt afraid, and, going back to the      
\par couch, lay there, gazing at the picture in sickened horror.                 
\par   One thing, however, he felt that it had done for him. It had made         
\par him conscious how unjust, how cruel, he had been to Sibyl Vane. It was      
\par not too late to make reparation for that. She could still be his wife.      
\par His unreal and selfish love would yield to some higher influence,           
\par would be transformed into some nobler passion, and the portrait that        
\par Basil Hallward had painted of him would be a guide to him through           
\par life, would be to him what holiness is to some, and conscience to           
\par others, and the fear of God to us all. There were opiates for remorse,      
\par drugs that could lull the moral sense to sleep. But here was a visible      
\par symbol of the degradation of sin. Here was an ever-present sign of the      
\par ruin men brought upon their souls.                                          
\par   Three o'clock struck, and four, and the half-hour rang its double         
\par chime, but Dorian Gray did not stir. He was trying to gather up the         
\par scarlet threads of life, and to weave them into a pattern; to find his      
\par way through the sanguine labyrinth of passion through which he was          
\par wandering. He did not know what to do, or what to think. Finally, he        
\par went over to the table and wrote a passionate letter to the girl he         
\par had loved, imploring her forgiveness, and accusing himself of madness.      
\par He covered page after page with wild words of sorrow, and wilder words      
\par of pain. There is a luxury in self-reproach. When we blame ourselves        
\par we feel that no one else has a right to blame us. It is the                 
\par confession, not the priest, that gives us absolution. When Dorian           
\par had finished the letter, he felt that he had been forgiven.                 
\par   Suddenly there came a knock to the door, and he heard Lord Henry's        
\par voice outside. "My dear boy, I must see you. Let me in at once. I           
\par can't bear your shutting yourself up like this."                            
\par   He made no answer at first, but remained quite still. The knocking        
\par still continued, and grew louder. Yes, it was better to let Lord Henry      
\par in, and to explain to him the new life he was going to lead, to             
\par quarrel with him if it became necessary to quarrel, to part if parting      
\par was inevitable. He jumped up, drew the screen hastily across the            
\par picture, and unlocked the door.                                             
\par   "I am so sorry for it all, Dorian," said Lord Henry, as he                
\par entered. "But you must not think too much about it."                        
\par   "Do you mean about Sibyl Vane?" asked the lad.                            
\par   "Yes, of course," answered Lord Henry, sinking into a chair, and          
\par slowly pulling off his yellow gloves. "It is dreadful, from one             
\par point of view, but it was not your fault. Tell me, did you go behind        
\par and see her, after the play was over?"                                      
\par  "Yes."                                                                     
\par   "I felt sure you had. Did you make a scene with her?"                     
\par   "I was brutal, Harry, perfectly brutal. But it is all right now. I        
\par am not sorry for anything that has happened. It has taught me to            
\par know myself better."                                                        
\par   "Ah, Dorian, I am so glad you take it in that way! I was afraid I         
\par would find you plunged in remorse, and tearing that nice curly hair of      
\par yours."                                                                     
\par   "I have got through all that," said Dorian, shaking his head, and         
\par smiling. "I am perfectly happy now. I know what conscience is, to           
\par begin with. It is not what you told me it was. It is the divinest           
\par thing in us. Don't sneer at it, Harry, any more- at least not before        
\par me. I want to be good. I can't bear the idea of my soul being               
\par hideous."                                                                   
\par   "A very charming artistic basis for ethics, Dorian! I congratulate        
\par you on it. But how are you going to begin?"                                 
\par   "By marrying Sibyl Vane."                                                 
\par   "Marrying Sibyl Vane! " cried Lord Henry, standing up, and looking        
\par at him in perplexed amazement. "But, my dear Dorian--"                      
\par   "Yes, Harry, I know what you are going to say. Something dreadful         
\par about marriage. Don't say it. Don't ever say things of that kind to me      
\par again. Two days ago I asked Sibyl to marry me. I am not going to break      
\par my word to her. She is to be my wife."                                      
\par   "Your wife! Dorian!... Didn't you get my letter? I wrote to you this      
\par morning, and sent the note down, by my own man."                            
\par   "Your letter? Oh, yes, I remember. I have not read it yet, Harry.         
\par I was afraid there might be something in it that I wouldn't like.           
\par You cut life to pieces with your epigrams."                                 
\par   "You know nothing, then?"                                                 
\par   "What do you mean?"                                                       
\par   Lord Henry walked across the room, and, sitting down by Dorian Gray,      
\par took both his hands in his own, and held them tightly. "Dorian," he         
\par said, "my letter- don't be frightened- was to tell you that Sibyl Vane      
\par is dead."                                                                   
\par   A cry of pain broke from the lad's lips, and he leaped to his             
\par feet, tearing his hands away from Lord Henry's grasp. "Dead! Sibyl          
\par dead! It is not true! It is a horrible lie! How dare you say it?"           
\par   "It is quite true, Dorian," said Lord Henry, gravely. "It is in           
\par all the morning papers. I wrote down to you to ask you not to see           
\par any one till I came. There will have to be an inquest, of course,           
\par and you must not be mixed up in it. Things like that make a man             
\par fashionable in Paris. But in London people are so prejudiced. Here,         
\par one should never make one's debut with a scandal. One should reserve        
\par that to give an interest to one's old age. I suppose they don't know        
\par your name at the theatre? If they don't, it is all right. Did any           
\par one see you going round to her room? That is an important point."           
\par   Dorian did not answer for a few moments. He was dazed with horror.        
\par Finally he stammered, in a stifled voice, "Harry, did you say an            
\par inquest? What did you mean by that? Did Sibyl--? Oh, Harry, I can't         
\par bear it! But be quick. Tell me everything at once."                         
\par   "I have no doubt it was not an accident, Dorian, though it must be        
\par put in that way to the public. It seems that as she was leaving the         
\par theatre with her mother, about half-past twelve or so, she said she         
\par had forgotten something upstairs. They waited some time for her, but        
\par she did not come down again. They ultimately found her lying dead on        
\par the floor of her dressing room. She had swallowed something by              
\par mistake, some dreadful thing they use at theatres. I don't know what        
\par it was, but it had either prussic acid or white lead in it. I should        
\par fancy it was prussic acid, as she seems to have died instantaneously."      
\par   "Harry, Harry, it is terrible!" cried the lad.                            
\par   "Yes; it is very tragic, of course, but you must not get yourself         
\par mixed up in it. I see by The Standard that she was seventeen. I should      
\par have thought she was almost younger than that. She looked such a            
\par child, and seemed to know so little about acting. Dorian, you               
\par mustn't let this thing get on your nerves. You must come and dine with      
\par me, and afterwards we will look in at the Opera. It is a Patti              
\par night, and everybody will be there. You can come to my sister's box.        
\par She has got some smart women with her."                                     
\par   "So I have murdered Sibyl Vane," said Dorian Gray, half to                
\par himself, "murdered her as surely as if I had cut her little throat          
\par with a knife. Yet the roses are not less lovely for all that. The           
\par birds sing just as happily in my garden. And to-night I am to dine          
\par with you, and then go on to the Opera, and sup somewhere, I suppose,        
\par afterwards. How extraordinarily dramatic life is! If I had read all         
\par this in a book, Harry, I think I would have wept over it. Somehow, now      
\par that it has happened actually, and to me, it seems far too wonderful        
\par for tears. Here is the first passionate love-letter I have ever             
\par written in my life. Strange, that my first passionate love-letter           
\par should have been addressed to a dead girl. Can they feel, I wonder,         
\par those white silent people we call the dead? Sibyl! Can she feel, or         
\par know, or listen? Oh, Harry, how I loved her once! It seems years ago        
\par to me now. She was everything to me. Then came that dreadful night-         
\par was it really only last night?- when she played so badly, and my heart      
\par almost broke. She explained it all to me. It was terribly pathetic.         
\par But I was not moved a bit. I thought her shallow. Suddenly something        
\par happened that made me afraid. I can't tell you what it was, but it was      
\par terrible. I said I would go back to her. I felt I had done wrong.           
\par And now she is dead. My God! my God! Harry, what shall I do? You don't      
\par know the danger I am in, and there is nothing to keep me straight. She      
\par would have done that for me. She had no right to kill herself. It           
\par was selfish of her."                                                        
\par   "My dear Dorian," answered Lord Henry, taking a cigarette from his        
\par case, and producing a gold-latten matchbox, "the only way a woman           
\par can ever reform a man is by boring him so completely that he loses all      
\par possible interest in life. If you had married this girl you would have      
\par been wretched. Of course you would have treated her kindly. One can         
\par always be kind to people about whom one cares nothing. But she would        
\par have soon found out that you were absolutely indifferent to her. And        
\par when a woman finds that out about her husband, she either becomes           
\par dreadfully dowdy, or wears very smart bonnets that some other               
\par woman's husband has to pay for. I say nothing about the social              
\par mistake, which would have been abject, which, of course, I would not        
\par have allowed, but I assure you that in any case the whole thing             
\par would have been an absolute failure."                                       
\par   "I suppose it would," muttered the lad, walking up and down the           
\par room, and looking horribly pale. "But I thought it was my duty. It          
\par is not my fault that this terrible tragedy has prevented my doing what      
\par was right. I remember your saying once that there is a fatality             
\par about good resolutions- that they are always made too late. Mine            
\par certainly were."                                                            
\par   "Good resolutions are useless attempts to interfere with                  
\par scientific laws. Their origin is pure vanity. Their result is               
\par absolutely nil. They give us, now and then, some of those luxurious         
\par sterile emotions that have a certain charm for the weak. That is all        
\par that can be said for them. They are simply cheques that men draw on         
\par a bank where they have no account."                                         
\par   "Harry," cried Dorian Gray, coming over and sitting down beside him,      
\par "why is it that I cannot feel this tragedy as much as I want to? I          
\par don't think I am heartless. Do you?"                                        
\par   "You have done too many foolish things during the last fortnight          
\par to be entitled to give yourself that name, Dorian," answered Lord           
\par Henry, with his sweet, melancholy smile.                                    
\par   The lad frowned. "I don't like that explanation, Harry," he               
\par rejoined, "but I am glad you don't think I'm heartless. I am nothing        
\par of the kind. I know I am not. And yet I must admit that this thing          
\par that has happened does not affect me as it should. It seems to me to        
\par be simply like a wonderful ending to a wonderful play. It has all           
\par the terrible beauty of a Greek tragedy, a tragedy in which I took a         
\par great part, but by which I have not been wounded."                          
\par   "It is an interesting question," said Lord Henry, who found an            
\par exquisite pleasure in playing on the lad's unconscious egotism- "an         
\par extremely interesting question. I fancy that the true explanation is        
\par this. It often happens that the real tragedies of life occur in such        
\par an inartistic manner that they hurt us by their crude violence,             
\par their absolute incoherence, their absurd want of meaning, their entire      
\par lack of style. They affect us just as vulgarity affects us. They            
\par give us an impression of sheer brute force, and we revolt against           
\par that. Sometimes, however, a tragedy that possesses artistic elements        
\par of beauty crosses our lives. If these elements of beauty are real, the      
\par whole thing simply appeals to our sense of dramatic effect. Suddenly        
\par we find that we are no longer the actors, but the spectators of the         
\par play. Or rather we are both. We watch ourselves, and the mere wonder        
\par of the spectacle enthralls us. In the present case, what is it that         
\par has really happened? Some one has killed herself for love of you. I         
\par wish that I had ever had such an experience. It would have made me          
\par in love with love for the rest of my life. The people who have              
\par adored me- there have not been very many, but there have been some-         
\par have always insisted on living on, long after I had ceased to care for      
\par them, or they to care for me. They have become stout and tedious,           
\par and when I meet them they go in at once for reminiscences. That             
\par awful memory of woman! What a fearful thing it is! And what an utter        
\par intellectual stagnation it reveals! One should absorb the colour of         
\par life, but one should never remember its details. Details are always         
\par vulgar."                                                                    
\par   "I must sow poppies in my garden," sighed Dorian.                         
\par   "There is no necessity," rejoined his companion. "Life has always         
\par poppies in her hands. Of course, now and then things linger. I once         
\par wore nothing but violets all through one season, as a form of artistic      
\par mourning for a romance that would not die. Ultimately, however, it did      
\par die. I forget what killed it. I think it was her proposing to               
\par sacrifice the whole world for me. That is always a dreadful moment. It      
\par fills one with the terror of eternity. Well- would you believe it?-         
\par a week ago, at Lady Hampshire's, I found myself seated at dinner            
\par next the lady in question, and she insisted on going over the whole         
\par thing again, and digging up the past, and raking up the future. I           
\par had buried my romance in a bed of asphodel. She dragged it out              
\par again, and assured me that I had spoiled her life, I am bound to state      
\par that she ate an enormous dinner, so I did not feel any anxiety. But         
\par what a lack of taste she showed! The one charm of the past is that          
\par it is the past. But women never know when the curtain has fallen. They      
\par always want a sixth act, and as soon the interest of the play is            
\par entirely over they propose to continue it. If they were allowed             
\par their own way, every comedy would have a tragic ending, and every           
\par tragedy would culminate in a farce. They are charmingly artificial,         
\par but they have no sense of art. You are more fortunate than I am. I          
\par assure you, Dorian, that not one of the women I have known would            
\par have done for me what Sibyl Vane did for you. Ordinary women always         
\par console themselves. Some of them do it by going in for sentimental          
\par colours. Never trust a woman who wears mauve, whatever her age may be,      
\par or a woman over thirty-five who is fond of pink ribbons. It always          
\par means that they have a history. Others find a great consolation in          
\par suddenly discovering the good qualities of their husbands. They flaunt      
\par their conjugal felicity in one's face, as if it were the most               
\par fascinating of sins. Religion consoles some. Its mysteries have all         
\par the charm of a flirtation, a woman once told me, and I can quite            
\par understand it. Besides, nothing makes one so vain as being told that        
\par one is a sinner. Conscience makes egotists of us all. Yes; there is         
\par really no end to the consolations that women find in modern life.           
\par Indeed, I have not mentioned the most important one."                       
\par   "What is that, Harry?" said the lad, listlessly.                          
\par   "Oh, the obvious consolation. Taking some one else's admirer when         
\par one loses one's own. In good society that always whitewashes a              
\par woman. But really, Dorian, how different Sibyl Vane must have been          
\par from all the women one meets! There is something to me quite beautiful      
\par about her death. I am glad I am living in a century when such               
\par wonders happen. They make one believe in the reality of the things          
\par we all play with, such as romance, passion, and love."                      
\par   "I was terribly cruel to her. You forget that."                           
\par   "I am afraid that women appreciate cruelty, downright cruelty,            
\par more than anything else. They have wonderfully primitive instincts. We      
\par have emancipated them, but they remain slaves looking for their             
\par masters, all the same. They love being dominated. I am sure you were        
\par splendid. I have never seen you really and absolutely angry, but I can      
\par fancy how delightful you looked. And, after all, you said something to      
\par the me the day before yesterday that seemed to me at the time to be         
\par merely fanciful, but that I see now was absolutely true, and it             
\par holds the key to everything."                                               
\par   "What was that, Harry?"                                                   
\par   "You said to me that Sibyl Vane represented to you all the                
\par heroines of romance- that she was Desdemona one night, and Ophelia the      
\par other; that if she died as Juliet, she came to life as Imogen."             
\par   "She will never come to life again now," muttered the lad, burying        
\par his face in his hands.                                                      
\par   "No, she will never come to life. She has played her last part.           
\par But you must think of that lonely death in the tawdry dressing-room         
\par simply as a strange lurid fragment from some Jacobean tragedy, as a         
\par wonderful scene from Webster, or Ford, or Cyril Tourneur. The girl          
\par never really lived, and so she has never really died. To you at             
\par least she was always a dream, a phantom that flitted through                
\par Shakespeare's plays and left them lovelier for its presence, a reed         
\par through which Shakespeare's music sounded richer and more full of joy.      
\par The moment she touched actual life, she marred it, and it marred            
\par her, and so she passed away. Mourn for Ophelia, if you like. Put ashes      
\par on your head because Cordelia was strangled. Cry out against Heaven         
\par because the daughter of Brabantio died. But don't waste your tears          
\par over Sibyl Vane. She was less real than they are."                          
\par   There was silence. The evening darkened in the room. Noiselessly,         
\par and with silver feet, the shadows crept in from the garden. The             
\par colours faded wearily out of things.                                        
\par   After some time Dorian Gray looked up. "You have explained me to          
\par myself, Harry," he murmured, with something of a sigh of relief. "I         
\par felt all that you have said, but somehow I was afraid of it, and I          
\par could not express it to myself. How well you know me! But we will           
\par not talk again of what has happened. It has been a marvellous               
\par experience. That is all. I wonder if life has still in store for me         
\par anything as marvellous."                                                    
\par   "Life has everything in store for you, Dorian. There is nothing that      
\par you, with your extraordinary good looks, will not be able to do."           
\par   "But suppose, Harry, I became haggard, and old, and wrinkled? What        
\par then?"                                                                      
\par   "Ah, then," said Lord Henry, rising to go, "then, my dear Dorian,         
\par you would have to fight for your victories. As it is, they are brought      
\par to you. No, you must keep your good looks. We live in an age that           
\par reads too much to be wise, and that thinks too much to be beautiful.        
\par We cannot spare you. And now you had better dress, and drive down to        
\par the club. We are rather late, as it is."                                    
\par   "I think I shall join you at the Opera, Harry. I feel too tired to        
\par eat anything. What is the number of your sister's box?"                     
\par   "Twenty-seven, I believe. It is on the grand tier. You will see           
\par her name on the door. But I am sorry you won't come and dine."              
\par   "I don't feel up to it," said Dorian, listlessly. "But I am               
\par awfully obliged to you for all that you have said to me. You are            
\par certainly my best friend. No one has ever understood me as you have."       
\par   "We are only at the beginning of our friendship, Dorian," answered        
\par Lord Henry, shaking him by the hand. "Good-bye. I shall see you before      
\par nine-thirty, I hope. Remember, Patti is singing."                           
\par   As he closed the door behind him, Dorian Gray touched the bell,           
\par and in a few minutes Victor appeared with the lamps and drew the            
\par blinds down. He waited impatiently for him to go. The man seemed to         
\par take an interminable time over everything.                                  
\par   As soon as he had left, he rushed to the screen, and drew it back.        
\par No; there was no further change in the picture. It had received the         
\par news of Sibyl Vane's death before he had known of it himself. It was        
\par conscious of the events of life as they occurred. The vicious               
\par cruelty that marred the fine lines of the mouth had, no doubt,              
\par appeared at the very moment that the girl had drunk the poison,             
\par whatever it was. Or was it indifferent to results? Did it merely            
\par take cognizance of what passed within the soul? He wondered, and hoped      
\par that some day he would see the change taking place before his very          
\par eyes, shuddering as he hoped it.                                            
\par   Poor Sibyl! what a romance it had all been! She had often mimicked        
\par death on the stage. Then Death himself had touched her, and taken           
\par her with him. How had she played that dreadful last scene, Had she          
\par cursed him, as she died? No; she had died for love of him, and love         
\par would always be a sacrament to him now. She had atoned for everything,      
\par by the sacrifice she had made of her life. He would not think any more      
\par of what she had made him go through, on that horrible night at the          
\par theatre. When he thought of her, it would be as a wonderful tragic          
\par figure sent on to the world's stage to show the supreme reality of          
\par Love. A wonderful tragic figure? Tears came to his eyes as he               
\par remembered her childlike look and winsome fanciful ways and shy             
\par tremulous grace. He brushed them away hastily, and looked again at the      
\par picture.                                                                    
\par   He felt that the time had really come for making his choice. Or           
\par had his choice already been made? Yes, life had decided that for            
\par him- life, and his own infinite curiosity about life. Eternal youth,        
\par infinite passion, pleasure subtle and secret, wild joys and wilder          
\par sins- he was to have all these things. The portrait was to bear the         
\par burden of his shame: that was all.                                          
\par   A feeling of pain crept over him as he thought of the desecration         
\par that was in store for the fair face on the canvas. Once, in boyish          
\par mockery of Narcissus, he had kissed, or feigned to kiss, those painted      
\par lips that now smiled so cruelly at him. Morning after morning he had        
\par sat before the portrait wondering at its beauty, almost enamoured of        
\par it, as it seemed to him at times. Was it to alter now with every            
\par mood to which he yielded? Was it to become a monstrous and loathsome        
\par thing, to be hidden away in a locked room, to be shut out from the          
\par sunlight that had so often touched to brighter gold the waving              
\par wonder of its hair? The pity of it! the pity of it!                         
\par   For a moment he thought of praying that the horrible sympathy that        
\par existed between him and the picture might cease. It had changed in          
\par answer to a prayer; perhaps in answer to a prayer it might remain           
\par unchanged. And, yet, who, that knew anything about Life, would              
\par surrender the chance of remaining always young, however fantastic that      
\par chance might be, or with what fateful consequences it might be              
\par fraught? Besides, was it really under his control? Had it indeed            
\par been prayer that had produced the substitution? Might there not be          
\par some curious scientific reason for it all? If thought could exercise        
\par its influence upon a living organism, might not thought exercise an         
\par influence upon dead and inorganic things? Nay, without thought or           
\par conscious desire, might not things external to ourselves vibrate in         
\par unison with our moods and passions, atom calling to atom in secret          
\par love or strange affinity? But the reason was of no importance. He           
\par would never again tempt by a prayer any terrible power. If the picture      
\par was to alter, it was to alter. That was all. Why inquire too closely        
\par into it?                                                                    
\par   For there would be a real pleasure in watching it. He would be            
\par able to follow his mind into its secret places. This portrait would be      
\par to him the most magical of mirrors. As it had revealed to him his           
\par own body, so it would reveal to him his own soul. And when winter came      
\par upon it, he would still be standing where spring trembles on the verge      
\par of summer. When the blood crept from its face, and left behind a            
\par pallid mask of chalk with leaden eyes, he would keep the glamour of         
\par boyhood. Not one blossom of his loveliness would ever fade. Not one         
\par pulse of his life would ever weaken. Like the gods of the Greeks, he        
\par would be strong, and fleet, and joyous. What did it matter what             
\par happened to the coloured image on the canvas? He would be safe. That        
\par was everything.                                                             
\par   He drew the screen back into its former place in front of the             
\par picture, smiling as he did so, and passed into his bedroom, where           
\par his valet was already waiting for him. An hour later he was at the          
\par Opera, and Lord Henry was leaning over his chair.                           
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                               CHAPTER IX                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   As he was sitting at breakfast next morning, Basil Hallward was           
\par shown into the room.                                                        
\par   "I am glad I have found you, Dorian," he said gravely. "I called          
\par last night, and they told me you were at the Opera. Of course I knew        
\par that was impossible. But I wish you hid left word where you had really      
\par gone to. I passed a dreadful evening, half afraid that one tragedy          
\par might be followed by another. I think you might have telegraphed for        
\par me when you heard of it first. I read of it quite by chance in a            
\par late edition of The Globe, that I picked up at the club. I came here        
\par at once, and was miserable at not finding you. I can't tell you how         
\par heartbroken I am about the whole thing. I know what you must suffer.        
\par But where were you? Did you go down and see the girl's mother? For a        
\par moment I thought of following you there. They gave the address in           
\par the paper. Somewhere in the Euston Road, isn't it? But I was afraid of      
\par intruding upon a sorrow that I could not lighten. Poor woman! What a        
\par state she must be in! And her only child, too! What did she say             
\par about it all?"                                                              
\par   "My dear Basil, how do I know?" murmured Dorian Gray, sipping some        
\par pale-yellow wine from a delicate gold-beaded bubble of Venetian glass,      
\par and looking dreadfully bored. "I was at the Opera. You should have          
\par come on there. met Lady Gwendolyn, Harry's sister, for the first time.      
\par We were in her box. She is perfectly charming; and Patti sang               
\par divinely. Don't talk about horrid subjects. If one doesn't talk             
\par about a thing, it has never happened. It is simply expression, as           
\par Harry says, that gives reality to things. I may mention that she was        
\par not the woman's only child. There is a son, a charming fellow, I            
\par believe. But he is not on the stage. He is a sailor, or something. And      
\par now, tell me about yourself and what you are painting."                     
\par   "You went to the Opera?" said Hallward, speaking very slowly, and         
\par with a strained touch of pain in his voice. "You went to the Opera          
\par while Sibyl Vane was lying dead in some sordid lodging? You can talk        
\par to me of other women being charming, and of Patti singing divinely,         
\par before the girl you loved has even the quiet of a grave to sleep in?        
\par Why, man, there are horrors in store for that little white body of          
\par hers!"                                                                      
\par   "Stop, Basil! I won't hear it!" cried Dorian, leaping to his feet.        
\par "You must not tell me about things. What is done is done. What is past      
\par is past."                                                                   
\par   "You call yesterday the past?"                                            
\par   "What has the actual lapse of time got to do with it? It is only          
\par shallow people who require years to get rid of an emotion. A man who        
\par is master of himself can end a sorrow as easily as he can invent a          
\par pleasure. I don't want to be at the mercy of my emotions. I want to         
\par use them, to enjoy them, and to dominate them."                             
\par   "Dorian, this is horrible! Something has changed you completely. You      
\par look exactly like the same wonderful boy who, day after day, used to        
\par come down to my studio to sit for his picture. But you were simple,         
\par natural, and affectionate then. You were the most unspoiled creature        
\par in the whole world. Now, I don't know what has come over you. You talk      
\par as if you had no heart, no pity in you. It is all Harry's influence. I      
\par see that."                                                                  
\par   The lad flushed up, and, going to the window, looked out for a few        
\par moments on the green, flickering, sun-lashed garden. "I owe a great         
\par deal to Harry, Basil," he said, at last, "more than I owe to you.           
\par You only taught me to be vain."                                             
\par   "Well, I am punished for that, Dorian- or shall be some day."             
\par   "I don't know what you mean, Basil," he exclaimed, turning round. "I      
\par don't know what you want. What do you want?"                                
\par   "I want the Dorian Gray I used to paint," said the artist, sadly.         
\par   "Basil," said the lad, going over to him, and putting his hand on         
\par his shoulder, "you have come too late. Yesterday when I heard that          
\par Sibyl Vane had killed herself--"                                            
\par   "Killed herself! Good heavens! is there no doubt about that?"             
\par cried Hallward, looking up at him with an expression of horror.             
\par   "My dear Basil! Surely you don't think it was a vulgar accident?          
\par Of course she killed herself."                                              
\par   The elder man buried his face in his hands. "How fearful," he             
\par muttered, and a shudder ran through him.                                    
\par   "No," said Dorian Gray, "there is nothing fearful about it. It is         
\par one of the great romantic tragedies of the age. As a rule, people           
\par who act lead the most commonplace lives. They are good husbands, or         
\par faithful wives, or something tedious. You know what I mean-                 
\par middle-class virtue, and all that kind of thing. How different Sibyl        
\par was! She lived her finest tragedy. She was always a heroine. The            
\par last night she played- the night you saw her- she acted badly               
\par because she had known, the reality of love. When she knew its               
\par unreality, she died, as Juliet might have died. She passed again            
\par into the sphere of art. There is something of the martyr about her.         
\par Her death has all the pathetic uselessness of martyrdom, all its            
\par wasted beauty. But as I was saying, you must not think I have not           
\par suffered. If you had come in yesterday at a particular moment- about        
\par half-past five, perhaps, or a quarter to six- you would have found          
\par me in tears. Even Harry, who was here, who brought me the news, in          
\par fact, had no idea what I was going through. I suffered immensely. Then      
\par it passed away. I cannot repeat an emotion. No one can, except              
\par sentimentalists. And you are awfully unjust, Basil. You come down here      
\par to console me. That is charming of you. You find me consoled, and           
\par you are furious. How like a sympathetic person! You remind me of a          
\par story Harry told me about a certain philanthropist who spent twenty         
\par years of his life in trying to get some grievance redressed, or some        
\par unjust law altered- I forget exactly what it was. Finally he                
\par succeeded, and nothing could exceed his disappointment. He had              
\par absolutely nothing to do, almost died of ennui, and became a confirmed      
\par misanthrope. And besides, my dear old Basil, if you really want to          
\par console me, teach me rather to forget what has happened, or to see          
\par it from a proper artistic point of view. Was it not Gautier who used        
\par to write about la consolation des arts? I remember picking up a little      
\par vellum-covered book in our studio one day and chancing on that              
\par delightful phrase. Well, I am not like that young man you told me of        
\par when we were down at Marlow together, the young man who used to say         
\par that yellow satin could console one for all the miseries of life. I         
\par love beautiful things that one can touch and handle. Old brocades,          
\par green bronzes, lacquerwork, carved ivories, exquisite surroundings,         
\par luxury, pomp, there is much to be got from all these. But the artistic      
\par temperament that they create, or at any rate reveal, is still more          
\par to me. To become the spectator of one's own life, as Harry says, is to      
\par escape the suffering of life. I know you are surprised at my talking        
\par to you like this. You have not realized how I have developed. I was         
\par a schoolboy when you knew me. I am a man now. I have new passions, new      
\par thoughts, new ideas. I am different, but you must not like me less.         
\par I am changed, but you must always be my friend. Of course I am very         
\par fond of Harry. But I know that you are better than he is. You are           
\par not stronger- you are too much afraid of life- but you are better. And      
\par how happy we used to be together! Don't leave me, Basil, and don't          
\par quarrel with me. I am what I am. There is nothing more to be said."         
\par   The painter felt strangely moved. The lad was infinitely dear to          
\par him, and his personality had been the great turning-point in his            
\par art. He could not bear the idea of reproaching him any more. After          
\par all, his indifference was probably merely a mood that would pass away.      
\par There was so much in him that was good, so much in him that was noble.      
\par   "Well, Dorian," he said, at length, with a sad smile, "I won't speak      
\par to you again about this horrible thing, after to-day. I only trust          
\par your name won't be mentioned in connection with it. The inquest is          
\par to take place this afternoon. Have they summoned you?"                      
\par   Dorian shook his head, and a look of annoyance passed over his            
\par face at the mention of the word "inquest." There was something so           
\par crude and vulgar about everything of the kind. "They don't know my          
\par name," he answered.                                                         
\par   "But surely she did?"                                                     
\par   "Only my Christian name, and that I am quite sure she never               
\par mentioned to any one. She told me once that they were all rather            
\par curious to learn who I was, and that she invariably told them my            
\par name was Prince Charming. It was pretty of her. You must do me a            
\par drawing of Sibyl, Basil. I should like to have something more of her        
\par than the memory of a few kisses and some broken pathetic words."            
\par   "I will try and do something, Dorian, if it would please you. But         
\par you must come and sit to me yourself again. I can't get on without          
\par you."                                                                       
\par   "I can never sit to you again, Basil. It is impossible!" he               
\par exclaimed, starting back.                                                   
\par   The painter stared at him. "My dear boy, what nonsense!" he cried.        
\par "Do you mean to say you don't like what I did for you? Where is it?         
\par Why, have you pulled the screen in front of it? Let me look at it?          
\par It is the best thing I have ever done. Do take the screen away,             
\par Dorian. It is simply, disgraceful of your servant hiding my work            
\par like that. I felt the room looked different as I came in."                  
\par   "My servant has nothing to do with it, Basil. You don't imagine I         
\par let him arrange my room for me? He settles my flowers for me                
\par sometimes- that is all. No; I did it myself. The light was too              
\par strong on the portrait."                                                    
\par   "Too strong! Surely not, my dear fellow? It is an admirable place         
\par for it. Let me see it." And Hallward walked towards the corner of           
\par the room.                                                                   
\par   A cry of terror broke from Dorian Gray's lips, and he rushed between      
\par the painter and the screen. "Basil," he said, looking very pale,            
\par "you must not look at it. I don't wish you to."                             
\par   "Not look at my own work! you are not serious. Why shouldn't I            
\par look at it?" exclaimed Hallward, laughing.                                  
\par   "If you try to look at it, Basil, on my word of honour I will             
\par never speak to you again as long as I live. I am quite serious. I           
\par don't offer any explanation, and you are not to ask for any. But,           
\par remember, if you touch this screen, everything is over between us."         
\par   Hallward was thunderstruck. He looked at Dorian Gray in absolute          
\par amazement. He had never seen him like this before. The lad was              
\par actually pallid with rage. His hands were clenched, and the pupils          
\par of his eyes were like disks of blue fire. He was trembling all over.        
\par   "Dorian!"                                                                 
\par   "Don't speak!"                                                            
\par   "But what is the matter? Of course I won't look at it if you don't        
\par want me to," he said, rather coldly, turning on his heel, and going         
\par over towards the window. "But, really, it seems rather absurd that I        
\par shouldn't see my own work. especially as I am going to exhibit it in        
\par Paris in the autumn. I shall probably have to give it another coat          
\par of varnish before that, so I must see it some day, and why not              
\par to-day?"                                                                    
\par   "To exhibit it! You want to exhibit it;" exclaimed Dorian Gray, a         
\par strange sense of terror creeping over him. Was the world going to be        
\par shown his secret? Were people to gape at the mystery of his life? That      
\par was impossible. Something- he did not know what- had to be done at          
\par once.                                                                       
\par   "Yes; I don't suppose you will object to that. Georges Petit is           
\par going to collect all my best pictures for a special exhibition in           
\par the Rue de Seze, which will open the first week in October. The             
\par portrait will only be away a month. I should think you could easily         
\par spare it for that time. In fact, you are sure to be out of town. And        
\par if you keep it always behind a screen, you can't care much about it."       
\par   Dorian Gray passed his hand over his forehead. There were beads of        
\par perspiration there. He felt that he was on the brink of a horrible          
\par danger. "You told me a month ago that you would never exhibit it,"          
\par he cried. "Why have you changed your mind? You people who go in for         
\par being consistent have just as many moods as others have. The only           
\par difference is that your moods are rather meaningless. You can't have        
\par forgotten that you assured me most solemnly that nothing in the             
\par world would induce you to send it to any exhibition. You told Harry         
\par exactly the same thing." He stopped suddenly, and a gleam of light          
\par came into his eyes. He remembered that Lord Henry had said to him           
\par once, half seriously, and half in jest, "If you want to have a strange      
\par quarter of an hour, get Basil to tell you why he won't exhibit your         
\par picture. He told me why he wouldn't, and it was a revelation to me."        
\par Yes, perhaps, Basil, too, had his secret. He would ask him and try.         
\par   "Basil," he said, coming over quite close, and looking him                
\par straight in the face, "we have each of us a secret. Let me know yours,      
\par and I shall tell you mine. What was your reason for refusing to             
\par exhibit my picture?"                                                        
\par   The painter shuddered in spite of himself. "Dorian, if I told you,        
\par you might like me less than you do, and you would certainly laugh at        
\par me. I could not bear your doing either of those two things. If you          
\par wish me never to look at your picture again, I am content. I have           
\par always you to look at. If you wish the best work I have ever done to        
\par be hidden from the world, I am satisfied. Your friendship is dearer to      
\par me than any fame or reputation."                                            
\par   "No, Basil, you must tell me," insisted Dorian Gray. "I think I have      
\par a right to know." His feeling of terror had passed away, and curiosity      
\par had taken its place. He was determined to find out Basil Hallward's         
\par mystery.                                                                    
\par   "Let us sit down, Dorian," said the painter, looking troubled.            
\par "Let us sit down. And just answer me one question. Have you noticed in      
\par the picture something curious?- something that probably at first did        
\par not strike you, but that revealed itself to you suddenly?"                  
\par   "Basil!" cried the lad, clutching the arms of his chair with              
\par trembling hands, and gazing at him with wild, startled eyes.                
\par   "I see you did. Don't speak. Wait till you hear what I have to            
\par say. Dorian, from the moment I met you, your personality had the            
\par most extraordinary influence over me. I was dominated, soul, brain,         
\par and power by you. You became to me the visible incarnation of that          
\par unseen ideal whose memory haunts us artists like an exquisite dream. I      
\par worshipped you. I grew jealous of every one to whom you spoke. I            
\par wanted to have you all to myself. I was only happy when I was with          
\par you. When you were away from me you were still present in my art....        
\par Of course I never let you know anything about this. It would have been      
\par impossible. You would not have understood it. I hardly understood it        
\par myself. I only, knew that I had seen perfection face to face, and that      
\par the world had become wonderful to my eyes- too wonderful, perhaps, for      
\par in such mad worships there is peril, the peril of losing them, no less      
\par than the peril of keeping them.... Weeks and weeks went on, and I grew      
\par more and more absorbed in you. Then came a new development. I had           
\par drawn you as Paris in dainty armour, and as Adonis with huntsman's          
\par cloak and polished boar-spear. Crowned with heavy lotus-blossoms you        
\par had sat on the prow of Adrian's barge, gazing across the green              
\par turbid Nile. You had leaned over the still pool of some Greek               
\par woodland, and seen in the water's silent silver the marvel of your own      
\par face. And it had all been what art should be, unconscious, ideal,           
\par and remote. One day, a fatal day I sometimes think, I determined to         
\par paint a wonderful portrait of you as you actually are, not in the           
\par costume of dead ages, but in your own dress and in your own time.           
\par Whether it was the Realism of the method or the mere wonder of your         
\par own personality, thus directly presented to me without mist or veil, I      
\par cannot tell. But I know that as I worked at it, every flake and film        
\par of colour seemed to me to reveal my secret. I grew afraid that              
\par others would know of my idolatry. I felt, Dorian, that I had told           
\par too much, that I had put too much of myself into it. Then it was            
\par that I resolved never to allow the picture to be exhibited. You were a      
\par little annoyed; but then you did not realize all that it meant to           
\par me. Harry, to whom I talked about it, laughed at me. But I did not          
\par mind that. When the picture was finished, and I sat alone with it, I        
\par felt that I was right.... Well, after a few days the thing left my          
\par studio, and as soon as I had got rid of the intolerable fascination of      
\par its presence it seemed to me that I had been foolish in imagining that      
\par I had seen anything in it, more than that you were extremely                
\par good-looking and that I could paint. Even now I cannot help feeling         
\par that it is a mistake to think that the passion one feels in creation        
\par is ever really shown in the work one creates. Art is always more            
\par abstract than we fancy. Form and colour tell us of form and colour-         
\par that is all. It often seems to me that art conceals the artist far          
\par more completely than it ever reveals him. And so when I got this offer      
\par from Paris I determined to make your portrait the principal thing in        
\par my exhibition. It never occurred to me that you would refuse. I see         
\par now that you were right. The picture cannot be shown. You must not          
\par be angry with me, Dorian, for what I have told you. As I said to            
\par Harry, once, you are made to be worshipped."                                
\par   Dorian Gray drew a long breath. The colour came back to his               
\par cheeks, and a smile played about his lips. The peril was over. He           
\par was safe for the time. Yet he could not help feeling infinite pity for      
\par the painter who had just made this strange confession to him, and           
\par wondered if he himself would ever be so dominated by the personality        
\par of a friend. Lord Henry had the charm of being very dangerous. But          
\par that was all. He was too clever and too cynical to be really fond           
\par of. Would there ever be some one who would fill him with a strange          
\par idolatry? Was that one of the things that life had in store?                
\par   "It is extraordinary, to me, Dorian," said Hallward, "that you            
\par should have seen this in the portrait. Did you really see it?"              
\par   "I saw something in it," he answered, "something that seemed to me        
\par very curious."                                                              
\par   "Well, you don't mind my looking at the thing now?"                       
\par   Dorian shook his head. "You must not ask me that, Basil. I could not      
\par possibly let you stand in front of that picture."                           
\par   "You will some day, surely?"                                              
\par   "Never."                                                                  
\par   "Well, perhaps you are right. And now good-bye, Dorian. You have          
\par been the one person in my life who has really influenced my art.            
\par Whatever I have done that is good, I owe to you. Ah! you don't know         
\par what it cost me to tell you all that I have told you."                      
\par   "My dear Basil," said Dorian, "what have you told me? Simply that         
\par you felt that you admired me too much. That is not even a compliment."      
\par   "It was not intended as a compliment. It was a confession. Now            
\par that I have made it, something seems to have gone out of me. Perhaps        
\par one should never put one's worship into words."                             
\par   "It was a disappointing confession."                                      
\par   "Why, what did you expect, Dorian? You didn't see anything else in        
\par the picture, did you? There was nothing else to see?"                       
\par   "No; there was nothing else to see. Why do you ask? But you               
\par mustn't talk about worship. It is foolish. You and I are friends,           
\par Basil, and we must always remain so."                                       
\par   "You have got Harry," said the painter, sadly.                            
\par   "Oh, Harry,?" cried the lad, with a ripple of laughter. "Harry            
\par spends his days in saying what is incredible, and his evenings in           
\par doing what is improbable. Just the sort of life I would like to             
\par lead. But still I don't think I would go to Harry if I were in              
\par trouble. I would sooner go to you, Basil."                                  
\par   "You will sit to me again?"                                               
\par   "Impossible!"                                                             
\par   "You spoil my life as an artist by refusing, Dorian. No man came          
\par across two ideal things. Few come across one."                              
\par   "I can't explain it to you, Basil, but I must never sit to you            
\par again. There is something fatal about a portrait. It has a life of its      
\par own. I will come and have tea with you. That will be just as                
\par pleasant."                                                                  
\par   "Pleasanter for you, I am afraid," murmured Hallward, regretfully.        
\par "And now good-bye. I am sorry you won't let me look at the picture          
\par once again. But that can't be helped. I quite understand what you feel      
\par about it."                                                                  
\par   As he left the room, Dorian Gray smiled to himself. Poor Basil!           
\par how little he knew of the true reason! And how strange it was that,         
\par instead of having been forced to reveal his own secret, he had              
\par succeeded, almost by chance, in wresting a secret from his friend! How      
\par much that strange confession explained to him! The painter's absurd         
\par fits of jealousy, his wild devotion, his extravagant panegyrics, his        
\par curious reticences- he understood them all now, and he felt sorry.          
\par There seemed to him to be something tragic in a friendship so coloured      
\par by romance.                                                                 
\par   He sighed and touched a bell. The portrait must be hidden away at         
\par all costs. He could not run such a risk of discovery again. It had          
\par been mad of him to have allowed the thing to remain, even for an hour,      
\par in a room to which any of his friends had access.                           
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                               CHAPTER X                                     
\par -                                                                           
\par   When his servant entered, he looked at him steadfastly, and wondered      
\par if he had thought of peering behind the screen. The man was quite           
\par impassive, and waited for his orders. Dorian lit a cigarette, and           
\par walked over to the glass and glanced into it. He could see the              
\par reflection of Victor's face perfectly. It was like a placid mask of         
\par servility. There was nothing to be afraid of, there. Yet he thought it      
\par best to be on his guard.                                                    
\par   Speaking very slowly, he told him to tell the housekeeper that he         
\par wanted to see her, and then to go to the frame-maker and ask him to         
\par send two of his men round at once. It seemed to him that as the man         
\par left the room his eyes wandered in the direction of the screen. Or was      
\par that merely his own fancy?                                                  
\par   After a few moments, in her black silk dress with old-fashioned           
\par thread mittens on her wrinkled hands, Mrs. Leaf bustled into the            
\par library. He asked for the key of the schoolroom.                            
\par   "The old schoolroom, Mr. Dorian," she exclaimed. "Why, it is full of      
\par dust. I must get it arranged, and put it straight before you go into        
\par it. It is not fit for you to see, sir. It is not, indeed."                  
\par   "I don't want it put straight, Leaf. I only want the key."                
\par   "Well, sir, you'll be covered with cobwebs if you go into it. Why,        
\par it hasn't been opened for nearly five years, not since his lordship         
\par died."                                                                      
\par   He winced at the mention of his grandfather. He had hateful memories      
\par of him. "That does not matter," he answered. "I simply want to see the      
\par place- that is all. Give me the key."                                       
\par   "And here is the key, sir," said the old lady, going over the             
\par contents of her bunch with tremulously uncertain hands. "Here is the        
\par key. I'll have it off the bunch in a moment. But you don't think of         
\par living up there, sir, and you so comfortable here?"                         
\par   "No, no," he cried, petulantly. "Thank you, Leaf. That will do."          
\par   She lingered for a few moments, and was garrulous over some detail        
\par of the household. He sighed, and told her to manage things as she           
\par thought best. She left the room, wreathed in smiles.                        
\par   As the door closed, Dorian put the key in his pocket, and looked          
\par round the room. His eye fell on a large purple satin coverlet               
\par heavily embroidered with gold, a splendid piece of late                     
\par seventeenth-century Venetian work that his grandfather had found it         
\par a convent near Bologna. Yes, that would serve to wrap the dreadful          
\par thing in. It had perhaps served often as a pall for the dead. Now it        
\par was to hide something that had a corruption of its own, worse than the      
\par corruption of death itself- something that would breed horrors and yet      
\par would never die. What the worm was to the corpse, his sins would be to      
\par the painted image on the canvas. They would mar its beauty, and eat         
\par its grace. They would defile it, and make it shameful. And yet the          
\par thing would still live on. It would be always alive.                        
\par   He shuddered, and for a moment he regretted that he had not told          
\par Basil the true reason why he had wished to hide the picture away.           
\par Basil would have helped him to resist Lord Henry's influence, and           
\par the still more poisonous influences that came from his own                  
\par temperament. The love that he bore him- for it was really love- had         
\par nothing in it that was not noble and intellectual. It was not that          
\par mere physical admiration of beauty that is born of the senses, and          
\par that dies when the senses tire. It was such love as Michael Angelo had      
\par known, and Montaigne, and Winckelmann, and Shakespeare himself. Yes,        
\par Basil could have saved him. But it was too late now. The past could         
\par always be annihilated. Regret, denial, or forgetfulness could do that.      
\par But the future was inevitable. There were passions in him that would        
\par find their terrible outlet, dreams that would make the shadow of their      
\par evil real.                                                                  
\par   He took up from the couch the great purple-and-gold texture that          
\par covered it, and, holding it in his hands, passed behind the screen.         
\par Was the face on the canvas viler than before, it seemed to him that it      
\par was unchanged; and yet his loathing of it was intensified. Gold             
\par hair, blue eyes, and rose-red lips- they all were there. It was simply      
\par the expression that had altered. That was horrible in its cruelty.          
\par Compared to what he saw in it of censure or rebuke, how shallow             
\par Basil's reproaches about Sibyl Vane had been!- how shallow, and of          
\par what little account! His own soul was looking out at him from the           
\par canvas and calling him to judgment. A look of pain came across him,         
\par and he flung the rich pall over the picture. As he did so, a knock          
\par came to the door. He passed out as his servant entered.                     
\par   "The persons are here, Monsieur."                                         
\par   He felt that the man must be got rid of at once. He must not be           
\par allowed to know where the picture was being taken to. There was             
\par something sly about him, and he had thoughtful, treacherous eyes.           
\par Sitting down at the writing-table, he scribbled a note to Lord              
\par Henry, asking him to send him round something to read, and reminding        
\par him that they were to meet at eight-fifteen that evening.                   
\par   "Wait for an answer," he said, handing it to him, "and show the           
\par men in here."                                                               
\par   In two or three minutes there was another knock, and Mr. Hubbard          
\par himself, the celebrated frame-maker of South Audley Street, came in         
\par with a somewhat rough-looking young assistant. Mr. Hubbard was a            
\par florid, red-whiskered little man, whose admiration for art was              
\par considerably tempered by the inveterate impecuniosity of most of the        
\par artists who dealt with him. As a rule, he never left his shop. He           
\par waited for people to come to him. But he always made an exception in        
\par favor of Dorian Gray. There was something about Dorian that charmed         
\par everybody. It was a pleasure even to see him.                               
\par   "What can I do for you, Mr. Gray?" he said, rubbing his fat freckled      
\par hands. "I thought I would do myself the honour of coming round in           
\par person. I have just got a beauty of a frame, sir. Picked it up at a         
\par sale. Came from Fonthill, I believe. Admirably suited for a                 
\par religious subject, Mr. Gray."                                               
\par   "I am so sorry you have given yourself the trouble of coming              
\par round, Mr. Hubbard. I shall certainly drop in and look at the frame-        
\par though I don't go in much at present for religious art- but to-day,         
\par I only want a picture carried to the top of the house for me. It is         
\par rather heavy, so I thought I would ask you to lend me a couple of your      
\par men."                                                                       
\par   "No trouble at all, Mr. Gray. I am delighted to be of any service to      
\par you. Which is the work of art, sir?"                                        
\par   "This," replied Dorian, moving the screen back. "Can you move it,         
\par covering and all, just as it is? I don't want it to get scratched           
\par going upstairs."                                                            
\par   "There will be no difficulty, sir," said the genial frame-maker,          
\par beginning, with the aid of his assistant, to unhook the picture from        
\par the long brass chains by which it was suspended. "And, now, where           
\par shall we carry it to, Mr. Gray?"                                            
\par   "I will show you the way, Mr. Hubbard, if you will kindly follow me.      
\par Or perhaps you had better go in front. I am afraid it is right at           
\par the top of the house. We will go up by the front staircase, as it is        
\par wider."                                                                     
\par   He held the door open for them, and they passed out into the hall         
\par and began the ascent. The elaborate character of the frame had made         
\par the picture extremely bulky, and now and then, in spite of the              
\par obsequious protests of Mr. Hubbard, who had the true tradesman's            
\par spirited dislike of seeing a gentleman doing anything useful, Dorian        
\par put his hand to it so as to help them.                                      
\par   "Something of a load to carry, sir," gasped the little man, when          
\par they reached the top landing. And he wiped his shiny forehead.              
\par   "I am afraid it is rather heavy," murmured Dorian, as he unlocked         
\par the door that opened into the room that was to keep for him the             
\par curious secret of his life and hide his soul from the eyes of men.          
\par   He had not entered the place for more than four years- not,               
\par indeed, since he had used it first as a playroom when he was a              
\par child, and then as a study when he grew somewhat older. It was a            
\par large, well-proportioned room, which had been specially built by the        
\par last Lord Kelso for the use of the little grandson whom, for his            
\par strange likeness to his mother, and also for other reasons, he had          
\par always hated and desired to keep at a distance. It appeared to              
\par Dorian to have but little changed. There was the huge Italian cassone,      
\par with its fantastically-painted panels and its tarnished gilt                
\par mouldings, in which he had so often hidden himself as a boy. There the      
\par satinwood bookcase filled with his dog-eared schoolbooks. On the            
\par wall behind it was hanging the same ragged Flemish tapestry where a         
\par faded king and queen were playing chess in a garden, while a company        
\par of hawkers rode by, carrying hooded birds on their gauntleted               
\par wrists. How well he remembered it all! Every moment of his lonely           
\par childhood came back to him as he looked round. He recalled the              
\par stainless purity of his boyish life, and it seemed horrible to him          
\par that it was here the fatal portrait was to be hidden away. How              
\par little he had thought, in those dead days, of all that was in store         
\par for him!                                                                    
\par   But there was no other place in the house so secure from prying eyes      
\par as this. He had the key, and no one else could enter it. Beneath its        
\par purple pall, the face painted on the canvas could grow bestial,             
\par sodden, and unclean. What did it matter? No one could see it. He            
\par himself would not see it. Why should he watch the hideous corruption        
\par of his soul? He kept his youth- that was enough. And, besides, might        
\par not his nature grow finer, after all? There was no reason that the          
\par future should be so full of shame. Some love might come across his          
\par life, and purify him, and shield him from those sins that seemed to be      
\par already stirring in spirit and in flesh- those curious unpictured sins      
\par whose very mystery lent them their subtlety and their charm.                
\par Perhaps, some day, the cruel look would have passed away from the           
\par scarlet sensitive mouth, and he might show to the world Basil               
\par Hallward's masterpiece.                                                     
\par   No; that was impossible. Hour by hour, and week by week, the thing        
\par upon the canvas was growing old. It might escape the hideousness of         
\par sin, but the hideousness of age was in store for it. The cheeks             
\par would become hollow or flaccid. Yellow crow's-feet would creep round        
\par the fading eyes and make them horrible. The hair would lose its             
\par brightness, the mouth would gape or droop, would be foolish or              
\par gross, as the mouths of old men are. There would be the wrinkled            
\par throat, the cold, blue-veined hands, the twisted body, that he              
\par remembered in the grandfather who had been so stern to him in his           
\par boyhood. The picture had to be concealed. There was no help for it.         
\par   "Bring it in, Mr. Hubbard, please," he said, wearily, turning round.      
\par "I am sorry I kept you waiting so long. I was thinking of something         
\par else."                                                                      
\par   "Always glad to have a rest, Mr. Gray," answered the frame-maker,         
\par who was still gasping for breath. "Where shall we put it, sir?"             
\par   "Oh, anywhere. Here: this will do. I don't want to have it hung           
\par up. Just lean it against the wall. Thanks."                                 
\par   "Might one look at the work of art, sir?"                                 
\par   Dorian started. "It would not interest you, Mr. Hubbard," he said,        
\par keeping his eye on the man. He felt ready to leap upon him and fling        
\par him to the ground if he dared to lift the gorgeous hanging that             
\par concealed the secret of his life. "I shan't trouble you any more            
\par now. I am much obliged for your kindness in coming round."                  
\par   "Not at all, not at all, Mr. Gray. Ever ready to do anything for          
\par you, sir." And Mr. Hubbard tramped downstairs, followed by the              
\par assistant, who glanced back at Dorian with a look of shy wonder in his      
\par rough, uncomely face. He had never seen any one so marvellous.              
\par   When the sound of their footsteps had died away, Dorian locked the        
\par door, and put the key in his pocket. He felt safe now. No one would         
\par ever look upon the horrible thing. No eye but his would ever see his        
\par shame.                                                                      
\par   On reaching the library he found that it was just after five              
\par o'clock, and that the tea had been already brought up. On a little          
\par table of dark perfumed wood thickly encrusted with nacre, a present         
\par from Lady Radley, his guardian's wife, a pretty professional                
\par invalid, who had spent the preceding winter in Cairo, was lying a note      
\par from Lord Henry, and beside it was a book bound in yellow paper, the        
\par cover slightly torn and the edges soiled. A copy of the third               
\par edition of The St. James Gazette had been placed on the tea-tray. It        
\par was evident that Victor had returned. He wondered if he had met the         
\par men in the hall as they were leaving the house, and had wormed out          
\par of them what they had been doing. He would be sure to miss the              
\par picture- had no doubt missed it already, while he had been laying           
\par the tea-things. The screen had not been set back, and a blank space         
\par was visible on the wall. Perhaps some night he might find him creeping      
\par upstairs and trying to force the door of the room. It was a horrible        
\par thing to have a spy in one's house. He had heard of rich men who had        
\par been blackmailed all their lives by some servant who had read a             
\par letter, or overheard a conversation, or picked up a card with an            
\par address, or found beneath a pillow a withered flower or a shred of          
\par crumpled lace.                                                              
\par   He sighed, and, having poured himself out some tea, opened Lord           
\par Henry's note. It was simply to say, that he sent him round the evening      
\par paper, and book that might interest him, and that he would be at the        
\par club at eight-fifteen. He opened The St. James languidly, and looked        
\par through it. A red pencil-mark on the fifth page caught his eye. It          
\par drew attention to the following paragraph:                                  
\par   "INQUEST ON AN ACTRESS.- An inquest was held this morning at the          
\par Bell Tavern, Hoxton Road, by Mr. Danby, the District Coroner, on the        
\par body of Sibyl Vane, a young actress recently engaged at the Royal           
\par Theatre, Holborn. A verdict of death by misadventure was returned.          
\par Considerable sympathy was expressed for the mother of the deceased,         
\par who was greatly affected during the giving of her own evidence and          
\par that of Dr. Birrell, who had made the postmortem examination of the         
\par deceased."                                                                  
\par   He frowned, and, tearing the paper in two went across the room and        
\par flung the pieces away. How ugly it all was! And how horribly real           
\par ugliness made things! He felt a little annoyed with Lord Henry for          
\par having sent him the report. And it was certainly stupid of him to have      
\par marked it with red pencil. Victor might have read it. The man knew          
\par more than enough English for that.                                          
\par   Perhaps he had read it, and had begun to suspect something. And,          
\par yet, what did it matter, What had Dorian Gray to do with Sibyl              
\par Vane's death? There was nothing to fear. Dorian Gray had not killed         
\par her.                                                                        
\par   His eye fell on the yellow book that Lord Henry had sent him. What        
\par was it, he wondered. He went towards the little pearl-coloured              
\par octagonal stand, that had always looked to him like the work of some        
\par strange Egyptian bees that wrought in silver, and taking up the             
\par volume, flung himself into an armchair, and began to turn over the          
\par leaves. After a few minutes he became absorbed. It was the strangest        
\par book that he had ever read. It seemed to him that in exquisite              
\par raiment, and to the delicate sound of flutes, the sins of the world         
\par were passing in dumb show before him. Things that he had dimly dreamed      
\par of were suddenly made real to him. Things of which he had never             
\par dreamed were gradually revealed.                                            
\par   It was a novel without a plot, and with only one character, being         
\par indeed, simply a psychological study of a certain young Parisian,           
\par who spent his life trying to realize in the nineteenth century all the      
\par passions and modes of thought that belonged to every century except         
\par his own, and to sum up, as it were, in himself the various moods            
\par through which the world-spirit had ever passed, loving for their            
\par mere artificiality those renunciations that men have unwisely called        
\par virtue, as much as those natural rebellions that wise men still call        
\par sin. The style in which it was written was that curious jewelled            
\par style, vivid and obscure at once, full of argot and of archaisms, of        
\par technical expressions and of elaborate paraphrases, that characterizes      
\par the work of some of the finest artists of the French school of              
\par Symbolistes. There were in it metaphors as monstrous as orchids, and        
\par as subtle in colour. The life of the senses was described in the terms      
\par of mystical philosophy. One hardly knew at times whether one was            
\par reading the spiritual ecstasies of some mediaeval saint or the              
\par morbid confessions of a modern sinner. It was a poisonous book. The         
\par heavy odor of incense seemed to cling about its pages and to trouble        
\par the brain. The mere cadence of the sentences, the subtle monotony of        
\par their music, so full as it was of complex refrains and movements            
\par elaborately repeated, produced in the mind of the lad, as he passed         
\par from chapter to chapter, a form of reverie, a malady of dreaming, that      
\par made him unconscious of the falling day and creeping shadows.               
\par   Cloudless, and pierced by one solitary star, a copper-green sky           
\par gleamed through the windows. He read on by its wan light till he could      
\par read no more. Then, after his valet had reminded him several times          
\par of the lateness of the hour, he got up, and, going into the next room,      
\par placed the book on the little Florentine table that always stood at         
\par his bedside, and began to dress for dinner.                                 
\par   It was almost nine o'clock before he reached the club, where he           
\par found Lord Henry sitting alone, in the morning-room, looking very much      
\par bored.                                                                      
\par   "I am so sorry, Harry," he cried, "but really it is entirely your         
\par fault. That book you sent me so fascinated me that I forgot how the         
\par time was going."                                                            
\par   "Yes: I thought you would like it," replied his host, rising from         
\par his chair.                                                                  
\par   "I didn't say I liked it, Harry. I said it fascinated me. There is a      
\par great difference."                                                          
\par   "Ah, you have discovered that?" murmured Lord Henry. And they passed      
\par into the dining-room.                                                       
