\par                                                                             
\par                               CHAPTER XI                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   For years, Dorian Gray could not free himself from the influence          
\par of this book. Or perhaps it would be more accurate to say that he           
\par never sought to free himself from it. He procured from Paris no less        
\par than nine large-paper copies of the first edition, and had them             
\par bound in different colours, so that they might suit his various             
\par moods and the changing fancies of a nature over which he seemed, at         
\par times, to have almost entirely lost control. The hero, the wonderful        
\par young Parisian, in whom the romantic and the scientific temperaments        
\par were so strangely blended, became to him a kind of prefiguring type of      
\par himself. And, indeed, the whole book seemed to him to contain the           
\par story of his own life, written before he had lived it.                      
\par   In one point he was more fortunate than the novel's fantastic             
\par hero. He never knew- never, indeed, had any cause to know- that             
\par somewhat grotesque dread of mirrors, and polished metal surfaces,           
\par and still waters, which came upon the young Parisian so early in his        
\par life, and was occasioned by the sudden decay of a beauty that had           
\par once, apparently, been so remarkable. It was with an almost cruel joy-      
\par and perhaps in nearly every joy, as certainly in every pleasure,            
\par cruelty has its place- that he used to read the latter part of the          
\par book, with its really tragic, if somewhat over-emphasized, account          
\par of the sorrow and despair of one who had himself lost what in               
\par others, and in the world, he had most dearly valued.                        
\par   For the wonderful beauty that had so fascinated Basil Hallward,           
\par and many others besides him, seemed never to leave him. Even those who      
\par had heard the most evil things against him, and from time to time           
\par strange rumours about his mode of life crept through London and became      
\par the chatter of the clubs, could not believe anything to his                 
\par dishonour when they saw him. He had always the look of one who had          
\par kept himself unspotted from the world. Men who talked grossly became        
\par silent when Dorian Gray entered the room. There was something in the        
\par purity of his face that rebuked them. His mere presence seemed to           
\par recall to them the memory of the innocence that they had tarnished.         
\par They wondered how one so charming and graceful as he was could have         
\par escaped the stain of an age that was at once sordid and sensual.            
\par   Often, on returning home from one of those mysterious and                 
\par prolonged absences that gave rise to such strange conjecture among          
\par those who were his friends, or thought that they were so, he himself        
\par would creep upstairs to the locked room, open the door with the key         
\par that never left him now, and stand, with a mirror, in front of the          
\par portrait that Basil Hallward had painted of him, looking now at the         
\par evil and aging face on the canvas, and now at the fair young face that      
\par laughed back at him from the polished glass. The very sharpness of the      
\par contrast used to quicken his sense of pleasure. He grew more and            
\par more enamoured of his own beauty, more and more interested in the           
\par corruption of his own soul. He would examine with minute care, and          
\par sometimes with monstrous and terrible delight, the hideous lines            
\par that seared the wrinkling forehead or crawled around the heavy sensual      
\par mouth, wondering sometimes which were the more horrible, the signs          
\par of sin or the signs of age. He would place his white hands beside           
\par the coarse bloated hands of the picture, and smile. He mocked the           
\par misshapen body and the failing limbs.                                       
\par   There were moments, indeed, at night, when, lying sleepless in his        
\par own delicately-scented chamber, or in the sordid room of the little         
\par ill-famed tavern near the Docks, which, under an assumed name, and          
\par in disguise, it was his habit to frequent, he would think of the            
\par ruin he had brought upon his soul, with a pity that was all the more        
\par poignant because it was purely selfish. But moments such as these were      
\par rare. That curiosity about life which Lord Henry had first stirred          
\par in him, as they sat together in the garden of their friend, seemed          
\par to increase with gratification. The more he knew, the more he               
\par desired to know. He had mad hungers that grew more ravenous as he           
\par fed them.                                                                   
\par   Yet he was not really reckless, at any rate in his relations to           
\par society. Once or twice every month during the winter, and on each           
\par Wednesday evening while the season lasted, he would throw open to           
\par the world his beautiful house and have the most celebrated musicians        
\par of the day to charm his guests with the wonder's of their art. His          
\par little dinners, in the settling of which Lord Henry always assisted         
\par him, were noted as much for the careful selection and placing of those      
\par invited, as for the exquisite taste shown in the decoration of the          
\par table, with its subtle symphonic arrangements of exotic flowers, and        
\par embroidered cloths, and antique plate of gold and silver. Indeed,           
\par there were many, especially among the very young men, who saw, or           
\par fancied that they saw, in Dorian Gray the true realization of a type        
\par of which they had often dreamed in Eton or Oxford days, a type that         
\par was to combine something of the real culture of the scholar with all        
\par the grace and distinction and perfect manner of a citizen of the            
\par world. To them he seemed to be of the company of those whom Dante           
\par describes as having sought to "make themselves perfect by the               
\par worship of beauty." Like Gautier, he was one for whom "the visible          
\par world existed."                                                             
\par   And certainly, to him Life itself was the first, the greatest, of         
\par the arts, and for it all the other arts seemed to be but a                  
\par preparation. Fashion, by which what is really fantastic becomes for         
\par a moment universal, and Dandyism, which, in its own way, is an attempt      
\par to assert the absolute modernity of beauty, had, of course, their           
\par fascination for him. His mode of dressing, and the particular styles        
\par that from time to time he affected, had their marked influence on           
\par the young exquisites of the Mayfair balls and Pall Mall Club                
\par windows, who copied him in everything that he did, and tried to             
\par reproduce the accidental charm of his graceful, though to him only          
\par half-serious fopperies.                                                     
\par   For, while he was but too ready to accept the position that was           
\par almost immediately offered to him on his coming of age, and found,          
\par indeed, a subtle pleasure in the thought that he might really become        
\par to the London of his own day what to imperial Neronian Rome the author      
\par of the "Satyricon" once had been, yet in his inmost heart he desired        
\par to be something more than a mere arbiter elegantiarum, to be consulted      
\par on the wearing of a jewel, or the knotting of a necktie, or the             
\par conduct of a cane. He sought to elaborate some new scheme of life that      
\par would have its reasoned philosophy and its ordered principles, and          
\par find in the spiritualizing of the senses its highest realization.           
\par   The worship of the senses has often, and with much justice, been          
\par decried, men feeling a natural instinct of terror about passions and        
\par sensations that seem stronger than themselves, and that they are            
\par conscious of sharing with the less highly organized forms of                
\par existence. But it appeared to Dorian Gray that the true nature of           
\par the senses had never been understood, and that they had remained            
\par savage and animal merely because the world had sought to starve them        
\par into submission or to kill them by pain, instead of aiming at making        
\par them elements of a new spirituality, of which a fine instinct for           
\par beauty was to be the dominant characteristic. As he looked back upon        
\par man moving through History, he was haunted by a feeling of loss. So         
\par much had been surrendered! and to such little purpose! There had            
\par been mad wilful rejections, monstrous forms of self-torture and             
\par self-denial, whose origin was fear, and whose result was a degradation      
\par infinitely more terrible than that fancied degradation from which,          
\par in their ignorance, they had sought to escape, Nature, in her               
\par wonderful irony, driving out the anchorite to feed with the wild            
\par animals of the desert and giving to the hermit the beasts of the field      
\par as his companions.                                                          
\par    Yes: there was to be, as Lord Henry had prophesied, a new Hedonisim      
\par that was to re-create life, and to save it from that harsh, uncomely        
\par Puritanism that is having, in our own day, its curious revival. It was      
\par to have its service of the intellect, certainly; yet, it was never          
\par to accept any theory, or system that would involve the sacrifice of         
\par any mode of passionate experience. Its aim, indeed, was to be               
\par experience itself, and not the fruits of experience, sweet or bitter        
\par as they might be. Of the asceticism that deadens the senses, as of the      
\par vulgar profligacy that dulls them, it was to know nothing. But it           
\par was to teach man to concentrate himself upon the moments of a life          
\par that is itself but a moment.                                                
\par   There are few of us who have not sometimes wakened before dawn,           
\par either after one of those dreamless nights that make us almost              
\par enamoured of death, or one of those nights of horror and misshapen          
\par joy, when through the chambers of the brain sweep phantoms more             
\par terrible than reality itself, and instinct with that vivid life that        
\par lurks in all grotesques, and that lends to Gothic art its enduring          
\par vitality, this art being, one might fancy, especially the art of those      
\par whose minds have been troubled with the malady of reverie. Gradually        
\par white fingers creep through the curtains, and they appear to                
\par tremble. In black fantastic shapes, dumb shadows crawl into the             
\par corners of the room, and crouch there. Outside, there is the                
\par stirring of birds among the leaves, or the sound of men going forth to      
\par their work, or the sigh and sob of the wind coming down from the            
\par hills, and wandering round the silent house, as though it feared to         
\par wake the steepers, and yet must needs call forth sleep from her purple      
\par cave. Veil after veil of thin dusky gauze is lifted, and by degrees         
\par the forms and colours of things are restored to them, and we watch the      
\par dawn remaking the world in its antique pattern. The wan mirrors get         
\par back their mimic life. The flameless tapers stand where we had left         
\par them, and beside them lies the half-cut book that we had been               
\par studying, or the wired flower that we had worn at the ball, or the          
\par letter that we had been afraid to read, or that we had read too often.      
\par Nothing seems to us changed. Out of the unreal shadows of the night         
\par comes back the real life that we had known. We have to resume it where      
\par we had left off, and there steals over us a terrible sense of the           
\par necessity for the continuance of energy in the same wearisome round of      
\par stereotyped habits, or a wild longing, it may be, that our eyelids          
\par might open some morning upon a world that had been refashioned anew in      
\par the darkness for our pleasure, a world in which things would have           
\par fresh shapes and colours, and be changed, or have other secrets, a          
\par world in which the past would have little or no place, or survive,          
\par at any rate, in no conscious form of obligation or regret, the              
\par remembrance even of joy having its bitterness, and the memories of          
\par pleasure their pain.                                                        
\par   It was the creation of such worlds as these that seemed to Dorian         
\par Gray to be the true object, or amongst the true objects, of like;           
\par and in his search for sensations that would be at once new and              
\par delightful, and possess that element of strangeness that is so              
\par essential to romance, he would often adopt certain modes of thought         
\par that he knew to be really alien to his nature, abandon himself to           
\par their subtle influences, and then, having, as it were, caught their         
\par colour and satisfied his intellectual curiosity, leave them with            
\par that curious indifference that is not incompatible with a real              
\par ardour of temperament, and that indeed, according to certain modern         
\par psychologists, is often a condition of it.                                  
\par   It was rumoured of him once that he was about to join the Roman           
\par Catholic communion; and certainly the Roman ritual had always a             
\par great attraction for him. The daily sacrifice, more awful really            
\par than all the sacrifices of the antique world, stirred him as much by        
\par its superb rejection of the evidence of the senses as by the primitive      
\par simplicity of its elements and the eternal pathos of the human tragedy      
\par that it sought to symbolize. He loved to kneel down on the cold marble      
\par pavement, and watch the priest, in his stiff flowered dalmatic, slowly      
\par and with white hands moving aside the veil of the tabernacle, or            
\par raising aloft the jewelled lantern-shaped monstrance with that              
\par pallid wafer that at times, one would fain think, is indeed the "panis      
\par caelestis," the bread of angels, or, robed in the garments of the           
\par Passion of Christ, breaking the Host into the chalice, and smiting his      
\par breast for his sins. The fuming censers, that the grave boys, in their      
\par lace and scarlet, tossed into the air like great gilt flowers, had          
\par their subtle fascination for him. As he passed out, he used to look         
\par with wonder at the black confessionals, and long to sit in the dim          
\par shadow of one of them and listen to men and women whispering through        
\par the worn grating the true story of their lives.                             
\par   But he never fell into the error of arresting his intellectual            
\par development by any formal acceptance of creed or system, or of              
\par mistaking, for a house in which to live, an inn that is but suitable        
\par for the sojourn of a night or for a few hours of a night in which           
\par there are no stars and the moon is in travail. Mysticism, with its          
\par marvellous power of making common things strange to us, and the subtle      
\par antinomianism that always seems to accompany it, moved him for a            
\par season; and for a season he inclined to the materialistic doctrines of      
\par the Darwinismus movement in Germany, and found a curious pleasure in        
\par tracing the thoughts and passions of men to some pearly cell in the         
\par brain, or some white nerve in the body, delighting in the conception        
\par of the absolute dependence of the spirit on certain physical                
\par conditions, morbid or healthy, normal or diseased. Yet, as has been         
\par said of him before, no theory of life seemed to him to be of any            
\par importance compared with life itself. He felt keenly conscious of           
\par how barren all intellectual speculation is when separated from              
\par action and experiment. He knew that the senses, no less than the soul,      
\par have their spiritual mysteries to reveal.                                   
\par   And so he would now study perfumes, and the secrets of their              
\par manufacture, distilling heavily-scented oils, and burning odorous gums      
\par from the East. He saw that there was no mood of the mind that had           
\par not its counterpart in the sensuous life, and set himself to                
\par discover their true relations, wondering what there was in                  
\par frankincense that made one mystical, and in ambergris that stirred          
\par one's passions, and in violets that woke the memory of dead                 
\par romances, and in musk that troubled the brain, and in Champak that          
\par stained the imagination; and seeking often to elaborate a real              
\par psychology of perfumes, and to estimate the several influences of           
\par sweet-smelling roots, and scented pollen-laden flowers, of aromatic         
\par balms, and of dark and fragrant woods, of spikenard that sickens, of        
\par hovenia that makes men mad, and of aloes that are said to be able to        
\par expel melancholy from the soul.                                             
\par   At another time he devoted himself entirely to music, and in a            
\par long latticed room, with a vermilion-and-gold ceiling and walls of          
\par olive-green lacquer, he used to give curious concerts in which mad          
\par gypsies tore wild music from little zithers, or grave yellow-shawled        
\par Tunisians plucked at the strained strings of monstrous lutes, while         
\par grinning Negroes beat monotonously upon copper drums, and, crouching        
\par upon scarlet mats, slim turbaned Indians blew through long pipes of         
\par reed or brass, and charmed, or feigned to charm, great hooded snakes        
\par and horrible horned adders. The harsh intervals and shrill discords of      
\par barbaric music stirred him at times when Schubert's grace, and              
\par Chopin's beautiful sorrows, and the mighty harmonies of Beethoven           
\par himself, fell unheeded on his ear. He collected together from all           
\par parts of the world the strangest instruments that could be found,           
\par either in the tombs of dead nations or among the few savage tribes          
\par that have survived contact with Western civilizations, and loved to         
\par touch and try them. He had the mysterious juruparis of the Rio Negro        
\par Indians, that women are not allowed to look at, and that even youths        
\par may not see till they have been subjected to fasting and scourging,         
\par and the earthen jars of the Peruvians that have the shrill cries of         
\par birds, and flutes of human bones such as Alfonso de Ovalle heard in         
\par Chile, and the sonorous green jaspers that are found near Cuzco and         
\par give forth a note of singular sweetness. He had painted gourds              
\par filled with pebbles that rattled when they were shaken; the long            
\par clarin of the Mexicans, into which the performer does not blow, but         
\par through which he inhales the air; the harsh ture of the Amazon tribes,      
\par that is sounded by the sentinels who sit all day long in high trees,        
\par and can be heard, it is said, at a distance of three leagues; the           
\par teponaztli, that has two vibrating tongues of wood, has her                 
\par monsters, things of bestial shape and with an elastic gum obtained          
\par from the milky juice of plants; the Yotl-bells of the Aztecs, that are      
\par hung in clusters like grapes; and a huge cylindrical drum, covered          
\par with the skins of great serpents, like the one that Bernal Diaz saw         
\par when he went with Cortes into the Mexican temple, and of whose doleful      
\par sound he has left us so vivid a description. The fantastic character        
\par of these instruments fascinated him, and he felt a curious delight          
\par in the thought that Art, like Nature, has her monsters, things of           
\par bestial shape and with hideous voices. Yet, after some time, he             
\par wearied of them, and would sit in his box at the Opera, either alone        
\par or with Lord Henry, listening in rapt pleasure to "Tannhauser," and         
\par seeing in the prelude to that great work of art a presentation of           
\par the tragedy of his own soul.                                                
\par   On one occasion he took up the study of jewels, and appeared at a         
\par costume ball as Anne de Joyeuse, Admiral of France, in a dress covered      
\par with five hundred and sixty pearls. This taste enthralled him for           
\par years, and, indeed, may be said never to have left him. He would often      
\par spend a whole day settling and resettling in their cases the various        
\par stones that he had collected, such as the olive-green chrysoberyl that      
\par turns red by lamplight, the cymophane with its wire-like line of            
\par silver, the pistachio-coloured peridot, rose-pink and wine-yellow           
\par topazes, carbuncles of fiery scarlet with tremulous four-rayed              
\par stars, flame-red cinnamon-stones, orange and violet spinels, and            
\par amethysts with their alternate layers of ruby, and sapphire. He             
\par loved the red gold of the sunstone, and the moonstone's pearly              
\par whiteness, and the broken rainbow of the milky opal. He procured            
\par from Amsterdam three emeralds of extraordinary size and richness of         
\par colour, and had a turquoise de la vieille roche that was the envy of        
\par all the connoisseurs.                                                       
\par   He discovered wonderful stories, also about jewels. In Alphonso's         
\par "Clericalis Disciplina" a serpent was mentioned with eyes of real           
\par jacinth, and in the romantic history of Alexander, the Conqueror of         
\par Emathia was said to have found in the vale of Jordan, snakes "with          
\par collars of real emeralds growing on their backs." There was a gem in        
\par the brain of the dragon, Philostratus told us, and "by the                  
\par exhibition of golden letters and a scarlet robe" the monster could          
\par be thrown into a magical sleep, and slain. According to the great           
\par alchemist, Pierre de Boniface, the diamond rendered a man invisible,        
\par and the agate of India made him eloquent. The cornelian appeased            
\par anger, and the hyacinth provoked sleep, and the amethyst drove away         
\par the fumes of wine. The garnet cast out demons, and the hydropicus           
\par deprived the moon of her colour. The selenite waxed and waned with the      
\par moon, and the meloceus, that discovers thieves, could be affected only      
\par by the blood of kids. Leonardus Camillus had seen a white stone             
\par taken from the brain of a newly-killed toad, that was certain antidote      
\par against poison. The bezoar, that was found in the heart of the Arabian      
\par deer, was a charm that could cure the plague. In the nests of               
\par Arabian birds was the aspilates, that, according to Democritus, kept        
\par the wearer from his city with fire.                                         
\par   The King of Ceilan rode through his city with a large ruby in his         
\par hand, at the ceremony of his coronation. The gates of the palace of         
\par John the Priest were "made of sardius, with the horn of the horned          
\par snake inwrought, so that no man might bring poison within." Over the        
\par gable were "two golden apples, in which were two carbuncles," so            
\par that the gold might shine by day, and the carbuncles by night. In           
\par Lodge's strange romance "A Margarite of America" it was stated that in      
\par the chamber of the queen one could behold "all the chaste ladies of         
\par the world, inchased out of silver, looking through fair mirrors of          
\par chrysolites, carbuncles, sapphires, and greene emeraults." Marco            
\par Polo had seen the inhabitants of Zipangu place rose-coloured pearls in      
\par the mouths of the dead. A sea monster had been enamoured of the             
\par pearl that the diver brought to King Perozes, and had slain the thief,      
\par and mourned for seven moons over its loss. When the Huns lured the          
\par king into the great pit, he flung it away- Procopius tells the              
\par story- nor was it ever found again, though the Emperor Anastasius           
\par offered five hundred-weight of gold pieces for it. The King of Malabar      
\par had shown to a certain Venetian a rosary of three hundred and four          
\par pearls, one for every god that he worshipped.                               
\par   When the Duke de Valentinois, son of Alexander VI., visited Louis         
\par XII. of France, his horse was loaded with gold leaves, according to         
\par Brantome, and his cap had double rows of rubies that threw out a great      
\par light. Charles of England had ridden in stirrups hung with four             
\par hundred and twenty-one diamonds. Richard II. had a coat, valued at          
\par thirty thousand marks, which was covered with balas rubies. Hall            
\par described Henry VIII., on his way to the Tower previous to his              
\par coronation, as wearing "a jacket of raised gold, the placard                
\par embroidered with diamonds and other rich stones, and a great bauderike      
\par about his neck of large balasses." The favourites of James I. wore          
\par earrings of emeralds set in gold filigrane. Edward II. gave to Piers        
\par Gaveston a suit of red-gold armour studded with jacinths, a collar          
\par of gold roses set with turquoise-stones, and a skull-cap parseme            
\par with pearls. Henry II. wore jewelled gloves reaching to the elbow, and      
\par had a hawk-glove sewn with twelve rubies and fifty-two great                
\par orients. The ducal hat of Charles the Rash, the last Duke of                
\par Burgundy of his race, was hung with pear-shaped pearls, and studded         
\par with sapphires.                                                             
\par   How exquisite life had once been! How gorgeous in its pomp and            
\par decoration! Even to read of the luxury of the dead was wonderful.           
\par   Then he turned his attention to embroideries, and to the                  
\par tapestries that performed the office of frescoes in the chill rooms of      
\par the Northern nations of Europe. As he investigated the subject- and he      
\par always had an extraordinary faculty of becoming absolutely absorbed         
\par for the moment in whatever he took up- he was almost saddened by the        
\par reflection of the ruin that Time brought on beautiful and wonderful         
\par things. He, at any rate, had escaped that. Summer followed summer, and      
\par the yellow jonquils bloomed and died many times, and nights of              
\par horror repeated the story of their shame, but he was unchanged. No          
\par winter marred his face or stained his flower-like bloom. Flow               
\par different it was with material things! Where had they passed to? Where      
\par was the great crocus-coloured robe, on which the gods had fought            
\par against the giants, that had been worked by brown girls for the             
\par pleasure of Athena? Where, the huge velarium that Nero had stretched        
\par across the Colosseum at Rome, that Titan sail of purple on which was        
\par represented the starry sky, and Apollo driving a chariot drawn by           
\par white gilt-reined steeds? He longed to see the curious table-napkins        
\par wrought for the Priest of the Sun, on which were displayed all the          
\par dainties and viands that could be wanted for a feast; the mortuary          
\par cloth of King Chilperic, with its three hundred golden bees; the            
\par fantastic robes that excited the indignation of the Bishop of               
\par Pontus, and were figured with "lions, panthers, bears, dogs,                
\par forests, rocks, hunters- all, in fact, that a painter can copy from         
\par nature;"- and the coat that Charles of Orleans once wore, on the            
\par sleeves of which were embroidered the verses of a song beginning            
\par "Madame, je suis tout joyeux," the musical accompaniment of the             
\par words being wrought in gold thread, and each note, of square shape          
\par in those days, formed with four pearls. He read of the room that was        
\par prepared at the palace at Rheims for the use of Queen Joan of               
\par Burgundy, and was decorated with "thirteen hundred and twenty-one           
\par parrots, made in broidery, and blazoned with the king's arms, and five      
\par hundred and sixty-one butterflies, whose wings were similarly               
\par ornamented with the arms of the queen, the whole worked in gold."           
\par Catherine de Medicis had a mourning-bed made for her of black velvet        
\par powdered with crescents and suns. Its curtains were of damask, with         
\par leafy wreaths and garlands, figured upon a gold and silver ground, and      
\par fringed along the edges with broideries of pearls, and it stood in a        
\par room hung with rows of the queen's devices in cut black velvet upon         
\par cloth of silver. Louis XIV. had gold embroidered caryatides fifteen         
\par feet high in his apartment. The state bed of Sobieski, King of Poland,      
\par was made of Smyrna gold brocade embroidered in turquoises with              
\par verses from the Koran. Its supports were of silver gilt, beautifully        
\par chased, and profusely set with enamelled and jewelled medallions. It        
\par had been taken from the Turkish camp before Vienna, and the standard        
\par of Mohammed had stood beneath the tremulous gilt of its canopy.             
\par   And so, for a whole year, he sought to accumulate the most exquisite      
\par specimens that he could find of textile and embroidered work,               
\par getting the dainty Delhi muslines, finely wrought with gold with            
\par gold thread palmates, and stitched over with iridescent beetles'            
\par wings; the Dacca gauzes, that from their transparency are known in the      
\par East as "wovenair," and "running water," and "evening dew"; strange         
\par figured cloths from Java; elaborate yellow Chinese hangings; books          
\par bound in tawny satins or fair blue silks, and wrought with fleurs de        
\par lys, birds and images: veils of lacis worked in Hungary point;              
\par Sicilian brocades, and stiff Spanish velvets; Georgian work with its        
\par gilt coins, and Japanese Foukousas with their green-toned golds and         
\par their marvellously plumaged birds.                                          
\par   He had a special passion, also, for ecclesiastical vestments, as          
\par indeed he had for everything connected with the service of the Church.      
\par In the long cedar chests that lined the west gallery of his house he        
\par had stored away many rare and beautiful specimens of what is really         
\par the raiment of the Bride of Christ, who must wear purple and jewels         
\par and fine linen that she may hide the pallid macerated body that is          
\par worn by the suffering that she seeks for, and wounded by                    
\par self-inflicted pain. He possessed a gorgeous cope of crimson silk           
\par and gold-thread damask, figured with a repeating pattern of golden          
\par pomegranates set in six-petalled formal blossoms, beyond which on           
\par either side was the pineapple device wrought in seed-pearls. The            
\par orphreys were divided into panels representing scenes from the life of      
\par the Virgin, and the coronation of the Virgin was figured in coloured        
\par silks upon the hood. This was Italian work of the fifteenth century.        
\par Another cope was of green velvet, embroidered with Heart-shaped groups      
\par of acanthus-leaves, from which spread long-stemmed white blossoms, the      
\par details of which were picked out with silver thread and coloured            
\par crystals. The morse bore a seraph's head in gold-thread raised work.        
\par The orphreys were woven in a diaper of red and gold silk, and were          
\par starred with medallions of many saints and martyrs, among whom was St.      
\par Sebastian, He has chasubles, also, of amber-coloured silk, and blue         
\par silk and gold brocade, and yellow silk damask and cloth of gold,            
\par figured with representations of the Passion and Crucifixion of Christ,      
\par and embroidered with lions and peacocks and other emblems; dalmatics        
\par of white satin and pink silk damask, decorated with tulips and              
\par dolphins and fleurs de lys; altar frontals of crimson velvet and            
\par blue linen; and many corporals, chalice-veils, and sudaria. In the          
\par mystic offices to which such things were put, there was something that      
\par quickened his imagination.                                                  
\par   For these treasures, and everything that he collected in his              
\par lovely house, were to be to him means of forgetfulness, modes by which      
\par he could escape, for a season, from the fear that seemed to him at          
\par times to be almost too great to be borne. Upon the walls of the lonely      
\par locked room where he had spent so much of his boyhood, he had hung          
\par with his own hands the terrible portrait whose changing features            
\par showed him the real degradation of his life, and in front of it had         
\par draped the purple-and-gold pall as a curtain. For weeks he would not        
\par go there, would forget the hideous painted thing, and get back his          
\par light heart, his wonderful joyousness, his passionate absorption in         
\par mere existence. Then, suddenly, some night he would creep out of the        
\par house, go down to dreadful places near Blue Gate Fields, and stay           
\par there, day after day, until he was driven away. On his return he would      
\par sit in front of the picture, sometimes loathing it and himself, but         
\par filled, at other times, with that pride of individualism that is            
\par half the fascination of sin, and smiling, with secret pleasure, at the      
\par misshapen shadow that had to bear the burden that should have been his      
\par own.                                                                        
\par   After a few years he could not endure to be long out of England, and      
\par gave up the villa that he had shared at Trouville with Lord Henry,          
\par as well as the little white walled-in house at Algiers where they           
\par had more than once spent the winter. He hated to be separated from the      
\par picture that was such a part of his life, and was also afraid that          
\par during his absence some one might gain access to the room, in spite of      
\par the elaborate bars that he had caused to be placed upon the door.           
\par   He was quite conscious that this would tell them nothing. It was          
\par true that the portrait still preserved, under all the foulness and          
\par ugliness of the face, its marked likeness to himself; but what could        
\par they learn from that? He would laugh at any one who tried to taunt          
\par him. He had not painted it. What was it to him how vile and full of         
\par shame it looked? Even if he told them, would they believe it?               
\par   Yet he was afraid. Sometimes when he was down at his great house          
\par in Nottinghamshire, entertaining the fashionable young men of his           
\par own rank who were his chief companions, and astounding the county by        
\par the wanton luxury and gorgeous splendor of his mode of life, he             
\par would suddenly leave his guests and rush back to town to see that           
\par the door had not been tampered with, and that the picture was still         
\par there. What if it should be stolen? The mere thought made him cold          
\par with horror. Surely the world would know his secret then. Perhaps           
\par the world already suspected it.                                             
\par   For, while he fascinated many, there were not a few who distrusted        
\par him. He was very nearly blackballed at a West End club of which his         
\par birth and social position fully entitled him to become a member, and        
\par it was said that on one occasion, when he was brought by a friend into      
\par the smoking-room of the Churchill, the Duke of Berwick and another          
\par gentleman got up in a marked manner and went out. Curious stories           
\par became current about him after he had passed his twenty-fifth year. It      
\par was rumoured that he had been seen brawling with foreign sailors in         
\par a low den in the distant parts of Whitechapel, and that he consorted        
\par with thieves and coiners and knew the mysteries of their trade. His         
\par extraordinary absences became notorious, and, when he used to reappear      
\par again in society, men would whisper to each other in corners, or            
\par pass him with a sneer, or look at him with cold, searching eyes, as         
\par though they were determined to discover his secret.                         
\par   Of such insolences and attempted slights, he, of course, took no          
\par notice, and in the opinion of most people his frank debonnair               
\par manner, his charming boyish smile, and the infinite grace of that           
\par wonderful youth that seemed never to leave him, were in themselves a        
\par sufficient answer to the calumnies, for so they termed them, that were      
\par circulated about him. It was remarked, however, that some of those who      
\par had been most intimate with him appeared, after a time, to shun him.        
\par Women who had wildly adored him, and for his sake had braved all            
\par social censure and set convention at defiance, were seen to grow            
\par pallid with shame or horror if Dorian Gray entered the room.                
\par   Yet these whispered scandals only increased in the eyes of many, his      
\par strange and dangerous charm. His great wealth was a certain element of      
\par security. Society, civilized society at least, is never very ready          
\par to believe anything to the detriment of those who are both rich and         
\par fascinating. It feels instinctively that manners are of more                
\par importance than morals, and, in its opinion, the highest                    
\par respectability is of much less value than the possession of a good          
\par chef. And, after all, it is a very poor consolation to be told that         
\par the man who has given one a bad dinner, or poor wine, is                    
\par irreproachable in his private life. Even the cardinal virtues cannot        
\par atone for half-cold entrees, as Lord Henry remarked once, in a              
\par discussion on the subject; and there is possibly a good deal to be          
\par said for his view. For the canons of good society are, or should be,        
\par the same as the canons of art. Form is absolutely essential to it.          
\par It should have the dignity of a ceremony, as well as its unreality,         
\par and should combine the insincere character of a romantic play with the      
\par wit and beauty that makes such plays delightful to us. Is                   
\par insincerity such a terrible thing? I think not. It is merely a              
\par method by which we can multiply our personalities.                          
\par   Such, at any rate, was Dorian Gray's opinion. He used to wonder at        
\par the shallow psychology of those who conceive the Ego in man as a thing      
\par simple, permanent, reliable, and of one essence. To him, man was a          
\par being with myriad lives and myriad sensations, a complex multiform          
\par creature that bore within itself strange legacies of thought and            
\par passion, and whose very flesh was tainted with the monstrous                
\par maladies of the dead. He loved to stroll through the gaunt cold             
\par picture-gallery of his country house and look at the various portraits      
\par of those whose blood flowed in his veins. Here was Philip Herbert,          
\par described by Francis Osborne, in his "Memoires on the Reigns of             
\par Queen Elizabeth and King James," as one who was "caressed by the Court      
\par for his handsome face, which kept him not long company." Was it             
\par young Herbert's life that he sometimes led? Had some strange poisonous      
\par germ crept from body to body till it had reached his own? Was it            
\par some dim sense of that ruined grace that had made him so suddenly, and      
\par almost without cause, give utterance, in Basil Hallward's studio, to        
\par the mad prayer that had so changed his life? Here, in gold-embroidered      
\par red doublet, jewelled surcoat, and gilt-edged ruff and wrist-bands,         
\par stood Sir Anthony Sherard, with his silver-and-black armour piled at        
\par his feet. What had this man's legacy been? Had the lover of Giovanna        
\par of Naples bequeathed him some inheritance of sin and shame? Were his        
\par own actions merely the dreams that the dead man had not dared to            
\par realize? Here, from the fading canvas, smiled Lady Elizabeth Devereux,      
\par in her gauze hood, pearl stomacher, and pink slashed sleeves. A flower      
\par was in her right hand, and her left clasped an enamelled collar of          
\par white and damask roses. On a table by her side lay a mandolin and an        
\par apple. There were large green rosettes upon her little pointed              
\par shoes. He knew her life, and the strange stories that were told             
\par about her lovers. Had he something of her temperament in him? These         
\par oval heavy-lidded eyes seemed to look curiously at him. What of George      
\par Willoughby, with his powdered hair and fantastic patches? How evil          
\par he looked! The face was saturnine and swarthy, and the sensual lips         
\par seemed to be twisted with disdain. Delicate lace ruffles fell over the      
\par lean yellow hands that were so overladen with rings. He had been a          
\par macaroni of the eighteenth century, and the friend, in his youth, of        
\par Lord Ferrars. What of the second Lord Beckenham, the companion of           
\par the Prince Regent in his wildest days, and one of the witnesses at the      
\par secret marriage with Mrs. Fitzherbert? How proud and handsome he            
\par was, with his chestnut curls and insolent pose! What passions had he        
\par bequeathed? The world had looked upon him as infamous. He had led           
\par the orgies at Carlton House. The star of the Garter glittered upon his      
\par breast. Beside him hung the portrait of his wife, a pallid,                 
\par thin-lipped woman in black. Her blood, also, stirred within him. How        
\par curious it all seemed! And his mother with her Lady Hamilton face, and      
\par her moist wine-dashed lips- he knew what he had got from her. He had        
\par got from her his beauty, and his passion for the beauty of others. She      
\par laughed at him in her loose Bacchante dress. There were vine leaves in      
\par her hair. The purple spilled from the cup she was holding. The              
\par carnations of the painting had withered, but the eyes were still            
\par wonderful in their depth and brilliancy of colour. They seemed to           
\par follow him wherever he went.                                                
\par   Yet one had ancestors in literature, as well as in one's own race,        
\par nearer perhaps in type and temperament, many of them, and certainly         
\par with an influence of which one was more absolutely conscious. There         
\par were times when it appeared to Dorian Gray that the whole of history        
\par was merely the record of his own life, not as he had lived it in act        
\par and circumstance, but as his imagination had created it for him, as it      
\par had been in his brain and in his passions. He felt that he had known        
\par them all, those strange terrible figures that had passed across the         
\par stage of the world and made sin so marvellous and evil so full of           
\par subtlety. It seemed to him that in some mysterious way their lives had      
\par been his own.                                                               
\par   The hero of the wonderful novel that had so influenced his life           
\par had himself known this curious fancy. In the seventh chapter he             
\par tells how, crowned with laurel, lest lightning might strike him, he         
\par had sat, as Tiberius, in a garden at Capri reading the shameful             
\par books of Elephantis, while dwarfs and peacocks strutted round him           
\par and the flute-player mocked the swagger of the censer, and, as              
\par Caligula, had caroused with the green-shirted jockeys in their              
\par stables, and supped in an ivory manger with a jewel-frontleted              
\par horse; and, as Domitian, had wandered through a corridor lined with         
\par marble mirrors, looking round with haggard eyes for the reflection          
\par of the digger that was to end his days, and sick with that ennui, that      
\par terrible taedium vitae, that comes on those to whom life denies             
\par nothing: and had peered through a clear emerald at the red shambles of      
\par the Circus, and then, in a litter of pearl and purple drawn by              
\par silver-shod mules, been carried through the Street of Pomegranates          
\par to a House of Gold, and heard men cry on Nero Caesar as he passed           
\par by; and, as Elagabalus, had painted his face with colours, and plied        
\par the distaff among the women, and brought the Moon from Carthage, and        
\par given her in mystic marriage to the Sun.                                    
\par   Over and over again Dorian used to read this fantastic chapter,           
\par and the two chapters immediately following, in which, as in some            
\par curious tapestries or cunningly-wrought enamels, were pictured the          
\par awful and beautiful forms of those whom Vice and Blood and Weariness        
\par had made monstrous or mad: Filippo, Duke of Milan, who slew his             
\par wife, and painted her lips with a scarlet poison that her lover             
\par might suck death from the dead thing he fondled; Pietro Barbi, the          
\par Venetian, known as Paul the Second, who sought in his vanity to assume      
\par the title of Formosus, and whose tiara, valued at two hundred thousand      
\par florins, was bought at the price of a terrible sin; Gian Maria              
\par Visconti, who used hounds to chase living men, and whose murdered body      
\par was covered with roses by a harlot who had loved him; the Borgia on         
\par his white horse, with Fratricide riding beside him, and his mantle          
\par stained with the blood of Perotto; Pietro Riario, the young Cardinal        
\par Archbishop of Florence, child and minion of Sixtus IV., whose beauty        
\par was equalled only by his debauchery, and who received Leonora of            
\par Aragon in a pavilion of white and crimson silk, filled with nymphs and      
\par centaurs, and gilded a boy that he might serve at the feast as              
\par Ganymede or Hylas; Ezzelin, whose melancholy could be cured only by         
\par the spectacle of death, and who had a passion for red blood, as             
\par other men have for red wine- the son of the Fiend, as was reported,         
\par and one who had cheated his father at dice when gambling with him           
\par for his own soul: Giambattista Cibo, who in mockery took the name of        
\par Innocent, and into whose torpid veins the blood of three lads was           
\par infused by a Jewish doctor; Sigismondo Malatesta, the lover of Isotta,      
\par and the lord of Rimini, whose effigy was burned at Rome as the enemy        
\par of God and man, who strangled Polyssena with a napkin, and gave poison      
\par to Ginevra d'Este in a cup of emerald, and in honour of a shameful          
\par passion built a pagan church for Christian worship; Charles VI., who        
\par had so wildly adored his brother's wife that a leper had warned him of      
\par the insanity that was coming on him, and who, when his brain had            
\par sickened and grown strange, could only be soothed by Saracen cards          
\par painted with the images of Love and Death and Madness; and, in his          
\par trimmed jerkin and jewelled cap and acanthus-like curls, Grifonetto         
\par Baglioni, who slew Astorre with his bride, and Simonetto with his           
\par page, and whose comeliness was such that, as he lay dying in the            
\par yellow piazza of Perugia, those who had hated him could not choose but      
\par weep, and Atalanta, who had cursed him, blessed him.                        
\par   There was a horrible fascination in them all. He saw them at              
\par night, and they troubled his imagination in the day. The Renaissance        
\par knew of strange manners of poisoning- poisoning by a helmet and a           
\par lighted torch, by an embroidered glove and a jewelled fan, by a gilded      
\par pomander and by an amber chain. Dorian Gray had been poisoned by a          
\par book. There were moments when he looked on evil simply as a mode            
\par through which he could realize his conception of the beautiful.             
\par                                                                             
