\par                              CHAPTER XII                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   It was on the ninth of November, the eve of his own thirty-eighth         
\par birthday, as he often remembered afterwards.                                
\par   He was walking home about eleven o'clock from Lord Henry's, where he      
\par had been dining, and was wrapped in heavy furs, as the night was            
\par cold and foggy. At the corner of Grosvenor Square and South Audley          
\par Street a man passed him in the mist, walking very fast, and with the        
\par collar of his grey ulster turned up. He had a bag in his hand.              
\par Dorian recognized him. It was Basil Hallward. A strange sense of fear,      
\par for which he could not account, came over him. He made no sign of           
\par recognition, and went on quickly, in the direction of his own house.        
\par   But Hallward had seen him. Dorian heard him first stopping on the         
\par pavement and then hurrying after him. In a few moments his hand was on      
\par his arm.                                                                    
\par   "Dorian! What an extraordinary piece of luck! I have been waiting         
\par for you in your library ever since nine o'clock. Finally I took pity        
\par on your tired servant, and told him to go to bed, as he let me out.         
\par I am off to Paris by the midnight train, and I particularly wanted          
\par to see you, before I left. I thought it was you, or rather your fur         
\par coat, as you passed me. But I wasn't quite sure. Didn't you                 
\par recognize me?"                                                              
\par   "In this fog, my dear Basil? Why, I can't even recognize Grosvenor        
\par Square, I believe my house is somewhere about here, but I don't feel        
\par at all certain about it. I am sorry you are going away, as I have           
\par not seen you for ages. But I suppose you will be back soon?"                
\par   "No: I am going to be out of England for six months. I intend to          
\par take a studio in Paris, and shut myself up till I have finished a           
\par great picture I have in my head. However, it wasn't about myself I          
\par wanted to talk. Here we are at your door. Let me come in for a moment.      
\par I have something to say to you."                                            
\par   "I shall be charmed. But won't you miss your train?" said Dorian          
\par Gray, languidly, as he passed up the steps and opened the door with         
\par his latch-key.                                                              
\par   The lamp-light struggled out through the fog, and Hallward looked at      
\par his watch.                                                                  
\par   "I have heaps of time," he answered. "The train doesn't go till           
\par twelve-fifteen, and it is only just eleven. In fact, I was on my way        
\par to the club to look for you, when I met you. You see, I sha'n't have        
\par any delay about luggage, as I have sent on my heavy things. All I have      
\par with me is in this bag, and I can easily get to Victoria in twenty          
\par minutes."                                                                   
\par   Dorian looked at him and smiled. "What a way for a fashionable            
\par painter to travel! A Gladstone bag and an ulster! Come in, or the           
\par fog will get into the house. And mind you don't talk about anything         
\par serious. Nothing is serious nowadays. At least nothing should be."          
\par   Hallward shook his head, as he entered, and followed Dorian into the      
\par library. There was a bright wood fire blazing in the large open             
\par hearth. The lamps were lit, and an open Dutch silver spirit-case            
\par stood, with some siphons of soda-water and large cut-glass tumblers,        
\par on a little marqueterie table.                                              
\par   "You see your servant made me quite at home, Dorian. He gave me           
\par everything I wanted, including your best gold-tipped cigarettes. He is      
\par a most hospitable creature. I like him much better than the                 
\par Frenchman you used to have. What has become of the Frenchman, by the        
\par bye?"                                                                       
\par   Dorian shrugged his shoulders. "I believe he married Lady Radley's        
\par maid, and has established her in Paris as an English dressmaker.            
\par Anglomanie is very fashionable over there now, I hear. It seems             
\par silly of the French, doesn't it? But- do you know?- he was not at           
\par all a bad servant. I never liked him, but I had nothing to complain         
\par about. One often imagines things that are quite absurd. He was              
\par really very devoted to me, and seemed quite sorry when he went away.        
\par Have another brandy-and-soda? Or would you like hock-and-seltzer? I         
\par always take hock-and-seltzer myself. There is sure to be some in the        
\par next room."                                                                 
\par   "Thanks, I won't have anything more," said the painter, taking his        
\par cap and coat off, and throwing them on the bag that he had placed in        
\par the corner. "And now, my dear fellow, I want to speak to you                
\par seriously. Don't frown like that. You make it so much more difficult        
\par for me."                                                                    
\par   "What is it all about?" cried Dorian, in his petulant way,                
\par flinging himself down on the sofa. "I hope it is not about myself. I        
\par am tired of myself to-night. I should like to be somebody else."            
\par   "It is about yourself," answered Hallward, in his grave, deep voice,      
\par "and I must say it to you. I shall only keep you half an hour."             
\par   Dorian sighed, and lit a cigarette. "Half an hour!" he murmured.          
\par   "It is not much to ask of you, Dorian, and it is entirely for your        
\par own sake that I am speaking. I think it right that you should know          
\par that the most dreadful things are being said against you in London."        
\par    "I don't wish to know anything about them. I love scandals about         
\par other people, but scandals about myself don't interest me. They have        
\par not got the charm of novelty."                                              
\par   "They must interest you, Dorian. Every gentleman is interested in         
\par his good name. You don't want people to talk of you as something            
\par vile and degraded. Of course you have your position, and your               
\par wealth, and all that kind of thing. But position and wealth are not         
\par everything. Mind you, I don't believe these rumours at all. At              
\par least, I can't believe them when I see you. Sin is a thing that writes      
\par itself across a man's face. It cannot be concealed. People talk             
\par sometimes of secret vices. There are no such things. If a wretched man      
\par has a vice, it shows itself in the lines of his mouth, the droop of         
\par his eyelids, the moulding of his hands even. Somebody- I won't mention      
\par his name, but you know him- came to me last year to have his                
\par portrait done. I had never seen him before, and had never heard             
\par anything about him at the time, though I have heard a good deal since.      
\par He offered an extravagant price. I refused him. There was something in      
\par the shape of his fingers that I hated. I know now that I was quite          
\par right in what I fancied about him. His life is dreadful. But you,           
\par Dorian, with your pure, bright, innocent face, and your marvellous          
\par untroubled youth- I can't believe anything against you. And yet I           
\par see you very seldom, and you never come down to the studio now, and         
\par when I am away from you, and I hear all these hideous things that           
\par people are whispering about you, I don't know what to say. Why is           
\par it, Dorian, that a man like the Duke of Berwick leaves the room of a        
\par club when you enter it? Why is it that so many gentlemen in London          
\par will neither go to your house nor invite you to theirs? You used to be      
\par a friend of Lord Staveley. I met him at dinner last week. Your name         
\par happened to come up in conversation, in connection with the miniatures      
\par you have lent to the exhibition at the Dudley. Staveley curled his          
\par lip, and said that you might have the most artistic tastes, but that        
\par you were a man whom no pure-minded girl should be allowed to know, and      
\par whom no chaste woman would sit in the same room with. I reminded him        
\par that I was a friend of yours, and asked him what he meant. He told me.      
\par He told me right out before everybody. It was horrible! Why is your         
\par friendship so fatal to young men? There was that wretched boy in the        
\par Guards who committed suicide. You were his great friend. There was Sir      
\par Henry Ashton, who had to leave England, with a tarnished name. You and      
\par he were inseparable. What about Adrian Singleton, and his dreadful          
\par end? What about Lord Kent's only son, and his career? I met his father      
\par yesterday in St. James's Street. He seemed broken with shame and            
\par sorrow. What about the young Duke of Perth? What sort of life has he        
\par got now? What gentleman would associate with him?"                          
\par   "Stop, Basil. You are talking about things of which you know              
\par nothing," said Dorian Gray, biting his lip, and with a note of              
\par infinite contempt in his voice. "You ask me why Berwick leaves a            
\par room when I enter it. It is because I know everything about his             
\par life, not because he knows anything about mine. With such blood as          
\par he has in his veins, how could his record be clean? You ask me about        
\par Henry Ashton and young Perth. Did I teach the one his vices, and the        
\par other his debauchery? If Kent's silly son takes his wife from the           
\par streets, what is that to me? If Adrian Singleton writes his friend's        
\par name across a bill, am I his keeper? I know how people chatter in           
\par England. The middle classes air their moral prejudices over their           
\par gross dinner-tables, and whisper about what they call the profligacies      
\par of their betters in order to try and pretend that they are in smart         
\par society, and on intimate terms with the people they slander. In this        
\par country it is enough for a man to have distinction and brains for           
\par every common tongue to wag against him. And what sort of lives do           
\par these people, who pose as being moral, lead themselves? My dear             
\par fellow, you forget that we are in the native land of the hypocrite."        
\par   "Dorian," cried Hallward, "that is not the question. England is           
\par bad enough I know, and English society is all wrong. That is the            
\par reason why I want you to be fine. You have not been fine. One has a         
\par right to judge of a man by the effect he has over his friends. Yours        
\par seem to lose all sense of honour, of goodness, of purity. You have          
\par filled them with a madness for pleasure. They have gone down into           
\par the depths. You led them there. Yes: you led them there, and yet you        
\par can smile, as you are smiling now. And there is worse behind. I,            
\par know you and Harry are inseparable. Surely for that reason, if for          
\par none other, you should not have made his sister's name a byword."           
\par   "Take care, Basil. You go too far."                                       
\par   "I must speak, and you must listen. You shall listen. When you met        
\par Lady Gwendolyn, not a breath of scandal had ever touched her. Is there      
\par a single decent woman in London now who would drive with her in the         
\par Park? Why, even her children are not allowed to live with her. Then         
\par there are other stories- stories that you have been seen creeping at        
\par dawn out of dreadful houses and slinking in disguise into the               
\par foulest dens in London. Are they true? Can they be true? When I             
\par first heard them, I laughed. I hear them now, and they make me              
\par shudder. What about your country house, and the life that is led            
\par there? Dorian, you don't know what is said about you. I won't tell you      
\par that I don't want to preach to you. I remember Harry saying once            
\par that every man who turned himself into an amateur curate for the            
\par moment always begin by saying that, and then proceeded to break his         
\par word. I do want to preach to you. I want you to lead such a life as         
\par will make the world respect you. I want you to have a clean name and a      
\par fair record. I want you to get rid of the dreadful people you               
\par associate with. Don't shrug your shoulders like that. Don't be so           
\par indifferent. You have a wonderful influence. Let it be for good, not        
\par for evil. They say that you corrupt every one with whom you become          
\par intimate, and that it is quite sufficient for you to enter a house,         
\par for shame of some kind to follow after. I don't know whether it is          
\par or not. How should I know? But it is said of you. I am told things          
\par that it seems impossible to doubt. Lord Gloucester was one of my            
\par greatest friends at Oxford. He showed me a letter that his wife had         
\par written to him when she was dying alone in her villa at Mentone.            
\par Your name was implicated in the most terrible confession I ever             
\par read. I told him that it was absurd- that I knew you thoroughly, and        
\par that you were incapable of anything of the kind. Know you? I wonder do      
\par I know you? Before I could answer that, I should have to see your           
\par soul."                                                                      
\par   "To see my soul!" muttered Dorian Gray, starting up from the sofa         
\par and turning almost white from fear.                                         
\par   "Yes," answered Hallward, gravely, and with deep-toned sorrow in his      
\par voice, "to see your soul. But only God can do that."                        
\par   A bitter laugh of mockery broke from the lips of the younger man.         
\par "You shall see it yourself, to-night!" he cried, seizing a lamp from        
\par the table. "Come: it is your own handiwork. Why shouldn't you look          
\par at it? You can tell the world all about it afterwards, if you               
\par choose. Nobody would believe you. If they did believe you, they             
\par would like me all the better for it. I know the age better than you         
\par do, though you will prate about it so tediously. Come, I tell you. You      
\par have chattered enough about corruption. Now you shall look on it            
\par face to face."                                                              
\par   There was the madness of pride in every word he uttered. He               
\par stamped his foot upon the ground in his boyish insolent manner. He          
\par felt a terrible joy at the thought that some one else was to share his      
\par secret, and that the man who had painted the portrait that was the          
\par origin of all his shame was to be burdened for the rest of his life         
\par with the hideous memory of what he had done.                                
\par   "Yes," he continued, coming closer to him, and looking steadfastly        
\par into his stern eyes, "I shall show you my soul. You shall see the           
\par thing that you fancy only God can see."                                     
\par   Hallward started back. "This is blasphemy, Dorian!" he cried. "You        
\par must not say things like that. They are horrible, and they don't            
\par mean anything."                                                             
\par   "You think so?" he laughed again.                                         
\par   "I know so. As for what I said to you to-night, I said it for your        
\par good. You know I have always been a staunch friend to you."                 
\par   "Don't touch me. Finish what you have to say."                            
\par   A twisted flash of pain shot across the painter's face. He paused         
\par for a moment, and a wild feeling of pity came over him. After all,          
\par what right had he to pry into the life of Dorian Gray? If he had            
\par done a tithe of what was rumoured about him, how much he must have          
\par suffered! Then he straightened himself up, and walked over to the           
\par fireplace, and stood there, looking at the burning logs with their          
\par frost-like ashes and their throbbing cores of flame.                        
\par   "I am waiting, Basil," said the young man, in a hard, clear voice.        
\par   He turned round. "What I have to say is this," he cried. "You must        
\par give me some answer to these horrible charges that are made against         
\par you. If you tell me that they are absolutely untrue from beginning          
\par to end, I shall believe you. Deny them, Dorian, deny them! Can't you        
\par see what I am going through? My God! don't tell me that you are bad,        
\par and corrupt, and shameful."                                                 
\par   Dorian Gray smiled. There was a curl of contempt in his lips.             
\par "Come upstairs, Basil," he said, quietly. "I keep a diary of my life        
\par from day to day, and it never leaves the room in which it is                
\par written. I shall show it to you if you come with me."                       
\par   "I shall come with you, Dorian, if you wish it. I see I have              
\par missed my train. That makes no matter. I can go to-morrow. But don't        
\par ask me to read anything to-night. All I want is a plain answer to my        
\par question."                                                                  
\par   "That shall be given to you upstairs. I could not give it here.           
\par You will not have to read long."                                            
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                              CHAPTER XIII                                   
\par -                                                                           
\par   He passed out of the room and began the ascent, Basil Hallward            
\par following close behind. They walked softly, as men do instinctively at      
\par night. The lamp cast fantastic shadows on the wall and staircase. A         
\par rising wind made some of the windows rattle.                                
\par   When they reached the top landing, Dorian set the lamp down on the        
\par floor and taking out the key turned it in the lock. "You insist on          
\par knowing, Basil?" he asked, in a low voice.                                  
\par   "Yes."                                                                    
\par   "I am delighted," he answered, smiling. Then he added, somewhat           
\par harshly: "You are the one man in the world who is entitled to know          
\par everything about me. You have had more to do with my life than you          
\par think:" and, taking up the lamp, he opened the door and went in. A          
\par cold current of air passed them, and the light shot up for a moment in      
\par a flame of murky orange. He shuddered. "Shut the door behind you,"          
\par he whispered, as he placed the lamp on the table.                           
\par   Hallward glanced around him, with a puzzled expression. The room          
\par looked as if it had not been lived in for years. A faded Flemish            
\par tapestry, a curtained picture, an old Italian cassone, and an almost        
\par empty bookcase- that was all that it seemed to contain, besides a           
\par chair and a table. As Dorian Gray was lighting a half-burned candle         
\par that was standing on the mantelshelf he saw that the whole place was        
\par covered with dust, and that the carpet was in holes. A mouse ran            
\par scuffling behind the wainscoting. There was a damp odour of mildew.         
\par   "So you think that it is only God who sees the soul, Basil? Draw          
\par that curtain back, and you will see mine."                                  
\par   The voice that spoke was cold and cruel. "You are mad, Dorian, or         
\par playing a part," muttered Hallward, frowning.                               
\par   "You won't? Then I must do it myself," said the young man; and he         
\par tore the curtain from its rod, and flung it on the ground.                  
\par   An exclamation of horror broke from the painter's lips as he saw          
\par in the dim light the hideous face on the canvas grinning at him. There      
\par was something in its expression that filled him with disgust and            
\par loathing. Good heavens! it was Dorian Gray's own face that he was           
\par looking at! The horror, whatever it was, had not yet entirely               
\par spoiled that marvellous beauty. There was still some gold in the            
\par thinning hair and some scarlet on the sensual mouth. The sodden eyes        
\par had kept something of the loveliness of their blue, the noble curves        
\par had not yet completely passed away from chiselled nostrils and from         
\par plastic throat. Yes, it was Dorian himself. But who had done it? He         
\par seemed to recognize his own brush-work, and the frame was his own           
\par design. The idea was monstrous, yet he felt afraid. He seized the           
\par lighted candle, and held it to the picture. In the left-hand corner         
\par was his own name, traced in long letters of bright vermilion.               
\par   It was some foul parody, some infamous, ignoble satire. He had never      
\par done that. Still, it was his own picture. He knew it, and he felt as        
\par if his blood had changed in a moment from fire to sluggish ice. His         
\par own picture! What did it mean? Why had it altered? He turned, and           
\par looked at Dorian Gray with the eyes of a sick man. His mouth twitched,      
\par and his parched tongue seemed unable to articulate. He passed his hand      
\par across his forehead. It was dank with clammy sweat.                         
\par   The young man was leaning against the mantelshelf, watching him with      
\par that strange expression that one sees on the faces of those who are         
\par absorbed in a play when some great artist is acting. There was neither      
\par real sorrow in it nor real joy. There was simply the passion of the         
\par spectator, with perhaps a flicker of triumph in his eyes. He had taken      
\par the flower out of his coat, and was smelling it, or pretending to do        
\par so.                                                                         
\par   "What does this mean?" cried Hallward, at last. His own voice             
\par sounded shrill and curious in his ears.                                     
\par   "Years ago, when I was a boy," said Dorian Gray, crushing the flower      
\par in his hand, "you met me, flattered me, and taught me to be vain of my      
\par good looks. One day you introduced me to a friend of yours, who             
\par explained to me the wonder of youth, and you finished a portrait of me      
\par that revealed to me the wonder of beauty. In a mad moment, that,            
\par even now, I don't know whether I regret or not, I made a wish, perhaps      
\par you would call it a prayer...."                                             
\par   "I remember it! Oh, how well I remember it! No! the thing is              
\par impossible. The room is damp. Mildew has got into the canvas. The           
\par paints I used had some wretched mineral poison in them. I tell you the      
\par thing is impossible."                                                       
\par   "Ah, what is impossible?" murmured the young man, going over to           
\par the window, and leaning his forehead against the cold, mist-stained         
\par glass.                                                                      
\par   "You told me you had destroyed it."                                       
\par   "I was wrong. It has destroyed me."                                       
\par   "I don't believe it is my picture."                                       
\par   "Can't you see your ideal in it?" said Dorian, bitterly.                  
\par   "My ideal, as you call it...."                                            
\par   "As you called it."                                                       
\par   "There was nothing evil in it, nothing shameful. You were to me such      
\par an ideal as I shall never meet again. This is the face of a satyr."         
\par   "Is it the face of my soul."                                              
\par   "Christ! what a thing I must have worshipped! It has the eyes of a        
\par devil."                                                                     
\par   "Each of us has Heaven and Hell in him, Basil," cried Dorian, with a      
\par wild gesture of despair.                                                    
\par   Hallward turned again to the portrait, and gazed at it. "My God!          
\par if it is true," he exclaimed, "and this is what you have done with          
\par your life, why, you must be worse even than those who talk against you      
\par fancy you to be!" He held the light up again to the canvas, and             
\par examined it. The surface seemed to be quite undisturbed, and as he had      
\par left it. It was from within, apparently, that the foulness and              
\par horror had come. Through some strange quickening of inner life the          
\par leprosies of sin were slowly eating the thing away. The rotting of a        
\par corpse in a watery grave was not so fearful.                                
\par   His hand shook, and the candle fell from its socket on the floor,         
\par and lay there sputtering. He placed his foot on it and put it out.          
\par Then he flung himself into the rickety chair that was standing by           
\par the table and buried his face in his hands.                                 
\par   "Good God, Dorian, what a lesson! What an awful lesson!" There was        
\par no answer, but he could hear the young man sobbing at the window.           
\par "Pray, Dorian, pray," he murmured. "What is it that one was taught          
\par to say in one's boyhood? 'Lead us not into temptation. Forgive us           
\par our sins. Wash away our iniquities.' Let us say that together. The          
\par prayer of your pride has been answered. The prayer of your                  
\par repentance will be answered also. I worshipped you too much. I am           
\par punished for it. You worshipped yourself too. We are both punished."        
\par   Dorian Gray turned slowly around, and looked at him with tear-dimmed      
\par eyes. "It is too late, Basil," he faltered.                                 
\par   "It is never too late, Dorian. Let us kneel down and try if we            
\par cannot remember a prayer. Isn't there a verse somewhere, 'Though            
\par your sins be as scarlet, yet I will make them as white as snow'?"           
\par   "Those words mean nothing to me now."                                     
\par   "Hush! don't say that. You have done enough evil in your life. My         
\par God! Don't you see that accursed thing leering at us?"                      
\par   Dorian Gray glanced at the picture, and suddenly an uncontrollable        
\par feeling of hatred for Basil Hallward came over him, as though it had        
\par been suggested to him by the image on the canvas, whispered into his        
\par ear by those grinning lips. The mad passions of a hunted animal             
\par stirred within him, and he loathed the man who was seated at the            
\par table, more than in his whole life he had ever loathed anything. He         
\par glanced wildly around. Something glimmered on the top of the painted        
\par chest that faced him. His eye fell on it. He knew what it was. It           
\par was a knife that he had brought up, some days before, to cut a piece        
\par of cord, and had forgotten to take away with him. He moved slowly           
\par towards it, passing Hallward as he did so. As soon as he got behind         
\par him, he seized it, and turned round. Hallward stirred in his chair          
\par as if he was going to rise. He rushed at him, and dug the knife into        
\par the great vein that is behind the ear, crushing the man's head down on      
\par the table, and stabbing again and again.                                    
\par   There was a stifled groan, and the horrible sound of some one             
\par choking with blood. Three times the outstretched arms shot up               
\par convulsively, waving grotesque stiff-fingered hands in the air. He          
\par stabbed him twice more, but the man did not move. Something began to        
\par trickle on the floor. He waited for a moment, still pressing the            
\par head down. Then he threw the knife on the table, and listened.              
\par   He could hear nothing, but the drip, drip on the threadbare               
\par carpet. He opened the door and went out on the landing. The house           
\par was absolutely quiet. No one was about. For a few seconds he stood          
\par bending over the balustrade, and peering down into the black                
\par seething well of darkness. Then he took out the key and returned to         
\par the room, locking himself in as he did so.                                  
\par   The thing was still seated in the chair, straining over the table         
\par with bowed head, and humped back, and long fantastic arms. Had it           
\par not been for the red, jagged tear in the neck, and the clotted black        
\par pool that was slowly widening on the table, one would have said that        
\par the man was simply asleep.                                                  
\par   How quickly it had all been done! He felt strangely calm, and,            
\par walking over to the window, opened it and stepped out on the                
\par balcony. The wind had blown the fog away, and the sky was like a            
\par monstrous peacock's tail, starred with myriads of golden eyes. He           
\par looked down, and saw the policeman going his rounds and flashing the        
\par long beam of his lantern on the doors of the silent houses. The             
\par crimson spot of a prowling hansom gleamed at the corner, and then           
\par vanished. A woman in a fluttering shawl was creeping slowly by the          
\par railings, staggering as she went. Now and then she  stopped, and            
\par peered back. Once, she began to sing in a hoarse voice. The                 
\par policeman strolled over and said something to her. She stumbled             
\par away, laughing. A bitter blast swept across the Square. The gas             
\par lamps flickered, and became blue, and the leafless trees shook their        
\par black iron branches to and fro. He shivered, and went back, closing         
\par the window behind him.                                                      
\par   Having reached the door, he turned the key, and opened it. He did         
\par not even glance at the murdered man. He felt that the secret of the         
\par whole thing was not to realize the situation. The friend who had            
\par painted the fatal portrait to which all his misery had been due, had        
\par gone out of his life. That was enough.                                      
\par   Then he remembered the lamp. It was a rather curious one of               
\par Moorish workmanship, made of dull silver inlaid with arabesques of          
\par burnished steel, and studded with coarse turquoises. Perhaps it             
\par might be missed by his servant, and questions would be asked. He            
\par hesitated for a moment, then he turned back and took it from the            
\par table. He could not help seeing the dead thing. How still it was!           
\par How horribly white the long hands looked! It was like a dreadful wax        
\par image.                                                                      
\par   Having locked the door behind him, he crept quietly downstairs.           
\par The woodwork creaked, and seemed to cry out as if in pain. He               
\par stopped several times, and waited. No: everything was still. It was         
\par merely. the sound of his own footsteps.                                     
\par   When he reached the library, he saw the bag and coat in the               
\par corner. They must be hidden away somewhere. He unlocked a secret press      
\par that was in the wainscoting, a press in which he kept his own               
\par curious disguises, and put them into it. He could easily burn them          
\par afterwards. Then he pulled out his watch. It was twenty minutes to          
\par two.                                                                        
\par   He sat down and began to think. Every year- every month, almost- men      
\par were strangled in England for what he had done. There had been a            
\par madness of murder in the air. Some red star had come too close to           
\par the earth.... And yet what evidence was there against him? Basil            
\par Hallward had left the house at eleven. No one had seen him come in          
\par again. Most of the servants were at Selby Royal. His valet had gone to      
\par bed.... Paris? Yes. It was to Paris that Basil had gone, and by the         
\par midnight train, as he had intended. With his curious reserved               
\par habits, it would be months before any suspicions would be aroused.          
\par Months! Everything could be destroyed long before then.                     
\par   A sudden thought struck him. He put on his fur coat and hat, and          
\par went out into the hall. There he paused, hearing the slow, heavy tread      
\par of the policeman on the pavement outside, and seeing the flash of           
\par the bull's-eye reflected in the window. He waited, and held his             
\par breath.                                                                     
\par   After a few moments he drew back the latch, and slipped out,              
\par shutting the door very gently behind him. Then he began ringing, the        
\par bell. In about five minutes his valet appeared, half dressed, and           
\par looking very drowsy.                                                        
\par   "I am sorry to have had to wake you up, Francis," he said,                
\par stepping in; "but I had forgotten my latchkey. What time is it?"            
\par   "Ten minutes past two, sir," answered the man, looking at the             
\par clock and blinking.                                                         
\par   "Ten minutes past two? How horribly late! You must wake me at nine        
\par to-morrow. I have some work to do."                                         
\par   "All right, sir."                                                         
\par   "Did any one call this evening?"                                          
\par   "Mr. Hallward, sir. He stayed here till eleven, and then he went          
\par away to catch his train."                                                   
\par   "Oh! I am sorry I didn't see him. Did he leave any message?"              
\par   "No, sir, except that he would write to you from Paris, if he did         
\par not find you at the club."                                                  
\par   "That will do, Francis. Don't forget to call me at nine to-morrow."       
\par   "No, sir."                                                                
\par   The man shambled down the passage in his slippers.                        
\par   Dorian Gray threw his hat and coat upon the table, and passed into        
\par the library. For a quarter of an hour he walked up and down the room        
\par biting his lip, and thinking. Then he took down the Blue Book from one      
\par of the shelves, and began to turn over the leaves. "Alan Campbell,          
\par 152, Hertford Street, Mayfair." Yes; that was the man he wanted.            
\par                                                                             
