\par                              CHAPTER XIV                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   At nine o'clock the next morning his servant came in with a cup of        
\par chocolate on a tray, and opened the shutters. Dorian was sleeping           
\par quite peacefully, lying on his right side, with one hand underneath         
\par his cheek. He looked like a boy who had been tired out with play, or        
\par study.                                                                      
\par   The man had to touch him twice on the shoulder before he woke, and        
\par as he opened his eyes a faint smile passed across his lips, as              
\par though he had been lost in some delightful dream. Yet he had not            
\par dreamed at all. His night had been untroubled by any images of              
\par pleasure or of pain. But youth smiles without any reason. It is one of      
\par its chiefest charms.                                                        
\par   He turned round, and, leaning upon his elbow, began to sip his            
\par chocolate. The mellow November sun came streaming into the room. The        
\par sky was bright, and there was a genial warmth in the air. It was            
\par almost like a morning in May.                                               
\par   Gradually the events of the preceding night crept with silent             
\par bloodstained feet into his brain and reconstructed themselves there         
\par with terrible distinctness. He winced at the memory of all that he had      
\par suffered, and for a moment the same curious feeling of loathing for         
\par Basil Hallward, that had made him kill him as he sat in the chair,          
\par came back to him, and he grew cold with passion. The dead man was           
\par still sitting there, too, and in the sunlight now. How horrible that        
\par was! Such hideous things were for the darkness, not for the day.            
\par   He felt that if he brooded on what he had gone through he would           
\par sicken or grow mad. There were sins whose fascination was more in           
\par the memory than in the doing of them, strange triumphs that                 
\par gratified the pride more than the passions, and gave to the                 
\par intellect a quickened sense of joy, greater than a joy they brought,        
\par or could ever bring, to the senses. But this was not one of them. It        
\par was a thing to be driven out of the mind, to be drugged with                
\par poppies, to be strangled lest it might strangle one itself.                 
\par   When the half-hour struck, he passed his hand across his forehead,        
\par and then got up hastily, and dressed himself with even more than his        
\par usual care, giving a good deal of attention to the choice of his            
\par necktie and scarf-pin, and changing his rings more than once. He spent      
\par a long time also over breakfast, tasting the various dishes, talking        
\par to his valet about some new liveries that he was thinking of getting        
\par made for the servants at Selby, and going through his                       
\par correspondence. At some of the letters he smiled. Three of them             
\par bored him. One he read several times over, and then tore up with a          
\par slight look of annoyance in his face. "That awful thing, a woman's          
\par memory!" as Lord Henry had once said.                                       
\par   After he had drunk his cup of black coffee, he wiped his lips slowly      
\par with a napkin, motioned to his servant to wait, and going over to           
\par the table sat down and wrote two letters. One he put in his pocket,         
\par the other he handed to the valet.                                           
\par   "Take this round to 152, Hertford Street, Francis, and if Mr.             
\par Campbell is out of town, get his address."                                  
\par   As soon as he was alone, he lit a cigarette, and began sketching          
\par upon a piece of paper, drawing first flowers, and bits of                   
\par architecture, and then human faces. Suddenly he remarked that every         
\par face that he drew seemed to have a fantastic likeness to Basil              
\par Hallward. He frowned, and getting up, went over to the bookcase and         
\par took out a volume at hazard. He was determined that he would not think      
\par about what had happened until it became absolutely necessary that he        
\par should do so.                                                               
\par   When he had stretched himself on the sofa, he looked at the               
\par title-page of the book. It was Gautier's "Emaux et Camees,"                 
\par Charpentier's Japanese-paper edition, with the Jacquemart etching. The      
\par binding was of citron-green leather, with a design of gilt                  
\par trellis-work and dotted pomegranates. It had been given to him by           
\par Adrian Singleton. As he turned over the pages his eye fell on the poem      
\par about the hand of Lacenaire, the cold yellow hand "du supplice              
\par encore mal lavee," with its downy red hairs and its "doigts de faune."      
\par He glanced at his own white taper fingers, shuddering slightly in           
\par spite of himself, and passed on, till he came to those lovely               
\par stanzas upon Venice;                                                        
\par -                                                                           
\par               "Sur une gamme chromatique,                                   
\par                 Le sein de perles ruisselant,                               
\par               La Venus de l'Adriatique                                      
\par                 Sort de l'eau son corps rose et blanc.                      
\par -                                                                           
\par               Les domes, sur l'azur des ondes                               
\par                 Suivant la phrase au pur contour,                           
\par               S'enflent comme des gorges rondes                             
\par                 Que souleve un soupir d'amour.                              
\par -                                                                           
\par               L'esquif aborde et me depose,                                 
\par                 Jetant son amarre au pilier,                                
\par               Devant une facade rose,                                       
\par                 Sur le marbre d'un escalier."                               
\par -                                                                           
\par   How exquisite they were! As one read them, one seemed to be floating      
\par down the green waterways of the pink and pearl city, seated in a black      
\par gondola with silver prow and trailing curtains. The mere lines              
\par looked to him like those straight lines of turquoise-blue that              
\par follow one as one pushes out to the Lido. The sudden flashes of colour      
\par reminded him of the gleam of the opal-and-iris-throated birds that          
\par flutter round the tall honey-combed Campanile, or stalk, with such          
\par stately grace, through the dim, dust-stained arcades. Leaning back          
\par with half-closed eyes, he kept saying over and over to himself:             
\par -                                                                           
\par               "Devant une facade rose,                                      
\par                 Sur le marbre d'un escalier."                               
\par -                                                                           
\par   The whole of Venice was in those two lines. He remembered the autumn      
\par that he had passed there, and a wonderful love that had stirred him to      
\par mad, delightful follies. There was romance in every place. But Venice,      
\par like Oxford, had kept the background for romance, and, to the true          
\par romantic, background was everything, or almost everything. Basil had        
\par been with him part of the time, and had gone wild over Tintoret.            
\par Poor Basil! what a horrible way for a man to die!                           
\par   He sighed, and took up the volume again, and tried to forget. He          
\par read of the swallows that fly in and out of the little cafe at              
\par Smyrna where the Hadjis sit counting their amber beads and the              
\par turbaned merchants smoke their long tasselled pipes and talk gravely        
\par to each other; he read of the Obelisk in the Place de la Concorde that      
\par weeps tears of granite in its lonely sunless exile, and longs to be         
\par back by the hot lotus-covered Nile, where there are Sphinxes, and           
\par rose-red ibises, and white vultures with gilded claws, and crocodiles,      
\par with small beryl eyes, that crawl over the green steaming mud; he           
\par began to brood over those verses which, drawing music from                  
\par kiss-stained marble, tell of that curious statue that Gautier compares      
\par to a contralto voice, the "monstre charmant" that couches in the            
\par porphyry-room of the Louvre. But after a time the book fell from his        
\par hand. He grew nervous, and a horrible fit of terror came over him.          
\par What if Alan Campbell should be out of England? Days would elapse           
\par before he could come back. Perhaps he might refuse to come. What could      
\par he do then? Every moment was of vital importance.                           
\par   They had been great friends once, five years before- almost               
\par inseparable, indeed. Then the intimacy had come suddenly to an end.         
\par When they met in society now, it was only Dorian Gray who smiled; Alan      
\par Campbell never did.                                                         
\par   He was an extremely clever young man, though he had no real               
\par appreciation of the visible arts, and whatever little sense of the          
\par beauty of poetry he possessed he had gained entirely from Dorian.           
\par His dominant intellectual passion was for science. At Cambridge he had      
\par spent a great deal of his time working in the Laboratory, and had           
\par taken a good class in the Natural Science Tripos of his year.               
\par Indeed, he was still devoted to the study of chemistry, and had a           
\par laboratory of his own, in which he used to shut himself up all day          
\par long, greatly to the annoyance of his mother, who had set her heart on      
\par his standing for parliament and had a vague idea that a chemist was         
\par a person who made up prescriptions. He was an excellent musician,           
\par however, as well, and played both the violin and the piano better than      
\par most amateurs. In fact, it was music that had first brought him and         
\par Dorian Gray together- music and that indefinable attraction that            
\par Dorian seemed to be able to exercise whenever he wished, and indeed         
\par exercised often without being conscious of it. They had met at Lady         
\par Berkshire's the night that Rubinstein played there, and after that          
\par used to be always seen together at the Opera, and wherever good             
\par music was going on. For eighteen months their intimacy lasted.              
\par Campbell was always either at Selby Royal or in Grosvenor Square. To        
\par him, as to many others, Dorian Dorian Gray was the type of                  
\par everything that is wonderful and fascinating in life. Whether or not a      
\par quarrel had taken place between them no one ever knew. But suddenly         
\par people remarked that they scarcely spoke when they met, and that            
\par Campbell seemed always to go away early from any party at which Dorian      
\par Gray was present. He had changed, too- was strangely melancholy at          
\par times, appeared almost to dislike hearing music, and would never            
\par himself play, giving as his excuse, when he was called upon, that he        
\par was so absorbed in science that he had no time left in which to             
\par practise. And this was certainly true. Every day he seemed to become        
\par more interested in biology, and his name appeared once or twice in          
\par some of the scientific reviews, in connection with certain curious          
\par experiments.                                                                
\par   This was the man Dorian Gray was waiting for. Every second he kept        
\par glancing at the clock. As the minutes went by he became horribly            
\par agitated. At last he got up, and began to pace up and down the room,        
\par looking like a beautiful caged thing. He took long stealthy strides.        
\par His hands were curiously cold.                                              
\par   The suspense became unbearable. Time seemed to him to be crawling         
\par with feet of lead, while he by monstrous winds was being swept towards      
\par the jagged edge of some black cleft of precipice. He knew what was          
\par waiting for him there; saw it indeed, and, shuddering, crushed with         
\par dank hands his burning lids as though he would have robbed the very         
\par brain of sight, and driven the eyeballs back into their cave. It was        
\par useless. The brain had its own food on which it battened, and the           
\par imagination, made grotesque by terror, twisted and distorted as a           
\par living thing by pain, danced like some foul puppet on a stand, and          
\par grinned through moving masks. Then, suddenly, Time stopped for him.         
\par Yes: that blind, slow-breathing thing crawled no more, and horrible         
\par thoughts, Time being dead, raced nimbly on in front, and dragged a          
\par hideous future from its grave, and showed it to him. He stared at           
\par it. Its very horror made him stone.                                         
\par   At last the door opened, and his servant entered. He turned glazed        
\par eyes upon him.                                                              
\par   "Mr. Campbell, sir," said the man.                                        
\par   A sigh of relief broke from his parched lips, and the colour came         
\par back to his cheeks.                                                         
\par   "Ask him to come in at once, Francis." He felt that he was himself        
\par again. His mood of cowardice had passed away.                               
\par   The man bowed, and retired. In a few moments Alan Campbell walked         
\par in, looking very stern and rather pale, his pallor being intensified        
\par by his coal-black hair and dark eyebrows.                                   
\par   "Alan! this is kind of you. I thank you for coming."                      
\par   "I had intended never to enter your house again, Gray. But you            
\par said it was a matter of life and death." His voice was hard and             
\par cold. He spoke with slow deliberation. There was a look of contempt in      
\par the steady searching gaze that he turned on Dorian. He kept his             
\par hands in the pockets of his Astrakhan coat, and seemed not to have          
\par noticed the gesture with which he had been greeted.                         
\par   "Yes: it is a matter of life and death, Alan, and to more than one        
\par person. Sit down."                                                          
\par   Campbell took a chair by the table, and Dorian sat opposite to            
\par him. The two men's eyes met. In Dorian's there was infinite pity. He        
\par knew that what he was going to do was dreadful.                             
\par   After a strained moment of silence, he leaned across and said,            
\par very quietly, but watching the effect of each word upon the face of         
\par him he had sent for, "Alan, in a locked room at the top of this house,      
\par a room to which nobody but myself has access, a dead man is seated          
\par at a table. He has been dead ten hours now. Don't stir, and don't look      
\par at me like that. Who the man is, why he died, how he died, are matters      
\par that do not concern you. What you have to do is this-"                      
\par   "Stop, Gray. I don't want to know anything further. Whether what you      
\par have told me is true or not true, doesn't concern me. I entirely            
\par decline to be mixed up in your life. Keep your horrible secrets to          
\par yourself. They don't interest me any more."                                 
\par   "Alan, they will have to interest you. This one will have to              
\par interest you. I am awfully sorry for you, Alan. But I can't help            
\par myself. You are the one mark who is able to save me. I am forced to         
\par bring you into the matter. I have no option. Alan, you are scientific.      
\par You know about chemistry, and things of that kind. You have made            
\par experiments. What you have got to do is to destroy the thing that is        
\par upstairs- to destroy it so that not a vestige of it will be left.           
\par Nobody saw this person come into the house. Indeed, at the present          
\par moment he is supposed to be in Paris. He will not be missed for             
\par months. When he is missed, there must be no trace of him found here.        
\par You, Alan, you must change him, and everything that belongs to him,         
\par into a handful of ashes that I may scatter in the air."                     
\par   "You are mad, Dorian."                                                    
\par   "Ah! I was waiting for you to call me Dorian."                            
\par   "You are mad, I tell you- mad to imagine that I would raise a finger      
\par to help you, mad to make this monstrous confession. I will have             
\par nothing to do with this matter, whatever it is. Do you think I am           
\par going to peril my reputation for you? What is it to me what devil's         
\par work you are up to?"                                                        
\par   "It was suicide, Alan."                                                   
\par   "I am glad of that. But who drove him to it? You, I should fancy."        
\par   "Do you still refuse to do this for me?"                                  
\par   "Of course I refuse. I will have absolutely nothing to do with it. I      
\par don't care what shame comes on you. You deserve it all. I should not        
\par be sorry to see you disgraced, publicly disgraced. How dare you ask         
\par me, of all men in the world, to mix myself up in this horror? I should      
\par have thought you knew more about people's characters. Your friend Lord      
\par Henry Wotton can't have taught you much about psychology, whatever          
\par else he has taught you. Nothing will induce me to stir a step to            
\par help you. You have come to the wrong man. Go to some of your                
\par friends. Don't come to me."                                                 
\par   "Alan, it was murder. I killed him. You don't know what he had            
\par made me suffer. Whatever my life is, he had more to do with the making      
\par or marring of it than poor Harry has had. He may not have intended it,      
\par the result was he same."                                                    
\par   "Murder! Good God, Dorian, is that what you have come to? I shall         
\par not inform upon you. It is not my business. Besides, without my             
\par stirring in the matter, you are certain to be arrested. Nobody ever         
\par commits a crime without doing something stupid. But I will have             
\par nothing to do with it."                                                     
\par   "You must have something to do with it. Wait, wait a moment;              
\par listen to me. Only listen, Alan. All I ask of you is to perform a           
\par certain scientific experiment. You go to hospitals and dead-houses,         
\par and the horrors that you do there don't affect you. If in some hideous      
\par dissecting-room or fetid laboratory you found this man lying on a           
\par leaden table with red gutters scooped out in it for the blood to            
\par flow through you would simply look upon him as an admirable subject.        
\par You would not turn a hair. You would not believe that you were doing        
\par anything wrong. On the contrary, you would probably feel that you were      
\par benefiting the human race, or increasing the sum of knowledge in the        
\par world, or gratifying intellectual curiosity, or something of that           
\par kind. What I want you to do is merely what you have often done before.      
\par Indeed, to destroy a body must be far less horrible than what you           
\par are accustomed to work at. And, remember, it is the only piece of           
\par evidence against me. If it is discovered, I am lost; and it is sure to      
\par be discovered unless you help me."                                          
\par   "I have no desire to help you. You forget that. I am simply               
\par indifferent to the whole thing. It has nothing to do with me."              
\par   "Alan, I entreat you. Think of the position I am in. Just before you      
\par came I almost fainted with terror. You may know terror yourself some        
\par day. No! don't think of that. Look at the matter purely from the            
\par scientific point of view. You don't inquire where the dead things on        
\par which you experiment come from. Don't inquire now. I have told you too      
\par much as it is. But I beg of you to do this. We were friends once,           
\par Alan."                                                                      
\par   "Don't speak about those days, Dorian: they are dead."                    
\par   "The dead linger sometimes. The man upstairs will not go away. He is      
\par sitting at the table with bowed head and outstretched arms. Alan!           
\par Alan! if you don't come to my assistance I am ruined. Why, they will        
\par hang me, Alan! Don't you understand? They will hang me for what I have      
\par done."                                                                      
\par   "There is no good in prolonging this scene. I absolutely refuse to        
\par do anything in the matter. It is insane of you to ask me."                  
\par   "You refuse?"                                                             
\par   "Yes."                                                                    
\par   "I entreat you, Alan."                                                    
\par   "It is useless."                                                          
\par   The same look of pity came into Dorian Gray's eyes. Then he               
\par stretched out his hand, took a piece of paper, and wrote something          
\par on it. He read it over twice, folded it carefully, and pushed it            
\par across the table. Having done this, he got up, and went over to the         
\par window.                                                                     
\par   Campbell looked at him in surprise, and then took up the paper,           
\par and opened it. As he read it, his face became ghastly pale, and he          
\par fell back in his chair. A horrible sense of sickness came over him. He      
\par felt as if his heart was beating itself to death in some empty hollow.      
\par   After two or three minutes of terrible silence, Dorian turned round,      
\par and came and stood behind him, putting his hand upon his shoulder.          
\par   "I am so sorry for you, Alan," he murmured, "but you leave me no          
\par alternative. I have a letter written already. Here it is. You see           
\par the address. If you don't help me, I must send it. If you don't help        
\par me, I will send it. You know what the result will be. But you are           
\par going to help me. It is impossible for you to refuse now. I tried to        
\par spare you. You will do me the justice to admit that. You were stern,        
\par harsh, offensive. You treated me as no man has ever dared to treat me-      
\par no living man, at any rate. I bore it all. Now it is for me to dictate      
\par terms."                                                                     
\par   Campbell buried his face in his hands, and a shudder passed               
\par through him.                                                                
\par   "Yes, it is my turn to dictate terms, Alan. You know what they            
\par are. The thing is quite simple. Come, don't work yourself into this         
\par fever. The thing has to be done. Face it, and do it."                       
\par   A groan broke from Campbell's lips, and he shivered all over. The         
\par ticking of the clock on the mantel-piece seemed to him to be                
\par dividing time into separate atoms of agony, each of which was too           
\par terrible to be borne. He felt as if an iron ring was being slowly           
\par tightened round his forehead, as if the disgrace with which he was          
\par threatened had already come upon him. The hand upon his shoulder            
\par weighed like a band of lead. It was intolerable. It seemed to crush         
\par him.                                                                        
\par   "Come, Alan, you must decide at once."                                    
\par   "I cannot do it," he said mechanically, as though words could             
\par alter things.                                                               
\par   "You must. You have no choice. Don't delay."                              
\par   He hesitated a moment. "Is there a fire in the room upstairs?"            
\par   "Yes, there is a gas-fire with asbestos."                                 
\par   "I shall have to go home and get some things from the laboratory."        
\par   "No, Alan, you must not leave the house. Write out on a sheet of          
\par notepaper what you want, and my servant will take a cab and bring           
\par the things back to you."                                                    
\par   Campbell scrawled a few lines, blotted them, and addressed an             
\par envelope to his assistant. Dorian took the note up and read it              
\par carefully. Then he rang the bell, and gave it to his valet, with            
\par orders to return as soon as possible, and to bring the things with          
\par him.                                                                        
\par   As the hall door shut, Campbell started nervously, and, having got        
\par up from the chair, went over to the chimney-piece. He was shivering         
\par with a kind of ague. For nearly twenty minutes, neither of the men          
\par spoke. A fly buzzed noisily about the room, and the ticking of the          
\par clock was like the beat of a hammer.                                        
\par   As the chime struck one, Campbell turned round, and, looking at           
\par Dorian Gray, saw that his eyes were filled with tears. There was            
\par something in the purity and refinement of that sad face that seemed to      
\par enrage him. "You are infamous, absolutely infamous!" he muttered.           
\par   "Hush, Alan: you have saved my life," said Dorian.                        
\par   "Your life? Good heavens! what a life that is. You have gone from         
\par corruption to corruption, and you have culminated in crime. In doing        
\par what I am going to do, what you force me to do, it is not of your life      
\par that I am thinking."                                                        
\par   "Ah, Alan," murmured Dorian, with a sigh, "I wish you had a               
\par thousandth part of the pity for me that I have for you." He turned          
\par away as he spoke, and stood looking out at the garden. Campbell made        
\par no answer.                                                                  
\par   After about ten minutes a knock came to the door, and the servant         
\par entered, carrying a large mahogany chest of chemicals, with a long          
\par coil of steel and platinum wire and two rather curiously-shaped iron        
\par clamps.                                                                     
\par   "Shall I leave the things here, sir?" he asked Campbell.                  
\par   "Yes," said Dorian. "And I am afraid, Francis, that I have another        
\par errand for you. What is the name of the man at Richmond who supplies        
\par Selby with orchids?"                                                        
\par   "Harden, sir."                                                            
\par   "Yes- Harden. You must go down to Richmond at once, see Harden            
\par personally, and tell him to send twice as many orchids as I ordered,        
\par and to have as few white ones as possible. In fact, I don't want any        
\par white ones. It is a lovely day, Francis, and Richmond is a very pretty      
\par place, otherwise I wouldn't bother you about it."                           
\par   "No trouble, sir. At what time shall I be back?"                          
\par   Dorian looked at Campbell. "How long will your experiment take,           
\par Alan?" he said, in a calm, indifferent voice. The presence of a             
\par third person in the room seemed to give him extraordinary courage.          
\par   Campbell frowned, and bit his lip. "It will take about five               
\par hours," he answered.                                                        
\par   "It will be time enough, then, if you are back at half-past seven,        
\par Francis. Or stay: just leave my things out for dressing. You can            
\par have the evening to yourself. I am not dining at home, so I shall           
\par not want you."                                                              
\par   "Thank you, sir," said the man, leaving the room.                         
\par   "Now, Alan, there is not a moment to be lost. How heavy this chest        
\par is! I'll take it for you. You bring the other things." He spoke             
\par rapidly, and in an authoritative manner. Campbell felt dominated by         
\par him. They left the room together.                                           
\par   When they reached the top landing, Dorian took out the key and            
\par turned it in the lock. Then he stopped, and a troubled look came            
\par into his eyes. He shuddered. "I don't think I can go in, Alan," he          
\par murmured.                                                                   
\par   "It is nothing to me. I don't require you," said Campbell, coldly.        
\par   Dorian half opened the door. As he did so, he saw the face of his         
\par portrait leering in the sunlight. On the floor in front of it the torn      
\par curtain was lying. He remembered that the night before he had               
\par forgotten, for the first time in his life, to hide the fatal canvas,        
\par and was about to rush forward, when he drew back with a shudder.            
\par   What was that loathsome red dew that gleamed, wet and glistening, on      
\par one of the hands, as though the canvas had sweated blood? How horrible      
\par it was!- more horrible, it seemed to him for the moment, than the           
\par silent thing he knew was stretched across the table, the thing whose        
\par grotesque misshapen shadow, on the spotted carpet showed him that it        
\par had not stirred, but was still there, as he had left it.                    
\par   He heaved a deep breath, opened the door a little wider, and with         
\par half-closed eyes and averted head walked quickly in, determined that        
\par he would not look even once upon the dead man. Then, stooping down,         
\par and taking up the gold-and-purple hanging, he flung it right over           
\par the picture.                                                                
\par   There he stopped, feeling afraid to turn round, and his eyes fixed        
\par themselves on the intricacies of the pattern before him. He heard           
\par Campbell bringing in the heavy chest, and the irons, and the other          
\par things that he had required for his dreadful work. He began to              
\par wonder if he and Basil Hallward had ever met, and, if so, what they         
\par had thought of each other.                                                  
\par   "Leave me now," said a stern voice behind him.                            
\par   He turned and hurried out, just conscious that the dead man had been      
\par thrust back into the chair, and that Campbell was gazing into a             
\par glistening yellow face. As he was going downstairs he heard the key         
\par being turned in the lock.                                                   
\par   It was long after seven when Campbell came back into the library. He      
\par was pale, but absolutely calm. "I have done what you asked me to            
\par do," he muttered. "And now, good-bye. Let us never see each other           
\par again."                                                                     
\par   "You have saved me from ruin, Alan. I cannot forget that," said           
\par Dorian, simply.                                                             
\par   As soon as Campbell had left, he went upstairs. There was a horrible      
\par smell of nitric acid in the room. But the thing that had been               
\par sitting at the table was gone.                                              
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                               CHAPTER XV                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   That evening, at eight-thirty, exquisitely dressed, and wearing a         
\par large button-hole of Parma violets, Dorian Gray was ushered into            
\par Lady Narborough's drawing-room by bowing servants. His forehead was         
\par throbbing with maddened nerves, and he felt wildly excited, but his         
\par manner as he bent over his hostess's hand was as easy and graceful          
\par as ever. Perhaps one never seems so much at one's ease as when one has      
\par to play a part. Certainly no one looking at Dorian Gray that night          
\par could have believed that he had passed through a tragedy as horrible        
\par as any tragedy of our age. Those finely-shaped fingers could never          
\par have clutched a knife of sin, nor those smiling lips have cried out on      
\par God and goodness. He himself could not help wondering at the calm of        
\par his demeanour, and for a moment felt keenly the terrible pleasure of a      
\par double life.                                                                
\par   It was a small party, got up rather in a hurry by Lady Narborough,        
\par who was a very clever woman, with what Lord Henry used to describe          
\par as the remains of really remarkable ugliness. She had proved an             
\par excellent wife to one of our most tedious ambassadors, and having           
\par buried her husband properly in a marble mausoleum, which she had            
\par herself designed, and married off her daughters to some rich, rather        
\par elderly men, she devoted herself now to the pleasures of French             
\par fiction, French cookery, and French esprit when she could get it.           
\par   Dorian was one of her especial favourites, and she always told him        
\par that she was extremely glad she had not met him in early life. "I           
\par know, my dear, I should have fallen madly in love with you," she            
\par used to say, "and thrown my bonnet right over the mills for your sake.      
\par It is most fortunate that you were not thought of at the time. As it        
\par was, our bonnets were so unbecoming, and the mills were so occupied in      
\par trying to raise the wind, that I never had even a flirtation with           
\par anybody. However, that was all Narborough's fault. He was dreadfully        
\par short-sighted, and there is no pleasure in taking in a husband who          
\par never sees anything."                                                       
\par   Her guests this evening were rather tedious. The fact was, as she         
\par explained to Dorian, behind a very shabby fan, one of her married           
\par daughters had come up quite suddenly to stay with her, and, to make         
\par matters worse, had actually brought her husband with her. "I think          
\par it is most unkind of her, my dear," she whispered. "Of course I go and      
\par stay with them every summer after I come from Homburg, but then an old      
\par woman like me must have fresh air sometimes, and besides, I really          
\par wake them up. You don't know what an existence they lead down there.        
\par It is pure unadulterated country life. They get up early, because they      
\par have so much to do, and go to bed early because they have so little to      
\par think about. There has not been a scandal in the neighbourhood since        
\par the time of Queen Elizabeth, and consequently they all fall asleep          
\par after dinner. You sha'n't sit next either of them. You shall sit by         
\par me, and amuse me."                                                          
\par   Dorian murmured a graceful compliment, and looked round the room.         
\par Yes: it was certainly a tedious party. Two of the people he had             
\par never seen before, and the others consisted of Ernest Harrowden, one        
\par of those middle-aged mediocrities so common in London clubs who have        
\par no enemies, but are thoroughly disliked by their friends; Lady Roxton,      
\par an overdressed woman of forty-seven, with a hooked nose, who was            
\par always trying to get herself compromised, but was so peculiarly             
\par plain that to her great disappointment no one would ever believe            
\par anything against her; Mrs. Erlynne, a pushing nobody, with a                
\par delightful lisp, and Venetian-red hair; Lady Alice Chapman, his             
\par hostess's daughter, a dowdy dull girl, with one of those                    
\par characteristic British faces, that, once seen are never remembered;         
\par and her husband, a red-cheeked, white-whiskered creature who, like          
\par so many of his class, was under the impression that inordinate              
\par joviality can atone for an entire lack of ideas.                            
\par   He was rather sorry he had come, till Lady Narborough, looking at         
\par the great ormolu gilt clock that sprawled in gaudy curves on the            
\par mauve-draped mantelshelf, exclaimed: "How horrid of Henry Wotton to be      
\par so late! I sent round to him this morning on chance, and he promised        
\par faithfully not to disappoint me."                                           
\par   It was some consolation that Harry was to be there, and when the          
\par door opened and he heard his slow musical voice lending charm to            
\par some insincere apology, he ceased to feel bored.                            
\par   But at dinner he could not eat anything. Plate after plate went away      
\par untasted. Lady Narborough kept scolding him for what she called "an         
\par insult to poor Adolphe, who invented the menu specially for you,"           
\par and now and then Lord Henry looked across at him, wondering at his          
\par silence and abstracted manner. From time to time the butler filled his      
\par glass with champagne. He drank eagerly, and his thirst seemed to            
\par increase.                                                                   
\par   "Dorian," said Lord Henry, at last, as the chaudfroid was being           
\par handed round, "what is the matter with you to-night? You are quite out      
\par of sorts."                                                                  
\par   "I believe he is in love," cried Lady Narborough, "and that he is         
\par afraid to tell me for fear I should be jealous. He is quite right. I        
\par certainly should."                                                          
\par   "Dear Lady Narborough," murmured Dorian, smiling, "I have not been        
\par in love for a whole week- not, in fact, since Madame de Ferrol left         
\par town."                                                                      
\par   "How you men can fall in love with that woman!" exclaimed the old         
\par lady. "I really cannot understand it."                                      
\par   "It is simply because she remembers you when you were a little girl,      
\par Lady Narborough," said Lord Henry. "She is the one link between us and      
\par your short frocks."                                                         
\par   "She does not remember my short frocks at all, Lord Henry. But I          
\par remember her very well at Vienna thirty years ago, and how                  
\par dicolletee she was then."                                                   
\par   "She is still dicolletee," he answered, taking an olive in his            
\par long fingers; "and when she is in a very smart gown she looks like          
\par an edition de luxe of a bad French novel. She is really wonderful, and      
\par full of surprises. Her capacity for family affection is extraordinary.      
\par When her third husband died, her hair turned quite gold from grief."        
\par   "How can you, Harry!" cried Dorian.                                       
\par   "It is a most romantic explanation," laughed the hostess. "But her        
\par third husband, Lord Henry! You don't mean to say Ferrol is the              
\par fourth?"                                                                    
\par   "Certainly, Lady Narborough."                                             
\par   "I don't believe a word of it."                                           
\par   "Well, ask Mr. Gray. He is one of her most intimate friends."             
\par   "Is it true, Mr. Gray?"                                                   
\par   "She assures me so, Lady Narborough," said Dorian. "I asked her           
\par whether, like Marguerite de Navarre, she had their hearts embalmed and      
\par hung at her girdle. She told me she didn't, because none of them had        
\par had any hearts at all."                                                     
\par   "Four husbands! Upon my word that is trop de zele."                       
\par   "Trop d' audace, I tell her," said Dorian.                                
\par   "Oh! she is audacious enough for anything, my dear. And what is           
\par Ferrol like? I don't know him."                                             
\par   "The husbands of very beautiful women belong to the criminal              
\par classes," said Lord Henry, sipping his wine.                                
\par   Lady Narborough hit him with her fan. "Lord Henry, I am not at all        
\par surprised that the world says that you are extremely wicked."               
\par   "But what world says that?" asked Lord Henry, elevating his               
\par eyebrows. "It can only be the next world. This world and I are on           
\par excellent terms."                                                           
\par   "Everybody I know says you are very wicked," cried the old lady,          
\par shaking her head.                                                           
\par   Lord Henry looked serious for some moments. "It is perfectly              
\par monstrous," he said, at last, "the way people go about nowadays saying      
\par things against one behind one's back that are absolutely and                
\par entirely true."                                                             
\par   "Isn't he incorrigible?" cried Dorian, leaning forward in his chair.      
\par   "I hope so," said his hostess, laughing. "But really if you all           
\par worship Madame de Ferrol in this ridiculous way, I shall have to marry      
\par again so as to be in the fashion."                                          
\par   "You will never marry again, Lady Narborough," broke in Lord              
\par Henry. "You were far too happy. When a woman marries again it is            
\par because she detested her first husband. When a man marries again, it        
\par is because he adored his first wife. Women try their luck; men risk         
\par theirs."                                                                    
\par   "Narborough wasn't perfect," cried the old lady.                          
\par   "If he had been, you would not have loved him, my dear lady," was         
\par the rejoinder. "Women love us for our defects. If we have enough of         
\par them they will forgive us everything, even our intellects. You will         
\par never ask me to dinner again, after saying this, I am afraid, Lady          
\par Narborough; but it is quite true."                                          
\par   "Of course it is true, Lord Henry. If we women did not love you           
\par for your defects, where would you all be? Not one of you would ever be      
\par married. You would be a set of unfortunate bachelors. Not, however,         
\par that that would alter you much. Nowadays all the married men live like      
\par bachelors, and all the bachelors like married men."                         
\par   "Fin de siecle," murmured Lord Henry.                                     
\par   "Fin du globe," answered his hostess.                                     
\par   "I wish it were fin du globe," said Dorian, with a sigh. "Life is         
\par a great disappointment."                                                    
\par   "Ah, my dear," cried Lady Narborough, putting on her gloves,              
\par "don't tell me that you have exhausted Life. When a man says that           
\par one knows that Life has exhausted him. Lord Henry is very wicked,           
\par and I sometimes wish that I had been; but you are made to be good- you      
\par look so good. I must find you a nice wife. Lord Henry, don't you think      
\par that Mr. Gray should get married?"                                          
\par   "I am always telling him so, Lady Narborough," said Lord Henry, with      
\par a bow.                                                                      
\par   "Well, we must look out for a suitable match for him. I shall go          
\par through Debrett carefully to-night. and draw out a list of all the          
\par eligible young ladies."                                                     
\par   "With their ages, Lady Narborough?" asked Dorian.                         
\par   "Of course, with their ages, slightly edited. But nothing must be         
\par done in a hurry. I want it to be what The Morning Post calls a              
\par suitable alliance, and I want you both to be happy."                        
\par   "What nonsense people talk about happy marriages!" exclaimed Lord         
\par Henry. "A man can be happy with any woman, as long as he does not love      
\par her."                                                                       
\par   "Ah! what a cynic you are!" cried the old lady, pushing back her          
\par chair, and nodding to Lady Ruxton. "You must come and dine with me          
\par soon again. You are really an admirable tonic, much better than what        
\par Sir Andrew prescribes for me. You must tell me what people you would        
\par like to meet, though. I want it to be a delightful gathering."              
\par   "I like men who have a future, and women who have a past," he             
\par answered. "Or do you think that would make it a petticoat party?"           
\par   "I fear so," she said, laughing, as she stood up. "A thousand             
\par pardons, my dear Lady Ruxton," she added, "I didn't see you hadn't          
\par finished your cigarette."                                                   
\par   "Never mind, Lady Narborough. I smoke a great deal too much. I am         
\par going to limit myself, for the future."                                     
\par   "Pray don't, Lady Ruxton," said Lord Henry. "Moderation is a fatal        
\par thing. Enough is as bad as a meal. More than enough is as good as a         
\par feast."                                                                     
\par   Lady Ruxton glanced at him curiously. "You must come and explain          
\par that to me some afternoon, Lord Henry. It sounds a fascinating              
\par theory," she murmured, as she swept out of the room.                        
\par   "Now, mind you don't stay too long over your politics and                 
\par scandal," cried Lady Narborough from the door. "If you do, we are sure      
\par to squabble upstairs."                                                      
\par   The men laughed, and Mr. Chapman got up solemnly from the foot of         
\par the table and came up to the top. Dorian Gray changed his seat, and         
\par went and sat by Lord Henry. Mr. Chapman began to talk in a loud             
\par voice about the situation in the House of Commons. He guffawed at           
\par his adversaries. The word doctrinaire- word full of terror to the           
\par British mind- reappeared from time to time between his explosions.          
\par An alliterative prefix served as an ornament of oratory. He hoisted         
\par the Union Jack on the pinnacles of Thought. The inherited stupidity of      
\par the race- sound English common sense he jovially termed it- was             
\par shown to be the proper bulwark for Society.                                 
\par   A smile curved Lord Henry's lips, and he turned round and looked          
\par at Dorian.                                                                  
\par   "Are you better, my dear fellow?" he asked. "You seemed rather out        
\par of sorts at dinner."                                                        
\par   "I am quite well, Harry. I am tired. That is all."                        
\par   "You were charming last night. The little Duchess is quite devoted        
\par to you. She tells me she is going down to Selby."                           
\par   "She has promised to come on the twentieth."                              
\par   "Is Monmouth to be there too?"                                            
\par   "Oh, yes, Harry."                                                         
\par   "He bores me dreadfully, almost as much as he bores her. She is very      
\par clever, too clever for a woman. She lacks the indefinable charm of          
\par weakness. It is the feet of clay that makes the gold of the image           
\par precious. Her feet are very pretty, but they are not feet of clay.          
\par White porcelain feet, if you like. They have been through the fire,         
\par and what fire does not destroy, it hardens. She has had experiences."       
\par   "How long has she been married?" asked Dorian.                            
\par   "An eternity, she tells me. I believe, according to the peerage,          
\par it is ten years, but ten years with Monmouth must have been like            
\par eternity, with time thrown in. Who else is coming?"                         
\par   "Oh, the Willoughbys, Lord Rugby and his wife, our hostess, Geoffrey      
\par Clouston, the usual set. I have asked Lord Grotrian."                       
\par   "I like him," said Lord Henry. "A great many people don't, but I          
\par find him charming. He atones for being occasionally somewhat                
\par over-dressed, by being always absolutely over-educated. He is a very        
\par modern type."                                                               
\par   "I don't know if he will be able to come, Harry. He may have to go        
\par to Monte Carlo with his father."                                            
\par   "Ah! what a nuisance people's people are! Try and make him come.          
\par By the way, Dorian, you ran off very early last night. You left before      
\par eleven. What did you do afterwards? Did you go straight home?"              
\par   Dorian glanced at him hurriedly, and frowned. "No, Harry," he said        
\par at last, "I did not get home till nearly three."                            
\par   "Did you go to the club?"                                                 
\par   "Yes," he answered. Then he bit his lip. "No, I don't mean that. I        
\par didn't go to the club. I walked about. I forget what I did.... How          
\par inquisitive you are, Harry! You always want to know what one has            
\par been doing. I always want to forget what I have been doing. I came          
\par in at half-past two, if you wish to know the exact time. I had left my      
\par latchkey at home, and my servant had to let me in. If you want any          
\par corroborative evidence on the subject you can ask him."                     
\par   Lord Henry shrugged his shoulders. "My dear fellow, as if I cared!        
\par Let us go up to the drawing-room. No sherry, thank you, Mr. Chapman.        
\par Something has happened to you, Dorian. Tell me what it is. You are not      
\par yourself to-night."                                                         
\par   "Don't mind me, Harry. I am irritable, and out of temper. I shall         
\par come round and see you to-morrow or next day. Make my excuses to Lady.      
\par Narborough. I sha'n't go upstairs. I shall go home. I must go home."        
\par   "All right, Dorian. I dare say I shall see you to-morrow at               
\par tea-time. The Duchess is coming."                                           
\par   "I will try to be there, Harry," he said, leaving the room. As he         
\par drove back to his own house he was conscious that the sense of              
\par terror he thought he had strangled had come back to him. Lord               
\par Henry's casual questioning had made him lose his nerves for the             
\par moment, and he wanted his nerve still. Things that were dangerous           
\par had to be destroyed. He winced. He hated the idea of even touching          
\par them.                                                                       
\par   Yet it had to be done. He realized that, and when he had locked           
\par the door of his library, he opened the secret press into which he           
\par had thrust Basil Hallward's coat and bag. A huge fire was blazing.          
\par He piled another log on it. The smell of singeing clothes and               
\par burning leather was horrible. It took him three-quarters of an hour to      
\par consume everything. At the end he felt faint and sick, and having           
\par lit some Algerian pastilles in a pierced copper brazier, he bathed his      
\par hands and forehead with a cool musk-scented vinegar.                        
\par   Suddenly he started. His eyes grew strangely bright and he gnawed         
\par nervously at his under-lip. Between two of the windows stood a large        
\par Florentine cabinet, made out of ebony, and inlaid with ivory and            
\par blue lapis. He watched it as though it were a thing that could              
\par fascinate and make afraid, as though it held something that he              
\par longed for and yet almost loathed. His breath quickened. A mad craving      
\par came over him. He lit a cigarette and then threw it away. His               
\par eyelids drooped till the long fringed lashes almost touched his cheek.      
\par But he still watched the cabinet. At last he got up from the sofa on        
\par which he had been lying, went over to it, and, having unlocked it,          
\par touched some hidden spring. A triangular drawer passed slowly out. His      
\par fingers moved instinctively towards it, dipped in, and closed on            
\par something. It was a small Chinese box of black and gold-dust                
\par lacquer, elaborately wrought, the sides patterned with curved waves,        
\par and the silken cords hung with round crystals and tasselled in plaited      
\par metal threads. He opened it. Inside was a green paste waxy in               
\par lustre, the odour curiously heavy and persistent.                           
\par   He hesitated for some moments, with a strangely immobile smile            
\par upon his face. Then shivering, though the atmosphere of the room was        
\par terribly hot, he drew himself up, and glanced at the clock. It was          
\par twenty minutes to twelve. He put the box back, shutting the cabinet         
\par doors as he did so, and went into his bedroom.                              
\par   As midnight was striking bronze blows upon the dusky air, Dorian          
\par Gray, dressed commonly, and with a muffler wrapped round his throat,        
\par crept quietly out of his house. In Bond Street he found a hansom            
\par with a good horse. He hailed it, and in a low voice gave the driver an      
\par address.                                                                    
\par   The man shook his head. "It is too far for me," he muttered.              
\par   "Here is a sovereign for you," said Dorian. "You shall have               
\par another if you drive fast."                                                 
\par   "All right, sir," answered the man, "you will be there in an              
\par hour," and after his fare had got in he turned his horse round, and         
\par drove rapidly towards the river.                                            
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                              CHAPTER XVI                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   A cold rain began to fall, and the blurred street-lamps looked            
\par ghastly in the dripping mist. The public-houses were just closing, and      
\par dim men and women were clustering in broken groups round their              
\par doors. From some of the bars came the sound of horrible laughter. In        
\par others, drunkards brawled and screamed.                                     
\par   Lying back in the hansom, with his hat pulled over his forehead,          
\par Dorian Gray watched with listless eyes the sordid shame of the great        
\par city, and now and then he repeated to himself the words that Lord           
\par Henry had said to him on the first day they had met, "To cure the soul      
\par by means of the senses, and the senses by means of the soul." Yes,          
\par that was the secret. He had often tried it, and would try it again          
\par now. There were opium-dens, where one could buy oblivion, dens of           
\par horror where the memory of old sins could be destroyed by the               
\par madness of sins that were new.                                              
\par   The moon hung low in the sky like a yellow skull. From time to            
\par time a huge misshapen cloud stretched a long arm across and hid it.         
\par The gas-lamps grew fewer, and the streets more narrow and gloomy. Once      
\par the man lost his way, and had to drive back half a mile. A steam            
\par rose from the horse as it splashed up the puddles. The side-windows of      
\par the hansom were clogged with a grey-flannel mist.                           
\par   "To cure the soul by means of the senses, and the senses by means of      
\par the soul!" How the words rang in his ears! His soul, certainly, was         
\par sick to death. Was it true that the senses could cure it? Innocent          
\par blood had been spilt. What could atone for that? Ah! for that there         
\par was no atonement; but though forgiveness was impossible, forgetfulness      
\par was possible still, and he was determined to forget, to stamp the           
\par thing out, to crush it as one would crush the adder that had stung          
\par one. Indeed, what right had Basil to have spoken to him as he had           
\par done? Who had made him a judge over others? He had said things that         
\par were dreadful, horrible, not to be endured.                                 
\par   On and on plodded the hansom, going slower, it seemed to him, at          
\par each step. He thrust up the trap, and called to the man to drive            
\par faster. The hideous hunger for opium began to gnaw at him. His              
\par throat burned, and his delicate hands twitched nervously together.          
\par He struck at the horse madly with his stick. The driver laughed, and        
\par whipped up. He laughed in answer, and the man was silent.                   
\par   The way seemed interminable, and the streets like the black web of        
\par some sprawling spider. The monotony became unbearable, and, as the          
\par mist thickened, he felt afraid.                                             
\par   Then they passed by lonely brickfields. The fog was lighter here,         
\par and he could see the strange bottle-shaped kilns with their orange          
\par fan-like tongues of fire. A dog barked as they went by, and far away        
\par in the darkness some wandering seagull screamed. The horse stumbled in      
\par a rut, then swerved aside, and broke into a gallop.                         
\par   After some time they left the clay road, and rattled again over           
\par rough-paven streets. Most of the windows were dark, but now and then        
\par fantastic shadows were silhouetted against some lamp-lit blind. He          
\par watched them curiously. They moved like monstrous marionettes, and          
\par made gestures like live things. He hated them. A dull rage was in           
\par his heart. As they turned a corner a woman yelled something at them         
\par from an open door, and two men ran after the hansom for about a             
\par hundred yards. The driver beat at them with his whip.                       
\par   It is said that passion makes one think in a circle. Certainly            
\par with hideous iteration the bitten lips of Dorian Gray shaped and            
\par reshaped those subtle words that dealt with soul and sense, till he         
\par had found in them the full expression, as it were, of his mood, and         
\par justified, by intellectual approval, passions that without such             
\par justification would still have dominated his temper. From cell to cell      
\par of his brain crept the one thought; and the wild desire to live,            
\par most terrible of all man's appetites, quickened into force each             
\par trembling nerve and fibre. Ugliness that had once been hateful to           
\par him because it made things real, became dear to him now for that            
\par very reason. Ugliness was the one reality. The coarse brawl, the            
\par loathsome den, the crude vileness of disordered life, the very              
\par vileness of thief and outcast, were more vivid, in their intense            
\par actuality of impression, than all the gracious shapes of Art, the           
\par dreamy shadows of Song. They were what he needed for forgetfulness. In      
\par three days he would be free.                                                
\par   Suddenly the man drew up with a jerk at the top of a dark lane. Over      
\par the low roofs and jagged chimney-stacks of the houses rose the black        
\par masts of ships. Wreaths of white mist clung like ghostly sails to           
\par the yards.                                                                  
\par   "Somewhere about here, sir, ain't it?" he asked huskily through           
\par the trap.                                                                   
\par   Dorian started, and peered round. "This will do," he answered,            
\par and, having got out hastily, and given the driver the extra fare he         
\par had promised him, he walked quickly in the direction of the quay. Here      
\par and there a lantern gleamed at the stern of some huge merchantman. The      
\par light shook and splintered in the puddles. A red glare came from an         
\par outward-bound steamer that was coaling. The slimy pavement looked like      
\par a wet mackintosh.                                                           
\par   He hurried on towards the left, glancing back now and then to see if      
\par he was being followed. In about seven or eight minutes he reached a         
\par small shabby house, that was wedged in between two gaunt factories. In      
\par one of the top windows stood a lamp. He stopped, and gave a peculiar        
\par knock.                                                                      
\par   After a little while he heard steps in the passage, and the chain         
\par being unhooked. The door opened quietly, and he went in without saying      
\par a word to the squat misshapen figure that flattened itself upon the         
\par shadow as he passed. At the end of the hall hung a tattered green           
\par curtain that swayed and shook in the gusty wind which had followed him      
\par in from the street. He dragged it aside, and entered a long, low            
\par room which looked as if it had once been a third-rate                       
\par dancing-saloon. Shrill flaring gas-jets, dulled and distorted in the        
\par fly-blown mirrors that faced them, were ranged round the walls. Greasy      
\par reflectors of ribbed tin backed them, making quivering discs of light.      
\par The floor was covered with ochre-coloured sawdust, trampled here and        
\par there into mud, and stained with rings of spilt liquor. Some Malays         
\par were crouching by a little charcoal stove playing with bone                 
\par counters, and showing their white teeth as they chattered. In one           
\par corner with his head buried in his arms, a sailor sprawled over a           
\par table, and by the tawdrily-painted bar that ran across one complete         
\par side stood two haggard women mocking an old man who was brushing the        
\par sleeves of his coat with an expression of disgust. "He thinks he's got      
\par red ants on him," laughed one of them, as Dorian passed by. The man         
\par looked at her in terror, and began to whimper.                              
\par   At the end of the room there was a little staircase, leading to a         
\par darkened chamber. As Dorian hurried up its three rickety steps, the         
\par heavy odour of opium met him. He heaved a deep breath, and his              
\par nostrils quivered with pleasure. When he entered, a young man with          
\par smooth yellow hair, who was bending over a lamp lighting a long thin        
\par pipe, looked up at him, and nodded in a hesitating manner.                  
\par   "You here, Adrian?" muttered Dorian.                                      
\par   "Where else should I be?" he answered, listlessly. "None of the           
\par chaps will speak to me now."                                                
\par   "I thought you had left England."                                         
\par   "Darlington is not going to do anything. My brother paid the bill at      
\par last. George doesn't speak to me either.... I don't care," he added,        
\par with a sigh. "As long as one has this stuff, one doesn't want friends.      
\par I think I have had too many friends."                                       
\par   Dorian winced, and looked around at the grotesque things that lay in      
\par such fantastic postures on the ragged mattresses. The twisted limbs,        
\par the gaping mouths, the staring lustreless eyes, fascinated him. He          
\par knew in what strange heavens they were suffering, and what dull             
\par hells were teaching them the secret of some new joy. They were              
\par better off than he was. He was prisoned in thought. Memory, like a          
\par horrible malady, was eating his soul away. From time to time he seemed      
\par to see the eyes of Basil Hallward looking at him. Yet he felt he could      
\par not stay. The presence of Adrian Singleton troubled him. He wanted          
\par to be where no one would know who he was. He wanted to escape from          
\par himself.                                                                    
\par   "I am going on to the other place," he said, after a pause.               
\par   "On the wharf?"                                                           
\par   "Yes."                                                                    
\par   "That mad-cat is sure to be there. They won't have her in this place      
\par now."                                                                       
\par   Dorian shrugged his shoulders. "I am sick of women who love one.          
\par Women who hate one are much more interesting. Besides, the stuff is         
\par better."                                                                    
\par   "Much the same."                                                          
\par   "I like it better. Come and have something to drink. I must have          
\par something."                                                                 
\par   "I don't want anything," murmured the young man.                          
\par   "Never mind."                                                             
\par   Adrian Singleton rose up wearily, and followed Dorian to the bar.         
\par A half caste, in a ragged turban and a shabby ulster, grinned a             
\par hideous greeting as he thrust a bottle of brandy and two tumblers in        
\par front of them. The women sidled up, and began to chatter. Dorian            
\par turned his back on them, and said something in a low voice to Adrian        
\par Singleton.                                                                  
\par   A crooked smile, like a Malay crease, writhed across the face of one      
\par of the women. "We're very proud to-night," she sneered.                     
\par   "For God's sake don't talk to me," cried Dorian, stamping his foot        
\par on the ground. "What do you want? Money? Here it is. Don't ever talk        
\par to me again."                                                               
\par   Two red sparks flashed for a moment in the woman's sodden eyes, then      
\par flickered out, and left them dull and glazed. She tossed her head, and      
\par raked the coins off the counter with greedy fingers. Her companion          
\par watched her enviously.                                                      
\par   "It's no use," sighed Adrian Singleton "I don't care to go back.          
\par What does it matter? I am quite happy here."                                
\par   "You will write to me if you want anything, won't you?" said Dorian,      
\par after a pause.                                                              
\par   "Perhaps."                                                                
\par   "Good-night, then."                                                       
\par   "Good-night," answered the young man, passing up the steps, and           
\par wiping his parched mouth with a handkerchief.                               
\par   Dorian walked to the door with a look of pain in his face. As he          
\par drew the curtain aside a hideous laugh broke from the painted lips          
\par of the woman who had taken the money. "There goes the devil's               
\par bargain!" she hiccoughed, in a hoarse voice.                                
\par   "Curse you," he answered, "don't call me that."                           
\par   She snapped her fingers. "Prince Charming is what you like to be          
\par called, ain't it?" she yelled after him.                                    
\par   The drowsy sailor leapt to his feet as she spoke, and looked              
\par wildly round. The sound of the shutting of the hall door fell on his        
\par ear. He rushed out as if in pursuit.                                        
\par   Dorian Gray hurried along the quay through the drizzling rain. His        
\par meeting with Adrian Singleton had strangely moved him, and he wondered      
\par if the ruin of that young life was really to be laid at his door, as        
\par Basil Hallward had said to him with such infamy of insult. He bit           
\par his lip, and for a few seconds his eyes grew sad. Yet, after all, what      
\par did it matter to him? One's days were too brief to take the burden          
\par of another's errors on one's shoulders. Each man lived his own life,        
\par and paid his own price for living it. The only pity was one had to pay      
\par so often for a single fault. One had to pay over and over again,            
\par indeed. In her dealings with man Destiny never closed her accounts.         
\par   There are moments, psychologists tell us, when the passion for            
\par sin, or for what the world calls sin, so dominates a nature, that           
\par every fibre of the body, as every cell of the brain, seems to be            
\par instinct with fearful impulses. Men and women at such moments lose the      
\par freedom of their will. They move to their terrible end as automatons        
\par move. Choice is taken from them, and conscience is either killed,           
\par or, if it lives at all, lives but to give rebellion its fascination,        
\par and disobedience its charm. For all sins, as theologians weary not          
\par of reminding us, are sins of disobedience. When that high spirit, that      
\par morning-star of evil, fell from heaven, it was as a rebel that he           
\par fell.                                                                       
\par   Callous, concentrated on evil, with stained mind, and soul hungry         
\par for rebellion, Dorian Gray hastened on, quickening his steps as he          
\par went, but as he darted aside into a dim archway, that had served him        
\par often as a short cut to the ill-famed place where he was going, he          
\par felt himself suddenly seized from behind, and before he had time to         
\par defend himself he was thrust back against the wall, with a brutal hand      
\par round his throat.                                                           
\par   He struggled madly for life, and by a terrible effort wrenched the        
\par tightening fingers away. In a second he heard the click of a revolver,      
\par and saw the gleam of a polished barrel pointing straight at his             
\par head, and the dusky form of a short thick-set man facing him.               
\par   "What do you want?" he gasped.                                            
\par   "Keep quiet," said the man. "If you stir, I shoot you."                   
\par   "You are mad. What have I done to you?"                                   
\par   "You wrecked the life of Sibyl Vane," was the answer, "and Sibyl          
\par Vane was my sister. She killed herself. I know it. Her death is at          
\par your door. I swore I would kill you in return. For years I have sought      
\par you. I had no clue, no trace. The two people who could have                 
\par described you were dead. I knew nothing of you but the pet name she         
\par used to call you. I heard it to-night by chance. Make your peace            
\par with God, for to-night you are going to die."                               
\par   Dorian Gray grew sick with fear. "I never knew her," he stammered.        
\par "I never heard of her. You are mad."                                        
\par   "You had better confess your sin, for as sure as I am James Vane,         
\par you are going to die." There was a horrible moment. Dorian did not          
\par know what to say or do. "Down on your knees!" growled the man. "I give      
\par you one minute to make your peace- no more. I go on board to-night for      
\par India, and I must do my job first. One minute. That's all."                 
\par   Dorian's arms fell to his side. Paralyzed with terror, he did not         
\par know what to do. Suddenly a wild hope flashed across his brain.             
\par "Stop," he cried. "How long ago is it since your sister died? Quick,        
\par tell me!"                                                                   
\par   "Eighteen years," said the man. "Why do you ask me? What do years         
\par matter?"                                                                    
\par   "Eighteen years," laughed Dorian Gray, with a touch of triumph in         
\par his voice. "Eighteen years! Set me under the lamp and look at my            
\par face."                                                                      
\par   James Vane hesitated for a moment, not understanding what was meant.      
\par Then he seized Dorian Gray and dragged him from the archway.                
\par   Dim and wavering as was the wind-blown light, yet it served to            
\par show him the hideous  error, as it seemed, into which he had fallen,        
\par for the face of the man he had sought to kill had all the bloom of          
\par boyhood, all the unstained purity of youth. He seemed little more than      
\par a lad of twenty summers, hardly older, if older indeed at all, than         
\par his sister had been when they had parted so many years ago. It was          
\par obvious that this was not the man who had destroyed her life.               
\par   He loosened his hold and reeled back. "My God! my God!" he cried,         
\par "and I would have murdered you!"                                            
\par   Dorian Gray drew a long breath. "You have been on the brink of            
\par committing a terrible crime, my man," he said, looking at him sternly.      
\par "Let this be a warning to you not to take vengeance into your own           
\par hands."                                                                     
\par   "Forgive me, sir," muttered James Vane. "I was deceived. A chance         
\par word I heard in that damned den set me on the wrong track."                 
\par   "You had better go home, and put that pistol away, or you may get         
\par into trouble," said Dorian, turning on his heel, and going slowly down      
\par the street.                                                                 
\par   James Vane stood on the pavement in horror. He was trembling from         
\par head to foot. After a little while a black shadow that had been             
\par creeping along the dripping wall, moved out into the light and came         
\par close to him with stealthy footsteps. He felt a hand laid on his arm        
\par and looked round with a start. It was one of the women who had been         
\par drinking at the bar.                                                        
\par   "Why didn't you kill him?" she hissed out, putting her haggard            
\par face quite close to his. "I knew you were following him when you            
\par rushed out from Daly's. You fool! You should have killed him. He has        
\par lots of money, and he's as bad as bad."                                     
\par   "He is not the man I am looking for," he answered, "and I want no         
\par man's money. I want a man's life. The man whose life I want must be         
\par nearly forty now. This one is little more than a boy. Thank God, I          
\par have not got his blood upon my hands."                                      
\par   The woman gave a bitter laugh. "Little more than a boy!" she              
\par sneered. "Why, man, it's nigh on eighteen years since Prince                
\par Charming made me what I am."                                                
\par   "You lie!" cried James Vane.                                              
\par   She raised her hand up to heaven. "Before God I am telling the            
\par truth," she cried.                                                          
\par   "Before God?"                                                             
\par   "Strike me dumb if it ain't so. He is the worst one that comes here.      
\par They say he has sold himself to the devil for a pretty face. It's nigh      
\par on eighteen years since I met him. He hasn't changed much since             
\par then. I have though," she added with a sickly leer.                         
\par   "You swear this?"                                                         
\par   "I swear it," came in hoarse echo from her flat mouth. "But don't         
\par give me away to him," she whined; "I am afraid of him. Let me have          
\par some money for my night's lodging."                                         
\par   He broke from her with an oath, and rushed to the corner of the           
\par street, but Dorian Gray had disappeared. When he looked back, the           
\par woman had vanished also.                                                    
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                              CHAPTER XVII                                   
\par -                                                                           
\par   A week later Dorian Gray was sitting in the conservatory at Selby         
\par Royal talking to the pretty Duchess of Monmouth, who with her husband,      
\par a jaded-looking man of sixty, was amongst his guests. It was tea-time,      
\par and the mellow light of the huge lace-covered lamp that stood on the        
\par table lit up the delicate china and hammered silver of the service          
\par at which the Duchess was presiding. Her white hands were moving             
\par daintily among the cups, and her full red lips were smiling at              
\par something that Dorian had whispered to her. Lord Henry was lying            
\par back in a silk-draped wicker chair looking at them. On a                    
\par peach-coloured divan sat Lady Narborough pretending to listen to the        
\par Duke's description of the last Brazilian beetle that he had added to        
\par his collection. Three young men in elaborate smoking-suits were             
\par handing tea-cakes to some of the women. The house-party consisted of        
\par twelve people, and there were more expected to arrive on the next day.      
\par   "What are you two talking about?" said Lord Henry, strolling over to      
\par the table, and putting his cup down. "I hope Dorian has told you about      
\par my plan for rechristening everything, Gladys. It is a delightful            
\par idea."                                                                      
\par   "But I don't want to be rechristened, Harry," rejoined the                
\par Duchess, looking up at him with her wonderful eyes. "I am quite             
\par satisfied with my own name, and I am sure Mr. Gray should be satisfied      
\par with his."                                                                  
\par   "My dear Gladys, I would not alter either name for the world. They        
\par are both perfect. I was thinking chiefly of flowers. Yesterday I cut        
\par an orchid, for my buttonhole. It was a marvellous spotted thing, as         
\par effective as the seven deadly sins. In a thoughtless moment I asked         
\par one of the gardeners what it was called. He told me that it was a fine      
\par specimen of Rooinsoniana, or something dreadful of that kind. It is         
\par a sad truth, but we have lost the faculty of giving lovely names to         
\par things. Names are everything. I never quarrel with actions. My one          
\par quarrel is with words. That is the reason I hate vulgar realism in          
\par literature. The man who could call a spade a spade should be compelled      
\par to use one. It is the only thing he is fit for."                            
\par   "Then what should we call you, Harry?" she asked.                         
\par   "His name is Prince Paradox," said Dorian.                                
\par   "I recognize him in a flash," exclaimed the Duchess.                      
\par   "I won't hear of it," laughed Lord Henry, sinking into a chair.           
\par "From a label there is no escape! I refuse the title."                      
\par   "Royalties may not abdicate," fell as a warning from pretty lips.         
\par   "You wish me to defend my throne, then?"                                  
\par   "Yes."                                                                    
\par   "I give the truths of to-morrow."                                         
\par   "I prefer the mistakes of to-day," she answered.                          
\par   "You disarm me, Gladys," he cried, catching the wilfulness of her         
\par mood.                                                                       
\par   "Of your shield, Harry: not of your spear."                               
\par   "I never tilt against Beauty," he said, with a wave of his hand.          
\par   "That is your error, Harry, believe me. You value beauty far too          
\par much."                                                                      
\par   "How can you say that, I admit that I think that it is better to          
\par be beautiful than to be good. But on the other hand no one is more          
\par ready than I am to acknowledge that it is better to be good than to be      
\par ugly?"                                                                      
\par   "Ugliness is one of the seven deadly sins, then?" cried the Duchess.      
\par "What becomes of your simile about the orchid?"                             
\par   "Ugliness is one of the seven deadly virtues, Gladys. You, as a good      
\par Tory, must not underrate them. Beer, the Bible, and the seven deadly        
\par virtues have made our England what she is."                                 
\par   "You don't like your country, then?" she asked.                           
\par   "I live in it."                                                           
\par   "That you may censure it the better."                                     
\par   "Would you have me take the verdict of Europe on it?" he enquired.        
\par   "What do they say of us?"                                                 
\par   "That Tartuffe has emigrated to England and opened a shop."               
\par   "Is that yours, Harry?"                                                   
\par   "I give it to you."                                                       
\par   "I could not use it. It is too true."                                     
\par   "You need not be afraid. Our countrymen never recognize a                 
\par description."                                                               
\par   "They are practical."                                                     
\par   "They are more cunning than practical. When they make up their            
\par ledger, they balance stupidity by wealth, and vice by hypocrisy."           
\par   "Still, we have done great things."                                       
\par   "Great things have been thrust on us, Gladys."                            
\par   "We have carried their burden."                                           
\par   "Only as far as the Stock Exchange."                                      
\par   She shook her head. "I believe in the race," she cried.                   
\par   "It represents the survival of the pushing."                              
\par   "It has development."                                                     
\par   "Decay fascinates me more."                                               
\par   "What of Art?" she asked.                                                 
\par   "It is a malady."                                                         
\par   "Love?"                                                                   
\par   "An illusion."                                                            
\par   "Religion?"                                                               
\par   "The fashionable substitute for Belief."                                  
\par   "You are a sceptic."                                                      
\par   "Never! Scepticism is the beginning of Faith."                            
\par   "What are you?"                                                           
\par   "To define is to limit."                                                  
\par   "Give me a clue."                                                         
\par   "Threads snap. You would lose your way in the labyrinth."                 
\par   "You bewilder me. Let us talk of some one else."                          
\par   "Our host is a delightful topic. Years ago he was christened              
\par Prince Charming."                                                           
\par   "Ah! don't remind me of that," cried Dorian Gray.                         
\par   "Our host is rather horrid this evening," answered the Duchess,           
\par colouring. "I believe he thinks that Monmouth married me on purely          
\par scientific principles as the best specimen he could find of a modern        
\par butterfly."                                                                 
\par   "Well, I hope he won't stick pins into you, Duchess," laughed             
\par Dorian.                                                                     
\par   "Oh! my maid does that already, Mr. Gray, when she is annoyed with        
\par me."                                                                        
\par   "And what does she get annoyed with you about, Duchess?"                  
\par   "For the most trivial things, Mr. Gray, I assure you. Usually             
\par because I come in at ten minutes to nine and tell her that I must be        
\par dressed by half-past eight."                                                
\par   "How unreasonable of her! You should give her warning."                   
\par   "I daren't, Mr. Gray. Why, she invents hats for me. You remember the      
\par one I wore at Lady Hilstone's garden-party? You don't, but it is            
\par nice of you to pretend that you do. Well, she made it out of                
\par nothing. All good hats are made out of nothing."                            
\par   "Like all good reputations, Gladys," interrupted Lord Henry.              
\par "Every effect that one produces gives one an enemy. To be popular           
\par one must be a mediocrity."                                                  
\par   "Not with women," said the Duchess, shaking her head, "and women          
\par rule the world. I assure you we can't bear mediocrities. We women,          
\par as some one says, love with our ears, just as you men love with your        
\par eyes, if you ever love at all."                                             
\par   "It seems to me that we never do anything else," murmured Dorian.         
\par   "Ah! then, you never really love, Mr. Gray," answered the Duchess,        
\par with mock sadness.                                                          
\par   "My dear Gladys!" cried Lord Henry. "How can you say that? Romance        
\par lives by repetition, and repetition converts an appetite into an            
\par art. Besides, each time that one loves is the only time one has ever        
\par loved. Difference of object does not alter singleness of passion. It        
\par merely intensifies it. We can have in life but one great experience at      
\par best, and the secret of life is to reproduce that experience as             
\par often as possible."                                                         
\par   "Even when one has been wounded by it, Harry?" asked the Duchess,         
\par after a pause.                                                              
\par   "Especially when one has been wounded by it," answered Lord Henry.        
\par   The Duchess turned and looked at Dorian Gray with a curious               
\par expression in her eyes. "What do you say to that, Mr. Gray?" she            
\par enquired.                                                                   
\par   Dorian hesitated a moment. Then he threw back his head and                
\par laughed. "I always agree with Harry, Duchess."                              
\par   "Even when he is wrong?"                                                  
\par   "Harry is never wrong, Duchess."                                          
\par   "And does his philosophy make you happy?"                                 
\par   "I have never searched for happiness. Who wants happiness? I have         
\par searched for pleasure."                                                     
\par   "And found it, Mr. Gray?"                                                 
\par   "Often. Too often."                                                       
\par   The Duchess sighed. "I am searching for peace," she said, "and if         
\par I don't go and dress, I shall have none this evening."                      
\par   "Let me get you some orchids, Duchess," cried Dorian, starting to         
\par his feet, and walking down the conservatory.                                
\par   "You are flirting disgracefully with him," said Lord Henry to his         
\par cousin. "You had better take care. He is very fascinating."                 
\par   "If he were not, there would be no battle."                               
\par   "Greek meets Greek then?"                                                 
\par   "I am on the side of the Trojans. They fought for a woman."               
\par   "They were defeated."                                                     
\par   "There are worse things than capture," she answered.                      
\par   "You gallop with a loose rein."                                           
\par   "Pace gives life," was the riposte. "I shall write it in my diary         
\par to-night."                                                                  
\par   "What?"                                                                   
\par   "That a burnt child loves the fire."                                      
\par   "I am not even singed. My wings are untouched."                           
\par   "You use them for everything, except flight."                             
\par   "Courage has passed from men to women. It is a new experience for         
\par us."                                                                        
\par   "You have a rival."                                                       
\par   "Who?"                                                                    
\par   He laughed. "Lady Narborough," he whispered. "She perfectly adores        
\par him."                                                                       
\par   "You fill me with apprehension. The appeal to Antiquity is fatal          
\par to us who are romanticists."                                                
\par   "Romanticists! You have all the methods of science."                      
\par   "Men have educated us."                                                   
\par   "But not explained you."                                                  
\par   "Describe us as a sex," was her challenge.                                
\par   "Sphinxes without secrets."                                               
\par   She looked at him, smiling. "How long Mr. Gray is!" she said. "Let        
\par us go and help him. I have not yet told him the colour of my frock."        
\par   "Ah! you must suit your frock to his flowers, Gladys."                    
\par   "That would be a premature surrender."                                    
\par   "Romantic Art begins with its climax."                                    
\par   "I must keep an opportunity for retreat."                                 
\par   "In the Parthian manner?"                                                 
\par   "They found safety in the desert. I could not do that."                   
\par   "Women are not always allowed a choice," he answered, but hardly had      
\par he finished the sentence before from the far end of the conservatory        
\par came a stifled groan, followed by the dull sound of a heavy fall.           
\par Everybody started up. The Duchess stood motionless in horror. And with      
\par fear in his eyes Lord Henry rushed through the flapping palms, to find      
\par Dorian Gray lying face downwards on the tiled floor in a death-like         
\par swoon.                                                                      
\par   He was carried at once into the blue drawing-room, and laid upon one      
\par of the sofas. After a short time he came to himself, and looked             
\par round with a dazed expression.                                              
\par   "What has happened?" he asked. "Oh! I remember. Am I safe here,           
\par Harry,?" He began to tremble.                                               
\par   "My dear Dorian," answered Lord Henry, "you merely fainted. That was      
\par all. You must have overtired yourself. You had better not come down to      
\par dinner. I will take your place."                                            
\par   "No, I will come down," he said, struggling to his feet. "I would         
\par rather come down. I must not be alone."                                     
\par   He went to his room and dressed. There was a wild recklessness of         
\par gaiety in his manner as he sat at table, but now and then a thrill          
\par of terror ran through him when he remembered that, pressed against the      
\par window of the conservatory, like a white handkerchief, he had seen the      
\par face of James Vane watching him.                                            
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                             CHAPTER XVIII                                   
\par -                                                                           
\par   The next day he did not leave the house, and, indeed, spent most          
\par of the time in his own room, sick with a wild terror of dying, and yet      
\par indifferent to life itself. The consciousness of being hunted, snared,      
\par tracked down, had begun to dominate him. If the tapestry did but            
\par tremble in the wind, he shook. The dead leaves that were blown against      
\par the leaded panes seemed to him like his own wasted resolutions and          
\par wild regrets. When he closed his eyes, he saw again the sailor's            
\par face peering through the mist-stained glass, and horror seemed once         
\par more to lay its hand upon his heart.                                        
\par   But perhaps it had been only his fancy that had called vengeance out      
\par of the night, and set the hideous shapes of punishment before him.          
\par Actual life was chaos, but there was something terribly logical in the      
\par imagination. It was the imagination that set remorse to dog the feet        
\par of sin. It was the imagination that made each crime bear its misshapen      
\par brood. In the common world of fact the wicked were not punished, nor        
\par the good rewarded. Success was given to the strong, failure thrust          
\par upon the weak. That was all. Besides, had any stranger been prowling        
\par round the house he would have been seen by the servants or the              
\par keepers. Had any footmarks been found on the flower-beds, the               
\par gardeners would have reported it. Yes: it had been merely fancy. Sibyl      
\par Vane's brother had not come back to kill him. He had sailed away in         
\par his ship to founder in some winter sea. From him, at any rate, he           
\par was safe. Why, the man did not know who he was, could not know who          
\par he was. The mask of youth had saved him.                                    
\par   And yet if it had been merely an illusion, how terrible it was to         
\par think that conscience could raise such fearful phantoms, and give them      
\par visible form, and make them move before one! What sort of life would        
\par his be if, day and night, shadows of his crime were to peer at him          
\par from silent corners, to mock him from secret places, to whisper in his      
\par ear as he sat at the feast, to wake him with icy fingers as he lay          
\par asleep! As the thought crept through his brain, he grew pale with           
\par terror, and the air seemed to him to have become suddenly colder.           
\par Oh! in what a wild hour of madness he had killed his friend! How            
\par ghastly the mere memory of the scene! He saw it all again. Each             
\par hideous detail came back to him with added horror. Out of the black         
\par cave of Time, terrible and swathed in scarlet, rose the image of his        
\par sin. When Lord Henry came in at six o'clock, he found him crying as         
\par one whose heart will break.                                                 
\par   It was not till the third day that he ventured to go out. There           
\par was something in the clear, pine-scented air of that winter morning         
\par that seemed to bring him back his joyousness and his ardour for             
\par life. But it was not merely the physical conditions of environment          
\par that had caused the change. His own nature had revolted against the         
\par excess of anguish that had sought to maim and mar the perfection of         
\par its calm. With subtle and finely-wrought temperaments it is always so.      
\par Their strong passions must either bruise or bend. They either slay the      
\par man, or themselves die. Shallow sorrows and shallow loves live on. The      
\par loves and sorrows that are great are destroyed by their own plenitude.      
\par Besides, he had convinced himself that he had been the victim of a          
\par terror-stricken imagination, and looked back now on his fears with          
\par something of pity and not a little of contempt.                             
\par   After breakfast he walked with the Duchess for an hour in the             
\par garden, and then drove across the park to join the shooting-party. The      
\par crisp frost lay like salt upon the grass. The sky was an inverted           
\par cup of blue metal. A thin film of ice bordered the flat reed-grown          
\par lake.                                                                       
\par   At the corner of the pine wood he caught sight of Sir Geoffrey            
\par Clouston, the Duchess's brother, jerking two spent cartridges out of        
\par his gun. He jumped from the cart, and having told the groom to take         
\par the mare home, made his way towards his guest through the withered          
\par bracken and rough undergrowth.                                              
\par   "Have you had good sport, Geoffrey?" he asked.                            
\par   "Not very good, Dorian. I think most of the birds have gone to the        
\par open. I dare say it will be better after lunch, when we get to new          
\par ground."                                                                    
\par   Dorian strolled along by his side. The keen aromatic air, the             
\par brown and red lights that glimmered in the wood, the hoarse cries of        
\par the beaters ringing out from time to time, and the sharp snaps of           
\par the guns that followed, fascinated him, and filled him with a sense of      
\par delightful freedom. He was dominated by the carelessness of happiness,      
\par by the high indifference of joy.                                            
\par   Suddenly from a lumpy tussock of old grass, some twenty yards in          
\par front of them, with black-tipped ears erect, and long hinder limbs          
\par throwing it forward, started a hare. It bolted for a thicket of             
\par alders. Sir Geoffrey put his gun to his shoulder, but there was             
\par something in the animal's grace of movement that strangely charmed          
\par Dorian Gray, and he cried out at once, "Don't shoot it, Geoffrey.           
\par Let it live."                                                               
\par   "What nonsense, Dorian!" laughed his companion, and as the hare           
\par bounded into the thicket he fired. There were two cries heard, the cry      
\par of a hare in pain, which is dreadful, the cry of a man in agony, which      
\par is worse.                                                                   
\par   "Good heavens! I have hit a beater!" exclaimed Sir Geoffrey. "What        
\par an ass the man was to get in front of the guns! Stop shooting               
\par there!" he called out at the top of his voice. "A man is hurt."             
\par   The head-keeper came running up with a stick in his hand.                 
\par   "Where, sir? Where is he?" he shouted. At the same time the firing        
\par ceased along the line.                                                      
\par   "Here," answered Sir Geoffrey angrily, hurrying towards the thicket.      
\par "Why on earth don't you keep your men back? Spoiled my shooting for         
\par the day."                                                                   
\par   Dorian watched them as they plunged into the alder-clump, brushing        
\par the lithe, swinging branches aside. In a few moments they emerged,          
\par dragging a body after them into the sunlight. He turned away in             
\par horror. It seemed to him that misfortune followed wherever he went. He      
\par heard Sir Geoffrey ask if the man was really dead, and the affirmative      
\par answer of the keeper. The wood seemed to him to have become suddenly        
\par alive with faces. There was the trampling of myriad feet, and the           
\par low buzz of voices. A great copper-breasted pheasant came beating           
\par through the boughs overhead.                                                
\par   After few moments, that were to him, in his perturbed state, like         
\par endless hours of pain, he felt a hand laid on his shoulder. He              
\par started, and looked round.                                                  
\par   "Dorian," said Lord Henry, "I had better tell them that the shooting      
\par is stopped for to-day. It would not look well to go on."                    
\par   "I wish it were stopped for ever, Harry," he answered, bitterly.          
\par "The whole thing is hideous and cruel. Is the man...?"                      
\par   He could not finish the sentence.                                         
\par   "I am afraid so," rejoined Lord Henry. "He got the whole charge of        
\par shot in his chest. He must have died almost instantaneously. Come; let      
\par us go home."                                                                
\par   They walked side by side in the direction of the avenue for nearly        
\par fifty yards without speaking. Then Dorian looked at Lord Henry, and         
\par said, with a heavy sigh, "It is a bad omen, Harry, a very bad omen."        
\par   "What is?" asked Lord Henry. "Oh! this accident, I suppose. My            
\par dear fellow, it can't be helped. It was the man's own fault. Why did        
\par he get in front of the guns? Besides, it is nothing to us. It is            
\par rather awkward for Geoffrey, of course. It does not do to pepper            
\par beaters. It makes people think that one is a wild shot. And Geoffrey        
\par is not; he shoots very straight. But there is no use talking about the      
\par matter."                                                                    
\par   Dorian shook his head. "It is a bad omen, Harry. I feel as if             
\par something horrible were going to happen to some of us. To myself,           
\par perhaps," he added, passing his hand over his eyes, with a gesture          
\par of pain.                                                                    
\par   The elder man laughed. "The only horrible thing in the world is           
\par ennui, Dorian. That is the one sin for which there is no                    
\par forgiveness. But we are not likely to suffer from it, unless these          
\par fellows keep chattering about this thing at dinner. I must tell them        
\par that the subject is to be tabooed. As for omens, there is no such           
\par thing as an omen. Destiny does not send us heralds. She is too wise or      
\par too cruel for that. Besides, what on earth could happen to you,             
\par Dorian? You have everything in the world that a man can want. There is      
\par no one who would not be delighted to change places with you."               
\par   "There is no one with whom I would not change places, Harry. Don't        
\par laugh like that. I am telling you the truth. The wretched peasant           
\par who has just died is better off than I am. I have no terror of              
\par Death. It is the coming of Death that terrifies me. Its monstrous           
\par wings seem to wheel in the leaden air around me. Good heavens! don't        
\par you see a man moving, behind the trees there, watching me, waiting for      
\par me?"                                                                        
\par   Lord Henry looked in the direction in which the trembling gloved          
\par hand was pointing. "Yes," he said, smiling, "I see the gardener             
\par waiting for you. I suppose he wants to ask you what flowers you wish        
\par to have on the table to-night. How absurdly nervous you are, my dear        
\par fellow! You must come and see my doctor, when we get back to town."         
\par   Dorian heaved a sigh of relief as he saw the gardener approaching.        
\par The man touched his hat, glanced for a moment at Lord Henry in a            
\par hesitating manner, and then produced a letter, which he handed to           
\par his master. "Her Grace told me to wait for an answer," he murmured.         
\par   Dorian put the letter into his pocket. "Tell Her Grace that I am          
\par coming in," he said, coldly. The man turned round, and went rapidly in      
\par the direction of the house.                                                 
\par   "How fond women are of doing dangerous things!" laughed Lord              
\par Henry. "It is one of the qualities in them that I admire most. A woman      
\par will flirt with anybody in the world as long as other people are            
\par looking on."                                                                
\par   "How fond you are of saying dangerous things, Harry! In the               
\par present instance you are quite astray. I like the Duchess very much,        
\par but I don't love her."                                                      
\par   "And the Duchess loves you very much, but she likes you less, as you      
\par are so excellently matched."                                                
\par   "You are talking scandal, Harry, and there is never any basis for         
\par scandal."                                                                   
\par   "The basis of every scandal is an immoral certainty," said Lord           
\par Henry, lighting a cigarette.                                                
\par   "You would sacrifice anybody, Harry, for the sake of an epigram."         
\par   "The world goes to the altar of its own accord," was the answer.          
\par   "I wish I could love," cried Dorian Gray, with a deep note of pathos      
\par in his voice. "But I seem to have lost the passion, and forgotten           
\par the desire. I am too much concentrated on myself. My own personality        
\par has become a burden to me. I want to escape, to go away, to forget. It      
\par was silly of me to come down here at all. I think I shall send a            
\par wire to Harvey to have the yacht got ready. On a yacht one is safe."        
\par   "Safe from what, Dorian? You are in some trouble. Why not tell me         
\par what it is? You know I would help you."                                     
\par   "I can't tell you, Harry," he answered, sadly. "And I dare say it is      
\par only a fancy of mine. This unfortunate accident has upset me. I have a      
\par horrible presentiment that something of the kind may happen to me."         
\par   "What nonsense!"                                                          
\par   "I hope it is, but I can't help feeling it. Ah! here is the Duchess,      
\par looking the Artemis in a tailor-made gown. You see we have come             
\par back, Duchess."                                                             
\par   "I have heard all about it, Mr. Gray," she answered. "Poor                
\par Geoffrey is terribly upset. And it seems that you asked him not to          
\par shoot the hare. How curious!"                                               
\par   "Yes, it was very curious. I don't know what made me say it. Some         
\par whim, I suppose. It looked the loveliest of little live things. But         
\par I am sorry they told you about the man. It is a hideous subject."           
\par   "It is an annoying subject," broke in Lord Henry. "It has no              
\par psychological value at all. Now if Geoffrey had done the thing on           
\par purpose, how interesting he would be! I should like to know some one        
\par who had committed a real murder."                                           
\par   "How horrid of you, Harry!" cried the Duchess. "Isn't it, Mr.             
\par Gray? Harry, Mr. Gray is ill again. He is going to faint."                  
\par   Dorian drew himself up with an effort, and smiled. "It is nothing,        
\par Duchess," he murmured; "my nerves are dreadfully out of order. That is      
\par all. I am afraid I walked too far this morning. I didn't hear what          
\par Harry said. Was it very bad? You must tell me some other time. I think      
\par I must go and lie down. You will excuse me, won't you?"                     
\par   They had reached the great flight of steps that led from the              
\par conservatory onto the terrace. As the glass door closed behind Dorian,      
\par Lord Henry turned and looked at the Duchess with his slumberous             
\par eyes. "Are you very much in love with him?" he asked.                       
\par   She did not answer for some time, but stood gazing at the landscape.      
\par "I wish I knew," she said at last.                                          
\par   He shook his head. "Knowledge would be fatal. It is the                   
\par uncertainty that charms one. A mist makes things wonderful."                
\par   "One may lose one's way."                                                 
\par   "All ways end at the same point, my dear Gladys."                         
\par   "What is that?"                                                           
\par   "Disillusion."                                                            
\par   "It was my debut in life," she sighed.                                    
\par   "It came to you crowned."                                                 
\par   "I am tired of strawberry leaves."                                        
\par   "They become you."                                                        
\par   "Only in public."                                                         
\par   "You would miss them," said Lord Henry.                                   
\par   "I will not part with a petal."                                           
\par   "Monmouth has cars."                                                      
\par   "Old age is dull of hearing."                                             
\par   "Has he never been jealous?"                                              
\par   "I wish he had been."                                                     
\par   He glanced about as if in search of something. "What are you looking      
\par for?" she enquired.                                                         
\par   "The button from your foil," he answered. "You have dropped it."          
\par   She laughed. "I have still the mask."                                     
\par   "It makes your eyes lovelier," was his reply.                             
\par   She laughed again. Her teeth showed like white seeds in a scarlet         
\par fruit.                                                                      
\par   Upstairs, in his own room, Dorian Gray was lying on a sofa, with          
\par terror in every tingling fibre of his body. Life had suddenly become        
\par too hideous a burden for him to bear. The dreadful death of the             
\par unlucky beater, shot in the thicket like a wild animal, had seemed          
\par to him to prefigure death for himself also. He had nearly swooned at        
\par what Lord Henry had said in a chance mood of cynical jesting.               
\par   At five o'clock he rang his bell for his servant, and gave him            
\par orders to pack his things for the night-express to town, and to have        
\par the brougham at the door by eight-thirty. He was determined not to          
\par sleep another night at Selby Royal. It was an ill-omened place.             
\par Death walked there in the sunlight. The grass of the forest had been        
\par spotted with blood.                                                         
\par   Then he wrote a note to Lord Henry, telling him that he was going up      
\par to town to consult his doctor, and asking him to entertain his              
\par guests in his absence. As he was putting it into the envelope, a knock      
\par came to the door, and his valet informed him that the head-keeper           
\par wished to see him. He frowned, and bit his lip. "Send him in," he           
\par muttered, after some moments' hesitation.                                   
\par   As soon as the man entered Dorian pulled his cheque-book out of a         
\par drawer, and spread it out before him.                                       
\par   "I suppose you have come about the unfortunate accident of this           
\par morning, Thornton?" he said, taking up a pen.                               
\par   "Yes, sir," answered the game-keeper.                                     
\par   "Was the poor fellow married? Had he any people dependent on him?"        
\par asked Dorian, looking bored. "If so, I should not like them to be left      
\par in want, and will send them any sum of money you may think necessary."      
\par   "We don't know who he is, sir. That is what I took the liberty of         
\par coming to you about."                                                       
\par   "Don't know who he is?" said Dorian, listlessly. "What do you             
\par mean? Wasn't he one of your men?"                                           
\par   "No, sir. Never saw him before. Seems like a sailor, sir."                
\par   The pen dropped from Dorian Gray's hand, and he felt as if his heart      
\par had suddenly stopped beating. "A sailor?" he cried out. "Did you say a      
\par sailor?"                                                                    
\par   "Yes, sir. He looks as if he had been a sort of sailor; tattooed          
\par on both arms, and that kind of thing."                                      
\par   "Was there anything found on him?" said Dorian, leaning forward           
\par and looking at the man with startled eyes. "Anything that would tell        
\par his name?"                                                                  
\par   "Some money, sir- not much, and a six-shooter. There was no name          
\par of any kind. A decent-looking man, sir, but rough-like. A sort of           
\par sailor we think."                                                           
\par   Dorian started to his feet. A terrible hope fluttered past him. He        
\par clutched at it madly. "Where is the body?" he exclaimed. "Quick! I          
\par must see it at once."                                                       
\par   "It is in an empty stable in the Home Farm, sir. The folk don't like      
\par to have that sort of thing in their houses. They say a corpse brings        
\par bad luck."                                                                  
\par   "The Home Farm! Go there at once and meet me. Tell one of the grooms      
\par to bring my horse round. No. Never mind. I'll go to the stables             
\par myself. It will save time."                                                 
\par   In less than a quarter of an hour Dorian Gray was galloping down the      
\par long avenue as hard as he could go. The trees seemed to sweep past him      
\par in spectral procession, and wild shadows to fling themselves across         
\par his path. Once the mare swerved at a white gate-post and nearly             
\par threw him. He lashed her across the neck with his crop. She cleft           
\par the dusky air like an arrow. The stones flew from her hoofs.                
\par   At last he reached the Home Farm. Two men were loitering in the           
\par yard. He leapt from the saddle and threw the reins to one of them.          
\par In the farthest stable a light was glimmering. Something seemed to          
\par tell him that the body was there, and he hurried to the door, and           
\par put his hand upon the latch.                                                
\par   There he paused for a moment, feeling that he was on the brink of         
\par a discovery that would either make or mar his life. Then he thrust the      
\par door open, and entered.                                                     
\par   On a heap of sacking in the far corner was lying the dead body of         
\par a man dressed in a coarse shirt and a pair of blue trousers. A spotted      
\par handkerchief had been placed over the face. A coarse candle, stuck          
\par in a bottle, sputtered beside it.                                           
\par   Dorian Gray shuddered. He felt that his could not be the hand to          
\par take the handkerchief away, and called out to one of the farm-servants      
\par to come to him.                                                             
\par   "Take that thing off the face. I wish to see it," he said, clutching      
\par at the door-post for support.                                               
\par   When the farm-servant had done so, he stepped forward. A cry of           
\par joy broke from his lips. The man who had been shot in the thicket           
\par was James Vane.                                                             
\par   He stood there for some minutes looking at the dead body. As he rode      
\par home, his eyes were full of tears, for he knew that he was safe.            
