\par                              CHAPTER XIX                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   "There is no use your telling me that you are going to be good,"          
\par cried Lord Henry, dipping his white fingers into a red copper bowl          
\par filled with rose-water. "You are quite perfect. Pray, don't change."        
\par   Dorian Gray shook his head. "No, Harry, I have done too many              
\par dreadful things in my life. I am not going to do any more. I began          
\par my good actions yesterday."                                                 
\par   "Where were you yesterday?"                                               
\par   "In the country, Harry. I was staying at a little inn by myself."         
\par   "My dear boy," said Lord Henry, smiling, "anybody can be good in the      
\par country. There are no temptations there. That is the reason why people      
\par who live out of town are so absolutely uncivilized. Civilization is         
\par not by any means an easy thing to attain to. There are only two ways        
\par by which man can reach it. One is by being cultured, the other by           
\par being corrupt. Country people have no opportunity of being either,          
\par so they stagnate."                                                          
\par   "Culture and corruption," echoed Dorian. "I have known something          
\par of both. It seems terrible to me now that they should ever be found         
\par together. For I have a new ideal, Harry. I am going to alter. I             
\par think I have altered."                                                      
\par   "You have not yet told me what your good action was. Or did you           
\par say you had done more than one?" asked his companion, as he spilt into      
\par his plate a little crimson pyramid of seeded strawberries, and through      
\par a perforated shell-shaped spoon snowed white sugar upon them.               
\par   "I can tell you, Harry. It is not a story I could tell to any one         
\par else. I spared somebody. It sounds vain, but you understand what I          
\par mean. She was quite beautiful, and wonderfully like Sibyl Vane. I           
\par think it was that which first attracted me to her. You remember Sibyl,      
\par don't you? How long ago that seems! Well, Hetty was not one of our own      
\par class, of course. She was simply a girl in a village. But I really          
\par loved her. I am quite sure that I loved her. All during this wonderful      
\par May that we have been having, I used to run down and see her two or         
\par three times a week. Yesterday she met me in a little orchard. The           
\par apple-blossoms kept tumbling down on her hair, and she was laughing.        
\par We were to have gone away together this morning at dawn. Suddenly I         
\par determined to leave her as flower-like as I had found her."                 
\par   "I should think the novelty of the emotion must have given you a          
\par thrill of real pleasure, Dorian," interrupted Lord Henry. "But I can        
\par finish your idyll for you. You gave her good advice, and broke her          
\par heart. That was the beginning of your reformation."                         
\par   "Harry, you are horrible! You mustn't say these dreadful things.          
\par Hetty's heart is not broken. Of course she cried, and all that. But         
\par there is no disgrace upon her. She can live, like Perdita, in her           
\par garden of mint and marigold."                                               
\par   "And weep over faithless Florizel," said Lord Henry, laughing, as he      
\par leant back in his chair. "My dear Dorian, you have the most                 
\par curiously boyish moods. Do you think this girl will ever be really          
\par contented now with any one of her own rank? I suppose she will be           
\par married some day to a rough carter or a grinning ploughman. Well,           
\par the fact of having met you, and loved you, will teach her to despise        
\par her husband, and she will be wretched. From a moral point of view, I        
\par cannot say that I think much of your great renunciation. Even as a          
\par beginning, it is poor. Besides, how do you know that Hetty isn't            
\par floating at the present moment in some star-lit mill-pond, with lovely      
\par water-lilies round her, like Ophelia?                                       
\par   "I can't bear this, Harry! You mock at everything, and then               
\par suggest the most serious tragedies. I am sorry I told you now. I don't      
\par care what you say to me. I know I was right in acting as I did. Poor        
\par Hetty! As I rode past the farm this morning, I saw her white face at        
\par the window, like a spray of jasmine. Don't let us talk about it any         
\par more, and don't try to persuade me that the first good action I have        
\par done for years, the first little bit of self-sacrifice I have ever          
\par known, is really a sort of sin. I want to be better. I am going to be       
\par better. Tell me something about yourself. What is going on in town?         
\par I have not been to the club for days."                                      
\par   "The people are still discussing poor Basil's disappearance."             
\par   "I should have thought they had got tired of that by this time,"          
\par said Dorian, pouring himself out some wine, and frowning slightly.          
\par   "My dear boy, they have only been talking about it for six weeks,         
\par and the British public are really not equal to the mental strain of         
\par having more than one topic every three months. They have been very          
\par fortunate lately, however. They have had my own divorce-case, and Alan      
\par Campbell's suicide. Now they have got the mysterious disappearance          
\par of an artist. Scotland Yard still insists that the man in the grey          
\par ulster who left for Paris by the midnight train on the ninth of             
\par November was poor Basil, and the French police declare that Basil           
\par never arrived in Paris at all. I suppose in about a fortnight we shall      
\par be told that he has been seen in San Francisco. It is an odd thing,         
\par but every one who disappears is said to be seen at San Francisco. It        
\par must be a delightful city, and possess all the attractions of the next      
\par world."                                                                     
\par   "What do you think has happened to Basil?" asked Dorian, holding          
\par up his Burgundy against the light, and wondering how it was he could        
\par discuss the matter so calmly.                                               
\par   "I have not the slightest idea. If Basil chooses to hide himself, it      
\par is no business of mine. If he is dead, I don't want to think about          
\par him. Death is the only thing that ever terrifies me. I hate it."            
\par   "Why?" said the young man, wearily.                                       
\par   "Because," said Lord Henry, passing beneath his nostrils the gilt         
\par trellis of an open vinaigrette box, "one can survive everything             
\par nowadays except that. Death and vulgarity are the only two facts in         
\par the nineteenth century that one cannot explain away. Let us have our        
\par coffee in the music-room, Dorian. You must play Chopin to me. The           
\par man with whom my wife ran away played Chopin exquisitely. Poor              
\par Victoria! I was very fond of her. The house is rather lonely without        
\par her. Of course married life is merely a habit, a bad habit. But then        
\par one regrets the loss even of one's worst habits. Perhaps one regrets        
\par them the most. They are such an essential part of one's personality."       
\par   Dorian said nothing, but rose from the table, and, passing into           
\par the next room, sat down to the piano and let his fingers stray              
\par across the white and black ivory of the keys. After the coffee had          
\par been brought in, he stopped, and, looking over at Lord Henry, said,         
\par "Harry, did it ever occur to you that Basil was murdered?"                  
\par   Lord Henry yawned. "Basil was very popular, and always wore a             
\par Waterbury watch. Why should he have been murdered? He was not clever        
\par enough to have enemies. Of course he had a wonderful genius for             
\par painting. But a man can paint like Velasquez and yet be as dull as          
\par possible. Basil was really rather dull. He only interested me once,         
\par and that was when he told me, years ago, that he had a wild                 
\par adoration for you, and that you were the dominant motive of his art."       
\par   "I was very fond of Basil," said Dorian, with a note of sadness in        
\par his voice. "But don't people say that he was murdered?"                     
\par   "Oh, some of the papers do. It does not seem to me to be at all           
\par probable. I know there are dreadful places in Paris, but Basil was not      
\par the sort of man to have gone to them. He had no curiosity. It was           
\par his chief defect."                                                          
\par   "What would you say, Harry, if I told you that I had murdered             
\par Basil?" said the younger man. He watched him intently after he had          
\par spoken.                                                                     
\par   "I would say, my dear fellow, that you were posing for a character        
\par that doesn't suit you. All crime is vulgar, just as all vulgarity is        
\par crime. It is not in you, Dorian, to commit a murder. I am sorry if I        
\par hurt your vanity by saying so, but I assure you it is true. Crime           
\par belongs exclusively to the lower orders. I don't blame them in the          
\par smallest degree. I should fancy that crime was to them what art is          
\par to us, simply a method of procuring extraordinary sensations."              
\par   "A method of procuring sensations? Do you think, then, that a man         
\par who has once committed a murder could possibly do the same crime            
\par again? Don't tell me that."                                                 
\par   "Oh! anything becomes a pleasure if one does it too often," cried         
\par Lord Henry, laughing. "That is one of the most important secrets of         
\par life. I should fancy, however, that murder is always a mistake. One         
\par should never do anything that one cannot talk about after dinner.           
\par But let us pass from poor Basil. I wish I could believe that he had         
\par come to such a really romantic end as you suggest; but I can't. I dare      
\par say he fell into the Seine off an omnibus, and that the conductor           
\par hushed up the scandal. Yes: I should fancy that was his end. I see him      
\par now lying on his back under those dull-green waters with the heavy          
\par barges floating over him, and long weeds catching in his hair. Do           
\par you know, I don't think he would have done much more good work. During      
\par the last ten years his painting had gone off very much."                    
\par   Dorian heaved a sigh, and Lord Henry strolled across the room and         
\par began to stroke the head of a curious Java parrot, a large                  
\par grey-plumaged bird, with pink crest and tail, that was balancing            
\par itself upon a bamboo perch. As his pointed fingers touched it, it           
\par dropped the white scurf of crinkled lids over black glass-like eyes,        
\par and began to sway backwards and forwards.                                   
\par   "Yes," he continued, turning round, and taking his handkerchief           
\par out of his pocket; "his painting had quite gone off. It seemed to me        
\par to have lost something. It had lost an ideal. When you and he ceased        
\par to be great friends, he ceased to be a great artist. What was it            
\par separated you? I suppose he bored you. If so, he never forgave you.         
\par It's a habit bores have. By the way, what has become of that wonderful      
\par portrait he did of you? I don't think I have ever seen it since he          
\par finished it. Oh! I remember your telling me years ago that you had          
\par sent it down to Selby, and that it had got mislaid or stolen on the         
\par way. You never got it back? What a pity! It was really a                    
\par masterpiece. I remember I wanted to buy it. I wish I had now. It            
\par belonged to Basil's best period. Since then, his work was that curious      
\par mixture of bad painting and good intentions that always entitles a man      
\par to be called a representative British artist. Did you advertise for         
\par it? You should."                                                            
\par   "I forget," said Dorian. "I suppose I did. But I never really             
\par liked it. I am sorry I sat for it. The memory of the thing is               
\par hateful to me. Why do you talk of it? It used to remind me of those         
\par curious lines in some play- 'Hamlet,' I think- how do they run?-            
\par -                                                                           
\par                     "'Like the painting of a sorrow,                        
\par                   A face without a heart.'                                  
\par -                                                                           
\par Yes: that is what it was like."                                             
\par   Lord Henry laughed. "If a man treats life artistically, his brain is      
\par his heart," he answered, sinking into an arm-chair.                         
\par   Dorian Gray shook his head, and struck some soft chords on the            
\par piano. "'Like the painting of a sorrow?'" he repeated, "'a face             
\par without a heart.'"                                                          
\par   The elder man lay back and looked at him with half-closed eyes.           
\par "By the way, Dorian," he said, after a pause, "'what does it profit         
\par a man if he gain the whole world and lose'- how does the quotation          
\par run?- 'his own soul?'"                                                      
\par   The music jarred and Dorian Gray started, and stared at his               
\par friend. "Why do you ask me that, Harry?"                                    
\par   "My dear fellow," said Lord Henry, elevating his eyebrows in              
\par surprise, "I asked you because I thought you might be able to give          
\par me an answer. That is all. I was going through the Park last Sunday,        
\par and close by the Marble Arch there stood a little crowd of                  
\par shabby-looking people listening to some vulgar street-preacher. As I        
\par passed by, I heard the man yelling out that question to his                 
\par audience. It struck me as being rather dramatic. London is very rich        
\par in curious effects of that kind. A wet Sunday, an uncouth Christian in      
\par a mackintosh, a ring of sickly white faces under a broken roof of           
\par dripping umbrellas, and a wonderful phrase flung into the air by            
\par shrill, hysterical lips- it was really very good in its way, quite a        
\par suggestion. I thought of telling the prophet that Art had a soul,           
\par but that man had not. I am afraid, however, he would not have               
\par understood me."                                                             
\par   "Don't, Harry. The soul is a terrible reality. It can be bought, and      
\par sold, and bartered away. It can be poisoned, or made perfect. There is      
\par a soul in each one of us. I know it."                                       
\par   "Do you feel quite sure of that, Dorian?"                                 
\par   "Quite sure."                                                             
\par   "Ah! then it must be an illusion. The things one feels absolutely         
\par certain about are never true. That is the fatality of Faith, and the        
\par lesson of Romance. How grave you are! Don't be so serious. What have        
\par you or I to do with the superstitions of our age? No: we have given up      
\par our belief in the soul. Play me something. Play me a nocturne, Dorian,      
\par and, as you play, tell me, in a low voice, how you have kept your           
\par youth. You must have some secret. I am only ten years older than you        
\par are, and I am wrinkled, and worn, and yellow. You are really                
\par wonderful, Dorian. You have never looked more charming than you do          
\par to-night. You remind me of the day I saw you first. You were rather         
\par cheeky, very shy, and absolutely extraordinary. You have changed, of        
\par course, but not in appearance. I wish you would tell me your secret.        
\par To get back my youth I would do anything in the world, except take          
\par exercise, get up early, or be respectable. Youth! There is nothing          
\par like it. It's absurd to talk of the ignorance of youth. The only            
\par people to whose opinions I listen now with any respect are people much      
\par younger than myself. They seem in front of me. Life has revealed to         
\par them her latest wonder. As for the aged, I always contradict the aged.      
\par I do it on principle. If you ask them their opinion on something            
\par that happened yesterday, they solemnly give you the opinions current        
\par in 1820, when people wore high stocks, believed in everything, and          
\par knew absolutely nothing. How lovely that thing you are playing is! I        
\par wonder did Chopin write it at Majorca, with the sea weeping round           
\par the villa, and the salt spray dashing against the panes? It is              
\par marvellously romantic. What a blessing it is that there is one art          
\par left to us that is not imitative! Don't stop. I want music to-night.        
\par It seems to me that you are the young Apollo, and that I am Marsyas         
\par listening to you. I have sorrows, Dorian, of my own, that even you          
\par know nothing of. The tragedy of old age is not that one is old, but         
\par that one is young. I am amazed sometimes at my own sincerity. Ah,           
\par Dorian, how happy you are! What an exquisite life you have had! You         
\par have drunk deeply of everything. You have crushed the grapes against        
\par your palate. Nothing has been hidden from you. And it has all been          
\par to you no more than the sound of music. It has not marred you. You are      
\par still the same."                                                            
\par   "I am not the same, Harry."                                               
\par   "Yes: you are the same. I wonder what the rest of your life will be.      
\par Don't spoil it by renunciations. At present you are a perfect type.         
\par Don't make yourself incomplete. You are quite flawless now. You need        
\par not shake your head: you know you are. Besides, Dorian, don't               
\par deceive yourself. Life is not governed by will or intention. Life is a      
\par question of nerves, and fibres, and slowly built-up cells in which          
\par thought hides itself and passion has its dreams. You may fancy              
\par yourself safe, and think yourself strong. But a chance tone of              
\par colour in a room or a morning sky, a particular perfume that you had        
\par once loved and that brings subtle memories with it, a line from a           
\par forgotten poem that you had come across again, a cadence from a             
\par piece of music that you had ceased to play- I tell you, Dorian, that        
\par it is on things like these that our lives depend. Browning writes           
\par about that somewhere; but our own senses will imagine them for us.          
\par There are moments when the odour of lilas blanc passes suddenly across      
\par me, and I have to live the strangest month of my life over again. I         
\par wish I could change places with you, Dorian. The world has cried out        
\par against us both, but it has always worshipped you. It always will           
\par worship you. You are the type of what the age is searching for, and         
\par what it is afraid it has found. I am so glad that you have never            
\par done anything, never carved a statue, or painted a picture, or              
\par produced anything outside yourself! Life has been your art. You have        
\par set yourself to music. Your days are your sonnets."                         
\par   Dorian rose up from the piano, and passed his hand through his hair.      
\par "Yes, life has been exquisite," he murmured, "but I am not going to         
\par have the same life, Harry. And you must not say these extravagant           
\par things to me. You don't know everything about me. I think that if           
\par you did, even you would turn from me. You laugh. Don't laugh."              
\par   "Why have you stopped playing, Dorian? Go back and give me the            
\par nocturne over again. Look at that great honey-coloured moon that hangs      
\par in the dusky air. She is waiting for you to charm her, and if you play      
\par she will come closer to the earth. You won't? Let us go to the club,        
\par then. It has been a charming evening, and we must end it charmingly.        
\par There is some one at White's who wants immensely to know you- young         
\par Lord Poole, Bournemouth's eldest son. He has already copied your            
\par neckties, and has begged me to introduce him to you. He is quite            
\par delightful, and rather reminds me of you."                                  
\par   "I hope not," said Dorian, with a sad look in his eyes. "But I am         
\par tired to-night, Harry. I sha'n't go to the club. It is nearly               
\par eleven, and I want to go to bed early."                                     
\par   "Do stay. You have never played so well as to-night. There was            
\par something in your touch that was wonderful. It had more expression          
\par than I had ever heard from it before."                                      
\par   "It is because I am going to be good," he answered, smiling. "I am a      
\par little changed already."                                                    
\par   "You cannot change to me, Dorian," said Lord Henry. "You and I            
\par will always be friends."                                                    
\par   "Yet you poisoned me with a book once. I should not forgive that.         
\par Harry, promise me that you will never lend that book to any one. It         
\par does harm."                                                                 
\par   "My dear boy, you are really beginning to moralize. You will soon be      
\par going about like the converted, and the revivalist, warning people          
\par against all the sins of which you have grown tired. You are much too        
\par delightful to do that. Besides, it is no use. You and I are what we         
\par are, and will be what we will be. As for being poisoned by a book,          
\par there is no such thing as that. Art has no influence upon action. It        
\par annihilates the desire to act. It is superbly sterile. The books            
\par that the world calls immoral are books that show the world its own          
\par shame. That is all. But we won't discuss literature. Come round             
\par to-morrow. I am going to ride at eleven. We might go together, and I        
\par will take you to lunch afterwards with Lady Branksome. She is a             
\par charming woman, and wants to consult you about some tapestries she          
\par is thinking of buying. Mind you come. Or shall we lunch with our            
\par little Duchess? She says she never sees you now. Perhaps you are tired      
\par of Gladys? I thought you would be. Her clever tongue gets on one's          
\par nerves. Well, in any case, be here at eleven."                              
\par   "Must I really come, Harry?"                                              
\par   "Certainly. The Park is quite lovely now. I don't think there have        
\par been such lilacs since the year I met you."                                 
\par   "Very well. I shall be here at eleven," said Dorian. "Good-night,         
\par Harry." As he reached the door he hesitated for a moment, as if he had      
\par something more to say. Then he sighed and went out.                         
\par                                                                             
\par                                                                             
\par                               CHAPTER XX                                    
\par -                                                                           
\par   It was a lovely night, so warm that he threw his coat over his            
\par arm, and did not even put his silk scarf round his throat. As he            
\par strolled home, smoking his cigarette, two young men in evening dress        
\par passed him. He heard one of them whisper to the other, "That is Dorian      
\par Gray." He remembered how pleased he used to be when he was pointed          
\par out, or stared at, or talked about. He was tired of hearing his own         
\par name now. Half the charm of the little village where he had been so         
\par often lately was that no one knew who he was. He had often told the         
\par girl whom he had lured to love him that he was poor, and she had            
\par believed him. He had told her once that he was wicked, and she had          
\par laughed at him, and answered that wicked people were always very old        
\par and very ugly. What a laugh she had!- just like a thrush singing.           
\par And how pretty she had been in her cotton dresses and her large             
\par hats! She knew nothing, but she had everything that he had lost.            
\par   When he reached home, he found his servant waiting up for him. He         
\par sent him to bed, and threw himself down on the sofa in the library,         
\par and began to think over some of the things that Lord Henry had said to      
\par him.                                                                        
\par   Was it really true that one could never change? He felt a wild            
\par longing for the unstained purity of his boyhood- his rose-white             
\par boyhood, as Lord Henry had once called it. He knew that he had              
\par tarnished himself, filled his mind with corruption and given horror to      
\par his fancy; that he had been an evil influence to others and had             
\par experienced a terrible joy in being so; and that of the lives that had      
\par crossed his own it had been the fairest and the most full of promise        
\par that he had brought to shame. But was it all irretrievable? Was             
\par there no hope for him?                                                      
\par   Ah! in what a monstrous moment of pride and passion he had prayed         
\par that the portrait should bear the burden of his days, and he keep           
\par the unsullied splendour of eternal youth! All his failure had been due      
\par to that. Better for him that each sin of his life had brought its           
\par sure, swift penalty along with it. There was purification in                
\par punishment. Not "Forgive us our sins" but "Smite us for our                 
\par iniquities" should be the prayer of man to a most just God.                 
\par   The curiously-carved mirror that Lord Henry had given to him, so          
\par many years ago now, was standing on the table, and the white-limbed         
\par Cupids laughed round it as of old. He took it up, as he had done on         
\par that night of horror, when he had first noted the change in the             
\par fatal picture, and with wild tear-dimmed eyes looked into its polished      
\par shield. Once, some one who had terribly loved him, had written to           
\par him a mad letter, ending with these idolatrous words: "The world is         
\par changed because you are made of ivory, and gold. The curves of your         
\par lips rewrite history." The phrases came back to his memory, and he          
\par repeated them over and over to himself. Then he loathed his own             
\par beauty, and flinging the mirror to the floor crushed it into silver         
\par splinters beneath his heel. It was his beauty that had ruined him, his      
\par beauty and the youth that he had prayed for. But for these two things,      
\par his life might have been free from stain. His beauty had been to him        
\par but a mask, his youth but a mockery. What was youth at best? A              
\par green, an unripe time, a time of shallow moods, and sickly thoughts.        
\par Why had he worn its livery? Youth had spoiled him.                          
\par   It was better not to think of the past. Nothing could alter that. It      
\par was of himself, and of his own future, that he had to think. James          
\par Vane was hidden in a nameless grave in Selby churchyard. Alan Campbell      
\par had shot himself one night in his laboratory, but had not revealed the      
\par secret that he had been forced to know. The excitement, such as it          
\par was, over Basil Hallward's disappearance would soon pass away. It           
\par was already waning. He was perfectly safe there. Nor, indeed, was it        
\par the death of Basil Hallward that weighed most upon his mind. It was         
\par the living death of his own soul that troubled him. Basil had               
\par painted the portrait that had marred his life. He could not forgive         
\par him that. It was the portrait that had done everything. Basil had said      
\par things to him that were unbearable, and that he had yet borne with          
\par patience. The murder had been simply the madness of a moment. As for        
\par Alan Campbell, his suicide had been his own act. He had chosen to do        
\par it. It was nothing to him.                                                  
\par   A new life! That was what he wanted. That was what he was waiting         
\par for. Surely he had begun it already. He had spared one innocent thing,      
\par at any rate. He would never again tempt innocence. He would be good.        
\par   As he thought of Hetty Merton, he began to wonder if the portrait in      
\par the locked room had changed. Surely it was not still so horrible as it      
\par had been? Perhaps if his life became pure, he would be able to expel        
\par every sign of evil passion from the face. Perhaps the signs of evil         
\par had already gone away. He would go and look.                                
\par   He took the lamp from the table and crept upstairs. As he unbarred        
\par the door, a smile of joy flitted across his strangely young-looking         
\par face and lingered for a moment about his lips. Yes, he would be             
\par good, and the hideous thing that he had hidden away would no longer be      
\par a terror to him. He felt as if the load had been lifted from him            
\par already.                                                                    
\par   He went in quietly, locking the door behind him, as was his               
\par custom, and dragged the purple hanging from the portrait. A cry of          
\par pain and indignation broke from him. He could see no change, save that      
\par in the eyes there was a look of cunning, and in the mouth the curved        
\par wrinkle of the hypocrite. The thing was still loathsome- more               
\par loathsome, if possible, than before- and the scarlet dew that               
\par spotted the hand seemed brighter, and more like blood newly spilt.          
\par Then he trembled. Had it been merely vanity that had made him do his        
\par one good deed? Or the desire for a new sensation, as Lord Henry had         
\par hinted, with his mocking laugh? Or that passion to act a part that          
\par sometimes makes us do things finer than we are ourselves? Or, perhaps,      
\par all these? And why was the red stain larger than it had been? It            
\par seemed to have crept like a horrible disease over the wrinkled              
\par fingers. There was blood on the painted feet, as though the thing           
\par had dripped- blood even on the hand that had not held the knife.            
\par Confess? Did it mean that he was to confess? To give himself up, and        
\par be put to death? He laughed. He felt that the idea was monstrous.           
\par Besides, even if he did confess, who would believe him? There was no        
\par trace of the murdered man anywhere. Everything belonging to him had         
\par been destroyed. He himself had burned what had been below-stairs.           
\par The world would simply say that he was mad. They would shut him up          
\par if he persisted in his story.... Yet it was his duty to confess, to         
\par suffer public shame, and to make public atonement. There was a God who      
\par called upon men to tell their sins to earth as well as to heaven.           
\par Nothing that he could do would cleanse him till he had told his own         
\par sin. His sin? He shrugged his shoulders. The death of Basil Hallward        
\par seemed very little to him. He was thinking of Hetty Merton. For it was      
\par an unjust mirror, this mirror of his soul that he was looking at.           
\par Vanity? Curiosity? Hypocrisy? Had there been nothing more in his            
\par renunciation than that? There had been something more. At least he          
\par thought so. But who could tell?... No. There had been nothing more.         
\par Through vanity he had spared her. In hypocrisy he had worn the mask of      
\par goodness. For curiosity's sake he had tried the denial of self. He          
\par recognized that now.                                                        
\par   But this murder- was it to dog him all his life? Was he always to be      
\par burdened by his past? Was he really to confess? Never. There was            
\par only one bit of evidence left against him. The picture itself- that         
\par was evidence. He would destroy it. Why had he kept it so long? Once it      
\par had given him pleasure to watch it changing and growing old. Of late        
\par he had felt no such pleasure. It had kept him awake at night. When          
\par he had been away, he had been filled with terror lest other eyes            
\par should look upon it. It had brought melancholy across his passions.         
\par Its mere memory had marred many moments of joy. It had been like            
\par conscience to him. Yes, it had been conscience. He would destroy it.        
\par   He looked round, and saw the knife that had stabbed Basil                 
\par Hallward. He had cleaned it many times, till there was no stain left        
\par upon it. It was bright, and glistened. As it had killed the painter,        
\par so it would kill the painter's work, and all that that meant. It would      
\par kill the past, and when that was dead he would be free. It would            
\par kill this monstrous soul-life, and without its hideous warnings, he         
\par would be at peace. He seized the thing, and stabbed the picture with        
\par it.                                                                         
\par   There was a cry heard, and a crash. The cry was so horrible in its        
\par agony that the frightened servants woke, and crept out of their rooms.      
\par Two gentlemen, who were passing in the Square below, stopped, and           
\par looked up at the great house. They walked on till they met a                
\par policeman, and brought him back. The man rang the bell several              
\par times, but there was no answer. Except for a light in one of the top        
\par windows, the house was all dark. After a time, he went away, and stood      
\par in an adjoining portico and watched.                                        
\par   "Whose house is that, constable?" asked the elder of the two              
\par gentlemen.                                                                  
\par   "Mr. Dorian Gray's, sir," answered the policeman.                         
\par   They looked at each other, as they walked away, and sneered. One          
\par of them was Sir Henry Ashton's uncle.                                       
\par   Inside, in the servants' part of the house, the half-clad                 
\par domestics were talking in low whispers to each other. Old Mrs. Leaf         
\par was crying, and wringing her hands. Francis was as pale as death.           
\par   After about a quarter of an hour, he got the coachman and one of the      
\par footmen and crept upstairs. They knocked, but there was no reply. They      
\par called out. Everything was still. Finally, after vainly trying to           
\par force the door, they got on the roof, and dropped down on to the            
\par balcony. The windows yielded easily: their bolts were old.                  
\par   When they entered, they found hanging upon the wall a splendid            
\par portrait of their master as they had last seen him, in all the              
\par wonder of his exquisite youth and beauty. Lying on the floor was a          
\par dead man, in evening dress, with a knife in his heart. He was               
\par withered, wrinkled, and loathsome of visage. It was not till they           
\par had examined the rings that they recognized who it was.                     
